<SLUG> BC-UNION-CLOUT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. UNIONS FLEX MUSCLES
</HEADLINE>
bc-UNION-CLOUT-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES With teachers authorizing a strike and county
employees set to join transit employees and commercial actors on
picket lines, Los Angeles has gone from a historically anti-union
town to one known for the muscle of its labor movement, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a historic moment,'' Art Pulaski, executive
secretary-treasurer of the California Labor Federation, said
Thursday. ``We see much more activism and we see much more
coordination and mutual support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workers have gone so long with backwards motion in terms of
wages and cost of living,'' he added, so if striking is what it
takes to regain lost ground, ``then they're up for the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say a combination of factors are at work to make unions
here more militant than before: a booming economy that has yet to
trickle down to society's lowest rungs, bitter memories of cutbacks
during the most recent recession, politicians who court union votes
by granting them major concessions, and the public's lack of true
awareness about the issues and vast amounts of money at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have weak mayors, lots of power in city councils, lots of
various authorities that fragment ultimate responsibility and
power,'' said Ralph Rossum, director of the Rose Institute of State
and Local Government at Claremont McKenna College. ``Therefore,
unions look strong relative to the weakness of the governmental
structure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one set of individuals who, if they do stand up to
unions, either take the blame if the public is behind the unions or
take the credit if the public is opposed to what the unions are
trying to secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Public employee unions are especially powerful, he said, because
they are negotiating with politicians who need their votes, and
because they have the power of monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   In the private sector, for example, if workers at an auto
factory go on strike, the public can always buy cars elsewhere. But
if bus drivers or public teachers go on strike, alternatives are
harder to find.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Los Angeles unions spoke out like never before. The
8,500-member janitors union went on strike earlier this year,
winning major concessions in wages and working conditions.
Commercial actors have been on strike for several months over
issues relating to residuals for cable television and overseas
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Transportation Authority bus and rail operators
have been on strike for two weeks, causing increased traffic
congestion and reduced economic activity while leaving nearly half
a million daily riders scrambling for alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, MTA officials asked United Transportation Union
chairman James Williams to agree to a federal mediator, submit
detailed written demands and allow bus and rail drivers to return
to work while talks continue, UTU spokesman Goldy Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he would work on a formal comprehensive proposal
but would not agree to call in a federal mediator or send members
back to work while negotiations continue, Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Unions representing Los Angeles teachers and county employees
are set to strike in the near future, while Hollywood is already
bracing for an expected Writers Guild strike next year over issues
similar to the commercial actors.
</P>
<P>
   Ezunial Burts, president of the Los Angeles Area Chamber of
Commerce, said this year's labor unrest was long expected because
of the convergence of major contracts expiring in the same period,
even as the economy is booming.
</P>
<P>
   But the good economy, he said, doesn't necessarily mean all
employers are flush with cash. Local governments, he said, tend to
get revenues later than the federal government, while private
sector employers are increasingly seeking to reduce costs to stay
competitive in the world market.
</P>
<P>
   Having all the strikes occur at roughly the same time, he said,
hurts the city's image and makes businesses less willing to stay or
relocate here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the cumulative effect I worry about,'' Burts said. ``One
or two of these isn't so tough to handle in the short run. You
settle it and a year from now you don't remember it. But you keep
having these and pretty soon the reputation we worked so hard to
gain to promote the positive things in this economy ... it can wipe
that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles City Councilman Mike Feuer, who helped negotiate a
police contract this summer, said management and union leaders need
to find a balance between bridging wage gaps and providing good
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential convergence of these labor actions would be
awful from the standpoint of the average resident of this city,''
Feuer said. ``I hope very much that the labor actions don't take
place and that reasonable people strike a middle ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossum said the unions are also vulnerable to a backlash, if
they appear to be too powerful and win too many concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the solution to a too-powerful public union?`` Rossum
asked rhetorically. ``Privatization. Vouchers. Privatize
transportation and trash, and even security matters and prison
guards. If they push too far, more people are going to say that the
only real solution is to introduce some competition.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
