<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTER OF ASU COACH WORKS AT UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Paige Snyder, a student employee in the UCLA
football office, is by all accounts a hard worker with a pleasant
personality. Everyone normally loves to have her around _ but not
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder happens to be the daughter of Arizona State coach Bruce
Snyder, whose team plays the Bruins at the Rose Bowl on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   So, each year when the Bruins play Arizona State, she's given
the week off. This year, with school just starting, she hadn't
begun to work anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, a junior, has worked in the football office the past two
years. She works mostly with recruits, playing host to players
during games and doing data entry. Another one of her duties is to
collate copies of the Bruins' scouting reports each week _ except
one, of course.
</P>
<P>
   She also isn't involved when UCLA and Arizona State are
recruiting the same player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona State week, it's a little odd, but she's a great
kid,'' said Lea Bean, a football administrative assistant and
Snyder's supervisor. ``We don't want to put her in an uncomfortable
situation. She says, `Yeah, I'm totally loyal to UCLA every week
but this one.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She has such a bubbly personality and is so much fun to work
with that it doesn't strain anything that she's the daughter of a
rival Pac-10 head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Add legacies: Snyder isn't the only member of the football
family with a famous father from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Ryan Nece is the son of former USC defensive back
Ronnie Lott, and fullback Chris Jackson is the son of former
Washington linebacker Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   __ Krohn out, Kealy in: Arizona State quarterback Jeff Krohn,
who missed Wednesday's practice with what was thought to be the
flu, has been diagnosed with mononucleosis and is out indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Kealy, the talented fifth-year senior who has been beset by
injuries and suspension, will make his first start of the season
for the Sun Devils.
</P>
<P>
   __ Dijon, s'il vous plait: It's not only a big weekend for the
football team, but also for the basketball team, whose coaches will
be entertaining Redondo High's 6-foot-7 guard Dijon Thompson on an
official recruiting visit.
</P>
<P>
   With Mayfair's Josh Childress turning the Bruins down, Thompson
is the wing player they've set their sights on.
</P>
<P>
   __ Good start for end Freshman Terrell Suggs has been a
sensation at defensive end for Arizona State with five sacks, a
forced fumble and a 48-yard interception returned for a touchdown.
Quietly doing the job at the other end has been another freshman,
redshirt Brian Montesanto of Simi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Montesanto, a 6-foot-6, 240-pound graduate of Royal, stepped
into a starting position when senior Quincy Yancy was suspended for
the season opener against San Diego State and hasn't given it up.
He's had four tackles and 1 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian is a real pleasant surprise,'' Arizona State coach Bruce
Snyder said. ``Talk about somebody who's gotten better every
practice and every game. It's not by much but over time it
accumulates. I think he's a much better player today than he was
three to four weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Bell dinged: Cornerback Jason Bell, who practiced earlier in
the week, has been limited the last two days because of the
hamstring he tweaked against Oregon. Behind Bell is Joe Hunter, who
broke up a pass when he replaced Bell for a play against the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's injury would have the most impact in nickel and dime
coverages since the Bruins are also without strong safety Marques
Anderson (surgery), one of their best cover men. Audie Attar will
replace Anderson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
