<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS COULD BE LEARNED HERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ I've always thought the criterion for a
sport being included in the Olympics was simple: If the Olympics
aren't the ultimate reward, the sport doesn't belong here.
</P>
<P>
   The impudence of people such as tennis gazillionaire Pete
Sampras, who waffles on competing at the Games because of the
inconvenience involved, galls me. It seems a stinging slap in the
face to all the athletes who gladly, gallantly endure lives of
spartan pleasures in the pursuit of a few seconds of Olympic glory.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Thursday the Williams sisters and Marion Jones both
spoke of being humbled by the Olympic experience and that's when it
hit me:
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a good thing to have millionaire sportsmen and
sportswomen mingling with lesser-known but no less accomplished
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the more professional athletes who compete in the Games
the better. Perhaps it's prudent to let John Rocker come on in
relief against Cuba, Ken Griffey Jr. swing for the fences against
Korea, Jalen Rose whine about every foul in a game against Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   I'm for anything that'll widen some notable athletes' frame of
references, which appear only large enough to hold a glossy
close-up of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If Venus and Serena Williams, who have three Grand Slam titles
between them, can be awed by Russian Greco-Roman wrestler Alexander
Karelin, why not Barry Bonds?
</P>
<P>
   Karelin had gone 13 years between defeats before falling to
American Rulon Gardner in the heavyweight gold-medal match. That no
doubt helped Venus Williams put her own 32-match winning streak in
persepective.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones, who has collected gold medals in the 100 and 200
meters here, can be humbled just being in the company of
weightlifter Cheryl Haworth and gymnast Elise Ray and judoka Sandra
Bacher, why not Allen Iverson?
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 24, is three gold medals away from becoming a global
icon. No female track star has collected five gold medals in a
single Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly no Olympic athlete, not the great Finn Paavo Nurmi
in the 1920s or the U.S. king Carl Lewis in the 1980s, had a
television network working so feverishly in the role of de facto
personal publicist. A win in the long jump today, followed closely
by victories in the 400 and 600 relays and Jones will be bigger
than Bill Gates (and nearly as rich).
</P>
<P>
   Being in the midst of so many talented athletes, Jones said, has
helped her put her historic quest in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this is so much bigger than one person or one team,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was heartening to hear Jones say that.
</P>
<P>
   After all she has been put through this week, it was reassuring
to see Jones was able to joke Thursday about being introduced
before her 200-meter final as hailing from the Bahamas (chalk it up
to wishful thinking by the stadium announcer, who in the 100-meter
final had introduced three Bahamian sprinters in addition to
Jones).
</P>
<P>
   It was refreshing to see the easy banter back and forth between
Jones and the loquacious 200-meters silver medalist, Pauline
Davis-Thompson, who was over the moon after winning her first
individual Olympic medal in this, her fifth Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marion,'' she said in a lovely lilt, so full of herself but
without seeming at all full of it, ``We're going to give you one
hell of a run in the (sprint) relay.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Davis-Thompson, alluding to Jones' mother being from
Belize, added, ``I know that you have some Caribbean blood in you,
Marion, so you're almost like us,''
</P>
<P>
   Jones laughed so loud it drowned out all the background noise
that has been ringing in her ears the past few days. For a few
seconds, the rest of the world fell away.
</P>
<P>
   Of such moments are the transcendental experience of the
Olympics made. In the long run, it probably would be good if more
professional athletes could speak of it firsthand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
