<SLUG> BC-LIFESPAN-INCREASE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG LIFE INCREASINGLY COMMON IN INDUSTRIALIZED COUNTRIES, REPORT 
 SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  The average life span of people in modern industrialized
countries has grown longer over the past century, and a University
of California at Berkeley researcher said the trend shows no sign
of slowing down.
<P>
   In a report to be published Friday in the journal Science,
demographer John R. Wilmoth and his colleagues suggest people may
one day routinely live to be 120 years old or more.
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists have long held that biology places a rigid limit
on human aging at 120 years, but Wilmoth maintains that the Swedish
records call that very much into question.
</P>
<P>
   The king of Sweden in 1686 decreed that every priest in his
country keep meticulous records of births and deaths in every
parish, and by 1860 those parish records were being kept by the
kingdom's government in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Swedes did it right,'' Wilmoth said Thursday, ``and
because they've done it, Sweden has the best continuous records of
births, deaths and age trends in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1860s, the Swedish records show, the oldest age at
death for both men and women centered around 101 years _ with
women, on average, tending to live somewhat longer than men.
</P>
<P>
   A century later, the average maximum age at death in Sweden had
risen slowly to 105. By the 1990s, it had reached 108, according to
the analysis by Wilmoth and his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Here in America, government reports have estimated that 37,000
``centenarians`` 100 years old or older were alive in 1990. That
the number has risen to 70,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not at all implausible, although it obviously can't go
on indefinitely,'' Wilmoth said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there must be some biological limit to how long people
can live, and although there's no scientific answer to that
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't expect that older people today could realistically
expect to reach more than 110 or 120 at most,'' Wilmoth said.
``That seems to be a realistic outer limit.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest human being whose age at death has been documented
was a French woman named Jeanne Calment of Arles. She knew Vincent
Van Gogh as a child, took fencing lessons at 85 and died in 1997
when she was 122.45 years old, according French records.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly are certainly living longer on average today _
primarily because better public health measures like immunizations,
sanitation and clean drinking water have enabled more of them to
survive in good health past childhood and better health care has
kept them healthier as they age, Wilmoth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as people reach the seventies,'' he said, ``they're
already healthier than the elderly were in the past, and so their
life expectancy becomes longer.''
</P>
<P>
   That improvement in health of the aged has largely resulted from
more effective treatments for heart disease and stroke, from a
year-by-year decline in smoking, and from the development of new
drugs, Wilmoth said.
</P>
<P>
   Today the average life expectancy among babies born in 24
industrial nations is more than 70 years, according to the World
Health Organization. But at the other extreme, life expectancy is
less than 40 years for children born in what is called the
developing world. Even worse, for sub-Saharan Africa where AIDS is
now the leading cause of death, life expectancy for new-borns is
less than 33 years, WHO figures show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
