<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE FOCUSES ON OWN LOSSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's not as if Cal State Northridge will be out of
contention for the Big Sky Conference title if it can't find a way
to beat Idaho State on Saturday at North Campus Stadium. Still, the
Matadors are approaching Saturday as if it's a do-or-die game.
</P>
<P>
   They have played well in spurts, but a sluggish offense,
turnovers and costly defensive mistakes have plagued them all
season. If they don't correct the problems _ and fast _ it could be
a long season.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors (1-2, 0-1) had a week to regroup after a bye and
are ready to erase the disappointment of a second-half collapse
against Northern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho State (2-1, 1-1) is coming off an emotional 41-39 win over
Sacramento State. However, CSUN coach Jeff Kearin said the focus
isn't on Idaho State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I must sound like a broken record, but we need to take
care of the ball,'' Kearin said. ``I've been preaching that and
we've yet to do that. It's not so much focusing on Idaho State as
it is us. We need to execute offensively, hang onto the ball and
play solid on defense. That's what we've been concentrating on.
That's what I've been talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that CSUN isn't concerned about Idaho State's
running game. Running back Nick Whitworth, who ran for 134 yards on
25 carries last week, was named a Big Sky player of the week.
Teammate DeRonn Finley, who had an 85-yard punt return for a
touchdown, also was honored.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that Idaho State has lost 10 consecutive road
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take a look at the program, I don't know if I'd say
it's mental,'' ISU coach Larry Lewis said. ``We've had a losing
streak in a lot of areas. We're just trying to string a number of
wins together, whether it's home or away. We want to take the
momentum from our wins at home and take it on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Amerson's status: Sophomore receiver Drew Amerson (right
knee) is probable for Saturday's game but it will be a game-time
decision. Amerson participated in drills full speed Thursday but
hasn't taken hits.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Harmon Forecast: CSUN 20, Idaho State 10.
</P>
<P>
   __ Penalty reduction: Kearin's focus on penalties has paid off.
Last year, CSUN was the most penalized team in the Big Sky. This
season, it's the !ital!least penalized team with 94 total yards in
three games.
</P>
<P>
   __ Keeping pace: CSUN punter Ethan Beck _ a preseason
All-American _ is having solid back-to-back seasons. He's ranked
fifth in Division I-AA punting with a 43.6 yards-per punt average.
</P>
<P>
   A Jacksonville Jaguars scout was at Thursday's practice looking
at him and liked what he saw. He was also impressed with
quarterback Marcus Brady.
</P>
<P>
   __ Felix quits: Senior receiver Ryan Felix _ a transfer from
Utah State _ has quit the team for personal reasons, according to
Kearin. Felix had no receptions this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Just a joke: Former CSUN athletic director Paul Bubb played a
joke on Kearin.
</P>
<P>
   Bubb read on the Internet that CSUN is willing to fill UCLA's
open date for the 2002 season opener. He had a CSUN secretary tell
Kearin that UCLA athletic director Pete Dalis had left a telephone
message for him. Kearin, very skeptical, later found out Bubb was
behind the joke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
