<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNINSURED-DECREASE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FEWER UNINSURED IN U.S., CENSUS SHOWS  &HT;     By LOUIS FREEDBERG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time in a decade, the number of
people without health insurance declined significantly last year,
in part because employers in a tight labor market have been forced
to offer coverage to attract and retain workers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of uninsured remains extremely high _ 42.6
million in 1999 _ that figure represented a decline of 1.7 million
from 1998, according to a report released Thursday by the U.S.
Census Bureau. The number of uninsured children declined to 10
million, a decline of 1 million from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that our nation's strong economic growth has
made it possible for more businesses to offer health care benefits
to their workers,'' said Kate Sullivan, director of health care
policy for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the Census Bureau found that the number of people
covered by insurance offered by their employers jumped by 1.2
million between 1998 and 1999, by far the biggest increase in a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   The census figures were met with some relief by health
officials, who have been grappling with the conundrum that during
the biggest economic boom in U.S. history, the number of people
without health coverage continued to climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a reason to be cautiously optimistic that that we may
have turned the corner,'' said Glen Rosselli, undersecretary of
California's Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, there were 33 million uninsured people. By 1998, that
number had risen to 44 million. One of the reasons for the increase
was that about 3 million people on Medicaid, the government health
program for the poor, dropped off the Medicaid rolls between 1994
and 1998, apparently as a result of welfare reforms at a state and
national level. The number of people on individual insurance plans
also dropped, mainly in response to rising premiums.
</P>
<P>
   What seems to be happening now is that the declines in
enrollments in Medicaid and private insurance programs have
steadied, while employers are offering more coverage. The federally
subsidized Child Health Insurance Program has also contributed to
the decline in uninsured children.
</P>
<P>
   California accounts for by far the largest proportion of
uninsured in the nation. According to the U.S. Census Bureau, the
number of uninsured people in California dropped from 7.4 million
in 1998 to 6.9 million in 1999. The number of uninsured children
declined from 1.9 to 1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   But many health experts said it is still worrisome that the
nation's booming economy has left millions of people stranded
without coverage, especially those in the lowest-paid jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that even with a good economy and employers competing
for workers, and increased government efforts to enroll children,
these have not been sufficient to make a real dent in the number of
uninsured,'' said Diane Rowland, executive director of the Kaiser
Commission on Medicaid and the Uninsured. ``We will need bigger and
broader interventions to make insurance affordable to millions of
Americans without coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent Kaiser survey showed that the proportion of businesses
with less than 200 workers offering health coverage jumped from 54
percent in 1998 to 67 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   But in California, only 48 percent of businesses offer health
insurance, compared with 61 percent nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers for the Service Employees International Union, which
has successfully organized some of the state's lowest-paid workers,
say employers are still reluctant to offer comprehensive health
coverage, and will only do so if they are forced to do so &LR;   &LR; by
strike action or other pressures. In the union's recent campaign to
organize janitors in Southern California, employers wanted to strip
workers of their existing health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has there been a sea change in employer's attitudes or desires
to provide comprehensive family health coverage to low-wage service
workers?'' asked Paul Kumar, political director of SEIU Local 250,
which represents 50,000 health workers in Northern California.
``The answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there is concern about what will happen when the
current economic boom ends. ``All we need is a downturn in the
economy, and we could see the numbers skyrocket again,'' said
Kaiser's Rowland.
</P>
</TEXT>
