</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-PILL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA APPROVES ABORTION PILL FOR SALE IN U.S.
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SABIN RUSSELL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  In an election-year blow to abortion opponents, the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration Thursday granted long-sought marketing
approval for mifepristone _ the French abortion pill known as
RU-486.
<P>
   Available in France since 1989, the drug makes available a
method of abortion that can be conducted in the privacy of a
woman's home. It is expected to eventually replace up to one-third
of the 1.4 million surgical abortions performed each year in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those who choose to have an early termination of their
pregnancy, this is a reasonable medical alternative,'' said FDA
Commissioner Jane Henney.
</P>
<P>
   The approval caps a 12-year effort by abortion rights advocates
to bring RU-486 to the United States following its approval in
France. That effort was hindered first by hostile Republican
administrations, then by difficulties in finding a willing
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Citing concerns about violence by anti-abortion extremists,
Henney took the unprecedented step of shielding the location of the
manufacturing plant, which is widely reported to be in China.
</P>
<P>
   The drug will be sold under the trade name Mifeprex by Danco
Laboratories LLC, a New York firm created by abortion rights
advocates for the sole purpose of bringing RU-486 to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Danco executives said Thursday that the abortion pills will be
ready for shipment to qualifying physicians within a month, but
abortion clinic operators do not expect Mifeprex to be widely
available until early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The imminent arrival of the drug in the United States has
invigorated abortion rights advocates, who had been eagerly
anticipating it since the early days of the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``At long last, science trumps anti-abortion politics and
medical McCarthyism,'' said Eleanor Smeal of the Feminist Majority
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion foes quickly denounced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before has the FDA approved a drug intended to kill
people,'' said Oklahoma Republican Tom Coburn, a physician from
Muskogee and vice chairman of the powerful House Commerce Health
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Coming only six weeks before the presidential election, the FDA
decision may reignite passions over the contentious abortion issue.
Although Democrat Al Gore supports abortion rights and Republican
George W. Bush does not, the subject has not been high on either
candidate's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Bush declared that the FDA decision was ``wrong'' and
that he feared it would make abortions in the United States more
common. ``As president,'' he said, ``I will work to build a culture
that respects life.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Cirmo, spokeswoman for the Family Research Council, a
Washington D.C.-based group opposed to abortion, vowed to make the
FDA ruling an election issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who respect life should get out there and express their
views,'' she said. ``A new president coming in will not only be
able to put a new Supreme Court on the bench, but will appoint a
new FDA commissioner who will have an ability to impact this
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said there could be some grounds
to challenge the approval. ``It appears the president does not have
the authority to order drugs off the market, but as president, he
would want a careful review to make sure the FDA considered all the
risks and didn't do this as a result of political pressure from the
White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, on the other hand, supported the FDA move and denied that
the decision was timed for the election. ``Today's decision is not
about politics, but the health and safety of American women and a
woman's fundamental right to choose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA decision sets several strict limits on the distribution
of mifepristone. It can only be dispensed at doctor's offices and
clinics where physicians are trained to recognize tubal pregnancies
_ a dangerous condition for which RU-486 would not be prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is also requiring that physicians who dispense the
abortion pill also be able to provide a surgical abortion _ or be
able to refer a woman to such a provider _ in the 5 percent to 8
percent of cases where the pill does not work.
</P>
<P>
   Taken in a two-drug regimen by women up to seven weeks pregnant,
the abortion pill will induce a miscarriage that most women will
experience in the privacy of their home as a week or more of
heavier-than-usual menstrual bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; 3 Doctors' Visits
</P>
<P>
   Women who seek an abortion using the pills must visit their
doctor or clinic three times, instead of the single visit required
for a surgical abortion. On their first visit, they will get a
three-pill dosage of mifepristone. The drug blocks progesterone, a
hormone that is essential for maintaining a healthy pregnancy. Two
days later, they receive a second pill that induces uterine
contractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a few hours, there are cramps and bleeding,'' said Dr.
Richard Fischer, associate medical director of Planned Parenthood
Golden Gate. ``There is typically heavy bleeding for an hour or
two, a bit heavier than a heavy period for most women. She may pass
some small blood clots.'' According to the FDA, bleeding and
spotting may continue for nine to sixteen days.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks, a third visit is required to confirm that the
abortion has been completed. In about 1-in-20 cases, tissue remains
in the uterus, and the patient must be referred to a doctor who can
complete the surgical abortion _ usually by vacuum aspiration of
the remaining tissue in the uterus.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said the embryo at seven weeks is so small that most
women would be unable to identify it. ``In surgical abortions at
this time, we see placental tissue and a gestational sac. We
virtually never see an embryo,'' he said. ``For most women, using
the pill is the same as having a miscarriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement with Danco and the Planned Parenthood
Federation of America, the pill will be made available to clinics
at a price that will allow the clinics to charge no more than they
do for surgical abortions. At Planned Parenthood Golden Gate,
patients who have abortions in the first trimester of pregnancy are
charged $400, according to Dian Harrison, president and chief
executive of the Bay Area clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said it was unfortunate that it has taken so long for
the pill to be approved in the United States. ``Women in countries
around the world have used this safely for more than a decade,''
she said. ``Even though it has taken so long, we are pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Developed by researchers at French pharmaceutical manufacturer
Roussel Uclaf in 1980, the pill known as RU-486 was tested in both
the United States and France. The French Ministry of Health
approved the pill for marketing in 1988, but at the same time the
Bush administration barred its importation into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Roussel Uclaf in May 1994 donated marketing rights to the
Population Council, a New York based nonprofit that primarily
worked on family planning issues in underdeveloped nations, which
agreed to find a U.S. manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   During the subsequent six years, the Population Council was
criticized for taking too long to get the drug through the approval
process. Part of the difficulty, executives there concede, was
finding a manufacturer willing to withstand the wrath of
anti-abortion opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Danco's efforts to win approval to market mifepristone were
aided by a $10 million loan from the David and Lucile Packard
Foundation, the Los Altos philanthropy funded by the founder of
electronics pioneer Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exciting day for us. The whole foundation is
pleased that this pill is finally available in this country,'' said
Sarah Clark, director of population programs.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle Staff Writer Carla Marinucci and Chronicle wire
services contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
