r a BC-FRAUD-SOFTWARE-SFCHRO     09-29 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAUD-SOFTWARE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FEDS CHARGE SOFTWARE EXECS IN $9 BILLION SCAM  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In one of the nation's biggest cases of
financial fraud, federal prosecutors in San Francisco Thursday
accused two former software executives of orchestrating a bogus
accounting scheme that cost investors $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The onetime executives of medical softwaremaker HBO &AMP; Co., which
merged last year with San Francisco's McKesson Corp., were charged
with falsifying company ledgers to boost HBOC's profits.
</P>
<P>
   When the alleged scheme was revealed just three months after the
merger, the combined firm's stock plunged nearly 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, officials at the U.S. attorney's office and the
Securities and Exchange Commission told The Chronicle that separate
fraud investigations are focusing on other Bay Area firms,
including companies in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Indictments were unsealed Thursday charging Jay Gilbertson, 40,
and Albert Bergonzi, 50, with 17 counts of securities fraud,
conspiracy, mail fraud and wire fraud related to what investigators
termed ``cooking of books'' at HBOC.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson and Bergonzi were HBOC's co-presidents and co-chief
operating officers prior to the merger. Gilbertson also served as
the company's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is a poster child for the devastating effect of
financial fraud by corporate management,'' said U.S. Attorney
Robert Mueller. ``McKesson HBOC shareholders lost $9 billion in a
single day as a result of the defendants' actions.''
</P>
<P>
   McKesson HBOC is North America's leading distributor of
pharmaceuticals and health care products and a world leader in
medical information systems and technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``These indictments represent one of the largest financial
crimes ever investigated by the FBI,'' said Bruce Gebhardt, who
oversees the FBI's San Francisco office.
</P>
<P>
   According to authorities, Gilbertson, Bergonzi and a third
suspect, Dominick DeRosa, conspired beginning in late 1997 to boost
HBOC's share price by fraudulently exaggerating the company's
financial results.
</P>
<P>
   DeRosa, who served as HBOC's vice president of enterprise sales,
has since settled with the SEC and agreed to pay more than $400,000
in restitution and fines. He is cooperating with investigators in
their case against the former co-presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Securities regulators said Gilbertson and Bergonzi coordinated
HBOC's efforts to manipulate accounting records by concealing and
back-dating various contracts and by altering ledgers to inflate
the company's net income.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew what they were doing was wrong,'' said Helane
Morrison, district administrator for the SEC's San Francisco
office. ``They succumbed to the pressures of the marketplace and
lined their own pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said that prior to the alleged accounting fraud being
revealed, Gilbertson sold off $7 million worth of HBOC shares and
Bergonzi unloaded $4 million worth of the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were misled when HBOC and, later, McKesson HBOC
reported financial results based on the bogus accounting, the SEC
said.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged scheme finally came to light when company auditors
reported to McKesson HBOC's board of directors that something was
seriously wrong with the books.
</P>
<P>
   An outside accounting firm was brought in to investigate, and
McKesson HBOC announced on April 28, 1999, that it would be forced
to restate several years' worth of earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, the company's stock tumbled to $34.50 from a high
of almost $66 a share.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson HBOC has yet to recover. The company's stock closed
Thursday up 38 cents at $30.50.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kurtz, a spokesman for McKesson HBOC, declined to comment
on the indictments of Gilbertson and Bergonzi. ``These are not
people who work here anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson left HBOC prior to the merger, in November 1998,
Kurtz said. Bergonzi, who had served as head of information
technology for the merged company, was fired in June 1999, along
with three other former HBOC executives.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz said McKesson HBOC has cooperated ``fully and completely''
with federal investigators since the alleged fraud was revealed.
</P>
<P>
   While he was unable to say whether McKesson executives harbored
resentment over having purchased a company that was allegedly
cooking its books, Kurtz acknowledged that the alleged fraud
clearly boosted HBOC's approximately $12 billion purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We overpaid,'' he said. ``We certainly did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller, the U.S. attorney, said Gilbertson and Bergonzi face up
to 10 years in prison and a fine of $1 million if found guilty of
violating securities fraud laws.
</P>
<P>
   Each count of conspiracy, mail fraud and wire fraud carries a
maximum penalty of five years in prison and a fine of $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When corporate managers engage in financial accounting fraud,
they must be held accountable,'' Mueller said. ``We cannot and will
not tolerate the deliberate cooking of books.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the investigation of McKesson HBOC is continuing
but declined to say whether additional indictments are expected.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the SEC filed charges against three former
executives of Sunnyvale softwaremaker Cylink Corp. alleging that
they, too, had fiddled with company ledgers to exaggerate financial
performance.
</P>
<P>
   A Chronicle investigation of Silicon Valley financial practices
earlier this year suggested that securities regulators have been
lax in uncovering fraud in the tech industry. However, the SEC's
Morrison said this was not an accurate characterization of her
agency's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking hard at financial fraud in Silicon Valley,'' she
said. ``Where we find it, we're going to prosecute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the SEC and U.S. attorney's office declined to
specify which Bay Area companies are now under scrutiny by federal
authorities for alleged fraud.
</P>
<P>
   They only confirmed that such investigations are under way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
