<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAVERS NO LONGER EASY PREY FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Paul Hackett was an assistant coach at USC nearly
25 years ago. Could he have foreseen that in 2000, as the Trojans'
head coach, he would be so worried about playing perennial doormat
Oregon State?
</P>
<P>
   ``No. I wouldn't have thought that,'' Hackett said Thursday as
his team concluded practice. ``I'd think (Oregon State) will be
down. But no, they're not. Football's changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody made the statement that when I was here before, we
had seven or eight wins in the summer, and then it was a matter of
winning three or four games. I think it's changed dramatically in
20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Keeping it loud: As promised, USC broke out the loudspeakers
for Thursday's practice, with something that was supposed to
resemble crowd noise blaring from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never experienced that before,'' tight end Alex Holmes said.
``It's not really sound. It's more like screeching. It
discombobulates you.''
</P>
<P>
   USC has never won a game for which it practiced with
loudspeakers in the past two years. Instead, the Trojans lost to
such teams as Oregon, Arizona, Notre Dame and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted them to be conscious about it,'' Hackett said.
``I don't want anybody to be surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   __ And then there were two: Holmes, who attended
Harvard-Westlake, and wide receiver Keary Colbert are the only two
freshmen who will play this season, something even Holmes didn't
expect before the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' he said. ``We came in with what we thought was
one of the best recruiting classes in the country. We had
(offensive lineman) Joe McGuire, (strong safety) Matt Grootegoed.
It just didn't work out. But Keary and I are really excited.''
</P>
<P>
   As the result of injuries and illness, McGuire and Grootegoed
are redshirting. Quarterback Matt Cassel of Chatsworth will make
the trip, but only as a precautionary measure in case quarterbacks
Carson Palmer and Mike Van Raaphorst are injured. He is scheduled
to redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   __ Left off the trip: USC is limited to taking 60 players to
Corvallis, Ore. Among those not making the trip are offensive
linemen Phillip Eaves and Nate Steinbacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've had to do that,'' Hackett said.
``It's always hard for me, because so many people contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   When USC goes into its goal-line offense, redshirt freshman
Jacob Rogers will fill in for Faaesea Mailo at fullback. At one
time, Eaves and Steinbacher were candidates for that job.
</P>
<P>
   __ Running with the ball: Assistant coach Kennedy Pola said one
reason tailback Sultan McCullough has fumbled twice in the first
three games is McCullough is used to running track, in which he
doesn't have to hold a football.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been running track for so long, he's a form runner, and
now he has to run with a ball under his arm,'' Pola said. ``As many
carries as he has, he's going to have some (fumbles).''
</P>
<P>
   Pola, a former USC player, remembers watching Marcus Allen work
out on the school's track in an effort to avoid fumbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran around the track with a football in his hand,'' Pola
said. ``It has to become a habit and it will for Sultan.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Two snappers? Hackett said he wasn't sure whether Zeke Moreno
or Norm Katnik would handle the snaps on punts. Moreno has been the
regular snapper, but Katnik replaced him last week so he could
rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as anything it's how much Zeke is playing,'' Hackett
said. ``It's not the snapping, it's the running down the field that
does it to you.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Weather update: The latest forecast for Corvallis called for
thunderstorms and a temperature of 71 degrees Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
