<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-BILL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA BILL ALLOWING DNA TESTING TO EXONERATE PRISONERS  SIGNED
INTO LAW
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ERIN HALLISSY and CHARLIE GOODYEAR 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hailed as the most important criminal justice legislation of the
year, a bill that will allow DNA testing to exonerate prisoners who
claim they were wrongly convicted was signed into law Thursday by
Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also approved DNA legislation that could help law
enforcement link more criminals to unsolved cases and set up a DNA
data bank for relatives of missing children. A bill that removes
the six-year statute of limitations in rape cases with DNA evidence
will also become law because it was tied to the bills signed
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new laws expand the use of DNA evidence so that law
enforcement can catch criminals as well as help locate missing
persons,'' said Attorney General Bill Lockyer, who has pushed for
more extensive use of genetic testing, which has been called the
most important forensic breakthrough since fingerprinting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new laws also provide an important framework by which
innocent persons who have been wrongly convicted may use new
scientific techniques to prove their innocence, while preventing
the guilty from manipulating procedures to delay or thwart the
administration of justice,'' Lockyer said.
</P>
<P>
   California becomes just the third state in the country to allow
inmates postconviction DNA testing of evidence. New York and
Illinois have similar statutes. The bill's author, Senate President
Pro Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco, called it ``probably the best
bill in the nation'' in allowing DNA testing for prisoners claiming
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a proud day for justice in the state of California,''
Burton said. ``This is very, very significant, far-reaching
legislation, and I'm pleased to have been a part of it and pleased
that the governor saw fit to sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendocino County Public Defender Jeff Thoma, a nationally
recognized expert on DNA who helped negotiate the final version of
the Burton bill, said postconviction testing in California will
have immediate tangible results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect that we will have at least 25 to 50 cases within the
first year come before different courts in the state in which
judges believe there is a genuine reason for postconviction DNA
testing,'' Thoma said. ``Sometimes you're talking about a life as
opposed to a test that costs less than $1,000. It seems like a
no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of DNABILLS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The Burton bill, which was supported by a broad coalition that
included prosecutors and victims' groups, was also welcomed by the
state chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly our view that this is probably the most
important criminal justice bill of the year,'' said ACLU
legislative director Francisco Lobaco. ``The last thing you want to
see is innocent people being incarcerated in prison, and that has
been the reality, as has been shown throughout the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Another bill that Lockyer backed, sponsored by Assemblyman Mike
Machado, D-Linden, will allow law enforcement to use DNA to solve
serial crimes. Previously, only samples from convicted felons could
be included in the state Justice Department's DNA data bank in
Berkeley. Under Machado's bill, a DNA sample can be taken from a
suspect who is charged with a crime and compared to other unsolved
cases.
</P>
<P>
   The bill could help make the DNA data bank more successful in
cracking cases. Lockyer's top priority this year has been to
improve the DNA lab. The Chronicle reported last year that the
lab's attempts to build a comprehensive data bank of convicted
murderers, rapists and other felons were mired in huge backlogs.
</P>
<P>
   The same lab will handle the new DNA data bank of relatives of
missing children. The legislation by Sen. Jackie Speier,
D-Hillsborough, will impose a $2 fee on death certificates,
providing $3 million a year for five years to pay for the data
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Samples voluntarily given by family members will be matched with
DNA taken from 2,000 unidentified remains in county morgues around
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Swartz, whose then 7-year-old daughter Amber disappeared
from her Pinole home in 1988, provided her own DNA sample for the
missing persons database earlier this month and welcomed the
governor's decision to sign Speier's bill into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although matching the missing to the unidentified dead is not
something most parents would want to hear, it's better to know
rather than to continue on not knowing,'' Swartz said. ``This bill
will not only answer the question for thousands of parents in
California, but potentially for parents in other states as well. It
just opens up the doors to so many possibilities of closure.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of DNABILLS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Speier said that along with providing closure for families, the
system could also provide law enforcement with new leads in solving
missing persons cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a remarkable and very important step forward in
addressing something we should have addressed a long time ago,''
Speier said. ``It's really unconscionable that we've had the
remains of 2,000 people, 150 of which we know are children, sitting
in coroner's offices for years unidentified.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
