<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6078 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-OPEC-TRADE-SFCHRON &LR;      09-29 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-TRADE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEC DEMANDS CONCESSIONS FROM WEST ON AID AND TRADE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  CARACAS _ Making a grab for the moral high ground in their
dispute with industrial nations over high fuel prices, the world's
main oil producers announced Thursday that they will use their
clout to demand that the West give aid and trade concessions to
poor nations.
<P>
   Ending a two-day summit, the leaders of the 11-nation
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries downplayed their
long-bitter divisions and declared a new, united front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have triumphed, we have achieved our objectives,''
Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez said in the conference's closing
speech. ``We have found the road again, we have relaunched OPEC on
the world stage.''
</P>
<P>
   A group long known more for its avid pursuit of wealth than for
social conscience, OPEC urged in its closing declaration that
``industrialized countries recognize that the biggest environmental
tragedy facing the globe is human poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the group took few concrete steps to implement social
goals. The declaration, which contained 20 resolutions, repeated a
series of platitudes and mild exhortations that did not commit OPEC
leaders to any major initiative beyond meeting again in five years.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration urged more coordination within OPEC, strongly
asserted its members' right to a fair price for their oil and
criticized consumer countries' high taxes on oil products.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also agreed to study proposals for an OPEC bank,
university and research and development institute _ steps that, if
implemented, would give substance to the group's claim to be acting
on behalf of developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   But simply having the feuding leaders _ representing rivalries
as bloody as Iraq and Kuwait or as religiously charged as Iran and
Saudi Arabia _ sign the same piece of paper was a great
achievement. The summit was OPEC's first since 1975 to be attended
by heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   And by making a big show of unity and lending their collective
economic weight to the fight against economic globalization _ which
speaker after speaker condemned as cruel and unjust - the assembled
leaders made clear their belief that OPEC is now a coherent,
powerful force to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, who chaired the summit, noted in a closing press
conference that French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and other
leaders of G-7 industrial nations have phoned him and sent messages
in recent days, asking for a summit meeting with OPEC to discuss
high fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez and the other leaders made clear that they will
insist on concessions on matters unrelated to oil _ such as
forgiving poor nations' debts. The declaration called for ``a
substantive effort for debt reduction initiatives by the
international donor community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we speak with the heads of state, we will not just talk
about oil prices,'' Chavez said. ``This is just one small point
among an infinite number of issues we need to discuss, such as debt
levels, technology transfer, oil price speculation and the
excessively high taxes levied by consumer countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez indicated that OPEC may become a major thorn on
environmental matters, too _ demanding fuel-tax cuts and loosening
of environmental fuel-content rules, which OPEC blames for
disrupting supply and raising prices.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the sort of pressure a united OPEC may wield
against the West _ and the complex political trouble it might cause
the White House _ Chavez cited Venezuela's victory in a 1996 ruling
by the World Trade Organization against the United States. Under
the ruling, U.S. gasoline-content laws were deemed to discriminate
against foreign gasoline _ mainly Venezuelan _ and the
Environmental Protection Organization was obliged to revise the
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists used the case as ammunition against the WTO
during chaotic protests at the organization's summit meeting in
Seattle last December.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC officials also have complained about California's gasoline
standards, blaming them for distribution bottlenecks because they
are stricter than the federal norm.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia, OPEC's largest producer of oil, sought to temper
the tone struck in the summit declaration by advocating prudence in
discussions with industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   Crown Prince Abdullah caused a minor flurry in international oil
markets by saying late Wednesday night that his government ``is
ready to supply whatever amount necessary to stabilize the world
market.'' In response, the benchmark crude price fell $1.12
Thursday to $30.34 a barrel, the lowest since Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   But Abdullah's comment was merely a restatement of oft-expressed
Saudi policy.
</P>
<P>
   The summit declaration noted that taxes comprise the bulk of oil
prices in Western nations and urged those countries to reduce them
``for the benefit of the consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, the United States will release 1 million barrels of
oil a day from its strategic reserve, in an attempt to drive down
prices, while OPEC will produce 800,000 more barrels a day in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez _ who frequently praised Abdullah throughout the summit _
appeared to have struck a personal bond with the prince, who is
next in line to the Saudi throne. In fact, Chavez seemed to have
made friends with nearly all the visiting heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main benefits of this summit has been simply to get
to know all the other heads of state closely, to develop a personal
rapport,'' Chavez said. ``We now can simply pick up the phone and
call each other to discuss things.''
</P>
<P>
   The only permanently stone-cold face was that of Iraqi Vice
President Taha Yassin Ramadan, whose demand for a summit
condemnation of the U.N. oil sanctions against his country was
rebuffed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
