<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GIANTS' ANSWER BLOWIN' IN THE WIND  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If the Giants are serious about winning the
World Series (and the playoffs that lead up to it), and I think
they are, I have some important advice.
</P>
<P>
   Flags.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Giants could cruise to the world title merely on the
strength of their current level of hitting and pitching. But why
not cover all your bases, so to speak?
</P>
<P>
   My feng shui expert recommends that the Giants install eight
flagpoles someplace behind center field, and fly eight flags like
the Giants' banners that currently fly from poles along the
Embarcadero.
</P>
<P>
   Flags promote good chi, center field is a strong chi power area,
and eight is a number associated with prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Do not dismiss my expert, Deborah Gee. When the Giants' ballpark
was nearing completion, Deborah and I toured the park so she could
assess the feng shui.
</P>
<P>
   Feng shui (pronounced fung shway) is the ancient Chinese art of
orderly arrangement of elements. Good feng shui promotes a positive
flow of chi (life force) in a room or building, and therefore in
the people.
</P>
<P>
   It was breakthrough research. Nobody had ever feng shui'd a
ballpark. I figured that if the Giants got their chi flowing, the
champagne wouldn't be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Gee gave the new ballpark a big thumbs-up. The green seats, the
view of the water and mountains, Willie Mays Plaza, the clock
towers _ all dandy chi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team will do much better in this location,'' Gee said.
</P>
<P>
   In her assessment (and my words), Candlestick Park's feng shui
couldn't carry Pac Bell Park's feng shui's jock.
</P>
<P>
   How accurate was Gee's reading? Go check the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to the Giants to add the eight flagpoles.
</P>
<P>
   Gee was on the money before, and as they say in baseball, you
should dance with the feng shui expert that brung you.
</P>
<P>
   DID YOU watch the big Greco-Roman wrestling upset at the
Olympics on Wednesday night? Unknown Wyoming farm boy (Farms in
Wyoming? Who knew?) beats Russian superstar for gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God for TV announcers, because I would have had no idea
who won. I didn't even know which part was Greco and which was
Roman.
</P>
<P>
   This is an esoteric sport. Even this monumental U.S. upset did
not inspire me to grab the phone and order season tickets. It was
like watching midgets move a piano, but without the comedic
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Confession: I was sort of rooting for the Russian. Undefeated
his whole  &UR; life &LR; , a great warrior who reads poetry, and this was
his last match.
</P>
<P>
   Russian athletes used to be such great evil villains, but now
they tend to be sympathetic, tragic characters from a crumbling
country.
</P>
<P>
   I root more for the stories than along national lines. I root
for the white guy sprinter, the black guy swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty sure the Russian wrestler got screwed somehow. The
judges didn't give him full credit for his triple axel or
something.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the great things about the Olympics. We all become
instant experts, making bold judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Diving judges: Blind as fruit bats. ... USA men's basketball
``dream team'': Room-Service All-Stars. ... Cathy Freeman: Babe.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I worry. That monstrous Olympic flame burning over the
stadium? That's got global warming written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION POLICE: San Marino is an old-money suburb of Los
Angeles. The money is so old that George Washington has pimples.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Willie saw a San Marino Police Officers Assn. ad in the
San Marino paper, an opinion poll. One question was, ``In the
summer months, when temperatures are in the 90s and 100s, would you
be willing for your police officers to wear a uniform of a polo
shirt and shorts?''
</P>
<P>
   And if it gets chilly, they could drape a sweater over their
shoulders?
</P>
<P>
   I worry that the idea will get the OK and the community will be
polarized into two warring shirt-logo factions: little polo-player
and little alligator.
</P>
<P>
   THE ELEVATOR at the Oakland Military Examining and Processing
Station _ which, I believe, is where they conduct the autopsies on
UFO aliens _ got stuck between floors.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jim Eldred, one of the passengers, picked up the emergency
telephone and found himself talking to a woman in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Her question: ``Just where, exactly, is Oakland.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the globalization of all phone services. In the old days
you would call directory assistance (then Information) for the
number of a restaurant and the operator would tout the joint's
onion rings.
</P>
<P>
   Now she or he says, ``San Francisco? What state is that a member
of?''
</P>
<P>
   So if Dr. Eldred's surgery team is still waiting for him, please
check the elevator shaft. He'll be glad to hear from you.
</P>
<P>
   SIZE COMMUNITY, that's the phrase one S.F. supervisorial
candidate used in reference to (I assume) people who transcend
petit-ness or svelte-ivity.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Elliott writes, ``The really weird thing is how automatic
it has become to call any group a `community,' as though they all
hang out together just because they have something in common.
Nobody gets to be an individual anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   A warm welcome, Beth, to the individuality-seeker community. You
may choose from among a wide variety of residence-card styles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
