<SLUG> BC-DRIVERS-COST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. TOPS IN CAR COSTS
</HEADLINE>
bc-DRIVERS-COST-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DANA BARTHOLOMEW 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES Los Angeles drivers pay more to motor their sedans
than drivers in any other city in the nation because of high fuel,
insurance and fix-it costs, according to a consultant's report. But
at least we don't live in Sioux Falls, S.D., where the study says
motorists have the lowest vehicle expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles ranks as the most expensive city in the country to
drive -- $9,254 a year -- while Sioux Falls ranks as the least
costly at $6,171, according to the study released Thursday by
Runzheimer International, a consulting firm for government and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But many Angelenos said they'd pay whatever it takes to power
their automobiles here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the car,'' said Michael Reyes, 22, of Woodland Hills, a
suburb 25 miles northwest of Los Angeles. ``That's why I got it,''
he said, speakers blaring from his 2000 Acura Integra. ``If I can
afford it, I'll drive it.''
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive areas to drive include Los Angeles,
Philadelphia, Providence, R.I.; Bridgeport, Conn.; and Detroit. The
least expensive areas include Sioux Falls; Des Moines, Iowa; Eau
Claire, Wis.; and Bismarck, N.D.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, it costs a 25-year-old man with a clean driving
record $2,800 to drive a 2000 Ford Taurus, as compared with $700 in
Sioux Falls, the study says.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, miscellaneous car taxes cost $352, but nothing
in South Dakota; and $56 vs. $47 in registration fees, said Peter
Packer, spokesman for Runzheimer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles is one of the most expensive cities in America,''
Packer said. ``Los Angeles has always been one of the most
expensive places to own a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks in South Dakota were elated to be ranked last for less
cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great. Geez. It's perfect, that's great,'' said Jeff From,
sales manager for Sioux Falls Ford, whose family leases a Taurus.
``We don't want everybody to know because we don't want everybody
moving out here.''
</P>
<P>
   There, a 2000 Ford Taurus driver will spend $3,083 less to
operate a car through rain and snow than a driver in the same-model
car cruising sunny Ventura Boulevard in the San Fernando Valley
region of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   For its study, the Rochester, Wis.-based company compared auto
insurance rates, fuel prices, the cost of oil, tires, maintenance,
license and registration fees, and vehicle depreciation in 105
cities.
</P>
<P>
   For its vehicle, analysts selected a fully loaded 2000 Ford
Taurus SE with a 3.0 liter, six-cylinder engine and automatic
transmission driven within 50 miles of any city. Costs are based on
four-year trade-in with 60,000 miles on the odometer.
</P>
<P>
   Critics attacked the report as failing to factor in bad weather
-- which adds rust, dings and the price of snow tires to many cars.
If the study considered those things, the cost of driving in South
Dakota and other snow-belt cities would be closer to what it costs
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these surveys normally don't take in consideration are
regional differences,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist for the
Los Angeles County Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``So these things make good headlines, but I think everybody
shrugs and says, So what?''
</P>
<P>
   Drive a Taurus in L.A. and pay 4.18 cents a mile, or go to Sioux
Falls and shell out 3.44 cents, Packer said. ``The least expensive
places are locations in the Midwest of the United States, the most
expensive tend to be on the East and West Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high cost of driving, many Angelenos wouldn't trade
their hometown for anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothin' to do there (Sioux Falls),'' said Canoga Park
resident Nefi Vargas, 23, his Ford Focus fresh with a new dealer
plate. ``Just to be here, I wouldn't mind paying $3,000 more.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Salvadore Villegas, 48, of Woodland Hills, who wasn't
surprised by the report: ``In Los Angeles the weather is the best
in the country. I love California.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff From of Sioux Falls had other things to say about his
city, with its population of about 128,000 residents -- about a
third of South Dakota's population -- living in the middle of the
prairie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it's 80 degrees. The sun shines. A little breeze. It's
beautiful. The leaves are just starting to turn their autumn
colors, it's great.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got our winters ... you get into some cold days, at
50, 60 degrees below (zero) with wind chill -- it's common,'' From
said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
