<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-DEFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RESERVE TACKLES MAY HAVE BIG HOLE TO FILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If any player on the Texas roster would be
apprehensive about playing a game without defensive tackle Shaun
Rogers in the lineup, logic dictates it would be linemate Casey
Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   As the other All-America candidate in a tackle tandem described
by coach Mack Brown as ``the best I've ever coached or played
against,'' Hampton figures to receive extra attention from Oklahoma
State blockers if Rogers is sidelined, as expected, for the game
Saturday because of a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers has not practiced this week, creating a major personnel
shuffle along the defensive line as No. 13 Texas (2-1) prepares for
the 11 a.m. Big 12 conference opener at Royal-Memorial Stadium
against Oklahoma State (2-1). Rogers' absence would force the
Longhorns to try to contain Cowboys tailback Reggie White, the
nation's No. 11 rusher (127.3 yards per game), without a player who
has collected a team-high 34 tackles for losses in his past 16
games, including seven this season.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, said Hampton, who expressed confidence that redshirt
freshman Marcus Tubbs and other reserves can fill Rogers' size-18
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be fine,'' Hampton said. ``The other guys didn't start
out as defensive tackles, but they're real strong. They're just as
strong as Shaun and me, but they are still learning how to use that
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs (6-foot-4, 280 pounds), who began his college career as a
tight end, played 46 snaps in the 48-0 rout of Houston last week
and recorded two sacks. Tubbs is expected to start Saturday but is
50 pounds lighter than Rogers (6-4, 330) and was barely tested in
the running game by the pass-happy Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries and off-season attrition at the tackle
positions, Hampton is the only tackle with extensive game
experience who has practiced this week. Tubbs and Miguel McKay, a
former linebacker, are the likely candidates to replace Rogers.
Cole Pittman, a starter at defensive end in the first three games,
has shifted to tackle this week to provide depth. Pittman's move
opens a starting spot at end for freshman Kalen Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   The moves were made, Brown said, to maximize Texas' chances of
putting the clamps on an OSU ground attack that ranks 21st
nationally, at 191 yards per game. After three consecutive games
against passing teams, Oklahoma State represents the first major
test for a Texas run defense allowing only 1.3 yards per carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't stop the run this week, we've got no chance to
win,'' said Brown, whose tackle ranks were thinned during preseason
camp by three noteworthy deletions.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Curry, a fifth-year senior, quit the team. Heralded
signees Marcel Moses and Sonny Davis enrolled in junior college
after failing to reach NCAA academic-eligibility requirements. In
addition, reserves Stevie Lee (foot) and Ryan Haywood (shoulder)
went on the injured list before Rogers joined them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Longhorns remain confident that the newcomers prepared
to join Hampton in makeshift tackle tandems will be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tubbs is probably as good as most starting defensive tackles
in the country,'' middle linebacker De'Andre Lewis said. ``But
people don't see that because Casey and Shaun are so spectacular,
they make everyone else around them seem average by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout the off-season, we've talked about building quality
depth at every position on defense. Marcus stepped in and showed
some of that against Houston. We're confident in what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he was ``amazed'' by Tubbs' two-sack effort against
Houston in his first extended stretch of playing time at the
college level. But he cautioned that the challenge will be greater
this week against a more balanced offense.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs, cousin of San Francisco 49ers linebacker Winfred Tubbs,
said Hampton has ``helped me out a lot'' in recent workouts and
expressed optimism that he can be a productive fill-in for Rogers.
But not a true replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch Shaun, just about every play is like watching a
highlight reel,'' Tubbs said. ``I'm not at that level, but I think
I can do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches and teammates are counting on it. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
