r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLAN     09-29 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ GETS HALF HIS WISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ After leading the Los Angeles Lakers to
their first championship in more than a decade, Shaquille O'Neal
had just two requests of his employer this summer: a burly power
forward and a fat contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   He got the player _ old friend Horace Grant, acquired in a
recent trade. But O'Neal is still waiting for the four-year, $117
million extension that owner Jerry Buss all but promised him in
June.
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, a lighthearted and delirious moment when Buss
made that commitment. On the night of the championship, covered in
confetti, O'Neal bellowed, ``Extension! Extension!'' To which Buss
replied happily, ``Whatever you want, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   The owner had made earlier public statements to that effect, as
well, but O'Neal enters next week's training camp without an offer
in hand. And considering the Lakers' tightening purse strings,
there's no guarantee O'Neal will get the deal he wants.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he's not making it an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I disappointed? Why don't you talk to Leonard about that,''
O'Neal said, referring questions to agent Leonard Armato. ``I've
never really been one to talk about money in the paper. I have a
great job and I make good money.''
</P>
<P>
   But, O'Neal acknowledged, he expected to have the deal signed by
now.
</P>
<P>
   It could become a sore point down the road as the NBA's MVP
seeks what could be his last major contract. A four-year extension,
the maximum allowed, would take O'Neal through 2007 and his 35th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Armato said it's up to the Lakers to get it done, but he was
uncertain whether an offer was forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, I don't want to speculate,'' he said. ``Maybe
you ought to talk to the Lakers organization. . . . I think the way
to approach this is to ask the Lakers if it's a priority for them.
Because that's really the determining factor here. It's incumbent
on them if they'd like to extend to take the initiative to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be a more complicated matter than it seems. Although
the Lakers want to reward O'Neal, who at age 28 just had the
greatest season of his eight-year career, they are working under
some onerous financial constraints, albeit self-imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Buss has ordered management not to exceed the
threshold for the NBA's impending luxury tax. After this season,
teams with payrolls above the threshold _ expected to be $55
million to $57 million _ will have to pay a dollar-for-dollar tax.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' payroll is already in that range, and most players
are due raises for 2001-02. For perspective, consider that this
season the combined salaries of O'Neal and Kobe Bryant alone will
be almost $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   If O'Neal is granted the maximum allowable extension _ $24.75
million in 2003-04, with 12.5 percent increases thereafter _ he
would make a staggering $34 million in 2006-07, the final year of
the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, O'Neal is widely considered the best player in the
game now, and the last person to hold that mantle _ Chicago's
Michael Jordan _ made $33 million in his final season, 1997-98.
Since that time, however, the NBA has adopted a new labor deal that
includes a maximum starting salary of $14 million, as well as the
payroll tax.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers paid O'Neal what he's worth _ a concept no one
argues _ they might be hamstrung when it comes time to sign other
players in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers officials won't discuss finances publicly, but general
manager Mitch Kupchak insisted the club wants to keep O'Neal happy
and under contract until he retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can't say 'Los Angeles Lakers' unless you say
Shaquille O'Neal,'' Kupchak said. The contract extension ``is first
and foremost on our agenda. I think he wants to be here forever and
we want him here forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Lakers could have offered the extension anytime
since Aug. 1, Kupchak said the club was consumed with other
personnel matters, specifically attempts to find a power forward
and to trade Glen Rice. They eventually dealt Rice for Grant and
also signed free agent Isaiah Rider.
</P>
<P>
   Buss has also been out of town for most of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaquille and his representative recognized what needed to be
done during the summer. Thankfully, they chose to be a little
patient and let us take care of the immediate, which was to try to
improve our (roster),'' Kupchak said. ``I think there's enough
incentive for the Lakers and Shaquille to address the extension
issue and have some type of resolution in a timely fashion, and
hopefully one that's beneficial to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains unclear is whether the Lakers are able or willing
to offer O'Neal the maximum.
</P>
<P>
   But in an era when Portland owner Paul Allen and Dallas owner
Mark Cuban throw around millions without even blinking _ and scoff
at the salary cap and luxury tax _ O'Neal's supporters believe the
Lakers cannot afford to be tight with the checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does (the luxury tax) stop Paul Allen from stockpiling
players?'' Armato said. ``Where there's a will, there's a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Other sources point to the Lakers' estimated value ($282
million) and the team's net profits (about $50 million) and note
that success is closely tied to O'Neal's popularity and production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has to develop his own or her own strategy with
respect to spending,'' Armato said. ``Paul Allen has demonstrated
his strategy and there are other strategies that are certainly
possible. So the Lakers have to decide for themselves what it is
that's important to them and implement a strategy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
