<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6094 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-MANAGERS-TURNOVER     09-29 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MANAGERS-TURNOVER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMEROUS FIRINGS OF MANAGERS EXPECTED IN OFF-SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most amazing statistic this season isn't the number of
homers hit by Sammy Sosa, the number of runs driven in by Frank
Thomas, the number of hits by Darin Erstad, the number of
strikeouts by Randy Johnson or the number of runs given up by Pedro
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The most amazing statistic this season is this: 0.
</P>
<P>
   That's the number of mangers fired. Zero. Nil.
</P>
<P>
   There were times when the Reds' Jack McKeon, the Astros' Larry
Dierker and the Phillies' Terry Francona appeared in imminent
danger of losing their jobs, but they survived.
</P>
<P>
   How amazing is it? Assuming no owner or general manager drops an
unexpected ax in the next three days, it will be the first time
since 1942 that no one has been canned during the season.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a realization that not even the best manager can win
with a team full of mediocre players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't build the Empire State Building out of Legos,'' is
the way Phillies closer Jeff Brantley put it in defense of
Francona.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but don't expect the trend to continue. Consider it a
fluke.
</P>
<P>
   Pink slips are expected to be handed out early and often in the
off-season. Add a couple of managers who might depart for better
jobs, and a dozen or more jobs could come vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Managers in real danger of being canned are Francona, McKeon,
Dierker, the Pirates' Gene Lamont, the Diamondbacks' Buck
Showalter, the Dodgers' Davey Johnson and the Devil Rays' Larry
Rothschild.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox's Jimy Williams and the Blue Jays' Jim Fregosi are
on the bubble, as is Tom Kelly, the Twins' manager since 1986.
Mariners manager Lou Piniella and Giants manager Dusty Baker are in
the last year of their contracts, and also could be moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Lamont will begin the merry-go-round, perhaps as soon as Monday.
Pirates owner Kevin McClatchy recently told Lamont that the club
will not be renewing his contract, a conversation that was leaked
to the media to the disgust of the Pirates' players.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's totally unprofessional,'' outfielder Brian Giles said.
``To have two weeks left in the season and let it leak out that the
guy is not going to have his contract renewed is unprofessional and
it's embarrassing to the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Giles is having a fine season, but the players have only
themselves to blame for Lamont's dismissal. McClatchy envisioned a
90-victory season, but the Pirates are going to fall about 20
short.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to meet expectations also is likely to be the demise of
Francona, Dierker, Johnson, Showalter and Rothschild. There are
valid reasons why their teams didn't play well in almost every
case.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies expected to be contenders after signing Andy Ashby
and Mike Jackson, but Ashby didn't pitch well and Jackson didn't
pitch at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros fell from the top of the National League Central
because they traded away pitcher Mike Hampton and outfielder Carl
Everett, because second baseman Craig Biggio was injured and
because their pitchers didn't adjust to pitching in Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays thought their offense would make them a force in
the AL East after trading for Vinny Castilla and signing Greg
Vaughn, but they overlooked the fact that their pitching staff
wasn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks saw themselves as a World Series team,
especially after acquiring Curt Schilling in July, but floundered
down the stretch. Injuries and players who couldn't repeat career
years were the primary culprit, but never mind. The blame goes to
the manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know in my mind what the problems were this year, but what
good does it do to talk about it?'' Showalter said. ``That sounds
like an excuse, and there are no excuses in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   If Williams leaves Boston, it won't be because of Boston's
record. It will be because of his deteriorating relationship with
GM Dan Duquette. Williams said last weekend that Duquette should
fire him because he refused to back him when it came time to
discipline outfielder Carl Everett. The Red Sox might have been
tempted to do just that when it appeared that Alou was going to be
available, but Duquette and CEO John Harrington met with Williams
on Monday in an attempt to mend fences.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there have been reports that Mariners GM Pat Gillick and
Williams have an informal agreement in which Williams would manage
in Seattle next season. That job is expected to be open because
Piniella is expected to go home to Tampa to manage the Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins' job also could be open for the first time in 15
years, as new management is tempted to clean house. GM Terry Ryan
is in trouble, but Kelly is such an icon in the Twin Cities that
he's probably safe.
</P>
<P>
   Managers being hired and fired in the off-season is nothing new,
of course. It happened eight times last year. The fact that no one
got fired this summer only means the total will rise this
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're having a bad year, you think it's the manager's
fault,'' Dierker said. ``A new manager gives you a fresh start
mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just amazing that no impatient owner opted for that fresh
start during the season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
