<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6095 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-HOLTZ-GAMECOCKS-T     09-29 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLTZ-GAMECOCKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOU'S VOODOO: HOLTZ FIGHTS SOUTH CAROLINA `CHICKEN CURSE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This might be the perfect marriage of football coach and school.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Lou Holtz, an unmatched poor-mouthing sandbagger, who,
when he coached Notre Dame, always managed to portray Navy as a
national-championship contender the week the Midshipmen played the
Fighting Irish.
</P>
<P>
   And here's South Carolina, a school whose mascot should be a
black cat, a school whose fans believe their only luck will be bad
luck. South Carolina, home of the Chicken Curse. When Holtz,
college football's Mr. Rescue, went 0-11 last year, Gamecocks fans
shrugged and said, ``Heck, even Holtz can't win here.''
</P>
<P>
   The honeymoon apparently was simply delayed a year.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina, which entered the 2000 season with the nation's
longest losing streak (21 games) is 4-0 and ranked No. 23. The
Gamecocks will try to beat Alabama for the first time when they
play the Crimson Tide on Saturday in Tuscaloosa, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're 23, there's a lot of bad football teams, because I
don't think we're the 23rd-best football team in the country,''
said Holtz, whose team rallied to defeat Mississippi State, 23-19,
Saturday. ``I was disappointed in our play. We made some foolish
mistakes, we've got our longest injury list and our longest list
for bonehead play of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are looking up at South Carolina. The Gamecocks are
undefeated and Holtz is pessimistic. \Nsubheds:KINDER, GENTLER
LOSER Last season, Holtz's woe-is-us comments were on target. The
0-11 record is the worst in his career, which is in its 29th
season. The Gamecocks, who because of injuries and inefficiency
used six quarterbacks, were outscored 278-87.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if there was one thing that came out of last year it
is how distasteful losing is to me,'' Holtz said. ``We went through
a difficult time. Adversity either pulls you together or pushes you
apart, and I think it's pulled us together.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, Holtz endured the death of his mother. His wife
Beth's throat cancer flared again. His son Skip, the team's
offensive coordinator, was hospitalized for a week with a severe
gastric infection. A plane on which Holtz was to make a recruiting
trip crashed, killing the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Holtz wondered about his decision to get back into
coaching. He ended a 11-year career at Notre Dame on tarnished
terms in 1996. His sometimes-grating methods, his high standards,
his intense practices wore thin with players and those surrounding
the program. He made up his mind to change his methods when he got
back on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the mistake of listening to how tough and difficult I
was,'' said Holtz, who spent the 1997 and 1998 seasons as a
college-football analyst for CBS. ``I decided last year to be a
kinder, gentler guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Zero victories and 11 defeats made Holtz realize kinder and
gentler wasn't going to work. When the season ended, he prepared
the Gamecocks for a boot camp of an off-season. Every morning, the
players showed up for 6 a.m. ``volunteer'' workout sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz pulled out the motivational stops. Players moved into
on-campus dorms. During two-a-days, players turned in their car
keys so they had to ride buses together. Freshmen were given media
guides and instructed to get the signatures of every teammate,
high-school-yearbook style.
</P>
<P>
   Before fall workouts, each South Carolina player stood in front
of his teammates and talked about himself. Call it emotional male
bonding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way for us to get to know our teammates,'' said Andre
Offing, a senior linebacker from Houston. ``My best friend told us
that his sister had been raped. I didn't know that. I told
everybody about growing up with a single parent, trying to stay out
of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a lot to do with how coach Holtz has brought us
together and the love we have now for one another.''
\Nsubheds:TURNING IT AROUND South Carolina defensive-ends coach and
recruiting coordinator Dave Roberts, a former Baylor coach,
believes it has taken a year for Holtz's style to take hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to lay a foundation,'' Roberts said. ``It took awhile
to teach them how to play, to practice, to get their intensity up.
It was a full-court press, on and off the field. More and more of
the players started to buy into being tough and physical. You could
see the changes.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past three decades, Holtz had been wedded to a
veer/option attack. Last December, though, Holtz decided to
modernize. He instructed son Skip to devise a four-wide-receiver
attack. The new scheme has spread the field, enabling the Gamecocks
to move the ball much more easily.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina is 39th in total offense, which is good enough to
support a defense that ranks sixth nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a hungry bunch,'' Florida coach Steve Spurrier said.
``I watched the tape of them playing Mississippi State. If we could
get our players to play that hard, we'd have a chance to be pretty
good this year. We're trying to get our guys to play as hard as
South Carolina's players play.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Saturday's game at Alabama, it is the Gamecocks who
are 4-0, while the Crimson Tide is 1-3. In his five previous
coaching stops, Holtz has had his team in a bowl in Year Two. South
Carolina needs two victories in its last seven games to qualify for
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always say, `How did you change this team around?' ''
the 63-year-old Holtz said. ``If you change people, you usually
change the product on the field. I've tried to get players to raise
their standards, raise their expectations, show them how to be
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every situation is different, but I think what's been the
constant is my stubbornness, my absolute refusal to accept failure.
I refuse to compromise. Sometimes that's an asset, and sometimes
that's a liability.'' \Nsubheds:BUT, THE CURSE... The Chicken Curse
was coined by sports writer Doug Nye of ``The State'' in Columbia,
S.C., in the early 1970s. It's a catch-all excuse for anything bad
that happens to South Carolina teams. It's a rural legend whose
power has extended to the Olympics (Kevin Joyce, a South Carolina
basketball player, was on the 1972 U.S. Olympic team that lost to
the Russians) to the NCAA basketball tournament (the Gamecocks
flamed out in the first round in 1997 and 1998) to baseball (South
Carolina was ranked No. 1 last season but was upset one step short
of the College World Series).
</P>
<P>
   But South Carolinians place their passions and their support
with football. Even though the Gamecocks were winless and woeful
last season, the school averaged 78,273 fans for six home games in
80,250-seat Williams-Brice Stadium, ranking 13th nationally. Only
Notre Dame and Louisiana State had losing records and averaged more
fans.
</P>
<P>
   In 106 seasons of football, South Carolina has won 10 games
exactly once (1984). George Rogers won the Heisman Trophy in 1980
for an 8-4 team. The school's only bowl victory in nine tries came
in the 1995 Carquest Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But the end of the 21-game losing streak, the victories against
ranked Southeastern Conference rivals Georgia and Mississippi
State, the 4-0 start have turned the fans giddy. Some travel
agencies are already offering bowl-trip packages.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicken Curse, though, looms.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've gotten excited before, and then we've come crashing
down,'' Jason Humphries, a native of Greenville, S.C. and a
lifelong Gamecocks fan, told ``The Associated Press.'' ``We just
don't want to crash again. Just when we get good, we get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Several key starters, including quarterback Phil Petty, could
wind up missing the Alabama game. Still, when Petty was hurt late
in the game with Mississippi State, walk-on quarterback Erik Kimrey
entered the game and, without even warming up, threw the
game-winning touchdown pass on a fourth-and-10 play.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the things that used to go against us seem to be working
for us,'' South Carolina junior center Philip Jones said. ``Maybe
the year 2000 brought an end to the Chicken Curse.''
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State cornerback Fred Smoot seemed to agree. He used
some words that South Carolina fans rarely hear associated with
their team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the magic,` he said, ``and the team with the magic
always prevails.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
