<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODWIN SPARKLES WITH ARM AND GLOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Outfielder Tom Goodwin is not known for his arm,
but in recent games he's combined it with his speed to become as
valuable to the Los Angeles Dodgers in center field as he is at the
top of the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in three games this week, Goodwin sparked a
key double play.
</P>
<P>
   He preserved Sunday's 1-0 victory over the Padres with a sliding
catch of a shallow fly by Ed Sprague and caught Ryan Klesko off
first for the final out of a game in which Goodwin also ran down a
ball at the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done a good job out there,'' Johnson said Sunday about
the 32-year-old, who was acquired in the July 31 trade involving
Todd Hollandsworth. However, Johnson added,``With his arm, I don't
know how he got it back in there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goodwin did it again Wednesday in the fourth inning, when he
ran down a fly ball by J.T. Snow and started a relay to first base
to double up Bill Mueller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just doing my job,'' Goodwin said. ``Sometimes I make them
look harder than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin was the beneficiary Thursday when Giants center fielder
Marvin Benard was unable to duplicate the solid outfield play.
Goodwin beat the throw to second after leading off the first with a
fly to left center that Benard could not handle.
</P>
<P>
   __ Another one goes down: At this point, it's almost easier for
Johnson to list the Dodgers who are healthy as opposed to those who
are injured.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Adrian Beltre became the latest member of the
disabled when he fouled a ball off his right foot earlier in the
week. He was removed from Wednesday's game because of the problem,
and Paul LoDuca started in Beltre's place Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the injured Dodgers, catcher Angel Pena, had surgery
Thursday morning to repair a ligament in his right thumb. Team
officials said the surgery was successful and Pena should be ready
by spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers Jeff Williams and Ismael Valdes are scheduled to have
more tests on their hands to determine whether further treatment is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   __ Record watch: With a playoff berth officially out of the
picture, the Dodgers season is reduced to tracking personal and
team milestones. Shawn Green reached one Wednesday when he hit his
43rd double of the season to tie him with Steve Sax for the
second-highest season total by a Los Angeles Dodger. Wes Parker
holds the record with 47 doubles in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Green entered Thursday's game two RBI shy of 100, a mark that
would put him with Eric Karros and Gary Sheffield to form the first
L.A. Dodger trio with at least 100 RBI each.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield is a home run away from tying Duke Snider's
franchise-record 43 home runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, the Dodgers tied the major-league record
for pinch-hit home runs in a season (12) as well as tying the
franchise record for home runs in a season (208).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
