<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS WON'T SPECIFY `DISCIPLINE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys handed out league-approved
``discipline'' Thursday to free safety George Teague and two other
players involved in Sunday's controversial demonstrations,
retaliations and ejections at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't be confirmed if Teague, strong safety Darren Woodson
or running Emmitt Smith was fined by the Cowboys, although Teague
said earlier in the day that he ``had been told'' to expect a fine
from either the league or the team. Excessive or embarrassing cases
of unsportsmanlike conduct have been known to carry a $5,000 fine
from the league office.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones declined to specify what he meant by
``discipline'' for his three players and emphasized Thursday that
the matter was ``being handled internally.'' He wouldn't even say
if the disciplinary actions varied from player to player.
</P>
<P>
   It was much clearer in San Francisco where wide receiver Terrell
Owens for one week without pay _ $24,294. Owens started the
controversy by running to the middle of the field and striking a
celebratory pose on the Cowboys' blue star after scoring his first
of two touchdowns. Owens later did it again.
</P>
<P>
   Teague used a flying shoulder to knock Owens off the blue star
the second time.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dave Campo called all the incidents ``a serious matter''
and didn't appreciate Teague and Woodson, who were ejected late in
the game, leaving the stadium before the rest of the team came off
the field and missing out on Campo's post-game talk.
</P>
<P>
   Smith wasn't given a penalty for running helmet-less to the
middle of the field, kneeling and slamming the ball atop the blue
star while staring at the 49ers bench. This came shortly after
Owens' first demonstration. Owens was penalized for taunting only
after the second incident in which Teague tagged him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cowboys have handled it,'' NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said.
``They've disciplined Smith, Woodson and Teague, and have discussed
it with Gene Washington \Rwho levies league fines\S. It is in line
with what normally would have been done by the league office. There
will be no further discipline by the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Teague met and talked briefly on the sideline at
practice Thursday. Teague listened, then ran off and made an
interception a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   If Teague was fined, he might not have to pay it because of
appreciative Cowboys fans who see Teague as a hero and Owens as a
no-class jerk who was trying to rub the Cowboys' collective noses
into a 41-24 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did get a phone call from some guy whom I met once, and he
told me, `If you get fined, my company will take care of it,' ''
Teague said Thursday before a decision came down. ``I figured they
all were drunk, watching TV. But the guy called me back probably
three more times this week.''
</P>
<P>
   After practice, Teague politely declined comment on the
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a ``weird'' week for him, beginning when he joined
up with some friends at Joe's Crab Shack immediately following the
game. He was both flattered and surprised by all the attention,
saying, ``I think it's kind of weird to get that kind of
recognition just for standing up for something.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tampa Bay, Bucs veteran guard Frank Middleton told reporters
that he would help Teague pay any fine and that ``if somebody
\Racted as Owens did\S at Raymond James, y'all would have a story
to write about for a whole month because I won't let it happen.
That's disrespectful.''
</P>
<P>
   Several callers to North Texas radio shows this week have asked
how to send in money to help pay Teague's fine.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it's being called ``discipline,'' without any
indication how much that is in dollars. \Nsubheds:Briefly Defensive
tackle Leon Lett (strained right hamstring) missed practice for the
second day in a row but is expected to start Sunday at Carolina.
Wide receiver Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail (sprained left ankle) also
missed practice for a second consecutive day, but coach Dave Campo
said he is ``comfortable'' Ismail can give playing a shot. Middle
linebacker Dat Nguyen (sprained ligament in his left knee) and
cornerback Charlie Williams (staph infection as a complication of
surgery on his left knee) are listed as day-to-day after practicing
Thursday. Campo said, ``If Dat is 100 percent, he's our middle
linebacker.'' Nguyen's fill-in, Barron Wortham, has had 17 tackles
in two games.  &LR; tagtop:This report contains material from ``The
Tampa Tribune.''
</P>
</TEXT>
