<HEADLINE>
SUPER DERBY IMPACT ON BREEDERS' CUP UNLIKELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a 3-year-old is shooting for a spot in the Breeders' Cup
Classic, the Super Derby at Louisiana Downs is always a good place
to prep. Sunday Silence, Unbridled and Concern are a few of the
horses that raced in the Super Derby and won the Breeders' Cup
Classic later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   And the Super Derby should get a lot of attention this year
(Saturday, 3-3:30 p.m. on ESPN), because the 3-year-old colts are
doing the best running on the track this fall. This trend started
when Captain Steve won the Kentucky Cup Classic over Golden Missile
two weeks ago at Turfway Park.
</P>
<P>
   But it really took hold last week at Belmont Park. First there
was Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus, who absolutely toyed
with a decent field to win the Jerome Handicap. It was his first
start in 125 days, but he still rattled off the fourth-fastest time
in the 131-year history of the race.
</P>
<P>
   In the race following the Jerome, the Vosburgh Stakes for
sprinters was dominated by 3-year-olds. Trippi and More Than Ready,
both also-rans in the Kentucky Derby this year, finished 1-2 while
beating older horses without much challenge in the Vosburgh. Though
they're not Classic horses _ they'll likely race in the Sprint on
Breeders' Cup day Nov. 4 _ their command of the Vosburgh shows the
sort of talent the 3-year-old class has this year.
</P>
<P>
   So there's bound to be a serious Breeders' Cup player among
Tiznow, Commendable and Mass Market _ the headlining horses in this
year's Super Derby. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Don't hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   Tiznow, who'll be the Super Derby favorite, is the brother to
Budroyale. Last year, Budroyale finished second in the Breeders'
Cup Classic. And Tiznow became a graded stakes winner in his own
right when he won the Affirmed Handicap this summer at Hollywood
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Tiznow also ran second to Skimming in the Pacific Classic in his
last start. In the process, Tiznow rang up a three-digit Beyer
speed figure (a ``Beyer'' assigns a figure to a final time of a
race that attempts to compare races conducted at other tracks _ the
higher the figure the better).
</P>
<P>
   But Skimming might be a horse for the course. He ran two big
races at Del Mar, but he couldn't beat Sir Bear or Ecton Park at
Prairie Meadows and he finished up the track in the Woodward
Stakes. And the Woodward is the race that has put to question the
abilities of Lemon Drop Kid because of the slow winning time of
that race.
</P>
<P>
   Tiznow will be heard from, but he won't become a big star until
the Strub Series early next year at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   Commendable and Mass Market appear to be second-tier
3-year-olds. Though they've won some races, the Belmont Stakes
included, it's always come against second-level competition by and
large.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Derby will be a nice race to watch, but it's unlikely
it will produce anything eye-catching come Breeders' Cup time.
LATE SCRATCHES...
\Nsubheds:Mattress Mac springs Houston businessman Jim ``Mattress
Mac'' McIngvale has pulled his sponsorship of the Texan Juvenile
Stakes _ and taken with it the expected purse of $550,000 _ because
of the controversy over his plan to restrict the race to horses
ridden by female jockeys. The race for 2-year-olds will still be a
part of Texas Champions Day on Dec. 2 at Sam Houston Race Park, but
the purse will be $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comment was made to me from people at the track that
anybody with a good horse would not run with female-only jockeys,''
McIngvale said. ``My answer to that was, `Why in the hell do they
put female riders on them in the mornings for workouts?' ''
</P>
<P>
   McIngvale, who owns a furniture store in Houston, said he wanted
to use female-only jockeys because his customer base has a high
percentage of women.
\Nsubheds:For openers Though Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie was
down in every business category compared with last year on opening
night of the quarter horse season, the three-date opening weekend
showed increases in almost every category. Average attendance of
5,609 per night was up 6 percent. On-track wagering on the live
races of $270,406 per night was down about 1 percent. And off-track
wagering was up 39 percent at $671,628 per night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening weekend was good,'' Lone Star general manager Steve
Sexton said. ``In the comparison between Saturday night this year
and last year we were up $41,000 in on-track live \Rwagering\S.
That was the only way to compare apples to apples, so that's a good
sign.''
\Nsubheds:Valhol's jockey Jim Jackson, a resident of Rockdale who
is the owner of Valhol, said he has had trouble attracting a
``name'' jockey to ride his horse since the disqualification in
last year's Arkansas Derby. Valhol, who's scheduled to race in the
$400,000 Meadowlands Cup with Ricky Frazier riding on Oct. 7 in
East Rutherford, N.J., was disqualified when jockey Billy Patin was
accused of carrying an electronic shocking device.
</P>
<P>
   Though Edgar Prado rode Valhol in the Preakness last year, that
was before Prado moved his tack to New York. And Jackson said he
thinks some other jockeys have avoided Valhol because Jackson
``dumped on'' Patin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy created a hell of his own making,'' Jackson said. ``I
had to defend myself like he had to defend himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gutierrez A year ago, Cat Thief was winner of the Breeders'
Cup Classic, but even jockey Pat Day questions what can be done for
the slumping horse.
\Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON ...
Cat Thief: From Classic win to classic also-ran Fusaichi Pegasus.
Lemon Drop Kid. Giant's Causeway. Captain Steve. Golden Missile.
Behrens.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time to discuss the possible favorites for the
Breeders' Cup Classic, which is 36 days away, the names keep
popping up. But the name of the defending champion isn't one of
them, and it has nothing to do with the often-used excuse _ that he
has been retired to the stud farm.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief has competed in nine races this year, but it looks as
though he's nowhere close to being in the form needed to repeat as
Breeders' Cup Classic champion on Nov. 4. In fact, he hasn't won a
single race this year, a feat that has put him in the record books.
</P>
<P>
   Since the inception of the Breeders' Cup in 1984, only one other
horse has gone 0-for-9 in the year after his Breeders' Cup victory.
That was Success Express, who won the Breeders' Cup Juvenile in
1987 and went 0-for-9 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``His last race just was not good,'' jockey Pat Day said. ``I
don't know what they'll do with him now.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if Cat Thief shows up for the Breeders' Cup
anyway. He won the Classic last year at double-digit odds and has
been successful at the site of this year's Breeders' Cup _
Churchill Downs. He finished third in the 1999 Kentucky Derby and
was second in the Stephen Foster Handicap to Golden Missile this
year at Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse that scares me is Cat Thief,'' Golden Missile
trainer Joe Orseno said. ``He's due.''
</P>
<P>
   He's overdue.
\Nsubheds:INSIDE THE NUMBERS... Record for Cat Thief Since the
inception of the Breeders' Cup in 1984, 21 horses have gone winless
the year after winning a race on Cup championship day. Cat Thief,
Breeders' Cup Classic winner last year, is one of those horses. But
he needs one more loss to break the record in this category. Horse
(trainer) Year, Breeders' Cup win Starts and losses the following
year Cat Thief (D. Wayne Lukas) '99 Classic 9 Success Express (D.
Wayne Lukas) '87 Juvenile 9 Thirty Slews (Bob Baffert) '92 Sprint 7
Answer Lively (Bobby Barnett) '98 Juvenile 7 Tikkanen (Jonathan
Pease) '94 Turf 7 Pleasant Stage (Chris Speckert) '91 Juvenile
Fillies 6 Capote (D. Wayne Lukas) '86 Juvenile 6 Ferdinand (Charlie
Whittingham) '87 Classic 6 _ The seven-race losing streak for
Thirty Slews includes two consecutive years after his Breeders' Cup
victory.
</P>
<P>
   To contact Tim Price, call (972) 237-4845 or e-mail him at
tprice &LR; star-telegram.com.
nn
</P>
