<HEADLINE>
HARVEY SIGNS, EAGER TO PLAY WITH MAVS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ After signing a three-year, $2.3 million contract
Thursday, rookie Donnell Harvey can focus on earning some playing
time at the Mavericks' crowded power forward position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of pressure off of me now because people can stop
asking me about when I'm going to sign,'' Harvey said. ``So I'm
ready to go now.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey said he held up signing his contract because he wanted to
set up a trust fund after Mavericks owner Mark Cuban arranged for
him to receive $646,920 of his first-year salary up front. That
trust fund has been established, Harvey said, allowing him to
receive a certain amount of living expenses each month.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey is scheduled to collect $718,800 this season, $772,800
next year and $826,700 for the 2002-03 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have signed all 16 players on their roster heading
into the start of training camp Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to sign my contract; it's just that I
hadn't taken the physical,'' Harvey said. ``I'm just waiting for
the season to start now that I've gotten that out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he was unsigned, Harvey played on the Mavericks' summer
league teams. Last month, he also spent three weeks in Los Angeles
working with Mavericks developmental coach Kiki Vandeweghe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of procedure now,'' Cuban said. ``Now, he's
just waiting on his money.''  &LR; subheds:Alexander, Finley impress
Courtney Alexander and Michael Finley gave Mavericks fans a reason
to be excited about the prospect of the high-scoring rookie and
high-scoring All-Star playing together.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander and Finley, both guards, worked so well together
Thursday at the Landry Center that it seemed as if they had been
teammates for years. In one sequence, Finley and Alexander were on
a two-on-one break, and Finley lobbed a perfect pass to Alexander,
who caught it on the fly and jammed it home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wondering how we would mesh,'' Alexander said. ``But
he's very unselfish, and he's definitely someone who I think I can
play very well with.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, noting that the Mavericks are deeper at every position,
said he is anxious to play alongside Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main thing is just to get the most out of my teammates, to
know their strengths and their weaknesses, and get them in a
comfortable position where they can be most effective,'' Finley
said.  &LR; subheds:Tickets to go on sale Single-game tickets for the
Mavericks' 41 regular-season home games go on sale at 12:01 a.m.
Sunday on the Internet at www.nba.com/mavericks/arena.html, or by
calling Ticketmaster at (214) 373-8000.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets also can be purchased at the Reunion Arena box office or
Ticketmaster locations, including Foley's Department Stores and
Fiesta and Kroger grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks hope to boost single-game sales with an event from
8 a.m. to 5 p.m. Sunday that includes three radio stations
broadcasting from Reunion and appearances by Mavericks owner Mark
Cuban, forward Gary Trent, Mavs Man, the Mavericks Street Team and
the Mavericks Dancers.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
