<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6106 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-BRUCKHEIMER-INTERVIEW     09-29 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUCKHEIMER-INTERVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
Bruckheimer: Film is about men, for men {hellip} and women &HT;     BC-BRUCKHEIMER-INTERVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    BRUCKHEIMER: FILM IS ABOUT MEN, FOR MEN {ndash} AND WOMEN(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's really no argument. Producer Jerry Bruckheimer likes to
blow things up.
</P>
<P>
   At least in his movies.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Bruckheimer built his reputation on films like
(beginitalic)The Rock, Con Air (enditalic)and
(beginitalic)Armageddon(enditalic), where spectacular action
sequences and special effects always take center stage.
</P>
<P>
   So it would seem that (beginitalic)Remember the
Titans(enditalic), a film about a high school football coach who
battles racism in the South, is a big departure.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says the man who virtually invented the rock-and-roll
action movie with (beginitalic)Top Gun(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's always really about the same thing,''
Bruckheimer says. ``It's about the camaraderie among men. It's
about doing the right thing. {ellipsis} It's always the brotherhood
of man, and the ability to look out for one another.''
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Remember the Titans (enditalic)is set in 1971 and
focuses on Herman Boone (Denzel Washington), a stubborn, defiant
man who's hired to coach the first integrated team in the history
of Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, who also worked with Bruckheimer on the nuclear
submarine drama (beginitalic)Crimson Tide(enditalic), was the only
actor that he considered to play the strong-willed Coach Boone.
</P>
<P>
   ``And had he said no, I don't know where I would have gone,''
Bruckheimer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to get this movie made - by the way, nobody wanted to
make it - both Denzel and I had to give up large portions of our
fee.''
</P>
<P>
   Although (beginitalic)Remember the Titans (enditalic)is clearly
another guy film, Bruckheimer says women will enjoy it as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a 10-city tour, and more women came up to me and said,
`Jerry I hate football. I would never go to a football movie. I
can't stand it when my husband watches. I love this movie. I'm
going to tell all my friends to go see it,''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because again, it's about emotion; it's about these guys,
about Will (Patton, who plays Washington's reluctant assistant
coach) and Denzel getting these kids to get along with one other
and become winners, against a very turbulent backdrop.''
</P>
<P>
   Tackling the sensitive issue of race relations was made easier
because the film is based on a true story, Bruckheimer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate because this is history, this happened, we
documented it,'' he says. ``It's not 100 percent correct. We had to
combine characters and change some things around to make it more
dramatic. But it's much easier when you're dealing with a real
subject, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing easy, however, about the training that the
actors received.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our actors went through a two-week training camp,''
Bruckheimer says. ``They hated it. They got up early in the
morning; they did calisthenics. They threw up. They were sore; they
were beat up. But you know what? It shows in the movie. They look
real. Some of the kids had never touched a football before.''
</P>
<P>
   Although (beginitalic)Remember the Titans (enditalic)promises to
be a hit at the box office, there's much more anticipation
surrounding Bruckheimer's next film, (beginitalic)Pearl
Harbor(enditalic), which is scheduled to open May 28.
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer says the World War II film, which he describes as a
``sweeping, epic love story'' that climaxes with the Japanese
attack on Pearl Harbor, is in post-production, where digital
effects are being added. He adds that (beginitalic)Pearl Harbor
(enditalic)will abandon the docudrama approach of war movies like
(beginitalic)Tora! Tora! Tora!(enditalic)
</P>
<P>
   In that film, Bruckheimer says, ``you really didn't get to know
a lot of the characters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was basically just about the attack. It was very well done.
Some of the battle sequences were terrific. And we certainly
learned from what they did, or what they did wrong,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Pearl Harbor(enditalic), Bruckheimer says, is a
``movie'' movie:
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie's not a documentary in any shape or form. Again,
we're going to try to do the same things we're doing on
(beginitalic)Titans(enditalic), and that's capture the essence of
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
