u s BC-CAR-DRIVERS-FITNESS-H     09-29 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DRIVERS-FITNESS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Drivers must remain in top shape to meet demands of auto racing
<TEXT>
<P>
   By TERRY BLOUNT
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ So you happen to be one of those people who thinks
race car drivers are not athletes. Here's a little test for you to
simulate what a driver will experience Sunday during the
Texaco/Havoline Grand Prix of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   First, go outside in your back yard. Take a treadmill. Put on
long flannel underwear, warm-up pants and a jacket _ the equivalent
of the Nomex firesuit the drivers wear.
</P>
<P>
   Find a motorcycle helmet or old football helmet in the garage
and put it on. Put golf gloves on each hand. Have buddies stand on
each side of you.
</P>
<P>
   Now get on the treadmill at a pace of 6 mph and maintain that
pace for two hours while your buddies give you forearm pops on your
arms and legs every few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   When it's over, assuming you are still alive, you probably won't
ever say again that race car drivers are not athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be fit,'' said Dario Franchitti, the 1998 winner
in Houston. ``I used to think driving was all about upper-body
strength, but it's not. You use your entire body. Endurance also is
very important, because you have to be able to go flat-out for two
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The example used above is not an arbitrary assumption. It comes
from the results of a study published this year in the Journal of
Strength and Conditioning Research.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Patrick Jacobs, a professor for exercise physiology at the
University of Miami, and Dr. Steve Olvey, CART's chief medical
officer, conducted the study to determine what a driver goes
through physiologically during a race.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed a person expends a lot of energy by driving
competitive laps on a track. Most of the exertion comes from
lateral forces while cornering and G-forces on the body under
acceleration and braking. A G-force is a unit measuring the
inertial stress of a body during acceleration in multiples of the
acceleration of gravity.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a driver will pull four to five G's on some turns
of a street course, like the 1.5-mile layout in downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   What does that mean? Pulling four G's in a corner means that in
order to keep your head upright, your neck muscles have to work
four times harder than you would if you were lying on your side in
the bed and holding your head off the pillow.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider the fact that drivers are doing that every lap for
a two-hour race while wearing a helmet, and you get the idea.
Fatigue can set in during a race, and fatigue can be costly _ even
disastrous _ to a driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a driver is fatigued, it can affect his responsiveness and
his ability to communicate properly with his team,'' Jacobs said.
``That's why it's so important for these drivers to be physically
fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the men who will compete this weekend have a fitness
level that would compare to a distance runner or an Olympic
swimmer. An example is Max Papis, who drives the Miller Lite
Ford/Reynard for Team Rahal.
</P>
<P>
   Papis, 30, an Italian, has a body fat count of only 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I needed to start working on my body because it was my
tool,'' Papis said. ``A driver has his body and his mind as his
throttle, brake and gearbox.
</P>
<P>
   ``The engineers and mechanics work very hard to give me a great
car, so I must be able to get 110 percent out of the car. To do
that, you have to be clear in your mind, and you can't do that
unless you are fit in your body.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitness is a top priority for Papis. He has a team of three
doctors in Italy _ Dr. Enrico Arcelli, Dr. Claudio Castiglione and
Dr. Giovanni Bassi _ that he corresponds with on a regular basis
about his fitness routine. The doctors also consult with former
Italian Olympic skier Alberto Tomba, along with other Italian
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctors have a tremendous amount of experience in training
the mind and the body,'' Papis said. ``They've taught me a lot,
including never being satisfied with my performance and how to turn
negative situations into positives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've also helped me to be a stronger person with a stronger
drive. They've taught me a lot about what athletes do to perform at
their best.''
</P>
<P>
   The workout routine Papis uses is designed to simulate his heart
rate during a race _ which can be as high as 170 beats per minute.
A typical workout includes one hour of running or cycling while
wearing a heart monitor to record data on a computer. That
information is e-mailed to Papis' team of doctors in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Papis also has a daily weight training routine that includes 12
machines. He moves from one machine to the next without resting in
order to keep his heart rate high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to my workout is to be stronger, mentally and
physically, so I'll be prepared to suffer in the race car,'' Papis
said. ``A driver can experience some big pain during a race. I have
to be able to overcome the pain and get the most out of my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers can get tossed around like a rag doll during a race.
They can suffer rib injuries, wrist and hand injuries and separated
shoulders just from being bumped against the car at high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ovals track aren't that physical for you,'' Franchitti said.
``But a road or street course will knock the heck out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti was the test subject Jacobs and Olvey used in their
research, some of which was done at the road course in Sebring,
Fla. They found that Franchitti's metabolic expenditure on one lap
was equal to cycling at 16 mph or running a mile in nine minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Franchitti's resting heart rate is 55 beats per minute, which
would compare to the heart rate of a competitive marathon runner.
During the four-lap test at Sebring, his heart rate increased to
125 beats per minute, proving how fit he is considering the amount
of energy he was exerting.
</P>
<P>
   Like Papis, Franchitti works hard at maintaining his fitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I will bike all day in the offseason, and I usually
run for an hour or so,'' Franchitti said. ``I've started doing
yoga, and it's amazing the strength you need to do it properly. But
there's nothing like driving the race car. You can work all winter
on your fitness, get in the car, and find muscles you haven't been
able to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Most drivers also are careful about what they eat. Papis is on a
specialized, high-complex carbohydrate, low-fat diet. Franchitti
said his diet includes lots of water, no junk food and little
alcohol during the season.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every driver in the CART series does something to stay
fit. Michael Andretti has a full gymnasium in his home and is a
fanatical user of his Stairmaster. Christian Fittipaldi competed in
a triathlon last year.
</P>
<P>
   They might sit in a car for a living, but these men realize
staying in shape is mandatory if they hope to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think of myself as an athlete,'' Papis said. ``If
I weren't a race car driver, I still would be involved in sports.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
