<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6110 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-dale-HNS &LR;      09-29 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-dale-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Super Mario not so according to A.J.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It's terrific that big-time auto racing has become an
annual fixture on the Houston sports scene because Houston and auto
racing always will be synonymous. Why? Because of one man, a man
with a famous last name that he hardly needs to use.
</P>
<P>
   Say A.J. and pretty much everybody in our town, or the United
States, knows of whom you speak. It makes not a bit of difference
that A.J. Foyt has been retired from competition for seven years
and hasn't won the Indianapolis 500 in almost a quarter of a
century.
</P>
<P>
   The best race car driver who ever lived? No point in asking that
question in Houston. Only two initials need apply.
</P>
<P>
   But a strange thing happened here Wednesday night. In
conjunction with this weekend's Texaco/Havoline Grand Prix of
Houston CART race downtown, they held a fancy party for a bunch of
folks in tuxedos at the George R. Brown Convention Center for the
express purpose of, besides raising money for charity, honoring
Mario Andretti as racing's driver of the century.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered what A.J. thought about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Poppycock),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt, to be sure, never has conceded anything to anybody when it
comes to driving a car fast. But what really got his goat was that
Texaco, the sponsor of several CART races, chose the one in Houston
for putting the king-of-racing crown on Mario's head.
</P>
<P>
   His beef is justified, too. That's tantamount to going into
Boston and proclaiming Wilt Chamberlain the finest center in
basketball history. Or feting Joe Montana in Baltimore as the
quarterback to end all quarterbacks. Or putting up a plaque at
Yankee Stadium for Ty Cobb, ordaining him the greatest baseball
player ever.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt, 65, doesn't claim to be the No. 1 driver for the ages. He
reels off a list of forgotten names from the first half of the
century, legends long before his time, who ``might have all been
able to beat my butt.'' A.J.'s point is that it's pointless to
ordain anybody the greatest with racing conditions having changed
so dramatically over the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   But his point also is that, if we're going to compare resumes
here, there's no way in Hades that Mario's holds any kind of edge
over his. For the sake of argument, here are their respective
credentials. You be the judge:
</P>
<P>
   Foyt _ Won USAC-CART national championship seven times. Won four
Indy 500s. Holds all-time CART record for victories with 67. Only
driver to win the Indy 500, the Daytona 500 and the 24 Hours at
LeMans.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti _ Won USAC-CART national championship four times. Won
Indy 500 once. Ranks second all-time in CART victories with 52.
Only driver to win the Indy 500, the Daytona 500 and the Formula
One world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt does seem to have a distinct advantage, save for that last
item on Mario's side of the ledger, the Formula One title. But,
yikes, don't get A.J. started. He swears it's common knowledge that
Andretti's F1 little-known teammate in 1978 consistently outdrove
him, yet was kept from reaping the rewards of same by the team's
bosses because Andretti was the superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt, by his own admission, never wanted any part of F1. He
hates its street courses, and he hates how money rules who wins the
races. Besides
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people made A.J. Foyt,'' he said. ``I didn't need
to prove anything in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   You won't see Foyt hanging around the Texaco Grand Prix. He
wants no part of it, either. His loyalties are solely to the Indy
Racing League, CART's North American rival in open-wheel racing,
and the rift between the circuits figures hugely in the distance
between him and Andretti, a CART backer.
</P>
<P>
   The two speed demons used to be good friends, though. Foyt is
godfather to John Andretti, the son of Mario's brother, Aldo. That
Mario has become the spokesman for Texaco, a company A.J. has
resented for snubbing him early in his career, heightens the
tension.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt was at Indy last week for the Formula One race and, when he
heard Andretti was ``badmouthing'' the Brickyard _ a sacred site to
A.J. _ he went ballistic. No matter that he had just had a heart
angioplasty, or that he would wind up in an emergency room there
when his post-op medicine gave him a fierce bellyache.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went over and told Mario what a (jerk) he is,'' Foyt said
proudly.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. grudgingly had accepted the Associated Press' voting him
and Andretti, recently turned 60, co-drivers of the century. But
being ignored at Wednesday's soiree _ save, ironically, for a brief
photo image of the two of them side by side and smiling after a
race _ brought out his feisty Super-Tex side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's settle this on the track,'' Foyt said. ``Just me and
Mario, at Indy or Texas World (Speedway). Any time. I'll still whip
his butt.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
