<HEADER>
A6112 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     09-29 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAIN, BROWN GETS NO SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's only fitting the Los Angeles Dodgers waited
until after Kevin Brown was gone to start hitting
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers managed just one hit through the first five innings
Thursday. An inning after Brown was removed from the game, they
produced three consecutive hits and scored two runs to take the
lead for the only time in an eventual 5-3 loss to San Francisco in
front of 44,513 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of run support throughout the season left Brown with a
13-6 record, which belies his effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's had a better season this season than last,''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``He's certainly been dominant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great year last year. Some of the production that was
there wasn't there this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown went 18-9 with a 3.00 ERA in 1999. He entered Thursday's
game ranked second in the National League with a 2.56 ERA, but had
five fewer victories than a year ago. The Dodgers have been shut
out three times and scored a total of 10 runs in Brown's six
losses.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Brown also hurt himself.
</P>
<P>
   He had two wild pitches, hit a batter and gave up two walks and
six hits in five innings in his final start of the season. It was
just the third time in 33 starts this year Brown lasted less than
six innings. He also had eight strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's hitting resumed in the seventh inning,
highlighted by a two-run home run by Barry Bonds. The shot to right
field off reliever Onan Masaoka was Bonds' 49th of the season.
Pinch hitter Felipe Crespo added a two-out solo home run off Mike
Fetters in the eighth inning to give the Giants 222 home runs this
season, a franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   Power hitting wasn't required to give San Francisco the initial
lead, though. A wild pitch scored the Giants' second run. Brown had
another wild pitch the next inning and loaded the bases by issuing
a walk. He got out of the jam when shortstop Alex Cora snagged a
line drive by Ellis Burks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' lone lead came when Paul LoDuca's sacrifice fly
scored Eric Karros to make it 3-2. Todd Hundley had tied the game a
batter earlier with an RBI-single that chased San Francisco starter
Shawn Estes.
</P>
<P>
   Estes did his best to help the Dodgers' offense in the fourth
inning, but all it could produce was one run. The rally started on
a two-base throwing error by Estes on a comebacker by Shawn Green.
A wild pitch advanced Green to third and the next two batters
walked to load the bases for Hundley, whose fielder's choice
grounder scored Green. LoDuca loaded the bases again, but Cora
struck out to end the threat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
