<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-PILL-REACT (Washington) _ Abortion-rights supporters
celebrated a victory Thursday with the FDA's approval of the
abortion pill RU-486, but they acknowledged that it could be an
exceedingly fragile one. At the same time, abortion opponents
denounced the administration and the FDA for furthering ``a culture
of death'' and vowed to keep fighting, legislatively and
politically. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-TRUDEAU (Undated) _ Pierre Elliott Trudeau, the
long-serving Prime Minister of Canada who successfully defended his
vision of federalism and a unified nation against the aroused
forces of Quebec separatism, died at age 80. By Michael T. Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ A growing percentage of women who
are treated for early-stage breast cancer are getting inappropriate
treatment, a new study has found. Researchers found that women who
are getting lumpectomies are not all getting radiation or having
lymph nodes examined, lapses that could lead to recurrence of
disease. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SC-SAUCE-RELIGION (Columbia, S.C.) _ Maurice Bessinger's famous
mustard BBQ sauce is being pulled from grocery shelves all across
South Carolina, and not because he refuses to use tomatoes.
Bessinger, who once waged a lawsuit to keep blacks segregated in
his restaurants, has been distributing religious tracts along with
his sandwiches, tracts that suggest that slavery was biblically
ordained, and that slaves were better off in the United States than
they were in Africa. He's also been flying a huge Confederate Flag
on his main store. Six major grocery chains, including Kroger and
Wal-Mart, are refusing to sell his sauce, and residents are either
infuriated or pleased, depending on their politics. Bessinger says
his religious freedom has been violated, and his business seriously
damaged. But he's hardly apologizing. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICH-CAMPAIGN (Pontiac, Mich.) _ On Feb. 22, Gov. George W. Bush
lost the Michigan Republican primary to Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, thanks to a notably poor showing among independents,
moderates and women. Seven months later, in this same pivotal Great
Lakes state, he is again having trouble attracting independents,
moderates and women in his race against Vice President Al Gore. The
race is close here, with Gore very narrowly ahead. By R.W. Apple
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-DEBATE (Washington) _ One of the fixtures of the 2000
campaign has been the candidates' efforts to connect themselves and
their policy proposals with everyday people. George W. Bush has his
tax families, who gladly tell how much money they will save under
his tax-cut proposal; Al Gore spends the night at the homes of
local teachers before spending the next day in their schools. But
the vice president is about to take the approach to another, much
higher, level. In the next day or so, he will transport a dozen
people from all corners of the country to Sarasota, Fla., to
participate in his debate preparation. They will then travel to
Boston to be in the audience. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DEBATE (Austin, Texas) _ It is impossible to know which
incarnation of George W. Bush will show up at the first debate
between Bush and Vice President Al Gore in Boston next week. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GORE-ENERGY (Washington) _ A look at the energy policies of
Bush and Gore. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EU-TIMEWARNER-ANTITRUST (Frankfurt, Germany) _ European
antitrust regulators plan to block Time Warner's joint venture with
the British music conglomerate EMI Group, but are much closer to
approving Time Warner's $135 billion merger with America Online,
people close to the talks said Thursday. Mario Monti, the European
antitrust commissioner, issued recommendations on both deals on
Wednesday in a closed meeting with antitrust regulators from
individual European countries, these people said. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-AD-COLUMN (Sydney) _ Unlike the 1996 Olympic Games held
in Coke's hometown of Atlanta, Sydney, Australia, has kept
so-called ambush marketers far from Olympic arenas and sites.
Although nonsponsor companies are visible here, Sydney has little
of the flea-market ambience that made the Atlanta Games a byword
for crass commercialism. By Mark Landler.
</P>
