<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-JONES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES SAYS COWBOYS CAN STILL BE A SUPER TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Despite Dallas' dismal start and woeful
performances in blowout home losses to Philadelphia and San
Francisco, owner Jerry Jones said reaching the playoffs and making
a Super Bowl run are still attainable goals for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Jones said if the Cowboys (1-3) don't recover and are
forced to rebuild in the off-season, he remains firmly behind
first-year head coach Dave Campo.
</P>
<P>
   Jones conceded that part of the motivation for hiring Campo to
replace Chan Gailey after last season was because of Campo's
stability as a member of the Cowboys' coaching staff since 1989 and
the opportunity for a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said tweaking, not massive changes, could put the Cowboys
on the path to another championship run. Hiring a coach from the
outside would require too much upheaval, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, however, said Campo is his man no matter what and won't
be blamed if the Cowboys continue to falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get to that point, and obviously I'm not conceding to
rebuilding, Dave is the right guy,'' Jones said. ``He is what Jimmy
\R Johnson\S was with me at the beginning. It's my sense, if we had
to go through tough times, the kind of individual you want in that
situation is a Dave Campo.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, however, reiterated that he's not interested in talking
about the future because he still has high hopes for the 2000
season, starting Sunday against the Carolina Panthers (1-2).
</P>
<P>
   Even with the season-ending knee injury to receiver Joey
Galloway, Jones' optimism is primarily based on the same things he
felt good about coming into the season, the Cowboys' core of
talent, especially with a healthy Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are counting on guys that are premium players who have been
Pro Bowl players,'' Jones said. ``Those kind of players we have
used and other teams have used to go to Super Bowls. This group
still has it. There's nothing I've seen out there that will keep
that core base of players from having the kind of year I'm talking
about. I'm talking about this year.''
</P>
<P>
   And though he's extremely disappointed in the Cowboys'
early-season play, he said he is not presiding over a dead football
team, just a poor-performing one.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Cowboys' 29th-ranked defense is at the
bottom or close to the bottom in nearly every statistical category
and that their 21st-ranked offense has been largely inconsistent
and shown no ability to keep up with the high-powered attacks
displayed by most of the top NFL teams.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said ``the thing that's really keeping me going is that I
see the adjustments we can make that will allow us to win games,''
adding that he believes the Cowboys need only nine victories to
make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to adjust upwards 50 to 60 percent of the areas
in our execution and play,'' Jones said. ``That's going to change
the L's to W's. That's not a huge adjustment across the board.
That's really a 15 or 20 percent adjustment. And it's really
execution and doing smart things out there across the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can change this things to wins, wins, wins. I'm not going
to say we can't win nine games.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is realistic enough to admit that a turnaround will be
difficult, especially considering the Cowboys' late-season schedule
includes Jacksonville, Baltimore, Tennessee, Tampa Bay and
Minnesota, in addition to divisional games with Washington,
Philadelphia and New York.
</P>
<P>
   He said the 32-31 loss to Arizona might end up being the most
damning because it reduced the Cowboys' margin of error. Yet Jones
said there is reason for hope, even after the embarrassing setbacks
to the Eagles (41-14) and 49ers (41-24).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen enough in the first four games to believe that,''
Jones said. ``That is based on the fact that I am not asking to
reverse a 41 to x score. I'm talking about reversing different
aspects of the game by 15 or 20 percent. That's how you get your
wins rather than your losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he would have a different outlook if the Cowboys had
played their best football and been trumped by those scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we can play better than we did in those two games,''
Jones said. ``If I thought we were looking at a dramatic
turnaround, the one you are looking at because of those scores and
1-3, I wouldn't say this. But it's closer than that in my mind. We
have to improve. But we are closer than that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
