r s BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     09-29 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' REBELLIOUS BUG WON'T DIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's like a big, fat roach. Even when you think you've squished
it, it somehow wriggles out from under your shoe and slips away.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, it's crawling up your leg, or scampering
over the cheese and crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Yuck.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same thing with this annual, ongoing conviction around
the NHL that it's only a matter of time until the weary and
frustrated Stars' players revolt and depose head coach Ken
Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   You know, pull their own little coup on the mean and nasty
tyrant who masquerades as a kindly Captain Kangaroo look-alike by
day, but turns into the grinch who steals all the pucks by night.
</P>
<P>
   And just think, the season doesn't even start until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tired story, as dog-eared as my personal well-worn
paperback copy of ``Lonesome Dove'', but without the substance.
It's plain foolishness, considering Hitchcock, in the past three
years, has led the Stars to the conference finals and two
consecutive Stanley Cup Finals appearances.
</P>
<P>
   His way wins and he has the hides on the wall to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, though, this ``roach'' just won't die.
</P>
<P>
   It was scurrying around the Stars' kitchen again yesterday, big
and black and ugly as you please, thanks to ESPN's Al Morganti, who
authored an NHL preview on the network's Web site this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dallas Stars will have `issues' with coach Ken
Hitchcock,'' Morganti predicted. ``It's no secret that the Stars'
locker room has been near revolt at times while under the reign of
Hitchcock. However, the team's success has always been enough to
convince the players that Hitchcock's way, while stressful, gets
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stars are now two seasons removed from their Cup in 1999,
and if there is any struggle early in the season, you can bet
Hitchcock will start hearing the rumblings of an unhappy locker
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Really? You mean professional players might whine and complain
and try to blame someone else if they're not producing? Say it
ain't so, Al.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Morganti added an important codicil to his
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the players need to realize is that GM Bob Gainey knows
the price a team has to pay to win a championship,'' he said, ``and
he will not surrender a premier coach for players who are tired of
paying the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is another way of saying that Gainey doesn't suffer fools
kindly.
</P>
<P>
   The point that Morganti is missing, or has forgotten, is that
Gainey took care of this last year.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a story broke out of Phoenix that the Stars
players were on the verge of a revolt. It was such a problem, the
Stars won the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, when the Stars struggled early and players began to
whine, Gainey made it a point to go down to the locker room and
tell them, in so many words, to shut up and play.
</P>
<P>
   They did.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't want to be the player that needs reminding this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, being somewhat removed, there are things I can see
or bring to the group that someone else might not see,'' Gainey
said during the Stars' 6-2 exhibition loss to Colorado on Thursday
night at Reunion Arena. ``It's my experience of being part of 25 or
30 different teams over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what \RMorganti\S is basing his story on. It's a
good story, I guess, but I go to the bookstore and the shelves are
full of good fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock also remained unruffled by Morganti's speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what people are saying is that we've been to the top
of the mountain so many times the last three years, they don't feel
like we can get back to that level again, or that we won't want to
pay that price again, and thus there'll be conflict,'' Hitchcock
said. ``Maybe there will. But I'm not backing off and I know the
leaders of our group aren't backing off.''
</P>
<P>
   There'll be no changes in his approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't win by being a nice guy,'' Hitchcock said. ``You win
because you push buttons. Players crave discipline because they
know discipline leads to success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there will be growing pains, especially as we add
younger players, but as far as effort and as far as discipline, I'm
not backing off a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   All the predictions of doom and revolt are predicated on a weary
Stars team getting off to a slow start, a scenario Hitchcock
vigorously disputes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evaluate us on our skill level, don't evaluate us because you
think we're going to be tired,'' Hitchcock said. ``Losing last year
cleaned the slate. This is new. When you've won, when you've been
as successful as we've been, just-abouts don't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players are very fresh and they feel good. We're not the
tired team people seem to think we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Not nearly as rebellious either. Nevertheless, I doubt we've
seen the last of this ``bug'' with nine lives.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody got a can of Raid?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
