r a bc-LASORDA-OLYMPICS-LADN     09-29 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASORDA-OLYMPICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS APPLAUD LASORDA'S GOLDEN OLYMPIC TRIUMPH
</HEADLINE>
bc-LASORDA-OLYMPICS-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES The loudest cheer at Dodger Stadium in 2000 was
reserved for somebody who hasn't worn a Dodgers uniform in four
years, for something he did thousands of miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Lasorda came home from Sydney, Australia, as an Olympic
hero, and the baseball fans of Los Angeles, who hadn't had much to
shout about this season, greeted him with open throats Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He was introduced -- as if the Hall of Fame manager needed an
introduction -- to the crowd between innings of a game against the
San Francisco Giants that happened to mark the end of the Dodgers'
home schedule. And the crowd of 44,513 responded with a two-minute
standing ovation as Lasorda took his bows in front of the
third-base dugout while the ballpark organist serenaded him with
``My Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, the Dodgers' senior vice president these days,
certainly will be the only club executive to earn applause this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But for a couple of minutes, you could forget the Dodgers'
disappointing season and bask in the Olympics afterglow. Lasorda
certainly has, in the two days since he coached an underdog team of
minor-league pros to a gold-medal-game victory over Cuba's seasoned
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bigger than the World Series, it's better than the
All-Star Game,'' said Lasorda, 73, who managed the Dodgers to
victories in two of the former and the National League to wins in
three of the latter. ``This is for the United States of America,
the land of opportunity! All of America was pulling for this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda said that soon after the 15-hour flight carrying him and
several of his gold medal-wearing players touched down at Los
Angeles International Airport on Thursday morning. Thursday evening
he was still carrying on in a pregame press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we won the World Series, the Dodger fans were happy but
the Giants fans weren't. But this is for all of America,'' he
roared. ``To win for your country, it's something to be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda said he has fielded congratulatory phone calls from
former President Bush and baseball great Ted Williams.
</P>
<P>
   His Olympics experience also included lunch with tennis stars
Lindsey Davenport, Monica Seles and Todd Martin, and a
command-performance pep talk to the gold medal-winning U.S.
softball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in a lot of fights in my day, but nobody could ever
knock a tear out of me,'' Lasorda said. ``But I cried when I saw
that American flag being raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody believed we had a chance. Nobody believed we belonged
on the same field as the Cubans. They had a lot of big, strong
guys, guys who were 32, 33, 34 years old. The first pitcher we
faced was throwing 95 miles an hour. We knock him out, and you'd
think it gets easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next guy throws 97, and the guy after that, he registered
100 on the radar gun three times. I had a bunch of kids nobody'd
ever heard of, and we beat 'em. ... This, really, I think, was the
greatest upset since David slew Goliath.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda said his greatest memory of the month with the U.S. team
was watching the players receive their medals -- ``and seeing those
Cubans over there crying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure they'll be cutting sugar cane when Castro finds out
we beat'em,'' he said as reporters winced.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reporters and autograph seekers at LAX to greet the
plane was Tommy Hawkins, the ex-basketball star who is the Dodgers'
vice president for external affairs. The two men are playfully
competitive about their achievements. When Hawkins received a Notre
Dame University alumnus of the year award in 1999, he made sure to
place it conspicuously on Lasorda's desk, with a note reading,
``Top this.'' Lasorda responded by leaving on Hawkins' desk a
certificate showing Tommy had received the blessing of the Pope.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought (after the U.S. victory) was, 'Now how am I
going to live with this guy?' '' Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me before he took off from San Diego, and he said,
'I feeeel it (victory) in my bones!' I said, 'Oh, here we go
again.' But if he feels it, you better believe. As close as I am to
him, I still listen to his babble.''
</P>
<P>
   His young players listened, and played like it.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Doug Mientkiewicz spoke at the airport of how
Lasorda talked him out of a batting slump during the pre-Olympics
exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'If you don't start hitting, I'm going to have to
send you out of here.' He had a smile on his face,'' Mientkiewicz
said. ``I've never had a manager joke about a slump before. It
broke the tension, and I went on to have a great Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins doubts his friend's brief return to uniform has made him
think about a return to major-league managing. Then again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy will leave this place seriously feeling there is one
more game to win. It's just his nature. For him to sit back and
rest on his laurels? No,'' Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be half of the fans cheering Lasorda Thursday were
thinking, ``This guy should manage the Dodgers next season''?
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, who contributes mostly advice and PR in his
front-office role, smiled but said: ``Tell them to forget it. I
don't want to manage. I've been to the top of the mountain in my
profession, the Hall of Fame. Besides, if I went back to managing,
it would cost me my marriage of 50 years. My wife (Jo) would be in
Reno before you knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   If this, then, was the last chapter of Lasorda's on-field
career, it makes for a definitive and overdue conclusion to one of
sports' true modern legends. Lasorda's retirement after 20 years as
Dodgers manager following a 1997 heart attack was clouded by
speculation he actually was fired.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe it isn't the last chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have asked me about four years from now in Athens,
Greece,'' Lasorda said, referring to the site of the 2004 Summer
Games. ``If I'm alive, they've got me.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
