<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 08:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6219 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-GIRLFIGHT-DIRECTOR-AZ     09-29 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLFIGHT-DIRECTOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    (SIDEBAR WITH `GIRLFIGHT'
</HEADLINE>
  
 BC-GIRLFIGHT-DIRECTOR-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    NO PUCHED-UP FIGH IN RING FOR `GIRLFIGHT' DIRECTOR(a)  &HT;    (For use by N.Y. BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Karyn Kusama wanted her (beginitalic)Girlfight (enditalic)to be
a lot of things: gritty, realistic, emotionally moving. But she
didn't want it to be (beginitalic)Rocky(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   In (beginitalic)Girlfight(enditalic), which stars Michelle
Rodriguez as an inner-city teenager who takes up boxing, the
fighters don't knock each other's head off with every punch. And
that's just how Kusama likes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't want a sort of an overstylized or
overchoreographed sensibility during those boxing sequences,'' says
Kusama, who wrote and directed (beginitalic)Girlfight(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   ``In amateur it's such a different style of fighting, and it's
quite a bit more raw and more desperate really. Because you're
dealing with kids who have less skill and more fear and are still
kind of figuring out whether or not they even want to be in the
ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with realistic fight scenes, Kusama wanted
(beginitalic)Girlfight(enditalic) to have a distinctive feel.
Because she was limited by her budget and shooting schedule, she
manipulated some old Fuji film stock to give the movie a richer but
grittier look.
</P>
<P>
   Kusama also paid close attention to finding sets that
illustrated the main character's inner-city environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just tried to keep an attention to color, an attention to
texture,'' she says, ``so that when there were really great peeling
walls already in a space where we were going to be shooting, we
just left those as they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who plays the female boxer Diana, adds to the film's
tone with her performance, Kusama says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she has a very un-self-conscious demeanor as an
actor,'' the director says. ``She's very unaware of the camera. I
think there's a lot going on in her that she just lets kind of
happen, and the camera can pick that up.''
</P>
<P>
   In writing (beginitalic)Girlfight(enditalic), Kusama wanted to
tell the story of one female's transformation. She picked boxing
because she is a fan of the sport, having watched it with her
father as a child. And several years ago, she started boxing to
keep in shape.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all Kusama's hard work, it's unclear how the film will
do at the box office. It has no major stars, and Sony released it
under the Screen Gems label rather than Columbia, which is reserved
for bigger movies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kusama says she believes the studio is ``behind it 100
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think sometimes we have disagreements about how to be
behind the film,'' she says, adding that she has taken issue with
some of the marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not particularly in love with the poster. {hellip} I feel
the trailer gives a lot away,'' she says. ``Just that kind of
stuff. It's a crapshoot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But then, at the same time, I look at posters and I look at
trailers, and I think my materials are actually pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
<P>
   Karyn Kusama
</P>
</TEXT>
