NYT-09-29-00 0801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 08:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6220 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-GIRLFIGHT-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      09-29 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLFIGHT-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
Formula KOs talent in `Girlfight' ring &HT;     BC-GIRLFIGHT-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `GIRLFIGHT THE SORT OF MOVIE THAT WEARS YOU OUT(a) 
 &HT;    (With GIRLFIGHT-DIRECTOR sidebar) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Girlfight is the sort of movie that wears you out.
</P>
<P>
   It's well-written and features a solid performance from Michelle
Rodriguez in the leading role, but it's so unrelentingly morose
that it becomes hard to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The movie seems to be purposely shot in bleak colors: grays,
blues and browns, and the settings are uniformly dark and dingy.
Yes, this is a movie about the inner city, but the first dozen
tenement shots sort of bring that home. And, hey, doesn't at least
one tree grow in Brooklyn?
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez plays Diana, an underprivileged teenager with family
troubles and a chip on her shoulder. After getting into several
fights at school, Diana decides to put her aggression to good use
and train as a boxer.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Rodriguez is the best thing in the movie. She plays
Diana with gritty intensity, and her reactions seem perfectly
natural and unrehearsed, as if she's completely unaware of the
camera.
</P>
<P>
   And because Rodriguez really creates a character you can root
for, some will find the film uplifting. At times you wish she would
lighten up a bit, but you could argue it's just not in her nature.
</P>
<P>
   The big problem with (beginitalic)Girlfight (enditalic)is that
it should be a non-traditional sports movie, but it's really not.
Except for a female being cast in the lead role,
(beginitalic)Girlfight (enditalic)follows the standard path of the
young fighter who must train like mad and overcome adversity to
come out on top.
</P>
<P>
   So (beginitalic)Girlfight (enditalic)ends up being
very-well-done formula, but formula all the same.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there are the usual raised eyebrows when Diana
shows up at a gym filled with guys to begin her training. But
because the movie must be more than 10minutes long, she ultimately
signs on with Hector (Jaime Tirelli), a wizened old trainer who
obviously attended the Burgess Meredith School of Cornermen and
Sages.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Diana must keep her training secret from her
dismissive father, Sandro (Paul Calderon), who is trying to
encourage her bookish brother to box. There are the usual fights at
the dinner table and other domestic squabbles as Diana battles for
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Her dad is sort of the central-casting domestic abuser that
always ends up in this type of movie. He can't understand his
daughter's love of boxing, or even bother to show up. Instead, he
just yells at her a lot, and we soon learn that he used to beat up
Diana's mom when she was still in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the film deserves credit for its
authentic-looking boxing sequences, which don't make every punch a
haymaker or every fighter a young Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Diana herself is no overnight sensation. She has to train hard
to get better, and never is able to walk into the ring and knock
out her opponent with one punch. In a way, the movie might have
been better served with more boxing and less angst, which actually
may have lightened the tone.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, (beginitalic)Girlfight (enditalic)packs some
emotional punch. You just might want to duck.
</P>
<P>
   Reach Bill Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
