<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 08:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6221 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-EXORCIST-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      09-29 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXORCIST-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-EXORCIST-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    RE-RELEASED `EXORCIST' SCARES UP NEW FOLLOWING(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've only seen (beginitalic)The Exorcist (enditalic)on
television, you haven't really seen (beginitalic)The
Exorcist(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   The terrifying tale of a possessed girl is a big-screen movie,
plain and simple. It is carefully constructed, filled with nuance,
designed to build fear one minute at a time. There can be no
escape, no break, just the horror unfolding before your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the scariest movie ever made, (beginitalic)The Exorcist
(enditalic)became an instant cultural phenomenon after it was
released in 1973. At theaters around the country, there were
reports of people collapsing or running out screaming.
</P>
<P>
   Those who were too young to see it at the movies heard about the
``bad parts'' from older siblings, or whispered during recess.
Everyone knew about the ``pea soup'' projectile vomit, the spinning
head, the levitating bed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many children of the '70s first saw the film on TV,
heavily edited and interrupted by commercials. It was still scary,
but Mr.Whipple gave you a chance to catch your breath.
</P>
<P>
   By the time cable and VCRs came around, (beginitalic)The
Exorcist (enditalic)already had been quoted, copied and parodied to
death. We could watch the original, uncut version, but only on the
small screen, which drained much of its remarkable power.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner Bros.' decision to re-release the film gives an
entire generation a chance finally to see director William
Friedkin's frightening masterpiece in all its glory.
</P>
<P>
   The studio has added 11minutes of unseen footage, including the
so-called ``spider walk'' sequence (you'll know it when you see
it), some subliminal flashes of the devil's face, and a new,
slightly more windy ending. It also seems like the demon that
possesses Linda Blair's character is even more foul-mouthed than
before.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest improvement was adding six-track digital surround
sound, especially because the film's unique soundtrack plays a key
role in (beginitalic)The Exorcist's (enditalic)ability to whip up
fear.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on a bestseller by William Peter Blatty, which
was inspired by an actual exorcism in the Washington, D.C., area.
</P>
<P>
   Although the movie is known for being frightening, Friedkin
actually spent quite a bit of time developing his characters and
building tension and suspense.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie opens, we watch Father Merrin (Max von Sydow)
search through a Persian archaeological dig and come across an evil
artifact.
</P>
<P>
   Then the story switches to Georgetown, where we meet Regan
(Blair), a happy young girl who lives with her actress mother,
Chris MacNeil (Ellen Burstyn), in a beautiful home. At first,
everything seems fine, but Chris starts hearing odd noises coming
from the attic.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Regan becomes afflicted with a strange ailment, which
has her speaking in a guttural voice and thrashing all over her
room. Doctors run countless tests but ultimately are stumped.
</P>
<P>
   Regan's condition worsens until she is hardly recognizable, tied
to her bed to prevent her from hurting herself or others. As
experts scratch their heads, Chris consults Father Karras (Jason
Miller), a priest who also has training in psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Though he's initially skeptical, Karras ultimately asks
permission to summon Merrin for a secret ritual known as an
exorcism. That's when this movie really starts to get scary.
</P>
<P>
   You may have seen it on TV, but it's time to check out
(beginitalic)The Exorcist (enditalic)on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   But look out for those nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
