<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 08:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-BEAUTIFUL-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      09-29 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUTIFUL-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-BEAUTIFUL-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ``BEAUTIFUL' FULL OF WARTS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beautiful just doesn't know what it wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   With the casting of Hallie Kate Eisenberg (the 7-year-old from
the Pepsi commercials), the movie seems to be making a major push
for the cute vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the plot is nowhere near cute. In fact, it's pretty darned
ugly.
</P>
<P>
   The film focuses on Mona (Minnie Driver), a ruthless woman so
eager to win beauty pageants that she turns her back on her
illegitimate daughter, Vanessa (Eisenberg). Because pageants
usually don't allow mothers to be contestants, Mona pretends that
the girl belongs to her best friend, Ruby (Joey Lauren Adams).
</P>
<P>
   And get this: Mona doesn't even tell Vanessa that she is her
mother, even though the two look very much alike. Instead, she lets
Ruby raise the girl while Mona pretends she's just a roommate.
</P>
<P>
   As my pal Daffy Duck used to say, ``Despicable.''
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Beautiful (enditalic)is supposed to be a comedy,
but it's just not all that funny to watch poor little Vanessa try
to figure out who her mommy is.
</P>
<P>
   This is Sally Field's first stint as a director, and it's too
bad she couldn't get a better script.
</P>
<P>
   The basic premise is contrived. We're never told how Mona
manages to hide her pregnancy - in a pretty small-looking town -
and then transfer the child to Ruby without anyone tumbling. We
don't even get a little two-minute scene of a pregnant Mona moving
away.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as Mona rises through the beauty pageant ranks, not a
single neighbor or relative asks the obvious question. It's just
really hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Mona's selfish, boorish behavior, which supposedly
comes from a bad childhood, isn't limited to the treatment of her
own daughter. She sabotages other beauty contestants, including a
woman who receives a horribly scarred hand from the ordeal. For
good measure, she exploits a pregnant woman and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   All of this really gives (beginitalic)Beautiful(enditalic)
nowhere to go. Because this is a movie, we know that Mona can't
stay evil forever, but by the time she repents, we're really not
that eager to forgive her.
</P>
<P>
   The bright spot of the film is Eisenberg, who is very cute and
perky as young Vanessa. In fact, she may be the only thing that was
keeping Driver awake through this one.
</P>
<P>
   Driver never really looks comfortable in the beauty queen
get-ups, though she wears them through most of the film. And she
never achieves the plastic Barbie sheen of a true beauty
contestant.
</P>
<P>
   In the last half-hour, the movie decides that it must show us
most of the fictional beauty pageant, complete with talent
competition and evening gowns. Real pageants are dull enough
without having to sit through a phony one.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, (beginitalic)Beautiful (enditalic)will never win Miss
Congeniality.
</P>
<P>
   Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
