<HEADLINE>
$ADV04 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, Oct. 04, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We hate to say it, but tonight really is must-see viewing for
NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The appetizer is the premiere of Aaron Spelling's ``Titans,'' at
8. The peacock network is advertising this as a guilty pleasure,
and that's about right _ it's a total throwback to the prime-time
soaps of the ``Dallas''/``Dynasty'' era, but it's a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Principal and Perry King play a rich divorced couple
who live across the street from each other in Beverly Hills.
Yasmine Bleeth is King's new bride-to-be. And Casper Van Dien is
the long-absent son who returns to find that he already knows Dad's
intended _ very, very well. And those are just the highlights of
the family dysfunction. The title refers to the family's aerospace
business, but don't worry, you won't have to know anything about
flying to enjoy this trashy bit of fun.
</P>
<P>
   The main course, however, is the two-hour season premiere of
``West Wing,'' beginning at 9. This White House drama won nine
Emmys a few weeks ago, wiping the floor with HBO's superior ``The
Sopranos.'' We could be bitter about that, but this is a very good
ensemble drama that actually touches on big issues in a meaningful
way, and for that we should be grateful. Martin Sheen is at the top
of his game as President Bartlet, and Allison Janney is the best of
a sterling cast of White House aides and political players.
</P>
<P>
   The show's fans were divided on the cliffhanger shooting at the
end of last season _ shocking and powerful or merely crass TV
melodrama? In any case, tonight we'll find out who got shot and
maybe even why.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Live from Lincoln Center,'' PBS at 8: An operatic concert with
soprano Renee Fleming and baritone Dmitri Hvorostovsky.
</P>
<P>
   ''34th Annual Country Music Association Awards,'' CBS at 8:
Vince Gill hosts the live, three-hour CMA show from the Grand Ole
Opry in Nashville. The Dixie Chicks and Faith Hill are among the
scheduled performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC at 8: Regis Philbin
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's Creek,'' WB at 8: Season premiere. Joey and Pacey
return from their romantic maritime adventure, and we all sigh
jealously.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball playoffs, Fox at 8: Teams TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew Carey Show,'' ABC at 9: Season premiere. Drew gets fired
from the store. Would you hire him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Norm,'' ABC at 9:30: Season premiere. Mr. Denby (Max Wright)
asserts himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felicity,'' WB at 9: Season premiere. Felicity returns to
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek: Voyager,'' UPN at 9: Season premiere. The Borg
Queen attacks. This is actually part two of the ``Ultimatrix Zero''
episode. Part one repeats at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mailer on Mailer,'' PBS at 10: An ``American Masters''
interview with the author.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry and the Hendersons,'' Disney Channel at 8:40: The great
John Lithgow (``Third Rock from the Sun'') stars in this gentle
1987 comedy about a family that runs into Bigfoot _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``FFANY Shoes on Sale,'' QVC at 7: OK, normally your
home-shopping channels aren't going to get mentioned in this
column. But this three-hour special highlights October as Breast
Cancer Awareness Month 2000. Members of the Fashion Footwear
Association of New York have donated 80,000 pairs of shoes that
will be sold at half their retail price this month to benefit five
hospitals engaged in breast cancer research. Joan Rivers hosts this
seventh-annual kickoff event live from New York's Pier 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City,'' HBO at 9: Charlotte and Samantha clash.
First aired Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul Food,'' Showtime at 10: Teri faces up to her feelings for
Miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside the Actor's Studio,'' Bravo at 10: Harrison Ford talks
about his roles. Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oz,'' HBO at 10: A crime puts the prison into lockdown.
Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Farrah Fawcett
and the great Loretta Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Norm MacDonald,
Spinal Tap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05 a.m.:
TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35: Willie
Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Joshua Jackson
of ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
