<HEADER>
A6399 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN0930-CO     09-29 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three's really the charm
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ My husband is a man of principle.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way, Jim declared, that our family would ever be a
three-cat family. Two cats? Maybe. But three cats, as he put it so
tactfully, ``bordered on crazy-cat-lady status.''
</P>
<P>
   My children are children of steadfast heart. There is no way,
they declared, that any cat would supplant Stella _ our great gray
cat who died in January _ in their affections.
</P>
<P>
   We have tried to be sensitive to their feelings. There has been
a lot of condescending adult talk about how Stella is in heaven and
how ``we're holding Stella in our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Stella is in our hearts and Stella is in heaven, does that
mean heaven is in our heart?'' asked Veronica, our fledgling
philosopher. But after a proper period of mourning, we felt ready,
early this summer, for another cat. One cat, for starters.
</P>
<P>
   Enter a magnificent orange-and-white cat whose owner had found
abandoned. Her other cats hadn't taken to the newcomer, so she was
looking for a new home.
</P>
<P>
   We would take the cat on a ``trial basis,'' we decided, while
his owner was on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   He had a name before he was in the car two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Having recently seen the Masterpiece Theatre production of
``David Copperfield,'' we thought Dickens.
</P>
<P>
   Jim proposed the more obscure but ironic name of ``Barkis,''
after the suitor of David's nursemaid Peggotty _ the character
known for that most concise of great literary lines, ``Barkis is
willin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Alec was thinking mainstream. ``Oliver,'' he said decisively.
``He's Oliver.'' And Oliver he was, a name that seemed to suit his
wayfarer status.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later, after Oliver had adjusted to his new home,
our friends Brian and Dea rescued a mother cat and four kittens
after one of the kittens became trapped in the sewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only takes one look,'' says my mother, an incorrigible cat
lover, and it only took one look for us all to agree to take home a
sleek black-and-gray tiger stripe kitten with inquiring eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Once again Jim hopefully suggested the name ``Barkis.'' Once
again the kids and I overruled him in naming the newcomer Dodger,
as in Oliver's artful accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   I also had my eye on Dodger's shy brother _ almost his twin
except for his gray-and-white markings and white socked feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Jim thundered, muttering something under his
breath about ``crazy cat woman.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been 18 years since I had a kitten in my life, and we all
fell irresistibly in love.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica carted Dodger around the house like a teddy bear, but
he never seemed to mind. She came to me one morning, Dodger scooped
in her arms, her brown eyes solemn. ``I'm holding Stella in my
heart,'' she said, as if guilty to be so attached to the
interloper.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger took to Jim the way cats always take to non-cat lovers.
``He likes me best,'' Jim observed. ``Do you notice how he always
snuggles up to me? And how loudly he purrs?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I agreed. ``He likes you best. But don't you think he
needs a playmate for the times when you're not here?''
</P>
<P>
   Jim agreed wholeheartedly: Dodger needed a companion. Oliver
tolerated him, not bothering any more with the perfunctory hiss,
but spurned overtures at friendship.
</P>
<P>
   While we're still holding Stella in our hearts, we find we still
have room there for not one, not two, but three new cats.
</P>
<P>
   The sock-footed cat, lo and be- hold, was still available for
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Barkis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
