<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6400 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MINTER-COLUMN0930-COX     09-29 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After being pilloried in Washington, Bert Lance finally honored
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Many years ago I knew a writer in New York who loved
to boast about what he considered the greatest accomplishment of
his moderately distinguished career. He sold Reader's Digest
articles on three different people for the magazine's then premier
feature, ``The Most Unforgettable Character I've Ever Known.''
</P>
<P>
   In later years, and more appropriate to the times,
``Unforgettable Character'' became ``Unforgettable Personality.''
The subject almost always was someone who had triumphed over great
adversity, usually with a sense of humor, humility and
perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny September morning at the Resaca rest stop north of
Calhoun, Ga., on I-75, the thought came to me that if I were trying
to sell the Digest a story about my own most unforgettable
personality, I might need two or three cracks. But I would start
with Bert Lance.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of a century ago Bert Lance was the designated
scapegoat of an upstart Carter administration that had usurped the
Washington establishment. Jimmy Carter had appointed him director
of the Office of Management and Budget, a job sometimes described
as general manager of the United States government. After
Watergate, Republicans, media sharks and some disgruntled Democrats
needed another scandal. Lance was elected.
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Georgia he had sinned terribly. He had run his bank
with his heart as well as his head. He had made some of his loans
on faith, out of a desire to help somebody he knew and trusted.
Never mind that he had never cost a single depositor a single dime,
and that Calhoun and Gordon County were dotted with businesses
started on one of those loans from Bert Lance's bank.
</P>
<P>
   A good banker shouldn't do things like marking over $100 to the
account when the young Baptist preacher in town had insufficient
funds to pay the grocery bill.
</P>
<P>
   Finally acquitted, he walked out of a federal courthouse in
Atlanta and went home to his roses and his apple trees on a high
hill in Gordon County, vowing to go without rancor. ``Bitterness,''
he said, ``breeds destruction.'' So there we were on a cool
September morning beside I-75 in Resaca, unveiling a sign that read
``Bert Lance Highway,'' an overdue recognition for the state's
first commissioner of the Department of Transportation and catalyst
for the completion of Georgia's superb interstate highway system.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a quarter of a century after leaving his Washington post
as the second most powerful man in the country, Bert Lance drew a
crowd to make presidential candidates envious. Gov. Roy Barnes was
there, along with former Gov. Joe Frank Harris, local and state
officials, legislators, a battalion of volunteers from a long-ago
gubernatorial campaign, newspaper folks, neighbors, and friends
from a lifetime of public and community service.
</P>
<P>
   The governors, present and past, and other distinguished
speakers gave eloquent tributes, pointing out that the honor was
much deserved and long overdue. Nobody put it better than an old
friend who was busy in Washington and had to write a letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Bert,
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Shirley and I could be with you, LaBelle and the family
for this important event.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one deserves having a section of one of the main
transportation arteries in this nation named in their honor more
than you. For more than four decades you have served the state and
this nation in an exemplary way.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has been a greater visionary for what Georgia could
become than you. No one has brought more common sense and
progressive thinking to public life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those highway signs will stand as a monument to your work and
your life, but many of us know that there are many more unnamed
monuments to Bert Lance from Brasstown Bald to the Okefenokee.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time we were in the first grade together you have
been a friend and your advice not to copy your arithmetic paper was
as right as your advice to accept this new challenge in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are precious to the Miller family. You have always been
there for us when we needed you. I'll never forget who was there
first when my mother died. I respect you. I admire you. I love you.
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely, Zell Miller''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people, if blessed with Zell Miller's talent with
words, could write such a letter to Bert Lance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
