<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6401 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0930-C     09-29 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The smell made me do it
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Dogs sniff one another because they are
communicating on some basic level.
</P>
<P>
   They are communicating with pheromones, odorless molecules that
waft from most animals. These powerful molecules carry important
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Pheromones tell animals what they are supposed to do, such as
run, fight or have sex.
</P>
<P>
   The nice thing about pheromone messages is that animals don't
have to worry if they are making the right decision. They have no
self-doubt. They are not conflicted. They don't worry about the
morality or repercussions of their pheromone-induced actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it smelled right, so I did it. What's the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists reason that humans also release and react to
pheromone messages.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists figure that humans have evolved beyond the use
of pheromones for cues that control behavior. Our superior brains
supposedly allow us to make these decisions without interference of
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ACTIONS CONTROLLED BY ODORS
</P>
<P>
   People concerned with religion and morals don't like the idea
that human behavior might be controlled by odors. Humans are
supposed to make decisions based on reason and concepts of right
and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Neurogeneticists at Yale and Rockefeller Universities now say
they have isolated a human gene, V1RL1, that encodes for a
pheromone receptor in the mucous lining of the nose _ human noses.
</P>
<P>
   So far, these scientists don't know whether people use this gene
as a part of a message system to communicate primal urges. It that
is the case, scientists also don't know which urge is be triggered.
</P>
<P>
   One scientist, Joseph Falke, a biochemist at the University of
Colorado, told the Associated Press that the next job is ``to find
a pheromone that binds to the receptor and triggers a measurable
physiological response.''
</P>
<P>
   These researchers will float pheromone molecules out to the
noses of test subjects and see if they are overcome with the urge
to have sex, fight, flee, build a nest or whatever pheromone
messages do.
</P>
<P>
   Mice have more than 100 functioning genes. It's hard to imagine
what 100 mice messages might contain. Perhaps animals can read
pheromone messages from other animals.
</P>
<P>
   This may be why dogs take an instant dislike to some people and
form quick friendships with other people.
</P>
<P>
   People who like animals may smell different. There may be
pheromones for fear, love, hate, fidelity, strength, weakness,
health and the like.
</P>
<P>
   If true, scientists might do the human race a favor if they
kick-start the human pheromone message center.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, people are making a mess of things by using their
judgment to make basic decisions.
</P>
<P>
   It might be better to smell whether your sweetheart really loves
you or whether the used car salesman is telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Some perfume manufacturers already sell fragrances that claim to
contain pheromones that attract the opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   Musk ox cologne supposedly has such a pheromone. Not many
people, however, want to attract huge, smelly bovines.
</P>
<P>
   Other fragrances claim to have actual human pheromones.
Insomniacs can buy these fragrances late at night on obscure cable
channels. These fragrances supposedly attract men or women,
depending on your tastes. Bisexuals must use both fragrances
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists know that hormones often override judgment and common
sense in many people. Why not pheromones? The Associated Press
story failed to say who is funding this research and what they
intend to do with it. Someone needs to find out if Bill Gates is
behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
