<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6402 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0930-CO     09-29 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Benches are simple, so dive in and make your own customized
plans
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once again I have been asked if I can provide plans
for an object that I've never heard of or seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to know if you have plans for a viewing bench for
a pool room, or where I could obtain one,'' a reader asks via
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   First, I have no plans, other than retirement as soon as it can
be arranged. Second, I'm not sure what a viewing bench for a pool
room entails. However, benches are pretty simple things, and I
would encourage my correspondent to forge ahead without commercial
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume that a viewing bench for a pool room needs to be
high enough to allow seated viewers to see what goes on atop the
table. Presumably that's the only thing that separates it from an
ordinary bench.
</P>
<P>
   Since I have no available measurements for a pool table, and I
don't know how far from the table the bench might be located, it
will be up to the correspondent to determine how high it should be.
I should think 2- 1/2 to 3 feet from the floor to the seat would be
in the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing to determine is how many people it should seat.
For the sake of argument, let's say four. More than that and we
might want to make two benches. Let's make it out of a good strong
wood, but not too hard to work. How about maple?
</P>
<P>
   Now, we want plenty of support, so let's make this fellow an
eight-legged bench, four in the front, four in the back. An
octobench, if you will. (You probably won't, but it was worth a
try.)
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to do is draw this octobench out to scale, an
inch to a foot. The undercarriage will need to have runners
connecting all the legs about halfway between the bottom of the
seat and the floor. If you want a back on it, extend the back legs
up high enough to support the back.
</P>
<P>
   Since it might be difficult to find 16/4 maple _ not to mention
its frightful expense _ let's laminate the legs from two pieces of
8/4 stock. This will also allow us to use bridle joints, rather
than mortise and tenons, to connect the runners and the seat
supports front and back. Mortise and tenons, however, will be
needed to connect the front of the understructure to the back. The
seat supports ought to be 4/4 stock about six inches wide. The
runners ought to be about three inches wide in 4/4 stock.
</P>
<P>
   The bench seat itself, of course, can be laminated from 4/4
stock, or if you want something airy you can put a half-inch of
separation between the planks. To make a comfortable back, the
uprights should be tapered back after they rise above the seat, so
the folks sitting on the bench can lean back a little. The boards
of the back could be let into the uprights; no more of a joint than
that would be required to make them very solid.
</P>
<P>
   You can make a lot of changes on this very simple bench, of
course, all without following anyone else's plans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
