<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week. The
layout is available now. )
</P>
<P>
   COXNET HEALTHY LIVING 0926 -- As the annual breast cancer
awareness campaign gets under way next month, women with a genetic
risk for breast cancer will seem to be everywhere. But they are the
exception. Of the 182,800 women diagnosed with the disease this
year, only 5 percent to 10 percent of the cases will be attributed
to the mutated genes known to raise risks of breast cancer
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 4-column color
illustration showing the facts about breast cancer and a 2-column
color photo of a teacher who has a high incidence of breast cancer
in her family.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ON THE WEB -- A new Web site created by the Harvard Center
for Cancer Prevention, an arm of Harvard Medical School, shows you
your cancer risk. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes a 6-pica color illustration of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HOSPICE CARE -- More terminally ill elderly people are
receiving hospice care, but for shorter lengths of time before
their death, according to a recently released congressional report.
(Lippman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: COMMENTARY -- As much as we need to open our minds and
mouths on the subject of dying, there are dangers when the hospice
movement glamorizes death the same way ``Friends'' makes New York
City look like a charming and affordable place for young adults.
(Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   END OF COXNET PAGE
</P>
<P>
   TELESCOPE _ Hal McAlister discovered the wonders of the night as
a fourth grader growing up in Chattanooga, captivated by the ``old
musty smell'' of a local observatory and the ability to see beyond
the limits of human vision. Now, at 51, he is about to realize the
dream of many youthful stargazers. Next month, Georgia State
University will dedicate an innovative new $13.5 million telescope
array high stop California's Mount Wilson _ one that will be able
to ``see'' distant stars as never before, exceeding even the limits
of the Hubble Space Telescope. In a way, the array of six
telescopes marks the realization of two parallel dreams _
McAlister's boyhood quest to probe the mysteries of the night sky
and Georgia's State's hopes of carving out a name for itself in
21st century astronomy. (Toner, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   TWIN-CONNECTION _ If it were written as a TV sitcom, the premise
would be rejected as ridiculous. Two strangers from Clark County,
Ohio, both redheads named Amy, are due to deliver twins within days
of each other. Both deliver twin girls. Both decide to be original
with their babies' names. Both choose Sidney (Sydney) and Savanna.
Both Savannas develop health complications requiring surgery. And
the women's friendship starts when a Dayton Children's Hospital
nurse makes the connection and tells Amy Combs, ``There's someone I
think you ought to meet.'' (Trump, Springfield News-Sun). WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CIVILWAR-REENACT _ A personal account of getting involved with
Civil War re-enactments _ as well as where in the heck you buy
those uniforms. (Nurse, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLTOWN-ART _ HAMILTON, Ohio _ Can you imagine a small city
basing its hopes on fine art? On sculpture? Is that too much of a
stretch? Hamilton, Ohio, hopes not. It recently designated itself
``The City of Sculpture,'' and installed an imposing piece of
public art in front of the new government center to make the point.
</P>
<P>
   (Dayton Daily News). 26. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ ATLANTA _ Once again I have been
asked if I can provide plans for an object that I've never heard of
or seen. ``I would like to know if you have plans for a viewing
bench for a pool room, or where I could obtain one,'' a reader asks
via e-mail. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CUECAT _ Some people find navigating the Internet kind of tricky
and would like to avoid typing in complicated Web site addresses
when they can. A new free device called :CueCat( The colon is cq)
was tailor-made for those reluctant explorers. :CueCat is a
hand-held scanner that lets Internet users locate a specific Web
site instantly by swiping the :CueCat across a bar code. (Cummings,
Dayton Daily News) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the
current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0923 -- It's hard to keep the weight down on a
cruise ship with tempting food at every turn. A reporter keeps a
seven-day journal of her battle with the temptations at sea. Final
score: MS Veendam: 50,000 gross tons; reporter, two pounds lighter.
(Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   with 4 col. illustration and 2 col. photo
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CRUISING -- Some of us are cruise people. Some of us are
not. Teen-agers are probably all cruise people, if you are in the
Caribbean and there are plenty of other teen-agers around. But
cruising is definitely not for everyone. (Thurman, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BARGES-- Now's the time to snap up a late-season deal on
barge cruises in France. (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
