<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week. The
layout is available now. )
</P>
<P>
   COXNET HEALTHY LIVING 0926 -- As the annual breast cancer
awareness campaign gets under way next month, women with a genetic
risk for breast cancer will seem to be everywhere. But they are the
exception. Of the 182,800 women diagnosed with the disease this
year, only 5 percent to 10 percent of the cases will be attributed
to the mutated genes known to raise risks of breast cancer
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 4-column color
illustration showing the facts about breast cancer and a 2-column
color photo of a teacher who has a high incidence of breast cancer
in her family.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ON THE WEB -- A new Web site created by the Harvard Center
for Cancer Prevention, an arm of Harvard Medical School, shows you
your cancer risk. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes a 6-pica color illustration of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HOSPICE CARE -- More terminally ill elderly people are
receiving hospice care, but for shorter lengths of time before
their death, according to a recently released congressional report.
(Lippman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: COMMENTARY -- As much as we need to open our minds and
mouths on the subject of dying, there are dangers when the hospice
movement glamorizes death the same way ``Friends'' makes New York
City look like a charming and affordable place for young adults.
(Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   END OF COXNET PAGE
</P>
<P>
   TELESCOPE _ Hal McAlister discovered the wonders of the night as
a fourth grader growing up in Chattanooga, captivated by the ``old
musty smell'' of a local observatory and the ability to see beyond
the limits of human vision. Now, at 51, he is about to realize the
dream of many youthful stargazers. Next month, Georgia State
University will dedicate an innovative new $13.5 million telescope
array high stop California's Mount Wilson _ one that will be able
to ``see'' distant stars as never before, exceeding even the limits
of the Hubble Space Telescope. In a way, the array of six
telescopes marks the realization of two parallel dreams _
McAlister's boyhood quest to probe the mysteries of the night sky
and Georgia's State's hopes of carving out a name for itself in
21st century astronomy. (Toner, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
