<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6419 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     09-29 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Friday, Sept. 29, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday or
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHARPSHOOTER-PROTESTS (Sonoma, Calif.) _ The effort by the
Sonoma County wine grape growers and their supporters to
soft-peddle possible adverse effects of the county's battle plan
against the glassy-winged sharpshooter was a flop. County
environmentalists turned out in force Thursday night to warn that
any attempt at mandatory pesticide spraying of inhabited areas
where a sharpshooter infestation was detected would be met with
stiff resistance. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PROFILING (San Antonio) _ Amid growing national concern
over racial profiling, the Texas Department of Public Safety has
acknowledged that it has been keeping detailed information since
March 1 about the race and sex of all people stopped by DPS
troopers. By DARYL BELL and RUDOLPH BUSH.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL (San Antonio) _ The U.S. Border Patrol says
cyberspace and an emphasis on recruiting helped it grow
dramatically this year. An increase of approximately 900 agents
brings the patrol's size to 9,061 _ the largest in its 76-year
history _ but it is still scrambling to meet a congressional call
for 10,000 agents by this time next year. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Apple Computer is warning that
its upcoming earnings report would be substantially below
expectations because of a sales downturn in September. The company
said it expected to report fiscal fourth-quarter earnings of
between $1.85 and $1.9 billion, representing a gain of 30 to 33
cents per share for investors. Wall Street analysts were expecting
Apple to report revenue somewhere near 45 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-WESTWING-REVIEW (Undated) _ The only downside to having as
great a season as ``The West Wing'' did is that everyone expects
you to do it again. When you are the best drama on network
television, you are judged only against yourself. After a brilliant
first season that culminated with nine Emmy wins _ including Best
Drama _ critical and ratings success and a controversial
cliff-hanger finale that left some television reviewers steaming,
``The West Wing'' returns next week in the season's most
anticipated premiere. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-THATSLIFE-REVIEW - The premise of CBS' ``That's Life'' isn't
Entirely new. Heather Paige Kent plays a late-blooming college
freshman just as Rhea Perlman did on ``Pearl,'' which bombed a few
seasons ago. That's life on television, though _ and this show has
a lot more going for it than ``Pearl'' ever did. The pilot airing
Sunday is good enough to bring you back next Saturday, when the
show moves into its regular time slot. By ANN HODGES.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-TAPE-REVIEWS (Undated) _ ``The Judas Judge,'' by Michael
McGarrity. Read by Bruce Greenwood. Abridged, approximately 4.5
hours. Simon &AMP; Schuster Audio. $25. It doesn't seem right that a
retired law enforcement officer can evolve into as skilled a writer
as McGarrity. Even if it's a matter of writing about what he knows
best _ New Mexico, state police and sex crimes _ he's doing it
well. By DOUG BLACKBURN. (For release Sunday, Oct. 1.)
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ALAMO-HISTORY (San Antonio) _ A bronze howitzer shell of the
same type fired on the Alamo in 1836 by Mexican troops goes on
exhibit at the Alamo Gift Museum on Saturday as part of Texas
Archeological Awareness Month. A wooden fuse and gunpowder removed
from the shell as well as other items left behind by the Mexican
army after the Battle of San Jacinto also will be on display, Alamo
historian Bruce Winders said. By CARMINA DANINI.
</P>
<P>
   GARDENCOLUMN - Houston Chronicle garden editor Kathy Huber
answers
</P>
<P>
   questions from readers on gardening topics.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWIM (Sydney, Australia) _ An American Olympic dynasty ended
on Friday, and it didn't involve a basketball, a softball or any of
the usual paraphernalia filling sporting-good stockrooms. The
synchronized swimming team, which had won a gold medal at every
Summer Games since the event joined the Olympic program in 1984,
finished fifth. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-REPORTER'S-JOURNAL (Sydney, Australia) _ I'm going for the
gold. It's down to the quarterfinals. Wish me luck. The sport, a
new one on the program at Sydney 2000, is Cell Phone Avoidance.
I've been in Australia 20 days now and haven't used a cell phone
once. That places me in a highly elite category of Stone Age
scribes who refuse to make concessions to this modern world of
ours. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
</TEXT>
