<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S SECRET CODE TOO SECRET FOR USERS' GOOD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I just installed a new hard drive. Now I need
the serial number for my Windows 95 disk. I bought this machine
secondhand, so I have never had the number.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wrong Number
</P>
<P>
   DEAR WRONG: No, you've always had the number. You just don't
know where it is.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most irritating aspects of installing and
reinstalling a Microsoft product is having to keep track of some
25-character string of gibberish. Lose the product key, and you
might as well buy another copy of the software.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I understand that Microsoft is worried about bootleggers,
but this key thing isn't the way to handle the problem. In the
first place, it's inconvenient for the user. It's usually pasted to
the back of the CD jewel case or on an accompanying card. I don't
know about you, but these are among the most likely items in my
computer room to be trodden upon, covered with spilled margarita
mix and taken out with the trash. If the geniuses at Microsoft can
label a CD with some fancy hologram, they can sure stick a stupid
serial number on there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Second, all it takes is one ``borrowed'' key and a counterfeiter
can start cranking out thousands of copies of Windows Me, or you
can reinstall Win95. So what, exactly, is the number protecting?
Microsoft should trust its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry to get off on a rant, but it seems I've lost my Office
2000 product key, and I'm in a rather foul mood about that.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, back to your Windows key: It's on your old hard drive,
if that still works. Just fire up Regedit (go to the Start menu,
select Run, type ``regedit'' in the blank and hit Enter). When the
Registry Editor is running, open the Edit menu and select Find.
Look for ``ProductKey'' (that's right, no spaces), and Regedit will
display the secret code.
</P>
<P>
   And here's a little hint that my close personal friend Heloise
will probably try to claim she came up with first: Get yourself a
Sharpie and scribble that number on the CD before you lose it
again. And, no, you can't write on the shiny side.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Here's an easy one for you: Is it more
practical to put the computer to sleep (on standby) or to turn it
off entirely when I know I will not be using it for the next 12 to
48 hours? I have it scheduled to defrag once a week at midnight
while I am sleeping. Will turning it off interfere with that
scheduled task?
</P>
<P>
   _ Perchance to Dream
</P>
<P>
   DEAR PERCHANCE: Uh, yeah, turning off the computer will most
definitely interfere with anything it's expected to do since it's,
you know, off.
</P>
<P>
   Listen, there's no reason to leave your computer on if you're
not going to be using it, unless you like helping the electric
company with its profit-loss margin. And there's really no task
that absolutely has to be performed in the middle of the night.
Personally, I don't like my computer doing things when I'm not
around to intercept error messages and make judgment calls.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's definitely a good idea to defrag the hard drive
occasionally. Windows Disk Defragmenter (in System Tools)
rearranges all the stuff on the drive so it can be retrieved or
used more efficiently. But once a week is too often. Try it monthly
while you're busy with other important chores, like knocking back a
few frosty ones, watching beach volleyball on ESPN. See, there's
another original hint Heloise didn't give you. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The only hint Heloise ever gave noted computerologist Dr.
Emilio Bombay was ``Get a life, loser. You'll never be as famous as
me!'' Write him at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
