<HEADLINE>
POLLS HAVE POWER, BUT ANYTHING CAN STILL HAPPEN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yeah, it's true. The pro-Bush crowd got a little cocky when
their guy was racking up double-digit leads in the presidential
preference polls before the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But the Al-Gore-can't-lose gang went off the deep end, too, when
the Democratic nominee bounced out of his August convention with a
surge that carried him to commanding leads in some of the polls.
For a while there, the Democrats and the vice president's
cheerleaders in the media just about had us believing that Gore was
ready to write his inaugural address while George W. Bush was on
the verge of pulling his hat out of the ring and tossing in a
towel.
</P>
<P>
   So. We all learned the hard way _ again _ about putting too much
faith in polls that are, at best, nothing more than a snapshot of
the electorate's mood at any given moment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush-boosters _ and you can count me among them _ should be
careful, therefore, to keep their enthusiasm in check as the
Republican candidate rallies from the September swoon that so
encouraged his opponents and disheartened his supporters. Poll
results in recent days suggest that Bush has not only embarked on a
comeback but has reclaimed the lead in his up-down-up-again
campaign for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's leads over Gore in most of the polls that show him ahead,
of course, fall within the margin of error _ meaning that the race
is a statistical dead heat. As most of the experts have predicted
all along, the battle for the White House is shaping up as a
barnburner that could keep us in suspense until the very last votes
are counted on election night.
</P>
<P>
   But considering that some polls showed Gore ahead by significant
margins as recently as last week, it seems fair to conclude that
the momentum has swung back to Bush. Which is not to say that the
pendulum won't lurch toward Gore in a day or two _ or maybe before
the ink dries on this particular exercise in wild-eyed guesswork.
</P>
<P>
   As long as we're guessing, though, let's take a stab at figuring
out what has caused the latest turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   During the first few weeks of September, it looked as though
Gore might keep building his lead in the polls until the polls
became a self-fulfilling prophecy. Most experts on polling will
tell you that polls are a scientific measurement of public opinion
but are not predictive of the outcome of an election _ or at least
they're not supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that once a candidate establishes a comfortable
lead in the polls, voters begin to sense that the contest is over.
Supporters of the candidate who's behind tend to get discouraged
and lose interest; undecided voters tend to start moving toward the
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   The polls don't predict the winner, but they can influence the
next poll, which can influence the next poll, which can influence
the next poll ...
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the aura of inevitability engendered by a
candidate's dominance of the polls can't help but affect voters'
expectations _ and voters' expectations can't help but affect their
votes.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon could still occur in the 2000 presidential race.
The election is more than five weeks away. The debates between Bush
and Gore don't begin until Tuesday. When two spirited racehorses
are eyeball to eyeball heading into the home stretch, anything can
happen.
</P>
<P>
   But the question remains: Why didn't Gore run off and hide when
everything was going his way? He got a convention bounce that
turned into a surge. He was winning the argument on his favorite
issues _ or the media said he was, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my theory: Gore isn't winning the argument on the issues.
Voters are still weighing his philosophy of more government and
more taxes against Bush's belief that the government should help
those who need help and get out of everybody else's way.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and another thing. Lots of voters like the idea that Bush is
exactly what he seems to be. Like him or not, there's no denying
that when it comes to the governor of Texas, what you see is what
you get.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, on the other hand, continues to apply the old saying about
acting to the art of politics: It's mostly about sincerity _ if you
can fake that, you've got it made.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has too many personalities, too many ever-evolving points
of view. He has been, everyone remembers, Bill Clinton's right-hand
man. Clinton has been, among other things, the nation's Liar in
Chief.
</P>
<P>
   The connection surely gives pause to thoughtful voters.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
