<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN     09-29 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS OF THE TIMES: TEAMMATES SHARE THE PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo OLY 10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Nobody on the Dream Team ever wailed, ``Oh,
God, stop this,'' the way Mia Hamm did to inject a note of levity
during her team's cry-a-thon Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dream Team never lost, and probably never will, but the U.S.
soccer team did lose to their worthy opponent from Norway, which
only adds to their luster as the greatest American women's team _
ever.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning after, they wept and passed the tissue box. This
is no cliche about women, no stereotype of female athletes, just a
straight reportorial fact. They love each other much more than
their silver medals, and they cried when they talked about it.
</P>
<P>
   They were back at the Nike Center, where they had met their
families Thursday night after the crushing 3-2 loss in sudden death
to Norway in the Summer Games final, a game that can legitimately
be put on a list of great sports events.
</P>
<P>
   It is always fascinating to watch athletes take defeat. The Boys
of Summer, the Brooklyn Dodgers, once lost a baseball playoff game
on Oct. 3, 1951, to their own worthy opponents _ only nobody in
Brooklyn called the New York Giants exactly that. It took the
Dodgers a decade or two to come to grips with what Bobby Thomson
had done to them.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was far too soon for the American women to deal with the
goal Dagny Mellgren produced in the 102nd minute. There was only
time to focus on the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine having Jordan and Bird and Magic and Ewing on the same
team,'' said April Heinrichs, the coach with the red eyes. ``We
did. For 14 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of them have been together practically since women's soccer
was invented. There are children either born or projected, second
careers to be pursued. Carla Overbeck, the captain who never got on
the field here, noted, ``I am the only one who has said I'm
retiring, but it's not like we won't see each other.''
</P>
<P>
   They were there for each other Thursday night. With their silver
medals around their necks, they repaired to the Nike Center in an
industrial park.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least my family loves me,'' said Kristine Lilly, one of the
old hands. ``They told us how proud they are. We had a chance to
reflect. My family had a great time here.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve and Brenda Mullinix were there for their daughter, Siri.
When she was a little girl back in North Carolina, her father would
kick soccer balls at a goal in their back yard, or she would bounce
on a trampoline, ``where I learned to dive.'' It always felt right
having the other side take pot shots at her, rather than romping
around the field like the Milbretts and Foudys of the world.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, three balls crossed the line, including the
ball that plunked to earth, was kicked and then skimmed the ground,
touching her fingertips, skittering into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' Mullinix said Friday. ``Particularly because I
got a touch on it. You wonder, did I do everything I could? I think
I replayed that last goal 1,000 times last night.''
</P>
<P>
   And on one of those 1,000 times, did Mullinix stay just a tad
closer to home?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some balls get through you,'' Mullinix said. ``You get down,
you get a hand on it, you hope you would stop it. But I wouldn't
change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs did not want to talk tough on this day of days, but
she hinted at other retirements and allowed as how there were great
young athletes in the system. She talked about learning from the
energy of Nigeria, the relentlessness of Germany, and the
gold-medal status of Norway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great game,'' she said. ``If we'd won, it would have
been even greater. But the fact that we lost and I'm considering it
was a great game tells you how great it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiffeny Milbrett, who jumped higher for her header than a
5-foot-2 woman is supposed to, used the word ``numb.'' They were
operating on little sleep, and no gold medal, and they needed each
other. The only trouble was, whenever one would start talking about
each other, the box of tissues would start flying.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm started it, as she often does on the field, her voice
catching, her eyes tearing, her nose suddenly red. When she
finished talking, she rubbed her face with both hands and the box
of tissues came her way.
</P>
<P>
   They passed the tissues with the generosity and precision of a
great team, coach to keeper to defenders to midfielders to forwards
and back to the subs. They played like a team. They lost like a
team. They cried like a team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
