<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS NOT REASSURING WHEN IT COMES TO OPEN GOVERNMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By J.R. LABBE 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There is no right to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words, expelled from the lips of state Sen. David Sibley,
did little to comfort the assembled journalists at this month's
annual Freedom of Information conference in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In a panel discussion titled ``A view from the Lege,'' Texas
lawmakers were supposed to preview upcoming privacy issues that
they expect to address in the Legislature. What they did was scare
the bejeepers out of anyone listening who is remotely committed to
open government in the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they talked about privacy, all right, in such ``Chicken
Little, the sky is falling,'' rev-up-the-black-helicopters
hyperbole that some in the audience weren't sure whether they were
at an open government conference or a preparedness convention.
</P>
<P>
   If these legislators communicate with their constituents in this
same vein, it's no wonder they are being besieged by people
demanding that something be done about invasions of their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley of Waco, state Sen. Ken Armbrister of Victoria and state
Rep. Steve Wolens of Dallas described in patronizing tones
scenarios of cybersnoops run amok. Why, citizens are under virtual
assault 24/7, with everything from their credit card numbers to
their medical records in peril.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not once did these elected luminaries make clear that there
are two distinctly different kinds of records: public and private.
Questions from audience members about the muddying of these lines
were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, as the new millennium dawns with all its rapidly advancing
technology, privacy concerns loom large on the radar screens of
Americans. Which is all the more reason for men who purport to be
leaders to act as moderating, rational, sane participants in the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Credibility. Accountability. That's what open government is all
about.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley, Armbrister and Wolens should be actively working to make
sure that their constituents clearly understand the difference
between publicly held information and that collected by private or
commercial entities. Government records, with few special
exemptions, must be available to any and all who wish to review
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Public Information Act sums up what every legislator
should take to heart: ``The people, in delegating authority, do not
give their public servants the right to decide what is good for the
people to know and what is not good for them to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but I forget. These are politicians, who can ride a wave of
privacy hysteria right into re-election. Plus, they don't consider
the media to be constituents; we're adversaries. Never mind that
the media has no more _ or no less _ access to public information
than any citizen.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Brian McCall of Plano was the fourth panel member. He
was the lone lawmaker to bring a degree of sanity and a modicum of
humility to the table. The others exuded an attitude of superiority
and condescension that was alarming.
</P>
<P>
   Armbrister used as an example of an abuse of open records
someone who filed a Freedom of Information request for a list of
locations for a protected species of cactus. According to the
senator, the information was used to poach the plant for sale on
the black market.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it never occurred to Armbrister that the state
already has trespassing laws that should have taken care of the
criminal act. Instead, legislation was drafted to exempt the
endangered list from disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   How about if the state stopped asking people to catalogue the
flora and fauna on their private property? Then there won't be any
records to request.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Shipp, a reporter for Dallas-Fort Worth's WFAA/Channel 8
and a board member of the Freedom of Information Foundation of
Texas, asked each of the legislators to pledge that public
information currently available in paper form be made available
electronically. All were quick to respond in the affirmative, until
Wolens put on the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Wolens reminded his colleagues that when it came to disclosing
campaign finances, the Lege voted only to make available names and
amounts _ no addresses _ on the Web. Addresses are available to
those willing to dig through paper documents housed in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   When Shipp called them on it, saying this kind of tinkering
leads to a slippery slope of closing off certain information from
ready access, Wolens said, ``We're in the slippery slope
business.''
</P>
<P>
   And dragging every Texan down with them.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe &LR; star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
