<SLUG> BC-TV-WESTWING-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HAIL OF BULLETS OPENS NEW SEASON OF `WEST WING' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only downside to having as great a season as ``The West
Wing'' did is that everyone expects you to do it again. When you
are the best drama on network television, you are judged only
against yourself.
</P>
<P>
   After a brilliant first season that culminated with nine Emmy
wins _ including Best Drama _ critical and ratings success and a
controversial cliff-hanger finale that left some television
reviewers steaming, ``The West Wing'' returns next week in the
season's most anticipated premiere.
</P>
<P>
   With its two-hour season kickoff Wednesday (9 p.m. Eastern, NBC)
the White House drama hoping to fend off the sophomore jinx that
has tripped up shows as forgettable as ``Laroquette'' and immortal
as ``The Sopranos'' (still better than almost anything on
television). Meanwhile, it must quell concerns raised from last
season's finale episode, which ended in a totally unexpected
assassination attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The drama will pick up moments after it left off last spring: A
hail of gunfire erupted on the presidential entourage, with the
shots coming from skinheads secreted in a building across a plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody definitely got hit. Somebody may or may not die. So far
the only plot development critics were able to get out of anybody
connected with the NBC show came from Martin Sheen (President
Josiah Bartlet):
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to kill Charlie, I will give you that much,''
Sheen said in July, referring to the black aide Charlie Young (Dule
Hill) who is dating the president's daughter, Zoey (Elizabeth
Moss). ``That is as much as I can tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   The only cast member not returning is Moira Kelly, and her
character Mandy Hampton was not involved in the shooting. So keep
guessing.
</P>
<P>
   That assassination attempt ticked off television critics and
other viewers, if only because it was such a radical departure from
the dialogue-driven show crafted by creator Aaron Sorkin and his
co-executive producers, John Wells and director Thomas Schlamme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know many of you were troubled by it, that it possibly
didn't quite seem like the show,'' Sorkin told critics in July.
``The cliffhanger seemed a step down from what you expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you that the season opener ... might possibly go
some way toward helping you a little bit with the last few minutes
of the season finale.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlamme said he though those disappointed with the finale
``will be really happy when they see the next episode.''
</P>
<P>
   In the show's next two hours you will see flashbacks dealing
with each of the key characters (including Sheen, who initially was
slated to appear in only a handful of episodes).
</P>
<P>
   ``(It) gives Aaron an opportunity to go back and see how these
people got together,'' said Bradley Whitford, who plays deputy
chief of staff Josh Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin, who also wrote the late, great ABC dramedy ``Sports
Night'' last season, is notorious for blowing deadlines but
delivering brilliant scripts at the very last moment in a burst of
inspiration. That was not the case for last season's final episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the one moment in the entire season that I planned
ahead, that wasn't written on the fly,'' he said. ``I knew how I
wanted to begin this season, and I knew how I had to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin said his idealized version of the White House caught on
with viewers because ``there is a certain amount of
wish-fulfillment on the show.'' Although some conservatives have
been upset with the liberal-leaning tendencies of the show
(Republicans Marlin Fitzwater and Peggy Noonan, both veterans of
GOP White Houses, have joined Democrat Dee Dee Myers as
consultants), Sorkin said everyone across the political spectrum
longs for a government that tries to do the right thing for the
right reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite initial critical acclaim _ it was universally
hailed as the best new show of the season last fall before its
debut _ ratings were weak at the start. ``We didn't think we were
going to make it,'' Sheen said. ``It took weeks and weeks and
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   And now ``The West Wing'' is the best hour on television each
week. Hopefully, at least for the season premiere, it will be the
best two hours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
