r l BC-ALAMO-HISTORY-HNS &LR;      09-29 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMO-HISTORY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EVENTS TO MARK TEXAS HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Texas)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CARMINA DANINI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A bronze howitzer shell of the same type fired on
the Alamo in 1836 by Mexican troops is scheduled to go on exhibit
at the Alamo Gift Museum on Saturday as part of Texas
Archaeological Awareness Month.
</P>
<P>
   A wooden fuse and gunpowder removed from the shell as well as
other items left behind by the Mexican army after the Battle of San
Jacinto also will be on display, Alamo historian Bruce Winders
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first opportunity for the public to see artifacts
associated with events of the Texas Revolution,'' Winders said.
``Many of these things were very common then but are very rare
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrated in October, Texas Archaeological Awareness Month is
coordinated by the Texas Historical Commission in association with
the Texas Archaeological Society and the Council of Texas
Archaeologists.
</P>
<P>
   As part of archaeological awareness, ``Fall at the Alamo,'' an
interpretation of life during the Republic of Texas period, will be
held Oct. 21 at the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   The Alamo's observance of the monthlong awareness begins
Saturday with a presentation by Dr. Gregg Dimmick of Wharton.
Dimmick is scheduled to speak on ``The Mar de Lodo,'' or ``Sea of
Mud,'' at 11 a.m. and 2 p.m. (CDT) at Alamo Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sea of mud is where the Mexican army got bogged down for
nine days,'' said Dimmick, a pediatrician and avocational
archaeologist who has been excavating for several years with
friends near the Wharton area in South Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always enjoyed archaeology and used to do some
excavations but hadn't done any until I began reading the history
of our area and realized the Mexican army had come through here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dimmick said he believes the Mexican army was not retreating but
regrouping and waiting for orders from the central government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our local mud was the final blow to the Mexican army,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the discoveries, including remnants of a Bowie knife, a
Spanish-style horseshoe, some musket parts, buttons, buckles and a
crossed-belt plate, have been made near the Middle Bernard River
near East Bernard.
</P>
<P>
   Dimmick's group has access to about 8,000 acres of rice fields
in Wharton County, where many discoveries have been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some rice fields are available to us only every three years,
so we can't really do traditional archaeology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Winders said both collections will be on loan and on exhibit at
the Alamo for several more years to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
