 Attn. Sports Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olympic stories from The New York Times News Service for
Saturday, Sept. 30:
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BKO-MEN (Sydney, Australia) _ In a game that came down to
the final shot, the United States edged Lithuania 85-83 Friday
night to reach the gold medal game. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BKO-WOMEN (Sydney, Australia) _ Lauren Jackson leads
Australia to its first appearance in a gold-medal game, where
Jackson and the Aussies will finally get their Olympic wish: a date
with Lisa Leslie and Team USA. Before nearly 15,000 of their
chanting fans, Australia beat Brazil, 62-54. Jackson's 16 points
and 9 rebounds leading the way. The United States struggled early
against South Korea before rallying for a 78-65 victory. By Mike
Wise.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BKO-ARATON-COLUMN (Sydney, Australia) _ Sports of The Times
Column on the men's basketball team's narrow victory over
Lithuania. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TRACK (Sydney, Australia) _ Marion Jones stood on the
runway. This was her sixth and final long jump. She crouched and
swung her arms, then she leaned back and hopped slightly and began
her final, urgent sprint toward history. Her form on the runway was
awkward as usual. She looked like exactly what she was, a sprinter
trying to master the long jump. No other woman possesses her speed,
however, and when Jones landed with a sandy jolt she was 23 feet,
maybe even 24 feet, from the takeoff board. She had hoped for one
big jump, and this was it, clearly the longest of the competition.
But was it legal? Jones turned and hoped to see an official waving
a white flag, but it was red. The gold medal went to Heike
Drechsler, the last of the former East German champions. By Jere
Longman. And perhaps the biggest upset of the Olympics occurred in
the men's 1,500 meters when Hicham El Guerrouj of Morocco lost to
Kenya's Noah Ngeny in 3:32.07.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RHODEN-COLUMN (Sydney, Australia) _ Sports of The Times
Column on Marion Jones' struggles and ultimate failure in the long
jump. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOC-VECSEY (Sydney, Australia) _ Sports column on the end of
an era in women's soccer in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-FIELD-HOCKEY (Sydney, Australia) _ The Hockeyroos are
Australia's wildly popular field hockey team. And by the end of
their 3-1 victory _ after the Hockeyroos had dismantled their
opponent's will with their deceptive stick skills, opportunistic
scoring and aggressive attack _ they were free to enjoy the buildup
to their gold medal. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BOX (Sydney, Australia) _ In the most exciting,
highest-scoring bout of the competition, Ricardo Williams Jr. beat
Cuba's Diogenes Luna 42-41 Friday night for a berth in the
139-pound final. By Bill Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-TV-EBERSOL (Sydney, Australia) _ Dick Ebersol, the chairman
of NBC Sports, insists that he is not depressed about
lower-than-expected ratings, nor is he frantic to change anything
to resuscitate them. He is astonished at criticism that he is
carrying the Olympics on tape from 15 to 18 time zones away and
won't carry live events at 4 or 5 in the morning. By Richard
Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IMPACT (Sydney, Australia) _ They call Australia the lucky
country, and there may be no better example of its good fortune
than the unexpected windfall Sydney is reaping at the end of these
Olympics. Thanks to a steep drop in the value of the Australian
dollar relative to the U.S. dollar, the broadcast rights earmarked
to the Sydney Olympic committee have risen in value by about $28
million. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SOC-MEN (Sydney, Australia) _ Chile beats United States,
2-0, to win the bronze medal. By Peter Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-CYC (Sydney, Australia) _ Lance Armstrong tres again for
Olympic gold. By George Vecsey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
