<P>
   EDITORS: The following photos of the 2000 Summer Olympics have
moved as part of the New York Times News Service photo report for
Friday, Sept. 29, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Additional photos will move as available.
</P>
<P>
   (OLY21) UNDATED -- Sept. 29, 2000 -- OLY-TV-EBERSOL -- Dick
Ebersol,
</P>
<P>
   chairman of NBC Sports, is the executive in charge of the 2000
Summer Olympic Games in Sydney for the network. Ebersol has worked
20-hour days, rarely seen his wife and his youngest son, and looks
as if he needs a vacation. But when Ebersol finishes producing the
last prime-time broadcast at 3 p.m. on Monday, he said: ``I'll be
sad because it's over. I'd like it to go on for another week.''
(NBC/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY20) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 29, 2000 -- OLY-BKO-MEN-8 --
Lithuania's Sarunas Jasikevicius tries a final shot over Antonio
McDyess seconds before the buzzer ends the Olympic semifinal match,
Friday. In a game that wasn't decided until Jasikevicius' final
shot missed by about a foot, the United States edged Lithuania
85-83 Friday night to reach the gold medal game. (Chang W. Lee/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY19) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 29, 2000 -- OLY-IMPACT -- A
crowd of olympic spectators gather on Kronos Hill to watch the
sunset, Friday. As Sydney closes the books on a generally
trouble-free Olympics, the bigger question is how much of a
long-term economic boost will the Games give to the city, and to
Australia as a whole? (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (OLY18) SYDNEY, Australia -- Sept. 29, 2000 -- OLY-BKO-MEN-7 --
Alonzo Mourning of the U.S. gets pressured by Lithuania's Darius
Songaila, left, and Mindaugas Timinskas during the second half of
their Olympic semifinal match, Friday. In a game that wasn't
decided until the final shot missed by about a foot, the United
States edged Lithuania 85-83 Friday night to reach the gold medal
game. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
