<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BORDER PATROL EXCEEDS RECRUITING FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DANE SCHILLER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The U.S. Border Patrol says cyberspace and an
emphasis on recruiting helped it double the number of new agents
from last year.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of some 900 agents brings the patrol's size to
9,061 _ the largest in its 76-year history _ but it is still
scrambling to meet a congressional call for 10,000 agents by this
time next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been a remarkable turnaround,'' Immigration and
Naturalization Service spokesman Sid Waldstreicher said from
Washington. ``We far exceeded what we thought we would be able to
hire.''
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 40,000 people _ 80 percent of the patrol's
prospects _ applied over the Internet as the agency posted want ads
on its Web site and a dozen other sites dedicated to sports,
minorities and employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to call them the millennium generation, this is
how they are recruited,'' Waldstreicher said.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Internet, applicants answer questions ranging from
educational background to willingness to pay relocation expenses.
The patrol also is branching out with ads in movie theaters and on
television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to marketing, the patrol has assigned 200 agents to
recruiting duty. This week, a recruiting team is visiting military
personnel in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning agents earn from $25,000 to $35,000 per year,
depending on experience, and must be based along the U.S.- Mexico
border.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 900 agents joined the agency during the fiscal
year that ends Saturday, compared with about 400 last year,
according to the INS.
</P>
<P>
   The increase occurred as the patrol, a branch of the INS, which
itself is part of the Justice Department, is competing with a
healthy economy to meet a five-year congressional mandate to become
of force of 10,000 agents by October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said the INS has dragged its feet recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, head of the House Judiciary
subcommittee on immigration, said the Clinton administration has
taken too long to make the Border Patrol a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they did better this year and that is progress,'' Smith
said. ``But they have been pulled along kicking and screaming for
the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he would introduce legislation next year to continue
to increase the strength of the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are still shifting agents around depending on
the latest pressure point,'' he said. ``I don't think there is
anybody that would argue seriously we have enough now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Silvestre Reyes, D-Texas, who was chief of the patrol's
McAllen and El Paso sectors before being elected to Congress, also
said the patrol needs to do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to recognize the outstanding efforts and
success of the Border Patrol this year, but let's not overlook the
fact that they have failed to hire the amount of agents mandated by
Congress over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem areas along the border, the areas that are still
not under control, are a direct result of the INS' inability to
follow through on (a) congressional mandate,'' Reyes said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
