<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6527 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-FBI-COMPUTER30-C     09-29 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FBI-COMPUTER30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBI takes computer from Bush media firm
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FBI agents have taken the office computer of an employee of
George W. Bush's campaign media firm as investigators stepped up
efforts to figure out who mailed Bush debate preparation materials
to an Al Gore dviser.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett told the Austin American-Statesman
today that Yvette Lozano's computer was voluntarily turned over to
the FBI late Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, FBI agents told Lozano they had seen a Post Office
surveillance videotape showing Lozano mailing a package on Sept.
11, two days before the debate preparation materials arrived at the
office of former U.S. Rep. Tom Downey of New York. She said she was
mailing clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked if we would volunteer the information and we said,
``Yes.''' Bartlett said today. ``We have said all along we want a
full and complete investigation and we hope this helps bring it to
a quick conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear why the FBI wanted the computer and
officials with the federal law enforcement agency declined to
comment today.
</P>
<P>
   Lozano is an administrator for Maverick Media, whose sole client
is the Bush campaign. The package, bearing an Austin postmark,
included a videotape of a Bush debate preparation session. At the
time, Downey was playing the part of Bush in Gore's debate
preparation sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Lozano and Mark McKinnon, head of Maverick Media, have said she
was at the Post Office on Sept. 11 to mail pants McKinnon was
returning to the Gap. Lozano and McKinnon also have said FBI agents
doubted the pants alibi, and said they beileve someone in the Bush
campaign might have mailed the debate materials to Downey as part
of a Bush campaign plot to have the upcoming debates postponed or
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has dismissed that theory as ridiculous.
Lozano and McKinnon have denied any role in the mailing of the
debate preparation materials.
</P>
<P>
   The first debate is set for Tuesday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign believes the debate preparation materials were
stolen and mailed to Downey.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
