<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV01-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUST SPOTS STAIN THROUGH REPAINTED CAST IRON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, October   1, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. It took a week to strip the cast-iron baseboard radiators,
but they came out very well. When I applied a latex enamel
undercoater as a primer, a few rust spots showed up. I don't think
I should paint over the rust spots, but what can I do?
</P>
<P>
   BARBARA McGURL, Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. What you can do is take this lesson to heart: Never paint
steel, iron, tin ceilings, or other ferrous material with latex
paint, at least as a primer. The water in the paint will cause the
rust spots.
</P>
<P>
   So, what else you can do? Sand the finish to remove those rust
spots, but you do not have to take off all the latex undercoater.
Apply an oil-based primer and finish with an oil- based enamel.
Actually, if you use an oil-based primer you can finish with a
latex paint, but I do not suggest it.
</P>
<P>
   You can paint brass, copper, stainless steel, and aluminum, but
since the first three are good looking by themselves, why bother?
Painting aluminum with latex primer and paint is A-OK.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am putting in a new shed in my backyard. I am concerned
about excessive heat buildup in summer. Can I insulate walls and
roof to prevent that heat buildup, and to allow it to cool off at
night?
</P>
<P>
   P.H., Cyberspace
</P>
<P>
   A. Insulating the shed will do nothing for preventing heat
buildup in summer, or letting it cool off at night. The only way
you will get any cooling is with ventilation. If the shed has a
gable roof (two slopes), install a ridge vent. Also, if the roof
overhangs the walls to form an eave, ventilate the soffits, too
(the underpart of the overhang). This air circulation will keep the
shed as cool as the outdoor air, generally. And, of course, keep
windows and door open when it is very hot, or when you are working
in it. The ventilation will also allow rapid cooling off at night
by automatically releasing air.
</P>
<P>
   Insulation is effective only when the interior space is heated,
because insulation slows down the passage of heat from indoors to
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. One of my long, bluestone outdoor treads has cracked, after
five years. The treads were mortared in place and neither part of
the cracked tread moves. Can I fill the crack, which is hairline,
with anything to keep it from getting bigger? I am concerned that
water will get in the crack and freeze and expand, making
everything worse.
</P>
<P>
   GERTRUDE MORRIS, West Roxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is something you can try, although the treatment is
designed for concrete and other masonry, not actual stone. But it
is worth trying, and you might become a pioneer in fixing cracks in
stone.
</P>
<P>
   Use Thompson's Water seal, Drylock, or any other masonry or tile
sealer. Brush it on the crack (you don't have to do the whole
surface), let it dry overnight, and brush on some more. Repeat this
as often as possible. Eventually the sealer will bond with the
stone and may seal the crack. Because it is liquid, it will take a
while for the bonding to be effective. This treatment is unlikely
to work on anything much bigger than a hairline crack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I put water-cleanup stain on my deck three years ago.
Recently I put on an oil-based semitransparent stain. Now the deck
is tacky in some spots, and some spots are shiny, others are not.
What happened and what can I do?
</P>
<P>
   KERRY REYNOLDS, Norton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You put on the new stain too soon, and it did not penetrate
the old stain, leaving some places shiny and tacky. I think you
should have waited at least five years for the old stain to wear
off, and since it is protected by a roof, it probably wouldn't have
worn off even then.
</P>
<P>
   To correct the situation, apply paint thinner liberally to the
deck, let it sit there for five minutes to dissolve the tacky
parts, scrub and rinse. Wtih luck you might flatten out the shiny
parts and dry up the tacky parts. If that doesn't work, you will
have to use chemical paint remover.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, when you apply any stain (and semitransparent
stain is the only type to use), try it on a small area; if it beads
up there is still some stain or sealer on the deck. If it
penetrates, then you can do the deck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
