A6541 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     09-29 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME TECH STOCKS RUNNING INTO A BUZZ SAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Uncle!
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has owned technology stocks knows you should be
strapped in and ready for some tough portfolio twists and turns
with those investments. But this year is turning out to be
extraordinarily hard on a large number of Massachusetts high-tech
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   What's remarkable in 2000 is the number of well-known names with
once-sizable stock market values that have been absolutely
hammered. The same trend has played out across the entire tech
stock market, erasing many billions of dollars of value.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at some of the Massachusetts companies that have
lost three-quarters or more of their stock market value this year,
a level of decline that usually befalls a handful of speculative
micro-cap stocks and one or two bigger companies in the midst of
epic-scaled business meltdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Allaire Corp., a well-known Newton company that sells
Web development software, have plunged more than 88 percent since
the start of the year. A company worth nearly $2 billion in January
was valued at $236 million this week.
</P>
<P>
   We can point to at least seven others (there are many more) in
the same league. They include Akamai Technologies Inc., one of the
hottest initial public stock offerings of 1999, which is down 85
percent this year, and CMGI Inc., the Andover Internet incubator
turned Web operating company that has plunged 78 percent so far in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The stock declines of CMGI and Akamai combined have vaporized
about $60 billion in market value.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of the tech stock decline across Massachusetts
involves companies that once attached themselves to the buzz of the
Internet in one way or another. Typically they rose on the story of
some Web specialty, such as e-commerce or Internet consulting, and
took a beating when investors turned their backs on an industry.
</P>
<P>
   Internet consulting? Look no further than Boston-based Viant
Corp. (down 87 percent), Cambridge Technology Partners Inc. (down
81 percent), or even Sapient Corp. of Cambridge (down 41 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Generally, local Internet commerce companies have fared even
worse, though they haven't lost so much money. Mothernature.com
Inc. of Concord is down 88 percent. Rowecom Inc. of Cambridge has
lost 91 percent of its value so far in 2000. Down 75 percent this
year is a Needham firm, Smarterkids.com Inc., which raised $63
million by selling a piece of the company in an IPO last November.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these companies have not performed badly, but investors
have lost faith in the rosy long-term assumptions required to
justify the stock values placed on hot technology sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you've seen since then is indiscriminate selling of those
same'' stock stories, said Dale Dutile, a Boston-based comanager of
MFS Emerging Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   Throw millions of new shares entering the market, thanks to the
expiration of lockup restrictions on insider investments at
companies that recently went public, and it only adds more pressure
on stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai stock was already struggling this year when 58 million
more shares were unlocked for possible trading. Who knows how much
that hurts, but it surely doesn't help.
</P>
<P>
   The question now: Where do those tech stocks go from here?
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund manager Fred Kobrick likens the spiral to the grim
investing environment of 1990, when worries about confrontation
with Iraq sent stock prices tumbling. ``I think the same thing will
happen,'' he said. ``We'll go normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobrick meant that a long series of investing momentum trends,
which tend to push stocks in a particular industry higher as a
group, would finally give way to pricing based more often on
individual merit.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to many of the stocks that have been hammered this
year, some money managers mince no words and say they had it
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a lot of those numbers and think it's a long overdue
correction of excesses,'' said Steven Demirjian of Westfield
Capital Management in Boston. ``This was such a big part of the
market last year, I don't think you can minimize what's happened
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone acknowledged at the time that many technology stocks
were being bid up in a bubble of investment euophoria. It should
come as no suprise that the price declines have been drastic, now
that the inevitable correction has taken place.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an unusual period of speculation and indiscriminate
buying,''said Dutile, the MFS manager. ``That's different than
saying you had big companies blowing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had small companies that people were ascribing huge market
capitalizations to, and that's reversing,'' he said. ``The
underlying fundamentals of many of these companies never changed.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make it any easier to watch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6542 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-VICK-BOS &LR;      09-29 1898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRGINIA TECH'S VICK HANDLES BALL _ AND FAME _ GRACEFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT NEWS, Va. _ The room sits off the gym, which is in a
back wing of the high school.
</P>
<P>
   It is what it is. A coach's office. A football coach's office.
Desk, chair, some equipment, books, a blackboard with the diagram
of a play yet to be used.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Reamon sits behind the desk on a day that is still more
summer than fall, talking about a season already played.
</P>
<P>
   Reamon has done this before. He is good at it. His days as a
running back at Missouri, as a wannabe actor who had a fling in
Hollywood and minor parts for a few years, including a role in
``North Dallas Forty'' _ his character was named Delma Huddle.
</P>
<P>
   But his role now is bigger, more important. He plays it with
more passion, too.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to get to Michael Vick, if you want to backtrack and
find out where it all started, you come here, to the head football
coach's office at Warwick High School.
</P>
<P>
   Reamon talks easily about the past _ and the future. He has
played a variety of roles with his former player. Mentor, father,
adviser, friend. Pick the day, pick the subject, and Reamon can
recite his lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw Michael was in seventh grade,'' said
Reamon, sitting back in his chair. ``He was just different. There
was something about him that seemed special.''
</P>
<P>
   Reamon says this knowing the outcome of the story _ or at least
as far as his role was concerned. ``It was down the road at
Ferguson High School in August of his freshman year,'' Reamon said.
``It was the first time I saw him throw a ball. I just said, `Wow.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He then came up to me and said, `Coach, I want you to make me
as good as Aaron Brooks.' '' Brooks was one of Reamon's former
players who went on to play at the University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Reamon laughs. As good as Aaron Brooks? Three years after
leaving high school, two years into his college career, and 10
months into a new role as the prototype quarterback of the future,
Michael Vick has gone way past what Aaron Brooks did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
One name says it all &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback who will start for Virginia Tech Saturday
afternoon against Boston College at Alumni Stadium has made the
quantum leap into that gray area where the persona is bigger than
the person.
</P>
<P>
   Where one word is enough for recognition, like when you talk
about golf and you only need to say ``Tiger'' to know the subject.
Where, if the discussion is basketball, you just say ``Michael''
and people know.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Vick is starting to feel the power of that, of being
part of the select _ and sometimes difficult _ world of a Tiger
Woods or a Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   All of it changed in New Orleans last January when Vick and the
Hokies fought a losing shootout with Florida State for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   FSU won the game _ and the national championship with its 46-29
victory _ but Vick won something more, something on such a large
scale that Vick still can't comprehend it.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the 323 yards of total offense. It was his style.
His flair. It was play after play of ``can you believe that?'' type
of football. So much so that a few days after the game, Vick was
back in Virginia with his buddies, watching a taped replay of the
game, and even he was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did some things in that game,'' said Vick, ``and I said to
myself, man, what was I thinking. How did I do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick says this sitting in an office of the newly renovated
football complex Virginia Tech has in Blacksburg.
</P>
<P>
   He is no longer Michael Vick, of course. ``My life has changed
in dramatic fashion,'' said Vick with a shrug. ``But I'm ready. I
take it in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's tough. He can't go out to eat anywhere in
Blacksburg anymore without being besieged. At Tech's annual fan day
festivities this summer, there were two lines for autographs. One
for Vick and one for the rest of the Hokies _ with the line for
Vick nearly doubled that of his teammates, stretching nearly the
length of a football field.
</P>
<P>
   Vick is clearly uncomfortable with that aspect of his fame.
``We're trying to make him feel as normal as possible,'' said Tech
coach Frank Beamer, who obviously has a vested interest in a happy
and contented Michael Vick. ``But he's kind of refreshing. He
hasn't changed. It's the people around him who have changed. He's
still a team guy. He likes to compete. And the more at stake the
better he is. He responds to competition. He responds to
challenges. He needs to continue to develop. There is more for him
to learn at the college level.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-ranked Hokies bring their 3-0 record to Boston
College. Vick has completed 26 of 44 attempts for 412 yards, or a
59.1 percent completion rate. He has rushed for 219 yards and three
touchdowns on 25 carries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A double life &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things are so much different now. The Hokies are no longer the
little school that could. And Vick may have an ``S'' underneath his
game jersey, but he also has a target on it.
</P>
<P>
   Get Vick and you get the Hokies is the game plan of the week.
</P>
<P>
   And Vick is leading two lives _ as a football player and as a
celebrity. He is one person, but there are two sets of rules, of
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Tech has tried to make things easier. Sharon McCloskey, a senior
associate athletic director, has filled the role of watchdog for
many of the outside activities and queries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he sat down and did everything people asked of him,'' said
McCloskey, ``he wouldn't have time to do anything at all. We try to
make sure that nothing interferes with his class time and with his
football. We've tried to tell him that his image is as important as
what he does on the football field. He can make more money from
endorsements than he will playing if he keeps the right image.''
</P>
<P>
   McCloskey says Vick has approached that aspect of his career the
way he prepares for a game. ``He absorbs a lot, like when he plays
football,'' she said. ``He goes out and reads defenses and figures
out what he is going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick knows what it's all about. ``I don't get a big head,'' he
said. ``I don't feel that any great pressure is on me. I'm going
out and playing football for me and my team. I don't think I have
to show what I can do or that I can top last year. I feel I'm
handling it in the right way. I feel I can be successful and do the
right things.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick says the attention, the notoriety, the loss of privacy
haven't affected him. ``I've enjoyed my life,'' he said, ``even
though it has changed. I want to make the most of it, while I have
a chance to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He first got an up close and personal look at the change when he
was invited to ESPN's annual award show last winter. ``That was
different,'' he said. ``I felt out of place there. Mark McGwire,
Peyton Manning, and Michael Irvin. I'm there with all those big
shots and they were coming up to me and saying, `Hey Michael, how
are you doing. We enjoy watching you play.' It made me feel like a
marquee player.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Humble beginnings &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bright lights couldn't be any further from where Brenda
Boddie is this late summer afternoon. She is at Gildersleeve Middle
School in Hampton Roads, waiting to take her annual physical _ just
like all the bus drivers in the Hampton Roads school system.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Boddie is 37. Her life is one of routine. Driving a bus,
taking care of her family. She is also Michael Vick's mother,
although she is and looks young enough to be his sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this person on the field,'' said Boddie, who was a high
school cheerleader and a mother at 16. ``But he's still my little
boy. Something like that is scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Vick has a younger brother and an older sister. His
father, Michael Boddie, has only recently come back into his life,
perhaps the reason Vick chose to use his mother's maiden name.
</P>
<P>
   Vick says his father wasn't around early in his life, but things
have gotten better. It has been Brenda and Tommy Reamon who were
his early anchors. And those anchors remain strong to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advice I give him,'' said Brenda with a wistful smile. ``I
tell him no kids, no drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Reamon is more forceful. He has been part of Vick's daily life
since he made the bold move to start him as a freshman in high
school over a more experienced senior. ``I said, `Michael, I'm
throwing you to the wolves.' He got creamed the first game, but he
worked at it and worked it. It was an introduction to the real
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Reamon has worked at keeping the wolves at bay. It
was Reamon who cut a deal with Beamer and Virginia Tech. Vick would
only go to Tech if he would be allowed to redshirt his freshman
season.
</P>
<P>
   After flirting with lots of colleges, including Florida State,
Syracuse, and Virginia, which was heavily courting Vick's main high
school rival, Hampton QB Ronald Curry (who went to North Carolina),
Vick chose Tech because of Beamer and the assurances that he would
not play as a true freshman.
</P>
<P>
   It was a true test of faith for Beamer, who saw three QBs go
down with injuries in fall 1998, but didn't budge on activating
Vick. ``He showed me something there,'' said Reamon. ``To his
credit he stayed with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Reamon is surprised at the rapidity of the climb Vick has
made. ``I always thought he would be great, but I didn't think it
would happen this fast,'' he said. ``The Sugar Bowl changed
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Reamon continues to prepare Vick for the changes yet to come.
Agents are already a problem, although Vick and Reamon and Brenda
have made it clear that if an agent contacts him now, it will mean
certain elimination. ``I've talked to him on how to be in front of
the camera,'' said Reamon. ``I want him to make the right choices.
I said to him, `You are now a product. Your private life is over.
You cannot get caught up in this stuff.' He needs to understand
it's a business now.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick has heard the words. He says he understands what it's all
about. A year ago at this time, people were just learning his name.
He could walk on campus and not many people would bother him. He
was just another redshirt freshman QB with big ambitions. He says
he had a master plan when he started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would go to college,'' he said. ``The first season
I would learn, the second season I would get better, and the third
and fourth seasons things would take off. Now things are happening
real fast. Things happened a little quicker than I thought. I think
of the difference between last year and now and it's amazing.
Everything is totally different.''
</P>
<P>
   He is asked about the future beyond this season _ which could
very well be his final collegiate season. ``In 10 years,'' he said,
in answer to a question, ``I see myself in the NFL, maybe finishing
up my career, having a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he comes back from the future with the quickness of one of
his passes. He understands he can't do it all or try to do it all.
``Sometimes I feel like I have to make a play, go for it all, but
sometimes you can't do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he focuses again on his goals, on his dreams. The dreams
that Brenda has for him, the hopes Tommy Reamon has for him. The
dreams he has for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' he said, ``it's right there for me. I just have
to go out and get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
