<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6545 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-PHILANTHROPIST-RETIRI     09-29 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILANTHROPIST-RETIRING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 CHARITY CRUSADER TO RETIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Her grandfather was a slave turned freedman, her father
a Baptist minister turned college president, and she an aspiring
musicologist turned Realtor before stumbling into the world of
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   The part-time job Anna Faith Jones took so she could spend more
time with her children turned into a passion and a career, and
Jones became the successful and widely admired president of the
Boston Foundation, increasing its endowment from $100 million to
nearly $700 million over 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the 68-year-old Jones, doyenne of the nonprofit world
in Boston and a prominent figure in reshaping local philanthropy,
said she will retire at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was the first African-American woman to head a community
foundation in the country, and has become a prominent leader of the
philanthropic world nationally, serving as chairwoman of the
Council on Foundations, a national group.
</P>
<P>
   Under her leadership, the Boston Foundation has been transformed
from a small but venerable institution to the region's dominant
local grant giver. And the foundation has just finished its best
year ever, benefiting from a new generation of philanthropists
seeking to give away money earned in the booming technology and
financial services industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a quintessential example of the person who helps to
connect those with resources to those who have needs, and she
brings to that a deep respect for the strengths of both parties,''
said the Rev. Ray Hammond, pastor of Bethel AME Church in Boston.
``She never saw poor or disadvantaged communities as being without
assets, and she always worked to develop those assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones also steered the foundation, which is focused on helping
the poor, toward supporting the arts and the environment. She
argued that poor people need cultural enrichment as much as anyone,
and the organization has pushed elite arts institutions to do more
for the needy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have real dollars that make real differences in people's
lives,'' said Mark Volpe, managing director of the Boston Symphony
Orchestra, who called Jones ``one of the most highly regarded
leaders in the philanthropic world.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the Boston Foundation supported the first Boston
Pops concert in the city's Franklin Park; the foundation also
supports a program at which artists-in-residence at the Isabella
Stewart Gardner Museum work with schoolchildren. In one recent
instance, the artists helped a group of Boston fifth-graders
compose an opera inspired by a Renaissance painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gardner does not have this kind of work endowed, so we are
dependent on grants,'' said Anne Hawley, the museum director.
``They have enabled this program to continue and thrive.''
</P>
<P>
   But the foundation gives the bulk of its money to educational
and social service organizations, and, unlike national foundations,
its charity largely stays within the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Jones said she decided to retire in
part because she has become a victim of her success _ in the
process of growing the Boston Foundation, her job has become
increasingly administrative and managerial, and she misses a more
active personal involvement with causes she cares about.
</P>
<P>
   She said she expects to spend her time volunteering for a
handful of causes _ she cited the Kettering Foundation, which
studies democracy around the world, and the NAACP legal defense
fund as examples.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've accomplished what I want to accomplish, and the job
itself is moving into a direction where most of the demands are
such that it doesn't engage my passion,'' Jones said. ``I will
follow this passion (for helping the poor), but it will be more
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Central to the foundation's ability to come to the aid of so
many has been Jones's successful transformation of the
organization's finances and its mission.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation had long been hamstrung by an antiquated
financial structure that by 1998 left it underperforming in the
rocketing stock market. Over the last two years, however, the
foundation has diversified its portfolio, hired a broad array of
managers, dramatically increased the percentage of its assets in
stocks, and, as a result, has seen its endowment grow more rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation now is facing intense competition from companies
such as Fidelity Investments, which is offering to manage the
charitable activities of its wealthy clients. In response, the
Boston Foundation has been a leader in a new form of active
philanthropy, popular among the newly rich entrepreneurs, in which
donors retain an active role in determining the distribution of
money managed by the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boston Foundation struck me as having a unique combination
of being august and innovative, and it's a pretty compelling choice
when you add that together,'' said Thomas W. Bird, a Boston venture
capitalist who made his money with a technology company in Silicon
Valley and then chose the foundation to help him give part of it
away when he moved to Concord. Bird wanted to give to educational
causes, and the foundation helps him find specific organizations
that interest him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking to be actively involved, with some professional
guidance. What's great is you get a partner in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation gives away about 5.5 percent of its endowment
each year _ an amount that totalled $53 million last year. The
group also gives many small grants to small organizations _ it had
1,900 beneficiaries last year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of her gender and ethnicity, Jones is seen as an
inspiration, particularly for black women, in a city not known for
the diversity of its power structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me personally, having Anna Faith Jones as one of the
first, if not the first, African-American women in a major
leadership role in this city, has provided me with a role model,''
said Linda Whitlock, president and chief executive of the Boys and
Girls Clubs of Boston. ``She's been a guidepost for me in my
role.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation board plans a national search to find a
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   A resident of the Fort Point Channel neighborhood of Boston,
Jones said she wants to spend more time with her grandchildren, and
to begin a project researching her family history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here because I wanted a part-time job, but now I think
I'm missing my grandchildren, and I want to spend more time with
them,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
