<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OLYMPIC DYNASTY ENDS FOR USA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ An American Olympic dynasty ended on Friday,
and it didn't involve a basketball, a softball or any of the usual
paraphernalia filling sporting-good stockrooms from Bangor to
Carlsbad.
</P>
<P>
   The synchronized swimming team, which had won a gold medal at
every Summer Games since the event joined the Olympic program in
1984, finished fifth. On Wednesday, the American duet had finished
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   After a poor showing in the technical routine Thursday, the
Americans hadn't expected to move into the gold-medal spot, but
they were disappointed in their scores for the free routine. The
judges gave them mostly 9.6s for technical merit and 9.7s for
artistic impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our sport, it seems like sometimes it's very poorly
called,'' said Anna Kozlova, who emigrated from Russia in 1993 and
became an American citizen, in time to compete for her new country.
``Since the U.S. has been on top for a long time, people are very
happy to pull them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozlova trains with the Santa Clara, Calif., Aquamaids. The
entire U.S. team belongs to either the Aquamaids or the Walnut
Creek, Calif., Aquanuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian team won the gold, and Kozlova watched unblinkingly
while the swimmers received their medals. She said she knew four
members of the championship team. Kozlova had been one of Russia's
top synchro swimmers, and she surely would have been on the podium
had she not emigrated.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she had any regrets, Kozlova said quietly but
firmly: ``I have everything I want.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russians swept both the duet and eight-woman team
competition. They scored perfect 10s from four of the 10 judges,
including the one from Japan, whose own team was in second place,
waiting to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very strong and very flexible,'' said American coach
Chris Carver.
</P>
<P>
   She praised the Russians for being able to lift their legs
extremely high above the surface when they did the synchro
equivalent of a handstand. She also said they moved quickly between
figures and held steady, barely quivering when they rose out of the
water.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians did an exceptional lift, boosting a teammate out of
the water on their legs. The Americans also did an assortment of
demanding lifts, boosting Kristina Lum up into crowd-pleasing
poses.
</P>
<P>
   The routine that really thrilled the audience, though, was the
Canadians' depiction of various Olympic sports. They came out last,
wearing simple costumes that looked like old-fashioned track
outfits, completely devoid of sequins.
</P>
<P>
   To the ``Chariots of Fire'' theme, the Canadians entered the
water out of a runners' starting crouch. They lifted teammates
posing as a cyclist with legs spinning, an archer, and a pair of
judo fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The routine didn't have the same degree of difficulty as others,
but it was good enough for bronze.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans performed to a medley of classical music,
including Vivaldi's ``Four Seasons,'' and acted out the life of a
storm. Their costumes were black with a picture of Father Winter,
blowing a cold burst of air, silk-screened on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans believed they tried one of the most difficult
routines in the program, partly because they stayed underwater for
3 1/2 minutes of the 5-minute program. But Carver conceded that the
judges probably considered the Russian performance even more
difficult. The Japanese, she said, delivered a lovely routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan, to me, is very decorative, very much like their
culture,'' she said. ``You know how beautifully they present their
food. That's how they do their synchronized swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's technical program, the Americans ran into trouble
immediately. One swimmer miscounted underwater and did an early leg
lift, about two beats ahead of everyone else. The judges put the
team in fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty hard to overcome,'' Carver said.
</P>
<P>
   So the women had to be content with a free routine that many of
them considered the best they'd ever done. One woman left the pool
with a small fist pump, and Carrie Barton and Elicia Marshall did
their traditional wave to the crowd, pounding their hearts and then
raising a peace sign.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Pease-Olson, a returning member of the 1996 team, said
she saw her husband, Eric, after the program, and he put the best
spin on the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `At least, it (the error) didn't happen today,'' she
said. ``So you know you had a recovery you can all feel good
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
