<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS A LINE MODEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Before and after. Best and worst. Night and
day.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offensive line and the Denver Broncos' offensive
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have a line Bill Belichick covets and he can only
hope his current group of nomads develops into something resembling
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver line is so good it has made former Marine Mike
Anderson a star running back. It's so good Brian Griese has had
enough time to accumulate the best passer rating (116.2) in the
league. Yes, even better than St. Louis Rams wonder Kurt Warner's
111.9.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got some athletic people on the line and I think
they're well-coached,'' Belichick said. ``Alex (Gibbs) is an
excellent offensive line coach, there's no question about that.
They play with real good continuity and they've been able to keep
the same people together through a period of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure about all the stats, all the weights and
everything. I coached Tony Jones at Cleveland and Tony's good, a
Pro Bowl left tackle, but he's no 275 pounds. I can tell you that
having coached him, he's no midget, he's as big as most left
tackles in the league. However big that is, that's plenty big
enough. And Matt Lespsis is no midget either. Whatever their size
or weight, they function well together as a unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs may be the most effective assistant coach in the NFL. He's
done his job quietly. In fact, he's had a policy of not speaking to
the media. His players normally have respected that and kept quiet
as well. Only at certain designated times _ when players face
$10,000 fines for not being accessible to the media at the Super
Bowl _ have some of the players chosen to speak.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also have an offensive line coach, Dante
Scarnecchia, who doesn't speak to the media (usually because he's
not allowed to). Unfortunately it hasn't worked for him. At least
not yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos epitomize strong line play, and they do it with
quickness and intelligence. That's not to say they aren't big and
strong, but as Belichick points out, ``When you get five guys
thinking as one and playing as one you see very few mistakes within
the group where they miss somebody or they turn a guy free or you
can see there is a missed assignment. And that's very, very rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs's system is so flawless that when he lost Gary Zimmerman
and Brian Habib, he plugged in Dan Neil at right guard and Lepsis
at right tackle and didn't miss a step. All-Pro center Tom Nalen, a
product of Boston College, is the anchor and seems to reflect the
temperament of the whole. The Broncos' line has an attitude that it
won't get beat and prides itself in opening gaping holes, be they
for Anderson or Olandis Gary or Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Who are these guys?
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlereth, 6 feet 3 inches, 287 pounds, has had 25
surgeries and one kidney stone procedure in 12 NFL seasons. He's
started 136 games and has spent six seasons with the Broncos. He
was a 10th round pick out of Idaho and joined the Washington
Redskins in 1989 as the first Alaska-born player in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 6-5, 291, is in his 13th year out of Western Carolina. He
was a rookie free agent pickup by the Browns in 1988 and has spent
the last four years with Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Nalen, 6-3, 286, is his seventh year, all with Denver. The
Foxborough native was a seventh-round pick (218th) overall out of
BC in 1994. He's played in three Pro Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Neil, 6-2, 281, out of Texas, was a third-round pick in 1997 by
Denver and already has established himself as one of the best
guards in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Lepsis, 6-4, 290, is in his fourth year out of Colorado. He was
signed by the Broncos as a rookie free agent in 1997. He started
all 16 games at right tackle last season and is now a fixture.
</P>
<P>
   With no 300-pounder in a day and age when every other line has
some if not all players at 300-plus pounds and some pushing 400,
how do the Broncos do it? The approach is not dissimilar to what
Belichick was trying to build in Cleveland, basically taking guys
who weren't drafted very high and developing them into quality
players. Belichick is trying to do this now with recent
acquisitions Sale Isaia and Joe Andruzzi to go along with a star
like Damien Woody, who was a No. 1 pick, veteran Bruce Armstrong,
and free agent pickup Grant Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil is another guy who was a low draft pick,'' said
Belichick. ``They had to wait a year for him because he couldn't
play because of an injury. Now he's a starting guard and he's a
good player. Lepsis is another guy, you can see him developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys have come along and they've developed them and the
players have worked hard and the system has pushed them and it's
brought them together. They've got a good football team and they've
done it over a period of time and I think that's the test, being
able to do it year in and year out.''
</P>
<P>
   While Belichick has been disappointed in the play of his line,
he has seen some improvement. He has second-round pick Adrian Klemm
(knee injury) waiting in the wings, and Greg Robinson-Randall, who
is getting his feet wet this season and will likely step into a
starting role by next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots allowed 12 sacks the first three games and only
five the last two weeks (conversely the Broncos have allowed eight
sacks in four games). Running back Kevin Faulk had a pair of
80-yard-plus games before being held to 46 last week, when the
holes just weren't there. The Broncos' defense is ranked fourth
against the run, which means the Patriots' offensive line will be
tested again.
</P>
<P>
   This is Week 5 of the new Patriots' system. It is Year 7 for
Nalen and his Bronco gang. Denver's great line wasn't born
overnight, but it's flowing now. One wonders if the Patriots' line
will ever be that good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
