<HEADLINE>
THIS FINISH SURELY WASN'T IN THE PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Rod Beck still watches the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we were eliminated,'' he says, ``I'd still be watching
the scoreboard. There's a little fan in all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   And every day this week, when Beck has looked back, he sees the
same thing. Yanks lose. Yanks lose. Yanks lose. Yanks lose.
</P>
<P>
   Four games in a row. They lost to the Tigers Monday, then were
swept by the Devil Rays in Florida. Ten losses in their last 12
games. The Bombers had a nine-game lead Sept. 13. They were 7 1/2
games ahead 12 days ago. Five and a half games ahead with eight
left to play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're 3 1/2 ahead with four to play. One Yankee win or Sox
loss, and it's over.
</P>
<P>
   It should have been over a long time ago. It ain't over yet.
Friday, while the Sox are in St. Petersburg to play the Devil Rays,
the Yankees go to Baltimore, where they have to face Mike Mussina,
who struck out 15 batters in seven innings Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On NESN, broadcaster Jerry Remy is joking about bus tours to
Florida being organized all over New England. Prediction: Another
Yank loss and a Sox win against the Devil Rays, and the Delta
counters at Logan Airport in Boston will be jammed.
</P>
<P>
   On Yawkey Way this morning, they'll be lining up extra help to
work in October. Just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be the damnedest thing I ever saw,'' said Beck, who
was the winner in relief Thursday night when the Sox completed a
three-game sweep of the White Sox, the team with the best record in
the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to say stranger things have happened,'' Beck said,
``but I don't know if anything stranger has ever happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope it plays out that way. The only way it can happen
is if we win out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox won with Carl Everett, Dante Bichette, Jason Varitek,
and Jose Offerman on the bench. They won with starting pitcher
Ramon Martinez recording two more hit batsmen than outs (0).
</P>
<P>
   They won with Izzy Alcantara hitting a three-run home run on a
3-and-0 pitch. They won despite a monster home run by Frank Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   They won with Derek Lowe on the mound once again to register the
final out, for his 41st save.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still alive,'' Lowe said with a laugh. ``We're still on
life support, OK, but we live for another day. You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks are 87-71. The Sox are 84-75. If the Sox sweep the
Devil Rays this weekend and the Yankees lose three in Baltimore and
a makeup game against the Florida Marlins Monday, a one-game
playoff will be necessary. Where will it be played?
</P>
<P>
   Don't know. It was such an unlikely scenario, they never
bothered to flip a coin to determine where such a playoff would be
held. Sox spokesman Kevin Shea said Major League Baseball informed
the Sox a coin flip will be held only if and when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the Yankees are thinking,'' Lowe said, ``but
sometimes winning one game is tougher than it seems. There's only
one thing for us to do, and that's win every game. Tampa has been a
tough customer. They've pretty much owned us the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox hadn't lost five games in a row all season until
the Red Sox came to town. Roger Clemens, one of the hottest
pitchers in the game since mid-June, was clocked early by the Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams sat in the visting manager's office with a bemused
expression on his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just got to try to keep winning,'' he said. ``We're going to
play a team that's hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez thought his season was over. Sox win Friday and
Saturday, Yanks lose both days, Petey's back in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   It's ridiculous. It's preposterous. It will never happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see us get this thing down to Sunday,'' Lowe said.
``It would just be something, having to come down to the last game
of year when we were 5 1/2 back with eight to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck, who was on a Giants team in 1993 that won 103 games and
didn't go to the playoffs and was on a Cubs team that had to win a
playoff game against the Giants to advance in 1998, was asked if he
would cut off his hair if it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happens, it will be because of the hair,'' Beck said.
``If it happens, everyone will have to grow their hair long.''
</P>
<P>
   He ran his hands across both sides of his receding forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``And shave their power alleys, too,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
