<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-MANLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR EBERSOL, OLYMPICS BET IS PAYING OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not easy being a sugar daddy.
</P>
<P>
   But Dick Ebersol doesn't seem to mind. The NBC Sports chairman
convinced his bosses at General Electric to spend $3.5 billion for
the next four Olympics, and the Sydney games _ the first under the
deal _ has generated so much criticism and ridicule about
everything from the dwindling TV ratings to dope stains on gold
medals, that a lesser man would have folded soon after the Opening
Ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Not Ebersol. Not the man who claims his one passion _ outside
his family _ is the Olympics, a flame that started in 1972 when the
Yalie dropped out of school to work as an intern in Munich for
network sports guru Roone Arledge.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Dick has not been happy with his critics and the
ongoing taped-versus-live debate. Oh sure, Ebersol would have loved
for the American gymnasts to have performed better, but he can't
control the athletes. He called sports editors ``fools'' and the
live coverage by Canadian Broadcasting ``a colossal joke.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the fact is that the ratings for these Games are off by
as much as 35 percent from those in Atlanta. Ebersol readily
concedes that he has been unable to deliver on his guarantee to
advertisers of a 16.1 minimum rating. As a result, NBC already has
had to add a ``make good commercial'' each hour during the Games
and will add more commercials to NBC's upcoming broadcasts of the
Major League Baseball playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Ebersol quickly points out that Olympics coverage is still
smoking the competition. For Tuesday's prime-time broadcast (8-11
p.m.), for instance, NBC drew a 13.5 rating/21 share, which was 80
percent above the network's normal average of 7.5 rating. NBC's
prime-time numbers more than tripled Fox's (4.4/7); more than
doubled CBS's (4.8/8) and was 73 percent better than ABC's 7.8/13.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen Media Research further reported that NBC's 12-day
Olympic prime-time average was 15.7/25, some 227 better than Fox,
191 percent over CBS, and 134 percent better than ABC.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty clear that having the Olympics in this age of
fragmentation _ even when the results are known and the coverage is
taped _ still provides a big advantage over the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Games' top markets are in the Mountain and Pacific
time zones, including Salt lake City, San Francisco, Sacremento,
Portland and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have repeatedly said the tape delay would not be a major
issue for most Olympic viewers,'' Ebersol told reporters in Sydney.
``The Western markets where the time difference is the greatest _
including Seattle, where they have the option to watch the Olympics
live before the sun comes up on CBC _ are the highest rated cities
in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol told the New York Times that the CBC strategy was ``so
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We compete with the CBC in Seattle,'' Ebersol said. ``In prime
time we are averaging a 20 rating there, and for the same events in
the early morning, it's getting a 0.6. When 100,000 people out of
32 million watch, it's a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol has acknowledged that NBC underestimated the competition
in September when viewers have a choice betweeen baseball and
football. Ebersol also told reporters that he plans to shorten the
five-hour prime-time telecasts by at least 30 minutes during the
Winter Games in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   But Ebersol makes no apologies. ``My No. 1 job is to deliver the
largest audience possible,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is just as clear. NBC sold about $900 million
worth of advertising. The Sydney games cost $705 million. You do
the math.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sizing up Patriots &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS analyst Phil Simms wouldn't be surprised if the Patriots
pulled an upset in Denver. He said the team has played hard in each
of its four games, and though the Patriots have lost every one, the
team ``doesn't have any glaring weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he also said ``they won't make the Super Bowl, and even
if they make the playoffs, they won't be a factor. They haven't
been able to come up with big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the former NFL quarterback, some of that is
coaching, but most of the problem lies in the hands of the players.
In the game against the New York Jets, Simms said the Patriots
played an almost perfect game and still lost because the Jets were
able to come up with the big plays when they needed them.
</P>
<P>
   Simms and Greg Gumbel will call Sunday's game in Denver. If the
Patriots lose, Simms said Bill Belichick will have to reevaluate
his team and make plans for the future. ``The big question facing
the Patriots is whether to make drastic changes or tweak the team
here and there,'' Simms said.
</P>
<P>
   The most important factor is Drew Bledsoe. Unlike previous
years, Bledsoe has been plagued by a weak offensive line and an
even weaker running game. Under those circumstances, Simms said,
Bledsoe must be more efficient and able to convert the few
opportunities he has into big plays. Bledsoe hasn't been able to
get it done.
</P>
<P>
   And when the offense is not producing, Simms said, ``defenses
have little to fear and become much more aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much do you think the Patriots miss Curtis Martin?'' Simms
asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
