<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-OLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OLD AMERICAN' IS CAPTIVATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
The Old American 
By Ernest Hebert 
Hardscrabble Books/University Press of New England, 287 pp.,
$24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the first American bestsellers were the ``captivity
narratives'' _ part adventure stories, part morality tales _ that
gave accounts of the capture of colonial settlers by Native
Americans. The best-known come from the New England frontier during
the century between the outbreak of King Philip's War in 1675 and
the end of the French and Indian War in 1763, a hundred-year period
during which some 1,200 men and 400 women were taken captive.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Rowlandson's account of her capture during a raid on
Lancaster during King Philip's War went through four printings
during the year after its publication in 1683. Cotton Mather wrote
three dramatic accounts of the capture of Hannah Dustan during a
raid on Haverhill in 1697, and her escape after killing and
scalping her captors. The narratives _ however straightforward or
dramatized _ led to a whole series of novels dealing with Indian
captivity that appeared during the 19th century, by authors such as
James Fenimore Cooper and Catherine Maria Sedgwick.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Hebert's ``The Old American'' stands firmly in this
near-forgotten tradition. It is a great story, convincingly and
colorfully told, though it tails off a bit toward the end _
perhaps, as was the case with so many of the captives themselves,
the story loses interest when the captivity comes to an end.
Hebert's tale is based on the story of Nathan Blake, who was taken
prisoner during a raid on Keene, N.H., in 1746 and was ransomed by
his wife three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, a professor of English at Dartmouth College, is best
known for a series of novels dealing with contemporary New England
life. His accomplishment in ``The Old American'' is to have written
about the people on both sides of the frontier conflict with the
benefit of contemporary insights into the relationships between
captives and captors (relationships frequently seen in hostage
situations) without losing a sense of the historical time and
place.
</P>
<P>
   In Hebert's fictionalized account, Blake is taken captive by an
aged Algonkian chieftain with the Franco-Indian name of
Caucus-Meteor and taken to a Native American village near Montreal
after successfully surviving the gauntlet _ by choosing to walk,
rather than run. A friendship between Blake and his captor
develops, which allows Blake to become Caucus-Meteor's confidant
and, eventually, a partner in his efforts to secure the future of
the village after his death. In a historical note, Hebert says that
the marriage of Blake and Caucus-Meteor's oldest daughter _ which
may seem a novelist's invention _ has its basis in the fact that
the real Blake was elected head of the family after his captor's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Caucus-Meteor is, of course, ``the old American'' of the title _
the early settlers initially called the native people
``Americans,'' as Hebert notes. It is part of Hebert's
accomplishment that his insight into the thinking of his Indian
characters at a time of cultural transition is generally credible.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert's account of a tribal gathering to debate whether the
village should abandon its nomadic traditions and create a
permanent farming community is a stunningly effective bit of
storytelling. ``The speeches go on and on,'' he writes, ``and a
mood of fear and desolation grips the villagers. For the first time
they understand how divided they are. It begins to look like the
Americans are going to split into two groups and go their separate
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   While the focus of Hebert's tale is the captor-captive
relationship, one particularly striking incident involves Blake and
another captive who had survived the gauntlet with him _ an
incident that suggests why so many captured settlers either
remained with their Native American captors, or recalled their
period of captivity as a happy time in their lives. After the
gauntlet, the two had been taken by different tribes; when they
meet several years later at a trading camp, ``they have difficulty
communicating.'' Neither speaks the other's Indian language, and
neither knows more than a few words of French. It is not until
later that Nathan tells Caucus-Meteor, ``Neither I nor Sam thought
to speak English.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Old American'' is an admirable book and deserves a place
among the classic tales based on the frontier captive experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
