<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARNOLD TO FLEX GLOBAL MUSCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the purchase of its parent company by Paris-based Havas
Advertising SA earlier this week, Arnold Communications is poised
to emerge as a global ad agency, Ed Eskandarian, its chairman and
chief executive, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Arnold has evolved in the last decade from a small
regional agency to a national player. And now, ranked as the
18th-argest ad agency in the United States and the largest in New
England, it prepares to pursue international ambitions as part of
the fourth-largest ad agency in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're entering the third stage of Arnold's lifetime,'' said
Eskandarian. He will now head a division of nine Havas-owned ad
agencies, including Arnold, with other home offices in Brazil,
Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Spain, and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold was a small Boston ad agency when Eskandarian bought it
10 years ago. Through acquisitions, Arnold quickly grew into a
regional powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   By Eskandarian's reckoning, Arnold entered its second stage in
1995 when it emerged as a national player by winning the ad account
for Volkswagen of America.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Drivers wanted'' campaign for VW has won much acclaim. It
was hailed again Thursday when it took top honors at the Hatch
Awards, which salutes the best creative efforts of New England ad
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold looked to be on its way to becoming a global player in
1998 when it was acquired by Snyder Communications Inc., a direct
marketing firm based in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The sale allowed Eskandarian, now 63, to cash out his investment
in Arnold. And Snyder seemed to offer a potential platform for
Arnold to broaden its reach.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was for Eskandarian to use Snyder's high-flying stock
price to finance a string of ad-agency acquisitions that would give
Arnold both bulk and scope.
</P>
<P>
   Then the value of Snyder's stock plunged, and founder Daniel
Snyder became focused on a new business _ the ownership of the
Washington Redskins, a National Football League team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock took a tumble, and acquisitions were put on hold,''
Eskandarian said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Havas Advertising announced plans to acquire
Snyder Communications for a reported $2.1 billion. That transaction
was completed Monday, and it gives Arnold, and Eskandarian, another
opportunity to evolve to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Havas operates four divisions, including two divisions of ad
agencies. Following the Snyder acquisition, plans call for
Eskandarian to head up one of those ad-agency divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition should make Havas the fourth-largest
communications company in the world behind WPP Group PLC of London,
the Omnicom Group of New York, and New York-based Interpublic Group
of Cos., which owns Boston ad agency Hill Holliday Connors
Cosmopulos and a majority stake of the Wenham ad agency Mullen.
</P>
<P>
   Under Snyder, Arnold was charged with putting together a network
of ad agencies from scratch. Under Havas, Arnold begins with a
network of nine agencies already in place on several continents.
</P>
<P>
   Having global reach should help the Havas network of ad agencies
led by Eskandarian attract more business.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how that is supposed to work: In France, for example,
Havas is the ad agency for Alcatel, a French telecommunications
giant. When Alcatel needed a US agency, Havas recommended Arnold
and, after a pitch, Arnold won the job.
</P>
<P>
   That's a pattern Havas and Arnold hope will be repeated. Arnold
now creates ads in the United States for EMC Corp. of Hopkinton,
the computer storage company, and Arnold recently won the US
account for Monster.com, the job-search Web site based in Maynard.
</P>
<P>
   Both EMC and Monster.com use other ad agencies outside the
United States, Eskandarian said. With partner agencies in Latin
America and Europe, Arnold can now go to such clients and offer to
handle a larger portion of their business, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of Eskandarian's new job, like his job at Snyder,
will be pursuing acquisitions, this time possibly in Australia,
Latin America, and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   One potential hitch: Stock prices for communications giants such
as Omnicom and Interpublic are off sharply this year as the US
economy slows, and stock is the currency such companies as Havas
use to make acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   With his new global role, Eskandarian said he plans to delegate
the day-to-day operations at Arnold. A new appointment should be
announced within a few weeks, he said. In 1999, Arnold reported
$140.9 million in revenues on billings of $1.1 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
