<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDELITY-NEWSPAPER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY SAYS IT'S TIME TO TURN A PAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One would hardly call Edward ``Ned'' Johnson III a
newspaper man.
</P>
<P>
   That his Fidelity Investments ever delved into the news business
has always been viewed with some irony in media circles. The
chairman of the investment giant is perhaps the most private man in
the mutual fund world. He rarely grants interviews and is almost
never seen at public events where other fund executives regularly
schmooze.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has approached the news business as dispassionately as
it reviews a Web-infrastructure venture deal or analyzes stocks in
its growth funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw early on that the clustering and consolidation of
newspapers was a key trend,'' said Steven Akin, president of
Fidelity Capital, the arm of Fidelity that controls venture
investments like Community Newspaper Co., which Fidelity agreed to
sell Thursday to Boston Herald publisher Patrick J. Purcell. ``We
got in on that, we believe, on the early side.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Akin said, Fidelity is content with its return on that
investment. ``We are very satisfied with where we come out on
CNC.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fidelity is ending its grand experiment as a newspaper
publisher, selling its chain of community papers to New England's
underdog daily and continuing its focus on fast-growth, high-tech
venture deals.
</P>
<P>
   The move follows a dogged effort by Purcell to acquire Community
Newspaper Co., which Fidelity had long declined to sell. Fidelity
finally gave in, it appears, rather than set out to acquire more
papers itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that to take the newspaper group to the next level,
we'd have to continue this clustering strategy,'' Akin said.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity entered the newspaper business in 1986, with the
acquisition of six North Shore papers. Many acquisitions later, the
company owns more than 100 local papers. In recent months, Fidelity
showed interest in acquiring additional properties. Community News
actively bid for the Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette, now owned by the
Globe's parent, The New York Times Co., and The Patriot Ledger of
Quincy, which was taken off the market last week.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Fidelity is leaving the field altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity would not reveal the sale price of its news group, but
industry sources said they expected the amount to top $100 million.
Akin said Fidelity's return on its investment from the newspaper
group was competitive with industry benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Kivijarv, director of publications at Veronis Suhler, a New
York investment bank that focuses on the media industry, said
newspapers _ even local papers _ are still hot properties. ``People
are paying more now for newspapers than they ever have before,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fears that the Internet would crush the newspaper
business, the firm predicts 6.4 percent annual growth in
advertising revenues through 2004 and 2.4 percent circulation
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's clear these are far from the blockbuster numbers
that venture capitalists, including Fidelity, are seeing from their
Internet, telecommunications, and networking investments. Asked
whether the Herald's offer had been too good to refuse, Akin said,
``I wouldn't couch it in financial terms only.''
</P>
<P>
   Akin suggested that helping the Herald build its franchise was
attractive: ``It looks like the right thing to do,'' he said,
declining to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has had several high-profile disputes with media
outlets over the years, including the Globe, over coverage that it
has deemed unflattering. The company has not advertised with the
Globe for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Akin said Fidelity Capital invests in companies for many
reasons, beyond pure investment returns. He said running a business
is a way for Fidelity to learn about a sector. With newspapers, he
said, ``We've been able to learn a lot about content and the role
it plays'' in the Web era.
</P>
<P>
   There were layoffs over the years, difficult cost-cutting, and
efforts to merge cultures that often clashed. Community News is now
profitable, Akin said. The red ink turned to black in 1998,
according to published reports.
</P>
<P>
   Other holdings in the Fidelity Capital group include
BostonCoach, the $90 million private car and van service, and the
Seaport Hotel, which the fund firm developed on the South Boston
Waterfront. Two years ago, Fidelity sold money-losing Worth and two
other magazines. In 1997, Fidelity sold Wentworth Gallery Ltd., a
chain of fine-art stores.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company is plowing money into software companies,
Internet infrastructure players, and telecom start-ups. Its
portfolio includes more than 60 investments, from Authoria, a human
resources software provider, to Adero, a Web content delivery
company, and Nextel, the digital cellular company.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity would not reveal the dollar value of its venture
portfolio. In the second quarter, Fidelity Ventures made four deals
worth $3.5 million, according to data compiled by
PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Ventures' best-known success is Colt, a European
telecommunications company that was the firm's first initial public
offering. Other wins include WebSpective, which was purchased by
Inktomi for $110 million, and Nexabit Networks, bought by Lucent
Technologies for $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper deal is expected to close by Nov. 1, contingent on
the Herald's completing its due diligence.
</P>
<P>
   Purcell said other investors are backing him in the deal, but he
did not name them.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas H. Lee Co., the Boston buyout firm, is often rumored to
be one of Purcell's partners, but it is not believed to be in this
deal. FleetBoston Financial Corp. (preceded by BankBoston) is
Purcell's longtime banker.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity said it was not financing the deal, calling it an
``outright sale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
