<HEADER>
A6606 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GIRLFIGHT-BOS &LR;      09-29 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GIRLFIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALISTIC `GIRLFIGHT' SCORES A KO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
GIRLFIGHT 
Written and directed by: Karyn Kusama 
Starring: Michelle Rodriguez, Jaime Tirelli, Paul Calderon,
Santiago Douglas, Ray Santiago 
Running time: 113 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Karyn Kusama's ``Girlfight'' is a terrific little uppercut of a
boxing movie and close to a perfect one. It immediately snaps you
to a keener, more intimately focused attention than the usual
studio behemoth. Not just because it puts a young woman in the ring
_ although that's certainly part of the reason _ but because it
operates on several levels, most of which never make their way into
boxing movies. Because Kusama has boxed, she gets the physicality
right. To Michelle Rodriguez's angry, bristly high school senior
named Diana Guzman, sweat and leather are perfume. The first time
she's sent to a gym on an errand by her macho father on behalf of
her brother, she feels at home. Her problem is persuading various
men she belongs there.
</P>
<P>
   One, her younger brother, is happy to hand her the gloves and
the money their father pays each week for training, declaring with
relief that he's content to be a geek. It takes her a little longer
to persuade the trainer, Hector (Jaime Tirelli). But he's impressed
enough by her raw talent and her attitude to take her on as a
student. In no time, he's asking himself whether a woman can fight
in a slightly different way because she has a lower center of
gravity. What Diana learns from Hector, apart from discipline, is a
scientific approach to fighting. Heart has its place, she learns,
but so does training.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Sandro (Paul Calderon) is not, in any sense, in her
corner. One reason Diana keeps getting into trouble at school for
punching out other kids is that she's still angry over her mother's
suicide, for which she blames her father. But as she gets better at
boxing, an unforeseen thing happens. She falls for another boxer
named Adrian (you can't say Kusama hasn't got a sense of humor with
this inverted reference to ``Rocky''). Between the two of them,
they move miles beyond the usual punch-your-way-out-of-the-ghetto
cliches in which this genre is rooted.
</P>
<P>
   They, of course, are punching their way out of the ghetto. But
Adrian (Santiago Douglas) also subverts genre stereotyping by being
gentle as well as being a good boxer. If Hector becomes the
benevolent surrogate father Diana never had, Adrian shows her a
masculine tenderness and solicitude that includes teaching her to
eat salads. The effect is to soften Diana and make her risk showing
her own emotional vulnerability. But ``Girlfight'' is too smart and
too realistic to fall into the usual Hollywood trap of having a man
come along and kill the toughness of a strong woman by neutralizing
it with romance (a venerable Hollywood tradition _ Samson and
Delilah in reverse).
</P>
<P>
   Diana stays strong, while growing and deepening emotionally.
Swinging from the heels, Kusama KO's conventional expectation. It
makes you want to cheer. Between them, Kusama and Rodriguez get a
couple of big things right. Kusama doesn't ask that Diana give up
boxing to get love and make contact with her femininity. And
because she herself has clocked time in gyms, Kusama neither
romanticizes what goes on there, nor deemphasizes it. What goes on
outside the gym is ultimately more important than what goes on
inside it. But ``Girlfight'' doesn't make the mistake of
downplaying or undervaluing what goes on when Diana has the gloves
on. ``Girlfight'' is comfortable with its physicality.
</P>
<P>
   It makes clear that part of Diana's growing self-confidence
stems directly from her increased physical prowess. This, in turn,
comes not via swinging from the heels and winning the big fight on
a last, desperate angry lunge (usually the case with movie
square-offs), but from hard work over a period of time. When we do
see Diana win a fight, it isn't by a falsely dramatic knockout;
it's by a decision. Rodriguez is an ideal Diana. Credible as one
who can throw a punch that can inflict pain, she's also credible as
one who sometimes is a pain. The film isn't afraid to have us
sometimes dislike her. But her purity and intensity make her
heroic. She and this film that respects her by rendering her and
her world in unadorned realistic terms, bypassing cheap prefab
myths, are twin blasts of fresh air. ``Girlfight'' could have gone
wrong in a dozen ways. But it goes shiningly right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
