<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLFLOWERS DELIVER `BREACH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thoughtful, well-constructed rock 'n' roll is having a hard time
getting heard these days. It is being overwhelmed on the one hand
by syrupy boy bands and navel-baring teen girls, and on the other
by angry metal-rappers who color everything with a macho brush.
</P>
<P>
   Jakob Dylan of the Wallflowers knows this isn't the easiest time
for his band to drop a new album, but he's moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you wait for the right time, you'll never get out
of the house,'' the son of Bob Dylan says. ``And if it is a great
time for what you do, then you're probably going to get a novelty
song on alternative radio and then be done. I actually take a lot
of comfort in not being lumped in with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence his credo: ``When you don't fit in, your actual chances of
longevity are a lot stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wallflowers hit their stride with their 1996 sophomore
album, the rootsy ``Bringing Down the Horse,'' which sold 4 million
copies, aided by hit singles ``Sixth Avenue Heartache,'' ``One
Headlight,'' and ``Three Marlenas.'' And the new ``Breach,'' which
comes out Oct. 10, is an even better album, showing Dylan's growth
and his willingness to take chances with different sonic textures
and lyrical twists, from the rocking new single, ``Sleepwalker,''
to the wistful ``Hand Me Down,'' which many observers say is about
his relationship with his dad.
</P>
<P>
   The latter tune has lines like ``Look at your worn-out shoes /
Living proof evolution's through'' and ``You feel good and you look
like you should / But you could never make us proud.'' The lyrics
give the media a juicy hook to grab on to, but Dylan, now 30 and
happily married with two of his own children, says that listeners
shouldn't jump to conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this a song directly about myself and him?'' he says,
referring to his father in the third person. ``Yeah, there are
parts of it in there, but it's not really unique to me. Having
insecurities and shadows to work with, and having expectations, I
mean I don't know anybody who doesn't have that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, I don't demand that people get exactly what I'm
talking about,'' Jakob says. ``So you're left with just the music
and you're left to interpret it and I like that. . . . A lot of
times when you find out what songs are really about, you're kind of
bummed out, because maybe your interpretation was better. But, hey,
these are not term papers. They're just songs _ half of them are
true, and half of them are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the success of the last Wallflowers album has changed
his relationship with his dad, Jakob says no. ``I don't think that
record changed anything. I hope it didn't. People have imagined
that there's a distance between (my father and me), or some kind of
rip or friction, but truthfully, there is not.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album has a consistency that the Wallflowers have not
matched before. ``Letters From the Wasteland'' is a powerful
breakup song, with Dylan singing the verse, ``You abandoned me into
these fields of rank and file.'' The song ``Murder 101'' likewise
details the death of a romance (Elvis Costello adds some snappy
backing vocals), while more hopeful, reassuring emotions are voiced
in the hidden track, ``Babybird,'' a love letter to Dylan's
children.
</P>
<P>
   The album took a long time to make _ and elicited rumors that
Dylan was suffering from writer's block _ but that wasn't the case,
he says. The problem was that he simply didn't like his first batch
of tunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when you go on tour for as long as us _ two and
one-half years,'' notes Dylan. ``All I seemed able to draw from was
touring and being successful or not successful. And I don't like
that kind of material. So I just had to take some time off. I
waited about five months to settle in until I had something I
thought was more inspiring to write about.''
</P>
<P>
   Dylan, whose group is expected to play the soon-to-be-reopened
Paradise club next week in a get-reacquainted show (no ticket
details yet), is clearly, like his dad, in this business for the
long haul. ``If you're going to continue doing this past your
adolescence, then you'd better care a little more and dig in a
little deeper,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6610 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-REMEMBER-BOS &LR;      09-29 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-REMEMBER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON CARRIES `REMEMBER THE TITANS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
REMEMBER THE TITANS 
Directed by: Boaz Yakin 
Screenplay by: Gregory Allen Howard 
Starring: Denbzel Washington, Will Patton, Wood Harris, Ryan Hurst,
Donald Faison, Craig Kirkwood, Ethan Suplee, Kip Pardue, Hayden
Panettiere 
Running time: 113 minutes 
Rated: PG (thematic elements and some language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Remember the Titans,'' starring Denzel Washington, wants to be
to high school football what ``Hoosiers'' is to high school
basketball _ namely, the best movie of its kind based on a true
story. It almost is, aided by the fact that it isn't just a sports
movie. When Harold Boone took over as coach of the T. C. Williams
High School football team in Alexandria, Va., in 1971, it was a
fishbowl job. Alexandria had just been integrated. The black and
white players weren't used to being in the same building, much less
on the same team. Boone, a type-A specimen, knew that a lot of eyes
were on him, and that many could not be considered friendly.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, you will say, a pall of uplift hovers over this saga
like an umbrella defense. But Washington crashes through it, and
carries the film with him, sometimes in spite of itself. Although
he's as dynamic as anybody on the A-list, Washington got there by
demonstrating the ability, as all top stars do, of seeming to let
the camera come to him. In this film, his face is not exactly a
mask of inscrutability. We know what Coach Boone wants. He wants to
win and get the crackers off his neck. But he wants to win in any
case. We can tell by the way he bites on his whistle, and by the
angry way he blows it.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is a drillmaster here, whose opponent isn't always
the other team, or even racist animosity. It's the intrinsically
messagey nature of the film _ or would be, if Washington didn't
catch us in his moment-to-moment channeling of Vince Lombardi as
Coach Boone. He basically doesn't give his squad time to develop
racial rifts. He works them too hard and too long to leave them
much energy for much else. Because the role is so strewn with
dramatic, if not moral, pitfalls, Washington's achievement in
making the coach a riveting figure is all the more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   I wish the film had trusted its story and its star a little
more, and refrained from detonating a big groundswell of music at
each and every plot point, each and every game. We don't need the
kind of prodding and cueing the film keeps throwing at us. Yet it
works, anyway. Ultimately we root for it more than we cringe from
it. Another big reason is Will Patton, who provides some of the
quiet contrast the film so desperately needs, as the dismissed
white coach, Bill Yoast, who decides to stay on as Boone's
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, he's motivated by loyalty to his returning players, and
by a need to get them through a difficult transition. But he also
does a superb job of embodying the message that not all Southern
whites were bigoted, that some were dignified gentlemen who acted
on their principles with quiet dignity, even when it got
inconvenient. One related moment comes when a transfer quarterback
from California, of whom the Southerners don't know what to make,
drops into their midst because his Army-officer father has
experienced integration, believes in it, and enrolls his son where
he thinks his family's principles should be.
</P>
<P>
   Kip Pardue is fine as the no-longer-surfing backfield ace, but
then the entire team is engaging, especially Ryan Hurst, as the
white team captain who surprises himself by turning out to be a
bridge-builder; Wood Harris, as the black teammate who becomes his
friend; Ethan Suplee, as the roughneck whose frequent family
relocations cause him to identify more with the team's black
members than his fellow whites. Hayden Panettiere, as the white
coach's young daughter and football maven, is one who could have
perished under a load of terminal cuteness, but doesn't. The
soundtrack, on the other hand, almost does.
</P>
<P>
   You're never unaware that a lot of buttons are being pushed in
this inspirational story. You can't help wishing that a bit more
doubt and complexity had been written into it, to say nothing of a
few quiet interludes. Perhaps the training camp sequences in
Gettysburg might profitably have been downplayed in this film that
isn't exactly starved for symbolic dimension. Still, while I'm
largely immune to the proddings of football uplift movies, I'd be
lying if I didn't admit to getting caught up in ``Remember the
Titans.'' Washington and the others score in this predictable but
rousing film where the big victory is over attitudes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6612 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-PLACE-BOS &LR;      09-29 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PLACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENEUVE ENTHRALLS IN `PLACE VENDOME' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
PLACE VENDOME 
Directed by: Nicole Garcia 
Screenplay by: Garcia, Jacques Fieschi 
Starring: Catherine Deneuve, Jean-Pierre Bacri, Emmanuelle Seigner,
Jacques Dutronc, Bernard Fresson, Francois Berleand 
Running time: 117 minutes 
Rating: Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some critics, writing of Catherine Deneuve's recent films, have
lazily referred to her as ageless, thus missing the whole point of
what has made her a much more interesting actor during the last two
decades of her career than the first two. Although she has always
been one of the world's most beautiful women, she has in recent
years struck me as the female equivalent of Paul Newman _ an actor
who learned how to act once dazzling youthful good looks were no
longer the issue. Deneuve is more than cool in manner; she has a
solid foundation of good horse sense that has enabled her to
incorporate into her characters the fact that she's aging, thus
deepening them, making them more complicatedly human and affecting.
</P>
<P>
   She'll startle more than a few longtime moviegoers as a factory
worker who is anything but glamorous in the forthcoming ``Dancer in
the Dark.'' Right now, there's much to savor in ``Place Vendome,''
Nicole Garcia's richly textured thriller packed with so many
criminal and amatory betrayals that Deneuve's alcoholic widow of a
highly regarded diamond dealer can hardly sort them out. The
latter's unexpected suicide means that she will either sink
permanently into the alcoholic fog that keeps her shuttling in and
out of a pricey private clinic, or sober up fast and get some
answers. She chooses the latter course, and although she backslides
a couple of times, she soon looks like the natural appraiser her
character once had been.
</P>
<P>
   What undid her as an ambitious diamond dealer in her youth was
an ill-advised shady deal with a charmer who left her in the lurch
after having seduced her into trouble. Now it appears he's back in
the picture, in the person of Jacques Dutronc, who brings a
wonderfully lived-in face to the wheeler-dealer who apparently has
been up to his old tricks, similarly seducing Emmanuelle Seigner's
Nathalie, who reminds the widow of herself 20 years ago. Deneuve's
character is named Marianne _ a play on Deneuve's having been
chosen as the personification of the personification of France
itself. Again, looks. Yet the thing that's moving about Deneuve's
Marianne is her vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, it was her emotional naivete. Now, Deneuve uses the
fact that age has begun to blur those perfect facial contours to
feed into a sense that Marianne is fighting hard to rally, to
empower herself out of the mess she's in. She's adamantly refusing
her brother-in-law's entreaties to sell the famous old family firm
on the flossy Place Vendome, home of the Ritz. ``You think you're
strong enough,'' she says at one point, sighing at how easy it
would be to just let go again when her resolve is tested by events.
Yet she learns she'd better be strong to play the game she's
playing with seven diamonds her husband had stashed away,
especially after she learns that the DeBeers monopoly and a new
Russian cartel have their eyes on the stones as well.
</P>
<P>
   Deneuve is wonderful in several ways. Once she comes out of her
alcoholic fog, her eyes make us realize that part of the reason she
drinks is that she can still be hurt. Yet there's also a certain
hardness and a hard-won wisdom in those eyes, right there alongside
her characteristic watchfulness. Nor is she entirely a victim. When
she catches up with her old flame, she skewers him with casual
cruelty, observing in passing that he dyes his hair now. And we can
see all the old acquisitive instincts kick in when she slips on the
jeweler's loupe and is obviously turned on by the diamonds. The
reason that she's able to exhibit so many facets, of course, is
that writer-director Garcia's script allows her to.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare that a crime movie achieves such emotional complexity,
but this one is smartly layered, allowing as well for French
culture's way of allowing human impulse to bend a rule here and
there. The other players are scarcely less juicily characterized.
Dutronc doesn't just give us the charmer's charm; he projects as
well a believable tenderness that makes the charm work as well as
it does. Seigner is another plus as the young comer who isn't as
hard-edged as she thinks she is. And the marvelous Jean-Pierre
Bacri carries off with hangdog triumph the role of a disbarred
lawyer and present-day repo man, who becomes Marianne's ally,
partly because his rumpled look and damaged life allow her to relax
and even identify with him. Rarely is a movie about gems itself a
gem, but ``Place Vendome'' is a rare exception as it snatches
romance and regeneration from a slag heap of venality and
world-weariness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
