<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-THATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THAT'S LIFE' LOOKS TO RISE ABOVE FORMULA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THAT'S LIFE 
Starring: Heather Paige Kent, Ellen Burstyn, Paul Sorvino, Debi
Mazar, Kevin Dillon, Sonny Marinelli 
On: CBS 
Time: Premieres Sunday at 8 p.m., then moves to Saturdays at 8
p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rule number one about judging a new TV series like ``That's
Life'': Be conditional in your affection. You never know if the
promise of a superior pilot is going to pan out and deliver the
next ``Once and Again,'' or if it's going to deteriorate into
string cheese and leave you forever branded with sheer and utter
disgrace and shame. Because even ``Veronica's Closet'' looked like
a winner for the first half hour _ I swear.
</P>
<P>
   That said, ``That's Life'' is a promising newcomer that recalls
the ethnic comedy and spirit of the movie ``Moonstruck.'' Its
strong-willed heroine is a 32-year-old working-class woman named
Lydia DeLucca (Heather Paige Kent), who dumps her lug of a fiance
and enrolls at nearby Montclair University, much to the disgust of
her Italian-American family. Off campus, Lydia's got the Sopranos
Lite: a whiny mother (Ellen Burstyn) who's allergic to her
daughter's independence, a cop brother (Kevin Dillon) who torments
her like she's still 10, a passive father (Paul Sorvino) who
operates a toll booth and listens to the music of Joe Pesci, and a
neighborhood of Old World women who send bereavement cards when she
breaks her engagement. On campus, she's got ``Felicity'' with
attitude: Muffys in BMWs, elitist professors, and the constant
trill of a thousand cell phones ringing.
</P>
<P>
   It all veers dangerously close to TV's familiar culture-clash
formula, with Lydia torn between her blue-collar roots and the
university snoots. But the show's creator, Diane Ruggerio, is also
interested in the well-acted ensemble and their nutty, Tri-State
flourishes. She's aiming for slice-of-life dramedy, a genre that
depends on local color as much as _ if not more than _ plotting.
Why else would she have recruited not only Burstyn and Sorvino but
Debi Mazar, who personifies local color? Mazar plays Lydia's
beautician friend Jackie with all the gum-chewing wisecracks and
scene-stealing you'd expect. When Jackie styles Lydia's hair on her
first day of college, she comes up with a twirling, towering
creation that couldn't be further from the flat-haired Gwyneths
also signed up for ``Post Modernism and the Decentering of Self.''
It's a kitsch coif that screams 1950s, and Lydia is horrified.
</P>
<P>
   The writing of ``That's Life,'' which airs Sunday at 8 p.m. on
CBS before moving to Saturdays at 8 p.m. also tries to lift it a
level above formula. The premiere episode is clever enough to bury
the series' central theme into the plot, when Lydia's psychology
professor assigns her a paper on whether her life is
pre-determined, or whether she has free will. Also, with Lydia's
voiceover guiding us through comic might-have-beens and early
memories, the narrative structure has a bit of dash. The only
gimmicky piece in ``That's Life'' is the soundtrack, which blasts
songs like ``Mambo Italiano'' like a nonstop jukebox in a
neighborhood cantina. They're Italian, we got it.
</P>
<P>
   As the lead, Kent is better than her recent sitcom gig in
``Stark Raving Mad'' might have suggested. She's passionate, tough,
not conventionally pretty, and a good mirror for the curious people
around her. She makes a desire to learn appealing, but not a big
moral deal. I hope, though, that the show continues to develop each
member of its ensemble, and not keep them hanging around Kent only
as comic relief. Kristin Bauer's Miss New Jersey 1988, for example,
who's still clinging to her former reigning glory. Surely, there's
a tragicomic backstory there.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Providence'' and ``Judging Amy,'' ``That's Life'' is
built around a woman chasing her own identity despite cultural and
familial pressures. But it doesn't seem bent on cloying
emotionality (except for a moment or two toward the end), and it
doesn't overwhelm us with gratuitous melodrama. It's breezy fun _
at least so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
