<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BEAUTIFUL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEAUTIFUL' IS BARELY SKIN DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BEAUTIFUL 
Directed by: Sally Field 
Screenplay by: Jon Bernstein 
Starring: Minnie Driver, Joey Lauren Adams, Leslie Stefanson,
Bridgette Wilson, Kathleen Turner, Hallie Kate Eisenberg, Kathleen
Robertson, Michael McKean, Gary Collins, Linda Hart, Brent Briscoe 
Running time: 112 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (language and thematic elements) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gap between satire and sentiment proves unbridgeable in
``Beautiful,'' Sally Field's directing debut. The idea is to have
Minnie Driver's love-starved Mona learn the difference between
outer and inner beauty as she grows from 12-year-old ugly duckling
to national beauty pageant finalist. But the lesson in life is
rendered in off-puttingly simplistic terms. Worse, the film cops
out at the end by embracing the beauty pageant, treating it as
something of value, not as an apotheosis of the shallow values the
film had been steering Mona to reject. Maybe the reason the film
seems so tepid and compromised is that Field is just too nice.
</P>
<P>
   What's funny at the start is young Mona's single-mindedness. She
keps entering contest after contest even though she never wins.
Fueling her drive, it soon becomes clear, is that she's looking for
love she isn't getting from her unaffectionate mother. The big
thing Mona has going for her is a mousy girlfriend, Ruby, whose
devotion approaches the saintly and whose sewing abilities mean
that Mona gets a succession of upgraded gowns and costumes. How
saintly is Joey Lauren Adams's Ruby? When Mona becomes pregnant and
gives birth to a daughter that would disqualify her from the beauty
pageant circuit, Ruby passes off the baby as hers.
</P>
<P>
   The comedy begins to ebb when Mona's desperation and dirty
competitive tricks give way to more basic emotional needs. When
Ruby is jailed because of a misunderstanding and Mona goes off to
California as Miss Illinois in her first national contest, it's
with the little girl who looks like Mona but has been told Ruby is
her mother. Events unfold along deflatingly predictable lines as
Mona feels more and more conflicted and the initial prickliness
that had existed between her and the little girl is replaced by
mutual neediness and chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   The tame, confused script sinks the film, although Field shows
skill directing actors. Driver totters under the sellout of Mona,
but Adams _ so memorable in ``Chasing Amy'' _ survives the
canonization conferred upon Ruby. Field's directorial abilities are
perhaps best revealed in the surprising degrees of complexity she
gets from Bridgette Wilson and Kathleen Robertson in peripheral
roles as Mona's competitors. Perhaps I'd have been less sour about
``Beautiful,'' and not demanded sharper, more wicked satire if I
hadn't just come from a screening of Christopher Guest's ``Best in
Show,'' opening Oct. 13, in which he does for dog shows what he did
for amateur theatricals in ``Waiting for Guffman.'' In any case,
``Beautiful'' is, on any level, anything but.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
