<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 U.S. BOXERS RETAIN GOLD MEDAL HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ From his corner ringside perch Friday night,
the U.S. boxing coach, Tom Mustin, watched the first round unfold
between his fighter, Ricardo Williams Jr., and Cuba's powerful
Diogenes Luna and had just one thought: We're in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the ring, Williams had already tested the prefight plan
and come to a similar conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to counterpunch over his right hand like we talked
about,'' Williams said afterward. ``He ducked it and threw a quick
right that hit me right in the forehead. I said to myself, `It's
going to be a long night.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan was to stick and move, don't slug it out. But I knew
right then my only chance was going toe-to-toe for four rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams willingly took on the hardy, more experienced Luna, but
by the midpoint of their semifinal, things weren't looking much
better for the American. Williams, a 139-pound light welterweight
from Cincinnati, had a sore left cheekbone and was behind in the
official scoring by 6 points.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this juncture that the referee separated the fighters
after a clinch. Williams dropped his hands because the referee had
shouted to stop punching. That's when Luna hit Williams on the side
of the head. Luna got a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said, ``I got mad.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was the most spirited round and a half of the 2000
Olympic boxing tournament.
</P>
<P>
   With a torrent of lefts and rights, Williams backed Luna onto
the ropes, then pounded him into a corner, outscoring the Cuban by
16-8 for the remainder of the third round to take the points lead.
Then, in an extraordinary final round, with both exhausted fighters
winging dozens of power punches, Williams and Luna traded the lead
with every exchange. Williams rallied last, a left and a right put
him ahead, and he held on to win on points, 42-41.
</P>
<P>
   The total of punches scored, 83, was 33 more than in any other
bout in these Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Williams will fight Mahamadkadyz Abdullaev of Uzbekistan for the
gold medal Sunday. Joining Williams in the gold medal round Friday
was the American featherweight Ricardo Juarez, who defeated Kamil
Dzamalutdinov of Russia on points, 23-12. The U.S. light
middleweight Jermain Taylor was defeated by Yermakhan Ibraimov of
Kazakhstan, 29-14.
</P>
<P>
   Ibraimov was too determined for Taylor, who for the first time
in the Olympics looked sluggish. Taylor will still receive a bronze
medal.
</P>
<P>
   Juarez, who will also face a Kazakh fighter, Bekzat
Sattarkhanov, in the finals, is a reigning world champion and was
expected to get to the gold medal round. Juarez is the team's
smartest fighter, its most disciplined and its most tenacious. He
has won 68 consecutive bouts and, among his teammates, should make
the most immediate impact as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams, 19, was not considered a top American medal
contender in part because he had a history of undertraining. And he
was hardly favored against Luna, especially after Luna won his
quarterfinal fight with a one-punch knockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to dig deep in a lot of ways,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Mustin has called Williams the most talented American fighter on
the team because of his hand-eye coordination and foot speed. But
his training habits, while adequate, at one time were not
exceptional. That has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I had talent and I could get by with that,''
Williams said Friday. ``But the other guys had talent and
determination. I had to fix that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a loss in last year's world championships to Abdullaev,
whom he will face again for the gold, which was the turning point
for Williams. Eleven years earlier, his father, Ricardo Sr., who
had a brief professional boxing career, had taken his son to the
gym to learn to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had three sisters,'' Ricardo Jr. said. ``They didn't want me
playing with Barbie dolls all the time. My dad taught me the sport,
and I liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   But last year, the father, a part-time artist and a full-time
painter for the Cincinnati housing authority, took the son aside
and suggested he make the most of his ring skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important time in my life,'' Ricardo Jr. said. ``It
was time to see just how much I could make of my boxing. It was
conditioning and ring work.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has charged through the Olympic tournament, with no
performance more convincing than Friday night's. Luna and Williams
were trading bombs in the middle of the ring and on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Or as Mustin said: ``That was no boxing match. They were tossing
some luggage out there.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fight's final seconds, Williams finally thought the extra
work was going to pay off. He heard his father yelling from his
ringside seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was yelling, `Stick and move,''' Williams said. ``The
original plan. He probably knew I was ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   With 15 seconds to go, Williams had a 1-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my track shoes on,'' Williams said. ``I think I would
have beat Michael Johnson late in that round.''
</P>
<P>
   Luna threw a left hand with six seconds left that Williams
danced away from, though it grazed his face. It was the last punch
in the fight of the tournament. But the judges, perhaps with
fatigue in their fingers, did not score it as a landed punch.
Williams had won.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that the two Ricardos _ Williams and Juarez _ are the
last gold medal hopes for the Americans. No U.S. boxing team has
failed to win at least one gold medal since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved that we've got two guys left,'' Mustin said. ``I
sure don't want to be the first coach not to win one in 52 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But the day's events, especially Williams' surprising and heroic
victory, had bolstered Mustin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty lucky to be going to war with these two guys,'' he
said.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
