u e BC-MUSIC-BANGLES-BOS &LR;      09-29 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BANGLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BANGLES REUNITE, IN HARMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Susannah Hoffs is breathless. She starts and stops and starts
again, searching for a way to describe what it feels like to be a
Bangle again. Once she finds the right words, they tumble out with
the giddy bounce of, well, a Bangles song.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of feeling completely like I've come home
to something that is so familiar, but that's also better,'' says
Hoffs, on the phone from a hotel room in Chicago. ``We're better
with age. It's like we understand each other in a new kind of way,
and we know how to be better friends. It's not that we weren't
before, because we were great friends before. But being on the road
all the time ... it can do something to you. We just needed a
change. And we ended it instead of taking a year off.''
</P>
<P>
   So goes the happy, then sad, then happy story of four
harmonizing girls _ women now _ who came up in LA's '60s-influenced
Paisley Underground and hit it big in the late '80s with a string
of Top 40 songs like ``Manic Monday,'' ``Walk Like an Egyptian,''
``If She Knew What She Wants,'' and ``Eternal Flame.'' They were on
top of the world and sinking fast.
</P>
<P>
   When singer-guitarist Hoffs, guitarist Vicki Peterson, and her
sister, drummer Debbi Peterson, and bassist Michael Steele decided
to call it quits in 1989, anything vaguely resembling harmony had
vanished. They'd had it on a lot of levels: a grueling cycle of
touring and recording, an increasingly glossy sound _ encouraged by
the record company and management _ that was responsible for their
biggests hits, and the media's focus on gamine, girlish Hoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult for everyone,'' Hoffs recalls. ``The band
wanted the world to know that this is a group, like Crosby, Stills,
Nash, and Young, that has a structure of four singers and four
writers, with no one focal point, no one lead singer. And I think
that created a frustration, and that frustration led to tension,
and it became painful all the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   So painful, in fact, that when Hoffs began calling the others a
few years ago to feel them out, to see if anyone had an interest in
getting together to write or play, she didn't get an enthusiastic
response, Hoffs confesses. ``I was pretty actively calling people
for years. It was so traumatic when it ended, I think they were in
a mind-set that it would just never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele had escaped to Northern California to write and paint.
Vicki Peterson was working with her band the Continental Drifters,
based in New Orleans. Debbi Peterson and Hoffs were both involved
in solo projects, recording with other bands, and raising families
in Los Angeles. Hoffs's ministrations finally succeeded, however,
and last year the band recorded a song for the soundtrack to
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' which her husband, Jay
Roach, directed. A few weeks later she got a call from an old
friend putting together a George Martin tribute, and the Bangles
reunited for their first live show in 10 years _ singing five
Beatles songs at the Hollywood Bowl. The chemistry, Hoffs says, was
back.
</P>
<P>
   So it's official: the Bangles are back together, out on a
mini-tour and approaching phase two with a newfound thoughtfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess one perk of getting older is all this wisdom and
understanding,'' Hoffs muses. ``For me, being a mom has given me a
lot in terms of figuring out a way to make things work. If
someone's cranky, instead of no one talking about it or dealing
with it, you ask `how do we fix this?' One of the prerequisites we
set up going in was it had to be a positive experience for
everybody. No one should feel like they're compromising. No one
should feel like they're having their souls ripped away. You can
say no.''
</P>
<P>
   The four have been writing like crazy, generating new material
and incorporating songs and ideas each has been honing over the
years. They're going into the studio as soon as they get off the
road in October, and hope to release the fourth Bangles album next
year. The band is starting to introduce new songs at the live
shows, and of course serving up plenty of old favorites. More
important, says Hoffs, there's a sense of personal harmony as sweet
as the vocal harmonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just did three shows in a row at House of Blues in LA. We
were careful planning our set, and it had this really nice flow. I
really think everybody saw what we wanted them to see _ that
there's this great balance going on. Everybody has their moment,''
says Hoffs. ``Everybody shines in their way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
