<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN30-CO     09-29 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOEMURRAY-COLUMN
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Life hasn't been the same since
meeting Earl Grey
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I like to start the day with a cuppa tea,
sitting on the balcony, reading the newspaper and watching the
morning traffic of people on their way to work.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when I drank coffee instead. But I have found tea to be
so much more ... well, civilized.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that it was my uncivilized appearance that led to
this realization.
</P>
<P>
   Some years back I was staying at the Ritz in London for a night
or two before heading off to Scotland and Ireland on assignment.
</P>
<P>
   I was traveling, as I do whenever I can, with only a single
piece of luggage, a carry-on bag at that.
</P>
<P>
   It never ceases to astonish airlines personnel at the check-in
counter that someone going to Europe for a couple of weeks has no
bags to check.
</P>
<P>
   But it's an easy way to travel and not so hard to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   You really don't need much more than a couple of extra pairs of
pants, a few neatly folded shirts, underwear, socks and toilet
accessories, all of which will go into a bag that will fit into the
overhead compartment.
</P>
<P>
   You may want to even throw in a tie and a sports coat, which I
had failed to include on the trip that had me staying at the Ritz.
</P>
<P>
   When I showed up at the hotel dining room that evening in my
usual garb _ a zipper jacket, blue Oxford shirt and khaki pants,
comfortable shoes and white socks _ the maitre 'd seemed sincerely
happy to see me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, good evening, sir!'' he sang out, smiling warmly and
nodding his head in a friendly way.
</P>
<P>
   Returning the smile and nod, I asked for a table for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm afraid not, sir,'' he said, shaking his head in a
friendly way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there a problem with the way I'm dressed?'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm afraid so, sir,'' he said, still smiling his warm
smile. ``But I'm sure you will be welcome in the tea room.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was that I ended up supping at the Ritz on tea and
biscuits. I stopped short of trying to order iced tea or, for that
matter, gravy with the biscuits. As it turned out, what they call
biscuits is what we call cookies.
</P>
<P>
   But I have to say that tea in the tea room of the Ritz was jolly
good and quite refreshing, and I came away much impressed with Earl
Grey.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you don't know about Earl Grey, whose name happened to be
Charles. The Epicurious Dictionary can tell you all about him and
his tea:
</P>
<P>
   ``Earl Grey: This popular black tea was named for Charles Grey,
the second earl in his line, who was also prime minister to King
William IV in the early 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``An amalgamation of Indian and Sri Lankan teas, Earl Grey gets
its elusive flavor from oil of bergamot. The Earl is said to have
been given the recipe by a Chinese mandarin with whom he was
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergamot (BER-gah-mot) is a small acidic orange, and bergamot
oil is produced from its peel. Funny they didn't use a mandarin
orange.
</P>
<P>
   No matter: Earl Grey tea, of which there is any number of
varieties, seems to have caught on over the last century and a
half.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays it's sold even in the supermarkets of my little
hometown _ though I wouldn't be surprised if you asked for Earl
Grey the clerk would scratch his head and tell you that to the best
of his knowledge they don't have anybody working there by that
name.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, if you're passing by my house on your way to work
in the morning, wave to me there on the balcony. Honk if you love
Earl Grey.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
