<P>
   DEBATES (Washington) _ Millions of voters will get a chance to
see Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush in a live,
unscripted showdown Tuesday night when they square off in the first
of three debates that could sway the outcome of the closest
presidential election in 20 years. In preparing this weekend for
the Tuesday debate, Gore is holing up in Sarasota, Fla., where he's
taking tips from some ordinary citizens invited to take part, and
Bush is practicing with aides and advisers at his ranch in
Crawford, Texas. BY STEWART M. POWELL. (1stLd-Writethru updating
story filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-ELECTION (Washington) _ Al Gore and George W. Bush are
knocking themselves out trying to one-up the other on education, an
issue at the top of voters' concerns. Each would dramatically boost
federal education spending, and each has a plan to raise student
achievement, but they are polar opposites on the controversial idea
of vouchers. We compare and contrast the two candidates' plans. By
DAN FREEDMAN. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
