<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-HOLOCAUSTRADIO _ JERUSALEM _ Offered 12 minutes a day to
try something new over the summer, Israeli radio host Yaron Enosh
opened the airwaves to people still looking for missing relatives
from the Nazi Holocaust. It turned into a moving and popular piece
of reality programming that exposed the many fractures that remain
in Jewish families 55 years after World War II. Now, hundreds of
Holocaust survivors or their children fax and call in their
requests daily. There have been about 100 reunions since Aug. 1.
One man located his missing father. Another found relatives who
could fill in details about a deceased uncle. Israelis have also
used the show to hook up with army buddies they lost track of after
the 1973 Yom Kippur War. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). With photo of
talk show host.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-0930 _ JERUSALEM _ In some of the worst
violence in four years, five Palestinians were killed in rioting
Friday at a religious holy site in Jerusalem's walled Old City. the
rioting, which also resulted in more than 100 people injured,
followed a controversial visit to the sacred Dome of Rock (or
Temple Mount) by Israeli Likud Party leader Ariel Sharon a day
earlier. Prime Minister Ehud Barak called for calm, and a
continuation of the fractured Mideast peace process. Developing.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
