<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Dogs sniff one another because
they are communicating on some basic level. They are communicating
with pheromones, odorless molecules that waft from most animals.
These powerful molecules carry important messages. Pheromones tell
animals what they are supposed to do, such as run, fight or have
sex. The nice thing about pheromone messages is that animals don't
have to worry if they are making the right decision. (Rowland
Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Many years ago I knew a
writer in New York who loved to boast about what he considered the
greatest accomplishment of his moderately distinguished career. He
sold Reader's Digest articles on three different people for the
magazine's then premier feature, ``The Most Unforgettable Character
I've Ever Known.'' In later years, and more appropriate to the
times, ``Unforgettable Character'' became ``Unforgettable
Personality.'' The subject almost always was someone who had
triumphed over great adversity, usually with a sense of humor,
humility and perseverance. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ My husband is a man of
principle. There is no way, Jim declared, that our family would
ever be a three-cat family. Two cats? Maybe. But three cats, as he
put it so tactfully, ``bordered on crazy-cat-lady status.''
(McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ I like to start the day with
a cuppa tea, sitting on the balcony, reading the newspaper and
watching the morning traffic of people on their way to work. Time
was when I drank coffee instead. But I have found tea to be so much
more ... well, civilized. Never mind that it was my uncivilized
appearance that led to this realization. (Murray, Cox News
Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-GALVESTON _ One hundred years after the nation's
deadliest hurricane washed away much of Texas' most advanced city,
Izola Collins _ 70 and a retired Galveston music teacher _ is
telling the story of blacks who survived the great Galveston storm
of 1900. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
