   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week. The
layout is available now. Art includes four color photos and two
color illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   CoxNet HEALTHY LIVING 0930: THE FIX ON FIBROIDS _ Until
recently, hysterectomy was the most frequently recommended
treatment for fibroids, a noncancerous tissue growth that is a
source of misery for legions of American women. But women now have
a new option: uterine artery embolization, a treatment still
considered experimental by some doctors and insurers. (Staples,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 4-column color
illustration showing facts about fibroids and a 2-column color
photo of a nurse who underwent a innovative fibroids procedure.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB _ Attention Deficit Disorder and its treatments are
as hotly debated on the Web as they are in society at large, with
possibly hundreds of sites linking families coping with the
disorder. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a
6-pica color illustration of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES STUDY _ A 19-year study of adult diabetics in Texas has
led to a surprising breakthrough: a gene carrying seemingly useless
``junk DNA'' makes some people likely targets for diabetes. (Roser,
Austin American-Statesman) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of
researcher.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING CONTROL _ Almost two years ago, Joseph ``Joey''
Cristofaro Jr. got sick of squeezing into his size 46 pants and
catching his breath in stairwells. He was tired of weighing 285
pounds. Here's how he lost 100 pounds in a year. (Hutchins, Palm
Beach Post) Art includes two color photos of man before and after
losing 100 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   TWIN-CONNECTION _ If it were written as a TV sitcom, the premise
would be rejected as ridiculous. Two strangers from Clark County,
Ohio, both redheads named Amy, are due to deliver twins within days
of each other. Both deliver twin girls. Both decide to be original
with their babies' names. Both choose Sidney (Sydney) and Savanna.
Both Savannas develop health complications requiring surgery. And
the women's friendship starts when a Dayton Children's Hospital
nurse makes the connection and tells Amy Combs, ``There's someone I
think you ought to meet.'' (Trump, Springfield News-Sun). WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CIVILWAR-REENACT _ A personal account of getting involved with
Civil War re-enactments _ as well as where in the heck you buy
those uniforms. (Nurse, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLTOWN-ART _ HAMILTON, Ohio _ Can you imagine a small city
basing its hopes on fine art? On sculpture? Is that too much of a
stretch? Hamilton, Ohio, hopes not. It recently designated itself
``The City of Sculpture,'' and installed an imposing piece of
public art in front of the new government center to make the point.
(Dayton Daily News). 26. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ ATLANTA _ Once again I have been
asked if I can provide plans for an object that I've never heard of
or seen. ``I would like to know if you have plans for a viewing
bench for a pool room, or where I could obtain one,'' a reader asks
via e-mail. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
