<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIANS CONFIDENT THEY CAN BRING GOLIATH DOWN IN WOMEN'S
BASKETBALL FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos OLY 3,4,5 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The kid from Adelaide finally caved in three
weeks ago. Between the interview requests, the slippage in her game
and the mounting expectations of a nation, Lauren Jackson no longer
felt like the star of the Australian national team.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, she was just another overwhelmed 19-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably shouldn't think about the pressure, but before the
Olympics I just collapsed in a crying heap,'' Jackson said. ``It
was everything I guess, the Olympics and everything else. I was
worried.''
</P>
<P>
   She spoke moments after leading Australia to its first
appearance in a gold medal game, where Jackson and the Australians
would finally get their Olympic wish: A date with Lisa Leslie and
Team USA.
</P>
<P>
   Before nearly 15,000 of their chanting fans at the Super Dome in
Olympic Park, Australia beat Brazil, 64-52. Jackson's 16 points and
9 rebounds led the way. The United States struggled early against
South Korea before rallying for a 78-65 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Swoopes scored 19 points before leaving the game with
about four minutes left while holding her left knee. She was
expected to play against Australia. Leslie added 15 points and 12
rebounds, while Natalie Williams contributed 11 rebounds and 10
points.
</P>
<P>
   The gold medal matchup on Saturday between the Americans and the
Australians has been anticipated for two and a half weeks after a
spirited exhibition between the two teams in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
   The Australians opened an 18-6 lead in the opening minutes of
that game and trailed only 38-37 at halftime. They were run off the
floor in the final minutes, losing, 83-62. The game featured a
minor altercation between Jackson and Leslie, who chest-bumped
Jackson after Jackson had scuffled with Swoopes under the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized what she was doing,'' Jackson said. ``I came back
to her and said, `What do you want? Do you want a piece of me?' She
ran off. I won't stand for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women are seeking their second straight gold medal.
They will have to battle not only Jackson, Michele Timms and
teammates but also a loud, partisan crowd that would love to see
Goliath brought down.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, we're the team you love to hate,'' Leslie
said. ``We have a saying back home: Don't player hate. Celebrate.
We play hard, is all. If they want to play clean, we'll play clean.
If they want to fight, we will fight. We can go any way.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled. ``Why we're the bad guys, I don't know. Can't we all
just get along?''
</P>
<P>
   The game will also mark the end to Teresa Edwards' 16-year
international career. The five-time Olympian and starting U.S.
point guard will finish her career against Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it, the end of my blessed career,'' she said, almost
facetiously. ``My family is ready for me to come home. Am I
thinking about it? I don't have time to worry about Teresa Edwards'
last game. I have to worry about the gold medal.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Australia won its first women's basketball medal in Atlanta four
years ago, taking home the bronze. With the development of Jackson
and the maturing of Timms, Kristi Harrower and Michelle Griffiths _
players with Women's National Basketball Association experience _
the Opals have become one of the world's strongest teams.
</P>
<P>
   They move the ball around the perimeter, wait for Jackson to
come open on the blocks and get back to play transition defense.
Australia swept through the preliminary games and is 7-0 over the
past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson entrenched herself as one of the game's preeminent
players, backing her way in for layups, spotting up for 3-pointers
and rejecting shots back to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We engulfed her with confidence,'' Timms said. ``She was just
young and going through a lot. She's back now, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jackson, ``I was crying after every game. I wasn't playing
well. I was getting really scared. After playing America in
Melbourne, it lifted a little bit and after that I was confident,
back to my old attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I really think we can beat the Americans. We showed
we could play with them. Now we just have to take the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
