<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-TV-EBERSOL-ART-62     09-29 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TV-EBERSOL-ART-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF NBC SPORTS ASSESSES COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo OLY 21 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ You must understand, Dick Ebersol said, he
loves the Olympics. He relishes controlling the production, is
riveted by athletic sacrifice and adores his staff. He has worked
20-hour days, rarely seen his wife and his youngest son, and looks
as if he needs a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Ebersol, the chairman of NBC Sports, finishes producing
the last prime-time broadcast at 3 p.m. on Monday, he said: ``I'll
be sad because it's over. I'd like it to go on for another week.''
</P>
<P>
   He insists that he is not depressed about lower-than-expected
ratings, nor is he frantic to change anything to resuscitate them.
He is astonished at criticism that he is carrying the Olympics on
tape from 15 to 18 time zones away and won't carry live events at 4
or 5 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media would love to have us treat the Olympics like a
basketball game: just tip it off and assume everyone knows
everything about the Olympics,'' he said Friday. ``But the reason
the Olympics are popular is that Roone Arledge decided in 1964 that
outside a core audience, Olympic sports don't have a core audience
in the U.S., so you can't treat them like any other sport.''
</P>
<P>
   This should be a time of lavish praise for Ebersol. It is not.
He will never receive the kudos accorded Arledge, his mentor at ABC
Sports, and still his guiding light. Arledge invented the Olympic
format that Ebersol has adopted, writ large, in the era of the
Internet, 100 or more cable channels and fractionalized viewer
interest. Arledge created the tape-delayed Olympics in a
three-network universe when the financial stakes were smaller and
mass audience easier to predict.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of hosannas for Ebersol is why he called his former
rival at CBS Sports, Neal Pilson, now an industry consultant, to
thank him for praising NBC's production and saying it is not
responsible for lower ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol laughed when he read in a newspaper column that he had
ruined the Olympics by carrying them on tape or was in trouble with
his bosses at General Electric for not delivering enough on the
$705 million Sydney rights fee. First, he said, the Games will
produce an estimated $80 million profit. Second, he said, ``You
can't get any more straightforward support than the chairman of
your company saying, `If you change a thing, I'll punch you in the
nose.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol is one of the smoothest executives in television, the
longest-serving of the network sports' division presidents, and the
most cognizant of shaping his public image. He is as fluent in the
language of production as he in the minutiae of Nielsen ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every day in Sydney, usually in late afternoon, he has
emerged from his control room for 5 to 30 minutes, tired but
somehow energetic, loquacious, sometimes puffing a fetid cigar,
eager to fill the pads of an audience of reporters sometimes as
small as one.
</P>
<P>
   He has rarely disappointed. If he hasn't put the best possible
spin on the ratings, he has alerted his audience to a particular
feature. Repeatedly he has excoriated ``jealous'' newspaper editors
for assigning stories comparing NBC's taped Olympics to what he
calls the Canadian Broadcasting Co.'s ludicrous live ones without
reporting on the CBC's minuscule predawn ratings.
</P>
<P>
   But if you've missed those numbers, he has them ready for you in
a handout.
</P>
<P>
   He described newspaper bashing of his production as
``bloodsport,'' a result of being more immediate, even on tape,
than newspapers are from Sydney. ``I'm convinced that this is the
newest Olympic sport,'' he said. ``It goes on in the United States,
in Australia, in Europe. Editors have had a hard time getting used
to the dominance of television in the Olympics.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He cannot see how his production is failing viewers. Nightly
surveys, he said, produce viewer satisfaction of more than 90
percent, and he added, he is not framing the questions. He
confesses to underestimating the depressing impact of an Olympics
in September, when young people are returning to school, and adults
are returning from vacation.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the September telecasts, he said, historically
high Olympic ratings from 11 p.m. to midnight have slumped. ``We
plateau at 11 o'clock, then the local news break hits, and you
could have live naked water polo and viewers won't come back for
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has minimized the effect of the Internet on viewing habits
and insists that until it is possible to wall off countries and
sell online rights the way television rights are sold; he will not
diminish his taped broadcasts with live video on his Web site,
nbcolympics.com.
</P>
<P>
   But Ebersol's strategy has been mocked in Australian newspapers
and on the ribald nightly Olympic recap program, ``The Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not letting it bother me much,'' he said. `` If I had any
sensitivity about it _ and it's far less than it was in Atlanta _ I
don't have any now.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Atlanta, he had superior ratings as a shield against
criticism of his production. Through Wednesday, NBC's average
Nielsen rating of a 14.5 and a 25 share is off 19 percent from the
1992 Barcelona and the 1988 Seoul Olympics, and 36 percent from the
22.5 and 42 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Each rating point equals slightly more than a million television
households and the share is the percentage of TV sets in use that
are tuned to a particular program.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Costas, the prime-time host, said Ebersol had handled the
Sydney broadcasts with the same equanimity he brought to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very optimistic person with a sure sense of himself,''
he said. ``It's an understanding of what a leader does. There is no
flagging of spirits here. That's largely because of Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   As he looks ahead, Ebersol said, much of the Winter Games in
Salt Lake City will be carried live, but the Athens Summer Olympics
in 2004 will be on tape. ``Live doesn't work in Athens with its
seven-hour time difference,'' he said. ``Where would a final fit in
prime time? You'd have to run it in the middle of the night. Do you
wake an athlete up and send him to the stadium at 2 in the
morning?''
</P>
<P>
   And so, it seems, Ebersol is arming for another media lashing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
