<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6652 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-REPORTER'S-JOURNA     09-29 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-REPORTER'S-JOURNAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PARADISE FOUND: A REFUGE FROM CELL PHONES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ I'm going for the gold. It's down to the
quarterfinals. Wish me luck.
</P>
<P>
   The sport, a new one on the program at Sydney 2000, is Cell
Phone Avoidance. I've been in Australia three weeks now and haven't
used a cell phone once. That places me in a highly elite category
of Stone Age scribes who refuse to make concessions to this modern
world of ours.
</P>
<P>
   I hate cell phones. That makes me a misanthrope on a grand
scale, since I appear to be one of the few people left without one.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ring that annoys me. If it's not
``dee-da-lee-da-da-da-dee,'' it's ``Waltzing Matilda'' or the
``Charge of the Light Brigade'' or the theme from ``Godfather.''
Aarrrgh!
</P>
<P>
   Put 200 reporters in one room waiting for a press conference and
an eruption of cell-phone ringing results. This is all the more
infuriating since a sign on the door clearly states ``Please turn
off your mobile phones.''
</P>
<P>
   As a press conference is about to begin, the moderator politely
asks people to turn their phones off. Fat lot of good that does. As
the bronze medalist from Jamaica is explaining her race strategy,
several cell phones go off within seconds of one another.
</P>
<P>
   Civility and common sense give way to an overriding sense of
self-importance: ``I'm soooo important, I have to take this call;
never mind the press conference.''
</P>
<P>
   My abstinence is actually counter-productive and altogether dumb
because cell phones represent an easy way to communicate with the
folks back home. Nothing worth doing is worth doing easily, I say.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's a liberating feeling not being in touch. Don't
call me, I'll call you. Find me if you can, Jack.
</P>
<P>
   While cell phones at the Olympics make sense (nothing worth
doing is worth doing sensibly, I say), back home they seem little
more than a fashion accessory.
</P>
<P>
   Get in the car, punch up the cell phone and tell people you're
in your car. Go to a bar, punch up the cell phone and tell people
you're in the bar, then show your lack of proper grammar by saying
in a loud voice, ``Where you at?''
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Where are you?'' and where that is is a place I don't
want to go.
</P>
<P>
   Where I want to go is the top of the medal platform for the gold
in Cell Phone Avoidance. Wish me luck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
