<HEADER>
A6698 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TEXAS-PROFILING-HNS &LR;      09-29 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PROFILING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS TROOPERS TAKING STEPS TO AVOID PROFILING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DARYL BELL and RUDOLPH BUSH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Amid growing national concern over racial
profiling, the Texas Department of Public Safety has acknowledged
that it has been keeping detailed information since March 1 about
the race and sex of all people stopped by state troopers.
</P>
<P>
   The results of this study should be released within two months,
department spokesman Tom Vinger said late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racial profiling is against DPS policy and we feel against the
(U.S.) Constitution and is illegal,'' Vinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Activists working to stop racial profiling praised that
statement and the study itself, but were concerned that the public
was not made aware sooner that such information is being gathered.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we're pleased they're doing it,'' said Will
Harrell, executive director of the Texas American Civil Liberties
Union in Austin. ``But I'll leave it to the philosophers if a tree
makes noise when it falls in the forest. As a member of the public,
I want to know if there is a problem. It's nice to know they're
taking a positive step, but it's a meaningless one if they don't
produce, analyze and publicize the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it seems like the DPS was hedging their bets. They
didn't want the public to know, especially if it raised a flag,
that they may have something to hide,'' Harrell said. ``The fact
they did it for some time and did not inform the public is
puzzling.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinger emphatically denied that the Department of Public Safety
was ``hedging its bets.'' He said the new record-keeping is in
response to growing public concern about racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't trying to sneak this under the radar,'' he said.
``Once we made a decision to gather the information it is by law
public record and it's going to come out sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping these records because it's a hot-button topic.
It's something the public is very interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the department has kept public records on the race
of people issued citations or involved in traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The racial breakdown, however, grouped whites and Hispanics
under one category.
</P>
<P>
   Now the agency is keeping tabs on all stops, including warning
tickets, and race is broken down into more specific categories _
primarily white, black, Hispanic and Asian.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Gov. George W. Bush said the governor supports
the policy. ``Governor Bush and the Department of Public Safety
absolutely do not tolerate law enforcement officers stopping people
simply because of their race or ethnicity,'' Linda Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   New laws requiring law enforcement officers to keep racial and
other demographic data on traffic stops have passed in Connecticut,
Kansas, North Carolina, Massachusetts, Missouri, Rhode Island,
Tennessee and Washington state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
