<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6715 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOK-TAPES-REVIEW-$AD     09-29 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TAPES-REVIEW-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COP CREATES A COMPELLING TALE IN `JUDAS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Judas Judge,'' by Michael McGarrity. Read by Bruce
Greenwood. Abridged, approximately 4.5 hours. Simon &AMP; Schuster
Audio. $25.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't seem right that a retired law enforcement officer can
evolve into as skilled a writer as McGarrity. Even if it's a matter
of writing about what he knows best _ New Mexico, state police and
sex crimes _ he's doing it well.
</P>
<P>
   This is McGarrity's fifth novel in five years, all featuring
Kevin Kerney, who, like the author, is an accomplished cop looking
to retire. Yet, each time out McGarrity adds layers of complexity
to Kerney, making him more and more compelling. For example, we
learn (as does Kerney) in ``The Judas Judge'' that Kerney and a
Native American woman he went to college with produced a son, who
is also in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, McGarrity takes the reader/listener to the
sun-splashed vistas of New Mexico and its wide-open highways with a
feel for the land and an ability to express it in sparse detail
that take his books beyond mere police procedurals. He is a real
writer who surely will soon be recognized as such.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Half A Heart,'' by Rosellen Brown. Read by Jayne Atkinson and
Lisagay Hamilton. Abridged, approximately 6 hours. Simon &AMP; Schuster
Audio. $25.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the acclaimed author of ``Before And After'' and ``Tender
Mercies'' among other novels, has almost penned a compelling story
with ``Half A Heart.'' Almost.
</P>
<P>
   In brief, a white, upper-crust Houstonian tries to reunite with
the biracial child she gave birth to two decades ago, when she was
a graduate student in Mississippi in the 1960s. By letter, she is
able to reach the girl, now a high school graduate who was raised
in Brooklyn by her father, a math professor.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, mother and child, virtual strangers since the
girl was just a few months old, find it difficult to connect
emotionally. When they do bond, it is as if a made-for-TV movie has
seen its two hours end with conclusion that is emotionally
satisfying but feels forced and unlikely. Jayne Atkinson, the
primary reader, and Lisagay Hamilton, the voice of Ronnee, the
girl, add drama to a saga that seldom ventures beyond stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Monster,'' by Jonathan Kellerman. Read by John Rubinstein.
Abridged, approximately 5 hours. Random House AudioBooks. $25.
</P>
<P>
   Kellerman has deftly demonstrated for the better part of two
decades that a psychologist can craft thrillers every bit the equal
of the heralded lawyers making a small fortune as fiction writers.
</P>
<P>
   His alter ego, Dr. Alex Delaware, returns, for the 13th time, in
``Monster.'' This time out he's helping solve a series of bizarre
and brutal murders. The detective whom Delaware assists, Milo
Sturgis, is actually a more interesting character than the
protagonist, and if Kellerman had given him a greater share of the
stage ``Monster'' might be an even more interesting tale.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is maze-like, and Delaware's knack for following the
correct trail defies belief. Simpler would have been better, I
think.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein, a Tony Award winner for his performance in
``Children of a Lesser God'' and the reader for four previous
Kellerman works, is right at home here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1446EDT &QL; 
