<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6723 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-SUB-COLUMN29-C     09-29 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-SUB-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RESENDING TO CHANGE MINN. TO WIS. FOR RUSS FEINGOLD
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: No honor in scrapping ban on honoraria
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hard to believe, but the chief justice of the United States, of
all people, is pushing to return bribery to the federal judicial
system. No less than William H. Rehnquist himself is asking
Congress to scrap the 1989 ban on honoraria for Supreme Court
justices and most other federal jurists.
</P>
<P>
   And what is more, he has support for this curious notion from
some substantial part of the GOP caucus, though not, thank goodness
for small favors, from all. Sen. Pat Roberts (R-Kansas), chairman
of the Senate Ethics Committee, for one, opposes the move,
accurately calling it a ``retreat to the discredited practices of
the past,'' and Roberts's office is counting steadily increasing
numbers in opposition with him.
</P>
<P>
   The speaking fees were declared off limits when it became
apparent that for some judges the honoraria were little more than a
thin veil over raunchy influence-peddling. Corporations and
organizations with on-going and substantial legal interests _ trade
associations, ideological action groups and other special pleaders
_ were ponying fees in the thousands of dollars for the dubious
privilege of sitting at the feet of spouting federal jurists for a
half-hour or so.
</P>
<P>
   The judges seemed less chosen for their legal acumen and
entertaining way with words than for their strategic location in
courts likely to take up cases and issues of abiding interest to
the sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist says it's necessary to let the speaking fees jingle
anew in judges' pockets to save the federal judiciary from
impending penury. If the judiciary has fallen on hard times, then
the proper and simple answer is to pitch for a pay raise, not to
ask Congress for a tin-cup franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Even the premise is iffy. Certainly jurists are losing out on
the white-hot oodles that partners in the big law firms are making
these days. Still, federal district judges make $141,300. Appellate
judges, $149,900, and Supreme Court justices $179,600.
</P>
<P>
   That's not exactly chump change, and the job has the best tenure
this side of death.
</P>
<P>
   Far from letting wink-and-nudge interests butter up judges with
speaking fees, Congress should be snapping up legislation
introduced by Sens. John Kerry (D-Mass.) and Russ Feingold (D-Wis.)
to outlaw another practice that is equally compromising.
</P>
<P>
   Barred from larding judges with honoraria, the same sort of
sponsors have taken to setting up legal, ahem, seminars and then
paying for judges to attend and be wined, dined and spit-shined. By
a strange coincidence, these seminars are almost always held in
exotic places _ the Caribbean, Hawaii, resorts and prized golf
courses _ and never in, say, lecture halls at the local community
college.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the executive committee of the governing U.S.
Judicial Conference, which opposes the Kerry-Feingold bill, says
that ending the junkets would be a draconian intrusion into ``the
marketplace of ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least he got the ``marketplace'' part right.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
