<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6739 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-BKO-ARATON-COLUMN     09-29 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BKO-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DONT LOOK NOW, BUT THEY'VE CAUGHT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ There should be no complaining now about the
result, the near shocking upset. No wingeing (whining), as they
like to say here. We wanted competition, didn't we? We've been
crying out for actual basketball contests of shooting and strength
and will, and not the dunk and pony shows that became so tedious
the minute Michael, Magic and Larry departed their grand Olympic
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of moaning about what Our Guys couldn't do on a night
the basketball world permanently readjusted its perception of
American dominance, how about we begin with what the Lithuanians
nearly did? How about that road stop of a country which in 1992
needed the Grateful Dead to chip in for uniforms so it could mark
its exit from Soviet stranglehold on the international sporting
stage?
</P>
<P>
   How about a population (3.7 million) that is less than Sydney's
waking up Saturday morning with the realization that its determined
collection of clashing consonants was a couple of heartbeats from
sending its opponent home as the Bad Dream Team? How about that
20-4 second-half run, as the Lithuanians sat back in the zone
defense, daring the Americans to make the jump shot? Years of
declining field goal percentages in our celebrated professional
league was the prophecy that our boys weren't going to convert
their jumpers here with any earthshaking regularity.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks here, Alonzo Mourning and Co. have been asking
people to stop comparing them to past U.S. teams, one in
particular, a most reasonable request. Yet at the same time,
Mourning also said that this team's defining trait was its defense,
and that Rudy Tomjanovich was coaching ``the greatest defensive
team ever.'' Excuse me, but was that a parade of Lithuanians,
French and Russians marching down the lane over the last several
days and, at times, scoring at will?
</P>
<P>
   The myth of the original Dream Team was that it was any kind of
team at all. In 1992, it was really an assemblage of great
individuals representing the 1980s, greatest of all basketball
decades. For the most part, those were the supremely talented
contemporary players who also had the fundamental skills of the
sport's more earthbound past. They stepped onto the court with a
pure sense of basketball intuition. They understood the game, its
ebb and flow, and when they sensed the time had come, they clamped
down defensively and the opponent would go eight or nine minutes
without scoring a point.
</P>
<P>
   The team staggering into Sunday afternoon's gold medal game
against France after an 85-83 semifinal victory Friday night was
just grateful it wasn't dead after Lithuania's best free throw
shooter clanked two of three late and crucial attempts. These guys
play with the least minute-to-minute continuity of any U.S. team
I've ever seen, and that includes the collegians who won the
Goodwill Games two years ago against some of these same
international outfits. If anything, Team 2000 is also a reflection
of the decade past. And with the exception of the Bulls, the 1990s
were about exciting but flawed players being marketed as the
transcendent superstars they were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sit here and make excuses and say we only won by two
points because Shaq wasn't here or Tim Duncan wasn't here,'' Vince
Carter said, composed again after he and the others on the U.S.
side looked as if they'd seen the Blair Witch in the game's final
minutes. Who's to say?
</P>
<P>
   Sure we can argue that if Shaquille O'Neal had come to Sydney,
Lithuania would not have been as close as it was. As earnest as he
is, Mourning has spent the last three playoff springs proving he is
not a dominant center, and in certain respects, is not a center at
all. O'Neal would be punishing these fellows but good, but he is
also the rarest of the physically gifted. So what are we saying?
The absence of one, even two, players from the big, bad USA is
enough to level the playing field against little ol' Lithuania?
</P>
<P>
   Based on Friday night, the close preliminary round game between
the two countries was no fluke. From the looks of things, the 21st
Century David Stern All Stars just aren't complete players enough
to be thrown together with a week's worth of practice in the
expectation that they will blow away teams that execute, shoot well
and _ most significantly _ are no longer in awe, or afraid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball has evolved in eight years,'' Carter said. ``My
expectation was just to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   True or not, what else could he say after running jubilantly off
the court with his index finger raised? On this night, he was just
happy to survive, to win at the Olympics, like all those other
athletes we've been saying we prefer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
