 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (l and f coding)  
 ON MOUNT WASHINGTON, `LOOK OUT, BELOW!'  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mount Washington has always been a place of wonderful personal
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   I've been atop, geared with crampons and ice axe, when the winds
topped 100 miles per hour and exposed flesh froze instantly. Skied
the precipitous face of Tuckerman Ravine. Gulped water to avoid
dehydration in a hot summer climb out of Great Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Was I ever afraid on the mountain? Only once _ riding in a car,
driven by someone else, as it negotiated the steeps and switchbacks
of the Mount Washington Auto Road. Now there's an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   And it's an adventure that, foliage season upon us, many New
Englanders and vistors from away will attempt (weather permitting,
since it has been known to snow up there in the fall) in the weeks
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some things you ought to know before you go.
</P>
<P>
   You may have seen the bumper stickers that read, ``THIS CAR
CLIMBED MOUNT WASHINGTON.'' To that, I say big deal. They ought to
read, ``THIS CAR GOT DOWN MOUNT WASHINGTON.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because, with modern engines and better cooling systems,
overheating on the way up is not the threat it once was. Instead,
the dangers lurk in the descent, where the wrong transmission, bad
brakes, poor driving technique, or too heavy a load can lead to
dangerous runaways.
</P>
<P>
   The folks who run the Auto Road do all they can to protect you.
</P>
<P>
   A sign at the bottom warns that it is a steep, narrow mountain
road _ WITHOUT GUARDRAILS. Believe me, round a hairpin turn looking
right over the edge of an unguarded shoulder _ looking off into the
sky or down onto rocks above treeline _ and you might not feel
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell people that if they have a fear of heights, they might
not enjoy the experience,'' says Howie Weymms, general manager of
the Auto Road.
</P>
<P>
   They give you a pamphlet telling you how to drive the road _
note especially the part about using a low gear rather than your
brakes _ and they check your car.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not your average Sunday drive,'' Weymms says is the
standard warning.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, there have been only two fatal wrecks in the history
of the road _ opened as the Carriage Road in 1861, first climbed by
auto in 1899 by an appropriately named Locomobile.
</P>
<P>
   The first was in 1880, when a drunk stage coach driver let his
team get away from him and a passenger was killed. Now there's a
refrain to echo down the ages: Don't drink and drive.
</P>
<P>
   The second was in 1984 when a Jeep Cherokee lost its brakes and
the driver tried to run out the journey to the flat fields at the
base. He hit the last tree on the way down and a passenger was
killed. See what I mean about being a passenger in a vehicle driven
by someone else. There's a pattern there.
</P>
<P>
   Running out failed brakes is not a good thing. If it happens to
you, drive onto an upslope off the side of the road, or dump your
car in a ditch.
</P>
<P>
   And don't think you're an expert so you don't need to pay
attention to the advice of those who know better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who thinks they're the greatest driver in the world
isn't,'' says Weymms.
</P>
<P>
   So you've been warned. But what about your car/van/truck/SUV?
</P>
<P>
   The Auto Road folks will check it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at the car not from a mechanical standpoint, but from
the make and model,'' according to Weymms.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a car whose low/first-gear setting won't stay in
that gear on the way down _ that is automatically shifts out as you
gain speed _ and forces you to rely on your brakes, that car won't
be allowed to make the climb.
</P>
<P>
   Cars on this list include models from Honda, Saturn, Acura, and
Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   Honda, in fact, has quietly negotiated a deal with the Auto Road
management under which Honda pays for Honda owners denied access to
the Auto Road to ride up in tour vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Vans are suspect, mostly because of how much weight in people
and and gear they carry. Any pre-1996 Caravan, for instance, cannot
carry more than 600 pounds combined because Auto Road workers have
learned they overheat on the way up and burn up their brakes on the
way down.
</P>
<P>
   SUVs are also scrutinized _ because of their size, weight and
carrying capacities, and because of the attitudes of their drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Just as on the highways, many of these drivers feel privileged
and invulnerable. They forget that 7,000 runaway-pounds is 7,000
runaway pounds of deadly steel. A boulder or tree does not know
that that was a Chevy Suburban that just smacked it.
</P>
<P>
   Many SUV drivers, confident in their equipment, also have no
idea how to use that equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Waymms says, ``It's amazing how many people come out of the
cities in their SUVs who don't even understand their basic
mechanical gear.''
</P>
<P>
   Auto Road workers have been known to have to explain to some of
these folks how to shift their SUVs into low range, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   If you show up with too much weight packed into your vehicle,
there are secure lockers at the base of the Auto Road to offload
gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't believe us when we tell them that 150 pounds
makes a big difference, but it does,'' says Weymms.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the rules, use common sense, and you won't end up like
the Canadian couple who, in 1984, lost their brakes about a mile
above the toll house and tried to ride it out. They went through
the toll area approaching 60 miles per hour, crossed a field even
as they avoided a crowd at the bottom, leaped a river and landed on
the bank. Amazingly, there were no major injuries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
