bc-JEAN-STAPLETON-FEATUR
h  
First lady 
For Jean Stapleton, it was an easy move from Dingbat to 'Eleanor'
... with plenty more in between 
By Valerie Kuklenski/Staff Writer 
There is something of a bygone time in Jean Stapleton that comes
through in little things, like the way she properly uses the
subjective ``one'' as in ``one would hope'' and little phrases like
``yes indeed.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Or the way she takes offense at an attempt to verify her age.
</P>
<P>
   It could be Stapleton's nature, or it could be the result of
having played Eleanor Roosevelt in the one-woman play ``Eleanor:
Her Secret Journey'' for more than 165 performances in Miami, San
Francisco and now at the Canon Theatre in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going wonderfully, and of course this is an important
engagement because there are all these professional types, and if
you get their approval, it's very strengthening and encouraging,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She gives seven performances a week of the Rhoda Lerman play, in
which the former first lady reflects on the post-World War I years,
her husband's early political career and his affair with his social
secretary, which left Eleanor craving his attention and affection.
</P>
<P>
   Stapleton has made a long and successful career of a wide
variety of supporting roles on stage and screen, from the devoted
nurse in ``Romeo and Juliet'' and the spunky Aunt Eller in
``Oklahoma!'' to the campy medium in ``Blithe Spirit'' and her most
famous part, the ditsy yet wise Edith Bunker on the 1970s
breakthrough sitcom, ``All in the Family.''
</P>
<P>
   A one-woman show offers different challenges and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting and it's a wonderful exercise,'' she said.
``Of course it can't help but benefit one's growth as an actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's best answered by saying I don't plan to spend the rest of
my career doing a one-person show because I like to work with
people on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, Stapleton will be taking the show to several more
cities (the tentative schedule includes Syracuse, N.Y.; Boston;
Palm Beach, Fla.; Houston; and San Diego) and hopes to land
off-Broadway next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleanor'' closes its four-week engagement at the Canon on Oct.
8, the same night Stapleton co-stars in the premiere of TNT's movie
``Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Stapleton plays the matriarch Byrd in the story of a family
still mourning an infant son's death when a baby girl named Sophie
is abandoned on their porch. Her mother's note says she loves the
baby and will come back for her someday, leaving the Malone family
torn between bonding with Sophie and trying to keep an emotional
detachment because of the inevitable separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby,'' based on the book by Patricia MacLachlan (``Sarah,
Plain and Tall''), stars Farrah Fawcett and Keith Carradine as the
parents and Alison Pill as their 12-year-old daughter, Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole story was so moving and so touching,''
Stapleton said. ``The script is so universal in how it deals with
family emotions. I was also attracted because Glenn Close was
connected to the project as an executive producer, and that was
enough for me. I knew then that the project would be quality.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the babies, multiple sets of towheaded twins portraying
Sophie's growth in a year, created some problems, especially one
child who seemed content only when Fawcett carried her around on
her hip, but they also delighted the cast and crew at the Nova
Scotia location.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one who was so outgoing, who's used most, the older one,
was so miraculous because she learned to speak during the shoot,''
Stapleton said. ``She started with one syllable here and there,
imitation. By the end of it she was speaking in sentences, and she
could name all our character names and with great joy she was
constantly calling them out. It was a miracle to watch this happen,
just marvelous.''
</P>
<P>
   As for her post-``Eleanor'' plans, Stapleton said she'll try
``whatever comes that's right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to do film, also theater,'' she said. ``A wonderful
play with people in it would be very satisfying. It's nice when one
can hop around in all the media, but the theater would be the place
I would care to stay for a long time, a long run if it's worthy.''
</P>
<P>
   In most New York productions that means eight shows a week, a
demanding schedule that wears out even the most vigorous actors.
That's where the age discussion comes up.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to confirm an almanac entry that gives her age as 77,
Stapleton bristled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never discuss age, nor do I confirm the accuracy of that.
It's a stereotype and it's not the right way to categorize people.
I think it's so wrong, so I don't indulge in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very bad for actors. It categorizes them and limits them.
I just disdain its use!''
</P>
<P>
   She paused. ``Nothing personal,'' she added with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   I replied that I was going to tell her she looked great for her
age, if in fact that age was accurate, but now I guessed I
wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, please,'' she said with a laugh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
