<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WAGON YOUR FATHER WOULD HAVE WANTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's that eternal question we all face: When do we give up
living for the box?
</P>
<P>
   No, I'm not talking life and death. I'm talking finally having
to sell that sporty two-seater or the zippy sedan for a station
wagon that will, with practicality, haul all that we have
accumulated in life _ outdoor gear, kids, pets or, dare it be
spoken, grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo has just made the transition easier, though describing it
in a phrase is difficult. Has Volvo been taken out of the box, or
has the box been taken out of Volvo?
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 V70 T5 wagon, you see, is a rounded, gentle automobile
with the hauling capacity _ spacewise and powerwise _ of some
thumping SUVs. It remains rock solid in construction, but soft
exterior lines and a plush interior erase the stereotype of a
pipe-smoking, bearded gent driving a stiff but sensible box from
campus to chautauqua.
</P>
<P>
   This is a great car for the youthful (we're purposely not saying
young here) driver, offering that certain je ne c'est quoi that
says, ``Hey, I'm not old yet. Watch this baby go.''
</P>
<P>
   So fill it with your mountain climbing gear, your tents, your
fishing poles, your soccer balls, your weekend lumber. Cover its
roof with mountain bikes and kayaks. Fill its seats and cargo space
with toddlers and their diapers. Then kick back and enjoy the
sporty ride.
</P>
<P>
   That comes from the 2.3-liter 247-horsepower, inline 5-cylinder
turbocharged engine _ one of three engine options on the V70 _ that
delivers more bang than you'd expect in a station wagon, and more
than you'll find in a lot of sedans. The other engines are a
2.4-liter light-pressure turbo delivering 197 horses and a normally
aspirated 170-horse unit for those seeking the environmental high
ground with an Ultra Low Emission Vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Enter this wonderfully rounded wagon, knowing that power will be
there for you whatever your load, and settle into the front leather
bucket seats. Legroom in vast, headroom the same, and the seats
themselves are armchair comfortable, but with stiff support up the
sides for those lateral challenges you'll face when you feel a
little sporty.
</P>
<P>
   It's billed as a five-passenger car (an optional third bench can
be installed in the rear cargo area), but more practically seats
four adults, given the hump in the middle of the rear bench seat.
Passengers back there will find good head- and legroom as well.
</P>
<P>
   This is a well-thought-out car. It has big buttons for climate
and sound control. Bins in the doors are divided into
subcompartments. The center console has two storage layers. The
glove box is divided. There are two pockets layered into the rear
of each of the front seats. And in the rear, folding out of the
floor of the cargo area, rises a grocery bag holder, winged,
netted, and bungeed to keep that yogurt and fruit from flying about
if you're feeling sporty even on the way home from shopping.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable thing about the Volvo is that, even though shorter
than European counterparts _ BMW 5 Series, the BMW X5, the Saab
9-6, or even Ford's Taurus, its cargo space is vast. Nearly 40
cubic feet behind the front seats. More than 70 cubic feet with
those seats folded down. If a full-blown, big SUV is not the car
for your, this Volvo may be. It's front-wheel drive, but if you
want it in all-wheel drive, there's the Cross Country version
hitting the market.
</P>
<P>
   Given its hauling capacity, if you plan to fill it up with
family and gear and go, you'll appreciate the turbo-charged engine.
The light-pressure turbo will give you boost when needed and you
may never even notice when it kicks in. It will likely be that
subtle. The regular turbo, this T5 was also subtle in activation,
yet distinct when the power kicked in. Aided by continuously
variable valve timing, it provided torque across a wide band of
RPMs (though the first few seconds of acceleration from a dead stop
are nothing special). But the latter is not what we're looking for
here. Solid power is, however, and the Volvo delivers that in
abundance, even while managing just over 20 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The ride can be a bit stiff, but given that you'll likely be
carrying big loads and you're handling all that power into corners,
that is a good thing. You don't need boaty body roll and dip in a
rig like this. Wouldn't want those bikes and kayaks swaying atop
the car in your pursuit of youthful exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension keeping it all in line has independent struts,
coil springs, and antiroll bar up front, and, at the rear, fully
independent multilink, also with coil springs and antiroll bar.
</P>
<P>
   Stability control _ limiting torque to spinning wheels _ and
enhanced ABS add to safer control.
</P>
<P>
   And this being Volvo, it is, of course, still built like a steel
box, with unit body construction, and airbags all around _ front,
side, and head airbags (with whiplash protection) and curtain bags
in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   This Volvo is part of a broad revolution taking place in the
auto industry today.
</P>
<P>
   Station wagons are becoming more SUV-like even as manufacturers
introduce new SUVs that address the complaints of those who say the
big beasts are dangerous, environmentally unfriendly, even
unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to watch those lines blur over the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, we'll watch cars like the Volvo V70, the
Beemers, the Saabs, and others roam the highways offering some of
the best features of each.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touch
</P>
<P>
   --The positioning of vents in the center door posts. What a fine
use of hollow, dead space. Each outer rear passenger can now direct
air flow from a shoulder-high opening.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance
</P>
<P>
   --Placement of the cell phone jack to the right of the center
console. If you're plugged in, you'll find the cord continually
getting snagged on the shifter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE NUMBERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $33,400 &QL; 
Price as tested: $38,675 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 247/243 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 108.7 inches/185.4 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 70.9 inches/57.5 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 3,455 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
