<HEADER>
A6752 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e bc-MTV-JACKASS-REVIEW     09-29 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
bc-MTV-JACKASS-REVIEW
cc,78p3  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The title fits, and he looks like one, too &QL; 
By David Kronke &QL; 
Who expected we'd be looking back so soon on the antics of MTV's
taste-impaired ``The Tom Green Show'' with a whiff of nostalgia for
its relative innocence? At its wildest, ``Jackass'' really defies
rational thought regarding what people will do to be on TV. Here's
how extreme this is: Repeatedly throughout the show, MTV airs this
disclaimer ``MTV insists that neither you or any of your dumb
little buddies attempt the dangerous crap in this show.''
</P>
<P>
   Host Johnny Knoxville (well, it's better than his real name,
P.J. Clapp) subjects himself to some fairly horrific and sometimes,
horrifically funny abuse. Like Green, he's a skateboard fan, so
there's some random thrashing, and some puerile silliness involving
cracking up shopping carts and bicycles, but that's just padding to
get to the stuff you'll be hearing about even if you can't imagine
watching the show.
</P>
<P>
   Knoxville allows himself to be hit head-on with pepper spray, a
stun gun and a Taser gun (his articulate response to each:
``(Expletive)!'' or ``(Expletive)in' hell!'') and discovers that
pepper spray is the worst. No, wait the worst is standing in a
well-stocked porta-potty when it's turned upside-down. Feel free to
die now basic-cable television can't possibly get any more
outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, though, Knoxville and his posse of pranksters
recall that line from ``This Is Spinal Tap,'' about the thin line
between clever and stupid. There are Green-style gags, like having
a trussed-up, nearly naked guy escape from the trunk of a car in
public, that are more about simple shock value than actual
inventiveness. As with Green's show, this kind of act has a fairly
brief shelf life before it becomes moldy, but unlike Green, there's
nothing witty about Knoxville beyond his being highly attuned to
his masochistic streak he's not funny unless he's being debased;
his responses to said debasement aren't clever or amusing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's very happy to humiliate himself most abjectly for
our amusement, so who are we to turn our heads? &QL; 
---``JACKASS'' &QL; 
What: Self-flagellation at its finest host Johnny Knoxville
subjects himself to much pain and suffering for laughs. &QL; 
Where: MTV. &QL; 
When: 9 p.m. Sundays. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
