<P>
   &UR; IDEAS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEE-GRANT-VIEWS (Undated) _ For the better part of the last
century the images of two of the greatest icons of the Civil War
remained fixed in the American imagination: Robert E. Lee as the
brilliant tactician fighting against overwhelming odds, and Ulysses
S. Grant as the heavy-drinking butcher who used the North's
superior resources to grind down the South. Those characterizations
are now being challenged by a string of books that are both more
admiring of Grant and more skeptical of Lee than would have seemed
imaginable only a short time ago. By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   MACHINES-HUMANIZED (Undated) _ Technological fears and hopes are
now focused less on machines with moving parts than on electronic
objects that don't have any moving parts at all. Machinery _ real,
moving, mechanical machinery _ has come to seem almost amiably
old-fashioned, less like something out of Charlie Chaplin's
``Modern Times'' and more like the fussy C-3PO of ``Star Wars.''
Machines now seem closer to the human world than the technological
one. A comic, nostalgic and admiring accommodation now seems to be
developing between moving contraptions and their creators. By
Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   DYING-LANGUAGES (Undated) _ In the face of doubts and many
difficulties, the revival of indigenous languages is a growing
movement among American Indian groups, and it is fast becoming a
new subspecialty in the field of linguistics as well. By Alexander
Stille.
</P>
<P>
   (Will be filed in category code ``a'')
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES _ NEW YORK FILM FESTIVAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TABOO-FILM-REVIEW (New York) _ Nagisa Oshima's elegant
historical film ``Gohatto'' recycles a familiar metaphor _ male
homosexuality as a symbol of ``decadence'' _ that is so loaded with
dramatic implication it simply refuses to die. Reviewed by Stephen
Holden.
</P>
<P>
   GLEANERS-FILM-REVIEW (New York) _ ``The Gleaners and I'' takes
its title, and some of its inspiration, from an 1867 painting by
Jean-Francois Millet that shows three women in a wheat field. The
painting itself shows up early in Agnes Varda's wonderful new
documentary, thronged by camera-wielding tourists. Reviewed by A.O.
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   POLLOCK-FILM-REVIEW (New York) _ Ed Harris' powerful
biographical film, ``Pollock,'' may be the first movie about a
painter to transcend the gushy cliches found in movies that try to
unravel the mysteries of artistic creation. It helps, of course,
that Jackson Pollock, the abstract expressionist giant whom Harris
portrays with a riveting blend of pent-up passion and unleashed
physicality, threw his entire body into his work. Reviewed by
Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPHOR-FILM-REVIEW (New York) _ Bahman Farmanara's ``Smell of
Camphor, Fragrance of Jasmine'' has a pixilated charm and, under
the surface, a current of despair. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   SEVEN-FILM-REVIEW (New York) _ At times ``Seven Men from Now,''
the compact and efficient 1956 Budd Boetticher Western starring
Randolph Scott, plays like a work by Harold Pinter. Reviewed by
Elvis Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   LOVE-FILM-REVIEW (New York) _ ``It is a restless moment. Hong
Kong 1962,'' reads a title card at the beginning of ``In the Mood
for Love,'' and a restiveness that's almost voluptuous fills the
movie. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-SYMPHONY-CENTENARY (Boston) _ The Boston Symphony has
learned something from Carnegie Hall: Instead of renovating before
the centenary, and risking having the celebration marred by worries
about what had happened to the acoustics, it is having the party
first and doing the maintenance work later. The centenary party
takes place in two weeks, in the days leading up to the anniversary
of the hall's opening, Oct. 15. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM-BALLET (New York) _ On the Birmingham Royal Ballet's
production of ``Jazz Triple'' at City Center. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
