<BODY>
bc-TV-KING-HILL-REVIEW
cc,78p3  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
'King' fell off its throne with this episode &QL; 
By David Kronke &QL; 
Hank Hill and the family make a, well, not so special but
particularly timely pre-season appearance on ``King of the Hill''
tonight. Hank's considering the upcoming presidential election he's
expecting his man, George W. Bush, to walk away with it all,
particularly if he can get dim-bulb Luanne to quit babbling about
the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   When Hank and the brood are invited to a Bush rally (Bobby
heroically rescues that proud Texas tradition, a diving pig, from
drowning in a pool), the man who makes propane his life is deflated
to discover his hero has a weak handshake. It's such a devastating
revelation he opts not to vote come Election Day: ``With voter
turnout at all-time lows, not voting makes me more American,'' he
tries to convince himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a particularly rich addition to the Hill canon. The
laughs, such as they are, are often forced, and the effort, however
backhanded, to do a little flag-waving for the democratic process
rings hollow. ``King of the Hill'' has managed to blend wry comedy
and poignancy in the past, but here, neither quality seems
particularly interested in coming to the fore. &QL; 
---``KING OF THE HILL'' &QL; 
What: The animated Texas family considers the presidential
election. &QL; 
When: 7:30 tonight. &QL; 
Where: Fox (Channel 11). &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1530EDT &QL; 
