<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-INTERNET-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ARABS FIND FREEDOMS ONLINE AS INTERNET GROWS
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Arabs might get in trouble for criticizing their
leaders on the streets of many Middle Eastern capitals, but now
they can get on the Internet and join in with ``Mock the
Governments.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one offering of an Arabic satire page on ``Al-Bawaba,'' a
new Internet portal not unlike the more familiar Yahoo!.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Bawaba users can also go to the ``relationships'' English
bulletin board to discuss taboo subjects in Arab society. There,
one writer named Rania asks, ``Why are men in the Arab world
allowed premarital relations and then women not?''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Bawaba, meaning ``The Gateway,'' opened over the summer as
the latest of several major Arab Internet service providers, or
ISPs, providing mostly unfettered news, chat and links to sites
around the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
   The still fledgeling Al-Bawaba joins the early Internet pioneer
Arabia.com, and the youth-oriented Planet Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Together, by being objective news gatherers and hosts for
bulletin boards, they are pushing the limits of free speech in a
region where dissenters from political or religious conventions are
often jailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sort of relief valve for people to say things they have
not been able to say or that have not been heard,'' said Daoud
Kuttab, director of the Institute for Modern Media at the
Palestinian Al-Quds University in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the new ISPs are testing the economic waters
in an industry that is volatile enough even in America. In the
Middle East, computers are just catching on for the masses.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a mixture of modern technology, strategic planning and
entrepreneurial nerve.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Al-Bawaba's main editorial office is here in Amman,
where a few dozen journalists sit in modern work pods in the new
Merrill Lynch building. But the company is registered in Delaware
and its directors are in New York, giving it a foreign status that
could help insulate it from any attempts to control the content.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the satire page, Al-Bawaba intends to publish
literature and articles that have been banned in some countries.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the Web sites say that governments are already
finding out that the Internet is tough to patrol, much less
control. While some sites are blocked by the monopoly government
server in Syria, for example, users have learned to easily hack
their way through.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some governments seem more willing to give Internet speech
a wider freedom than, say, local newspapers or radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have resisted sacrificing or compromising the way we think
people ought to be able to communicate,'' said Osama El-Sharif,
editor in chief of Jordan-based Arabia.com. ``Eventually, it is not
us who will be changed, but the way the authorities will view
things that will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the main obstacle to success at the Arab Web sites
may be the same as that faces in the freewheeling Western Internet
world _ money.
</P>
<P>
   Even American ISPs and Web portals are cutting back and facing
advertising shortages. The Arab sites, meanwhile, have to carve out
a niche in a much smaller computer world.
</P>
<P>
   The Nua Internet Survey, used by the U.S. Department of Commerce
for on-line estimates, reports that only about 2 million of the
more than 270 million Arabs in the Middle East have regular
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   There is potential for growth. Though home computers are too
expensive for most Arabs, Internet cafes are flourishing in Jordan,
Egypt and Lebanon. Palestinians, exposed to computers in the
Western countries where many have made homes, help spread the word
and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Money for Al-Bawaba and Arabia.com comes mainly from a mix of
Arab conglomerates. One of Arabia.com's chief investors is hi-tech
savvy Saudi billionaire Prince al Waleed bin Talal bin Abdul Aziz
al Saud.
</P>
<P>
   Investors look toward a future that the Nua survey group says
could see 12 million Arab users in this region the next two years.
But, for now, the Web sites compete for a small pool of users and,
therefore, skeptical advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   El-Sharif says Arabia.com users click on 33 million of its pages
every month. But, he estimates that nearly half of its 300,000
regular users are Arab Americans. The 5-year-old Web site does not
expect to see any profits for another couple years.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to increase the audience, Arabia.com this month
launched a million-dollar ad campaign plugging the site throughout
the region, from newspapers in Egypt to billboards in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The ads are targeted at young people. Not only are they open to
new technology, El-Sharif says, but they will become used to free
speech and spread the word as they mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the ones who will affect change in the future,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be contacted at larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   To sample some of the Websites see:
</P>
<P>
   www.albawaba.com
</P>
<P>
   www.arabia.com
</P>
<P>
   www.planetarabia.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
