<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ATTN: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Oct. 1, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-BOXERS _ (New York) _ At the April Golden Gloves
championships in Madison Square Garden, nearly 20 percent of the
entrants were women. Nationally, there are than 1,500 amateur and
400 professional female boxers, including the headline-grabbing
daughters of Mohammad Ali, Joe Frazier and George Foreman. Now a
new new wave of books and movies about women's boxing is giving the
sport a cultural context. The writers are educated women who also
box. ``They say that men box to get out of the ghetto,'' said Kate
Sekules, author of ``The Boxers Heart.'' ``I joke that boxing was
my way into the ghetto.'' (Eds: also see FILM-GIRLFIGHT) and
FILM-GIRLFIGHT-REVIEW.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photographs.
</P>
<P>
   GUCCI-MISTRESS (New York) _ The former mistress of the late
Maurizio Gucci has been described as the single ``ray of sunshine''
in Gucci's life, which ended when his wife had him killed in 1995.
Now the mistress, Sheree McGlaughlin Loud, a former model,
describes her six-year relationship with Gucci, whom she met during
preliminaries for the 1984 America's Cup regatta. Loud said Gucci
suspected his wife was trying to poison him, but she just dismissed
it as too bizarre. ``All that belongs to another world,'' she said.
``And I was another person...'' Now she is married, expecting a
child and is communications director for Giorgio Armani's Le
Collezioni label.
</P>
<P>
   By Ruth La Ferla.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-FASHION (London) _ Cathy Horyn, the Times fashion critic
asks, ``Whatever became of London's surly, shoe-string
inventiveness?'' The recent shows were not worth getting out of bed
for, let alone crossing the Atlantic. There were moments of honest
fun (Matthew Williamson's raunchy skirts with rhinestone-flocked
baseball sweaters), but mostly what Horyn noticed were designers
mired in 1980s revivalism. Notable exceptions she writes were
Hussein Chalayan and Alexander McQueen, who alluded to images of
trauma and insanity in their shows last week. By Cathy Horyn.
</P>
<P>
   With photographs.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIC-CARS (New York ) _ The Louis Vuitton Classic at
Rockefeller Center, an annual event since 1995, is an exhibition of
50 of the world's rarest classic cars. According to the New York
City Police, last year's event drew 2 million spectators. This year
Murray Livingstone Smith, the show's curator, came up with another
classic event, the New York Style Awards with celebrities to judge
the cars. The 1940 Duesenberg won for A Night on the Town. The dark
green Rolls Royce won for Timeless Style Regardless of Age. Most
Surprising was the silver 1936/37 Dubonnet Hispano and Most Like to
Own was the 1953 Ferrari 342 America. By Alex Witchel, who
personally preferred the Lancia.
</P>
<P>
   With photograph.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTO-FASHION-SPANISH (Undated) _ Custodio Dalmau, better known
as Custo, had his creative epiphany on a California beach. ``I saw
the first printed T-shirt in my life,'' he recalled. ``It existed
in Europe as a means for publicity, to advertise something, but not
as a fashion statement... It was the experience of my life.'' Today
Dalmau's snug-fitting psychedelic T-shirts decorated with images of
party girls are the marquee items of a moderately priced clothing
line that has a cult following. Customers line up for the
designer's personal appearances and to have him autograph their
t-shirts. By Elizabeth Hayt.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-DEFELITTA-RISPOLI (New York) _ The talk on a jaunt
through Manhattan with Raymond De Felitta and Michael Rispoli was:
bars we have known and loved, bars we have worked in, bartenders we
miss, bars we miss, drinks we miss, bars where we fell in love and
the movie, ``Two Family House,'' which is about a bar. Raymond De
Felitta, the director and writer, had an uncle named Buddy, who
wanted to buy a place in Staten Island, live upstairs, and open a
bar where he could sing for customers. To play Buddy, De Felitta
chose Michael Rispoli, an actor who once worked as a bartender. In
this Night Out With ... column, they discover they have some bars
in common. By Linda Lee.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ The author loses restraint at bulb
bins, particularly when it comes to hyacinths. In the heyday of
hyacinths, the late 19th century, hundreds of varieties were on the
market. In 1872, the writer notes, one catalog listed 60 blues. Few
suppliers sell more than two dozen varieties; the author includes a
box on where the best can be bought. By Marty Ross.
</P>
