<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6782 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      09-29 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     LINCOLN: `WHO's BEEN SLEEPING IN MY BED?'
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _Poor Mr. Lincoln. There have been so many visitors
sleeping in his seven-foot bed.
</P>
<P>
   It's fine and proper to have overnight guests in the lonely
White House, but there is a strong perception that some of the
hospitality offered by President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton
has been offered for a price.
</P>
<P>
   The White House acknowledges that many of the major donors to
the first lady's Senate campaign coffers have been invited to spend
the night.
</P>
<P>
   When the story first broke after the 1996 election that 938
persons, including many political donors, had been invited to sleep
in the Lincoln suite during Clinton's first term, I asked
then-press secretary Mike McCurry if the White House were for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' McCurry replied sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Despite criticism that the Clintons have turned the White House
into a bed and breakfast for political contributors, it appears
that the first couple apparently sees nothing wrong in putting the
Lincoln Bedroom on the auction block.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the historic rooms represent hallowed ground. On the
wall of the Lincoln suite there is a picture of the Civil War
president reading the Emancipation Proclamation to his Cabinet.
Lincoln signed the proclamation in that room.
</P>
<P>
   Also on a wall is a copy of the Gettysburg Address, which
Lincoln signed and donated for the benefit of the Civil War
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the White House released the names of 404 persons
who have stayed overnight at the Executive Mansion or Camp David
since the first lady launched her Senate campaign in July 1999. It
turns out that about 100 of the houseguests have chipped into her
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if there was any link between the White House slumber
guests and their donations to Hillary Clinton's campaign, press
secretary Joe Lockhart said: ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are friends, public officials and supporters to whom
they wanted to extend the opportunity to stay with them in their
home,'' he added. ``Any suggestion to the contrary is false and
unsupportable.''
</P>
<P>
   When quizzed, the first lady took the same tack. They have lots
of friends and supporters ``who spend time with us, spend the night
with us,'' she said, adding that the vast majority of guests had
not contributed to her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is particularly newsworthy,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chutzpah,'' an expression the first lady has adopted, comes to
mind when one considers that such transactions cheapen the White
House. Where is the reverence for this stately mansion that
represents so much to Americans? Apparently the appearance of a
payoff does not bother the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   The president loves showing his guests the Lincoln Bedroom and
the other historic rooms in the family quarters, which are not on
the regular visitor tours. On the same floor is the Treaty Room,
which was decorated by Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis and is used as a
private office by presidents. The nearby Queen's Room is also a
guestroom.
</P>
<P>
   Every president I've covered has said ``the White House belongs
to the American people.'' Clinton and other presidents like to quip
that they live in public housing. I have never heard a president
say the White House belongs to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, other presidents have invited major campaign donors
to functions at the White House and certainly have had friends and
relatives spend the night there. Former Presidents Ronald Reagan
and George Bush hosted many private gatherings in the Executive
Mansion for the deep-pocket members of the ``President's Club'' to
thank them for their generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, a number of celebrities have enjoyed the Clinton
hospitality without having to fork over money to the first lady's
campaign, including former President Jimmy Carter, and King Juan
Carlos of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   So far none of the houseguests seems to have encountered the
legendary ghost of Lincoln who, in years past, was said to be heard
clumping down the hallway in his heavy boots. But we don't want to
scare away any potential guests-or donors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the self-designated ``cheerleader-in-chief,'' President
Clinton is on a roll these days, captivating his audiences at
fundraisers with nostalgic anecdotes. During one Washington
fundraiser recently, he recalled he had worked in Texas in the 1972
campaign for the losing Democratic presidential candidate George
McGovern against Richard Nixon. He said he would never forget
hopping on a plane in Dallas to go home to Little Rock when a
businessman asked him what he was doing. When he told the man he
was working for McGovern in Texas, Clinton said the man ``looked at
me, didn't crack a smile, and he said, `You know you're the only
white man I ever met for McGovern.'''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later while the Watergate scandal hearings were
underway, Clinton said his phone rang ``and it was this guy on he
phone. He had kept my card and he said: `I just called to tell you,
you were right and I was wrong.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton apparently expects to have a lot of time for
reading in the next several weeks. On a recent trip to California
he dropped by a bookstore and left with a bag of books, including
Thomas Perry's ``Vanishing Act''; Tom Clancy's ``The Bear and the
Dragon,'' Michael Lerner's ``The Spirit Matters,'' Pat Many's ``The
Roosevelt Preserve,'' Margaret Mahoney's ``Saving the Soul of
Medicine'' and Jeff Shaara's ``Gone for Soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was prominently displayed in the store, he shunned
``The Breach'' by Washington Post correspondent Peter Baker. It's
the story of Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is working for his wife Hillary's election to a U.S.
Senate seat from New York, but he also is on a relentless travel
schedule to help Democrats win back the House and the Senate this
year. House Democratic leader Richard Gephardt says Clinton has
attended 137 fundraisers for the House, the Senate and the
Democratic National Committee. ``No other president in history has
come that close to that kind of industry to win the House, to win
the Senate,'' said Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
