<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VOL-MEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA AND RUSSIA TO MEET FOR MEN'S VOLLEYBALL GOLD MEDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER BERLIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ As Vladimir Grbic drove the final spike into
their Olympic obsession Friday night, the Italians didn't even wait
for the ball to hit the floor before turning to trudge to the net
for the ritual handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Italian team had entered an Olympic men's
volleyball tournament as world champion. And for 30 minutes before
that final blow, the Italians had played as if they knew that once
again they would exit without the gold. After squandering a fistful
of set points in each of the first two sets, the Italians
capitulated in the third and lost to Yugoslavia, 27-25, 34-32,
25-14.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, all four semifinalists had come from Pool B of
the qualifying round. In the evening's first semifinal, Russia
outlasted Argentina, 27-25, 32-30, 21-25, 25-11. Argentina had
finished fourth in the six-team group, winning only two matches
before upsetting Cuba, the Pool A victor, in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Italy had topped Pool B, winning all five matches including a
five-set victory over Yugoslavia. But in the semifinals, the
Italian nerve failed. Italy has won the last three world
championships _ in 1990, 1994 and 1998 _ but has stumbled in each
subsequent Olympics. In Barcelona, Spain, in 1992, Italy lost in
the quarterfinals to the Netherlands, and in Atlanta in 1996, the
Italians lost in five sets in the final, again to the Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past 11 years, the team has been the favorite for
every tournament we've entered,'' said Andrea Gardini, the Italian
captain. ``We're used to pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first set Friday night, Italy had three set points at
24-21, allowed the Yugoslavs to draw level, and then had another at
25-24, before losing the next three points. In the second set, the
Italians had the first set point at 24-23. They squandered that,
and six more, before the Yugoslavs took the set at their third
opportunity. The Italians caved in, losing the first three points
of the third set, and trailed the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must apologize for the last set,'' Gardini said.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians played Friday night as they had for most of the
tournament, without the injured Andrea Giani, a 30-year-old veteran
of the three world championship teams. That placed an added weight
on Andrea Sartoretti's booming left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Sartoretti prepared to serve, standing 10 feet behind
the line, the Italian fans would begin to bellow, building to a
crescendo as he ran forward, hurled the ball high into the air,
leaped and unleashed a blow that sent it diving over the net at up
to 75 mph.
</P>
<P>
   On attack, Sartoretti's hammering spikes from the wing were the
favorite weapon of the Italians. In the crucial late stages of the
second set, Italy went to him time and again. But the Yugoslavs,
who knew what was coming, were lined up at the net ready to block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the 23rd point of the second set, everything was fine,''
Sartoretti said. ``After that everything was missing and I don't
know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12 men in the Yugoslav team, six earn a living with
Italian clubs. Zoran Gajic, the Yugoslav coach, used only seven
players all night.
</P>
<P>
   In the first semifinal, Argentina wasted seven set points in the
second set but preserved their dignity by winning the third before
running out of steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team knew it was inferior to the Russians,'' said Carlos
Alberto Getzelvich, the Argentine coach, ``but had dreams of
reaching the final.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the second semifinal had even started, Gennadi
Chipouline, the Russian coach, was asked how he thought his team
might do against the Italians in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Results are difficult to predict because of the psychological
pressure is so great at the Olympics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Italy would testify to that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
