<HEADLINE>
THE WRITE STUFF?
</HEADLINE>
bc-JOEY-ADAMS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
 
 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joey Lauren Adams, now seen with Minnie Driver in ``Beautiful,''
is an actress, but what she really wants to do is write. And write
and write and write.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who was the object of Ben Affleck's desire in Kevin
Smith's ``Chasing Amy,'' is enthusiastic about how much fun she has
had writing her first screenplay. The story is built around
characters much like her own family in North Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   If someday the movie is made, she envisions herself starring and
says that male lead would be her soulmate, if only he really
existed. Although she got off to a slow start with the project, it
now seems to have its own momentum as she nears completion of her
first draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'll be writing and it's like, 'Slow down, guys.'
They (her characters) just start going, and it's not even anything
I planned or thought about them saying,'' Adams said. ``I'm
writing, and I'm saying, 'Guys, you're going to Granny's for
dinner,' and they're like, 'No we're not, we're going out for a
drink.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although Adams, who received a Golden Globe nomination for
``Amy'' and starred opposite Adam Sandler in ``Big Daddy,'' said
she would be happy to work again with her ``Beautiful'' director
Sally Field, she's not sure whether she'll show this script to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really small movie. I don't know if she wants to
rough it in Arkansas, you know what I mean? We're going to be
staying on Granny's couch,'' she laughed. ``I don't know if I could
ask Sally to do that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6794 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-DEBATES-NAT     09-29 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-DEBATES-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  HOW TO GET THE MOST OUT OF DEBATE NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   By Tania Anderson
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 29 - One of the most important events of the
presidential race is the first debate on Tuesday night. The two men
vying for The Seat in the Oval Office will try to convince
television viewers that their positions will best serve the needs
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   For the candidates, it could make or break the rest of their
campaign because a substantial amount of viewers are either still
undecided or not solidly supporting - Gov. George W. Bush or Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time debates are said and done, people make up their
mind,'' said Diana Carlin, professor of communication studies and
dean of the graduate school and international programs at the
University of Kansas. She serves as an advisor to the commission
that sets the format for the presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will make those leaning, solidify their leanings,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   While communication experts say previous presidential debates
don't show obvious patterns, they do know that candidates generally
don't say anything in debates that they haven't said before while
on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   And Carlin added that she doesn't think there will be much
mudslinging in Tuesday's debate even though Bush and Gore have
launched a steady stream of attacks on each other in the last few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them are wanting to put on their best face,'' she
said. ``They will challenge one another. Candidates who have tried
to launch attacks during debates have had it backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FORMAT
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 8 p.m., local television viewers tuned to a major
network or PBS will see Bush and Gore standing at podiums with Jim
Lehrer, PBS executive director and anchor of the NewsHour with Jim
Lehrer, as the debate moderator. This first of three presidential
debates will take place at the University of Massachusetts in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For about 90 minutes, Bush and Gore will answer questions tossed
out by Lehrer, who has formulated the questions but kept them
private from the campaigns. Each of the candidates has two minutes
to respond and then one minute to reply with Lehrer having the
discretion to extend the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   According to communication experts, there are three types of
questions that could potentially be asked by the moderator in a
presidential debate: initial, follow-up and cross examination.
</P>
<P>
   Initial questions get the debate started by asking candidates to
explain or defend a position or compare it to an opponent's. Many
initial questions are hypothetical, such as, ``What would you do
if_''
</P>
<P>
   Follow-up questions are directed at a candidate after an answer
is given. It's a way to probe the original response by asking for
elaboration or clarification or can be asked on an unrelated topic.
These questions can be asked immediately after the original
response or after each candidate has answered the first question.
</P>
<P>
   Cross examination questions are used by one candidate to
another. A separate time can be set aside for cross examination
questions or included in the follow ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very seldom does a single question turn a debate,'' Carlin
said. ``In the past, when something has gone wrong, it has slipped
past people. Viewers take pieces from every piece and patch it all
together.''
</P>
<P>
   All presidential debates are structured by the non-partisan
Commission on Presidential Debates, which was established in 1987
as a permanent part of every general election. The non-profit
group, based in Washington, D.C., is tasked with choosing the
location of the debate, its format and its moderator.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO LOOK FOR?
</P>
<P>
   Carlin, along with a group of university communication
professors, drafted a set of seven key points for how to get the
most of the presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   First, a viewer must set aside their partisan views and learn as
much as possible about each of the candidates and their positions.
</P>
<P>
   Second, viewers must pay close attention to Bush and Gore when
they talk about how to solve problems. This is a way to pull out
comparisons the Republican and Democrat make between or among their
programs and each other.
</P>
<P>
   Third, the candidate's debate strategy should be a major
concern, as well. Do Bush and Gore speak directly to the issues,
provide specifics and present new policies or information? Viewers
should pay attention to whether the candidates evasively interpret
questions to suit their agenda?
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates will try to create images for themselves.
Most candidates try to portray themselves as leaders and with
cherished American values while suggesting that their opponents
lack these qualities. Viewers should ask themselves what in the
responses supports their claims.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth, viewers should be aware of the technical limitations of
televised debates. Television works by showing action and to create
action and minimize monotony, directors will show ``reaction
shots'' to show one candidate's responses to an opponent's
statement. Viewers should not let this distract them.
</P>
<P>
   The questions asked by Lehrer Tuesday night also should be taken
into consideration, specifically if they are adding to the debate.
One question to ask is if his questions encourage alternative
viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Carlin says a debate doesn't determine a winner or
a loser. Both Bush and Gore have goals for a debate and both could
claim victory if winning is defined as achieving goals set by their
campaigns. She says viewers should focus on the question of who
would make a better president.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE THE DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   A good way to get the most out of Tuesday's debate is to debate
the debate with other people watching. The Commission on
Presidential Debates will hold discussion groups called DebateWatch
2000 around the country. Each group will send back a report on
people's reaction to the debate Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   One of these discussions will be held at Wabash College in
Crawfordsville, Ind. The intent of the discussion, which could draw
between 20 and 60 people, is to shape the structure of future
presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   Todd McDorman, assistant professor of speech at Wabash College
and a facilitator of the school's DebateWatch 2000, said he also
hopes it encourages this small group of participants to at least
vote in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``By doing something like this, if we can get more students to
come out, it will increase the possibility of these people
voting,'' he said. ``Ideally we would have students be more
politically active.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
