r e bc-TV-CHOICE-2000     09-29 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHOICE-2000-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CANDIDATES, TWO DYNASTIES?
</HEADLINE>
bc-TV-CHOICE-2000 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `TONIGHT' IS SUN., OCT. 1) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
 
BY DAVID KRONKE 
c. 2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure, the new fall season begins tonight, but we're electing a
president this year, and ``Frontline'' offers fairly useful
biographies of Al Gore and George W. Bush on ``The Choice 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   To folks not born into political dynasties, this year's decision
has to be a fairly deflating one, powerfully suggesting as it does
that a ruling class has in fact emerged in America. Both
candidates' families have led lives of privilege and power, which
might make it difficult for the rest of us to shoehorn our own
aspirations into the old-boys club called Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Choice 2000'' implies that virtually everything Gore has
done in his life outside of some recreational pot use has had an
eye on political placement (his enlisting for service in Vietnam
was even exploited by his father's senatorial campaign in the
'70s). Footage in which Gore proudly allies himself with tobacco
growers is eventually juxtaposed against his attack on Big Tobacco.
His intelligence, however, is never called into question.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, everything Bush has accomplished in his life can be
chalked up to his daddy's brand name, as Dubya has made a practice
of failing upward. Ironically, when his father was running against
Michael Dukakis in 1988, the younger Bush warned gravely against
electing an inexperienced governor president. He is, nonetheless,
shown to be a guy who knows how to use his wry sense of humor to
get things accomplished (amusingly, he ran a pointedly corrupt
stickball league in prep school).
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes that the next president will have to prove
himself ``substantial enough, authentic enough to lead.'' ``Choice
2000'' sort of splits the difference Gore, it shows, is clearly the
substantial one, while Bush is posited as the more authentic of the
two. &QL; 
---``THE CHOICE 2000'' &QL; 
What: ``Frontline'' biographies on Al Gore and George W. Bush. &QL; 
Where: KCET. &QL; 
When: 9 tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
