<HEADER>
A6802 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-YOAKAM-TOUR-TEX     09-29 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOAKAM-TOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONKY-TONK MAN BACK TO HAUNTING BARROOMS ON NEW TOUR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dwight Yoakam is back. After spending several years preoccupied
primarily with film work, Yoakam is again touring and recording
extensively, and even doing club dates to get up-close-and-personal
with fans.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rootsy return for the
singer-songwriter-actor-director-author, and it will bring Yoakam
to the Cowboys Concert Hall stage in Arlington, Texas, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam appeared in concert in July at the arena-sized Smirnoff
Music Centre in Dallas, then was quickly recruited for the more
intimate tour date at Cowboys in Arlington, where he's never played
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't booked acts that big before, but we thought we'd
give it a shot and see what happened,'' said Chris Lutz, Cowboys
Arlington marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   The Yoakam date has already paid off for Cowboys, which is known
as much for being a dancing and mingling place as a concert spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ticket sales are great,'' Lutz said. ``Pre-sales for this
concert are the best we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam's current national tour is low-key and lengthy, having
kicked off in early June and consisting of more than 50 dates,
ranging from casinos and festivals to fairs and clubs.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Yoakam was set to appear at two fairs (the Kern
County Fair in Bakersfield, Calif., and the South Plains Fair in
Lubbock, Texas) and a couple of clubs, the Celebrity Theatre in
Phoenix and the Far West Rodeo in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam took a three-year break from performing in the mid-'90s,
returning to the road again for his ``Last Chance'' tour in
mid-'99. That's when he discussed the the allure of returning to
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of nights, maybe it's hard to make that
shift, and I am getting older,'' he said at the outset of that
tour. ``But it's something you fall toward the way you would a
comfortable bed. It allows you a certain kind of embrace.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his long gaps off the road weren't aimed at getting out
of the live-touring business, as some had speculated; they were
just a way of keeping himself fresh artistically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've (toured) all my life,'' he said. ``I hope we still have
an access to (the fans) and always will.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his recent acoustic album,
``dwightyoakamacoustic.net,'' was planned as a special thanks to
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam released a message on his Web site, saying the album was
``a result of the audience's gracious and enthusiastic response''
to the acoustic performances on the ``Last Chance'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   New this year for Yoakam is an upcoming studio album to be
released Oct. 31, ``Tomorrow's Sounds Today.''
</P>
<P>
   Guests include Buck Owens, Chris Hillman (Byrds, Flying Burrito
Brothers) on mandolin, Flaco Jimenez on accordion, and Jim
Lauderdale on vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam's self-described ``gothic western'' film ``South of
Heaven, West of Hell'' debuted in Europe last spring, marking his
first turn as a film writer and director as well as actor. The
movie also stars Peter Fonda, Bridget Fonda, Billy Bob Thornton,
Vince Vaughn and Paul Rubens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was originally a morality tale of a person with survivor
guilt,'' Yoakam explained. ``It's like `Once Upon a Time in the
West.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yoakam insists he focuses totally on each project when he's
working on it, which is why he was away from touring for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music will never leave me,'' Yoakam said, when asked if he'd
ever choose between film work and recording/touring. ``It's an
outlet to articulate all emotion for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why he's coming to Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DWIGHT YOAKAM
</P>
<P>
   Sunday: 8 p.m. at Cowboys, 2540 E. Abram St., Arlington
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $15 advance, $20 at the door, $35 for reserved seats
</P>
<P>
   Information: (817) 265-5819
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Shirley Jinkins writes on country music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 548-5565, or e-mail:
syjinkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
