<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6825 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-RUN-JONES-BOS &LR;      09-29 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG JUMP A LINE TOO FAR FOR JONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Being gifted has never been enough to make Marion Jones
a legitimate paid-up member of the Long Jump Club.
</P>
<P>
   She has jumped as far as 7.31 meters, the seventh-best female
long jump in history, but she did it on raw talent, not technique,
and not much has changed. She kind of wobbles around from jump to
jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a fighter, and she has so much speed,'' observed Heike
Dreschler. ``She's the fastest I've seen. But she has to work on
the run-up. With a very good rhythm, she will do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   That was free, media-solicited advice from someone who knows
whereof she speaks. Dreschler is the Once and Current Queen of the
Long Jump, having won the event in Barcelona eight years ago and
having won it again, this time at age 36, Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing she put an end to Jones's quest for five Olympic
gold medals. Then throw in Italy's Fiona May, whose best jump of
6.92 meters gave her the silver medal. Jones likewise jumped 6.92
on her third attempt, but May placed ahead of Jones because her
second-best jump exceeded Jones's, 6.82 to 6.68. Jones had to
settle _ and we do mean settle _ for a (yuck) bronze. ``After
having two golds around my neck,'' said the 100-and 200-meter
champion, ``a bronze doesn't quite compare. But it's better than
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the privacy of her apartment, she may very well have
bawled her eyes out to hubby C.J. Hunter, but in front of the
international media she was a wonderfully cheerful and gracious
interview subject.
</P>
<P>
   She had given it her best shot, she said. On this occasion her
best just wasn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   She fouled on her first, fourth, fifth, and sixth attempts. The
final try was a real tease, because she had landed out beyond the
numeral ``7,'' for what would have been a dramatic victory. There
was only one problem . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``On the last jump,'' she explained, ``I got to lay it all on
the line. It's what every athlete dreams of, coming back on the
last jump and jumping better than you ever have before. I saw the
7-meter mark, and then I saw the man holding up the red flag. It
kind of dashed all my hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no doubt about it. She had taken off a good
half-a-shoe over the line.
</P>
<P>
   There were no regrets. The four fouls were clear proof that she
was going after that gold medal, that she wasn't going to hope
someone ceded it to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' she said. `I put it out there. That's why
I had so many fouls. I went for it. I was flying down that
runway.''
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly. Everyone knows now that she is the Fastest Woman In
The World, and a certain amount of raw speed is necessary to be
successful in the long jump. Whom would you like in a sprint? Jones
or 36-year-old Dreschler? Jones, or 31-year-old May? This event is
about more than speed. Watching craftsfolk like those two is
enlightening, especially since Jones was trying to steal a gold
while practicing the event three times a week, and while refusing
to hire a long jump coach.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare public moment of pique, the otherwise unflappable Ms.
Jones didn't seem to like it when she was asked if she would
consider employing a full-time coach in this event. ``No,'' she
said, somewhat icily, ``I wouldn't consider it at all. I've said
several times that I jumped 24 feet in 1998. I haven't seen that
form in the last couple of years. But I think I'll get back to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps she will. Doubting this woman is very foolish.
</P>
<P>
   With both the 4x100 and 4x400 relay teams qualifying for their
respective finals in her absence, her revised target was four
golds. But she made it very clear she would not apologize for
having brought up the idea of bagging five herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't regret at all having said I was going for five,'' she
declared. ``I had a shot at it, but it didn't turn out, you know.
I'll try to get refocused and help my US teammates bring home the
gold. I'm very happy we made the finals in both relays.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the long jump, well, this was simply a night for someone
else, not that there's anything embarrassing about taking home a
bronze. Any one of the full-time long jumpers in the field, nine of
whom finished behind this moonlighting sprinter, would have been
very honored to have that bronze.
</P>
<P>
   This night belonged to the fascinating Dreschler, who jumped for
the old GDR (the evil East Germans) while supposedly full of drugs
and who has had an even more impressive career without artificial
aid while jumping for the Good Germans. Winning jumping golds at
age 35 is a stupendous achievement, as Jones herself acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Heike deserved to win,'' Jones said. ``In 30 years I'll be able
to tell my grandchildren I competed against one of the best long
jumpers ever.''
</P>
<P>
   And in case you're wondering, Jones expects someone to be saying
that about her at some future Olympics, coach or no coach. If she
didn't believe that, she wouldn't be Marion Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
