<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6829 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-29 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAR-LOSS TO LITHUANIA WAS UGLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Eight years ago, it was ``Beat me, whip me, take my
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's ``Bleep you.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years. That's all it has taken for the United States of
America to go from being the most respected force in the game of
basketball to the most reviled. Friday night, in the Super Dome at
Sydney's Olympic Park, the US came amazingly close to being the
most humiliated athletic team in the history of mankind. The
national team of tiny Lithuania absolutely, positively could have
won this game, and if it had, what transpired at Lake Placid 20
years ago would have looked, in hindsight, like some kind of
American mortal lock. This would have been the greatest sports
upset.
</P>
<P>
   Ever.
</P>
<P>
   Anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   What a truly pathetic sight it was from an American/NBA
perspective. Here was its sickeningly arrogant juggernaut, already
made to sweat by the likes of Lithuania (85-76), France (106-94),
and Russia (85-70 and a 4-point game at the half), needing every
bounce of the ball and every call and every last bit of defensive
energy on the game's final possession to salvage an 85-83 victory
over a team that is missing its two best players, Portland Trail
Blazer center Arvydas Sabonis and former Seton Hall standout, and
European star, Arturas Karnisovas.
</P>
<P>
   You had Americans kneeling on the sidelines on that last play,
looking very much like kids on those 15 seeds in the first round of
the NCAA when they're on the verge of defeating the No. 2 seed.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Understand something: Lithuania is not what it once was. Absent
Sabonis, Sarunas Marciulonis, and the other veterans who were the
core of the 1988 Soviet Union team that won in Seoul, it is a
fair-to-middlin' European team; no more, no less. There are three
players on the roster with an American college exerience, but none
were, or are, important players. The rest are OK European types.
Not one would interest an NBA scout.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we were definitely the best team in the (Olympic) village
to play the US,'' points out Lithuanian assistant coach/advisor
Donnie Nelson, who has been associated with the Lithuania team for
a decade. ``Three reasons. One, we are the best defensive team of
all the others. Two, we follow a game plan religiously. Three, we
play as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   By playing aggressive defense, by doing what the coaches told
them to do on offense, and by playing selfless basketball, this
unimposing European squad has twice humbled the haughty Americans,
who are now so defensive about being exposed as something less than
demigods of the hardwood that they are resorting to infantile
behavior to justify themselves, to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thinks Americans would have said if the US team
had lost, Vince Carter sizzled. ``We didn't lose,'' he snapped. ``I
don't care what the world thinks. Look at the scoreboard.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Vince Carter who has endeared himself to the
international basketball community by acting offended when anyone
dares to guard him and who is so clueless he whooped it up and
pointed to the crowd after making a sneakaway dunk that gave the US
a 3-point lead late in the game, and who was yapping at Lithuania's
Mindaugas Timinskas after the game instead of shaking his hand and
walking off the court with his head down and his mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, Vince Carter was a pretty nice kid from North
Carolina. Now he is VINCE CARTER, the Slam Dunk King, and he can't
understand why these scruffy kids from the Baltic won't show him a
little respect.
</P>
<P>
   Ya see, Vince, it's not like that, anymore. The days of an
Argentine player yelling to the bench to have his picture taken
while he's posting up Magic Johnson have given way to unawed,
unimpressed athletes spitting in the great NBA faces. The awe
factor no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   This is precisely what FIBA president Borislav Stankovic had in
mind when he led the movement to get the NBA involved in regular
international competition. He reasoned that the gap between the US
and the rest of the world could be narrowed quicker if the rest of
the world had more direct exposure to the beast in order to learn
what made it tick.
</P>
<P>
   The whole original Dream Team business was strictly Show Biz, as
we all know. But the situation changed within two years, when, at
the 1994 World Championships in Toronto, US coach Don Nelson made a
simple substitution.
</P>
<P>
   One of the little Chuck Daly quirks in both the 1992 Tournament
of the Americas and the Barcelona Olympics was that he never called
a timeout, nor made a substitution that wasn't based on spreading
out playing time or politics. But early in the second half of a
game against the Russians, coach Nelson did something interesting.
He made a substitution based on need. The US was struggling with
the Russians, and he decided things would be better if he took out
Alonzo Mourning and inserted Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   So that's where the aura of invincibility was shattered forever.
Six years later, forget about invinciblity. Let's talk about
vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, the fact that the international rules are
different was a mere irritation. Now it matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different game,'' explains Nelson. ``The
international game is not all about post-ups and isos. And I think
any time you have a compilation of players like a `Dream Team,' one
thing that's missing is a `glue' player, like a Kurt Rambis, a guy
who does the little things on a championship caliber team. Here,
it's more the passing game. NBA players aren't used to the need to
play for 30 seconds. The ball goes side-to-side three or four
times. It's just a different game.''
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, but in this case there is still a huge talent gap.
We are talking about multimillion dollar NBA players against a team
containing, at best, a CBA player or two. Somewhere in here we need
to discuss the US team mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   After the Lithuanians had played the US tough last week,
Lithuanian guard Sarunas Jasikevicius, who played for Gary Williams
at Maryland (not always that well), had this to say: ``I think
they're gonna lose a game, and I think they're gonna lose a game
here. They are treating this like a vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting.
</P>
<P>
   We can only observe that the US was a disgrace against the
Lithuanians. ``Anarchy'' is not too strong a word to describe the
bench goings-on. Though lip service would later be paid to the
sense of urgency in the game's last minutes, actions indicated that
the US was a team that couldn't understand why the opposition
wouldn't simply surrender and allow them to get this thing over
with so they could go party.
</P>
<P>
   That type of arrogance was never a problem in the old days. It
was never becoming, but neither was it counterproductive. Now it is
both. People are no longer afraid of the Americans, and as long as
they keep acting the way they are on the court, people are starting
to despise them. This group is demonstrating zero class.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. and Mrs. America would be so much better served if
represented by Lithuania, which respects the game and plays it
honorably, than by Team USA, which, being the finest embodiment of
the Entitlement Generation, plays with no purpose and then forces
its coach, Rudy Tomjanovich, to embarrass himself in front of
people who know differently by telling us what great people
comprise this reprehensible team of his.
</P>
<P>
   The shame of all this isn't that the US might lose. That would
only be justice. The shame of it is that a team doesn't even have
to be very good to expose them as people. What's happening here
isn't really a basketball story. It's a people story as old as
mankind. The rest of the world is simply standing up to a classless
bully.
</P>
<P>
   The US plays for the gold Sunday. An awful lot of people around
here are shouting, ``Vive La France!'' Some of them are carrying
American passports.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1616EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
