<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-QNA-FIRSTCALL-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENNESS CAN BE A TWO-WAY STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunshine is healthy. But it also can burn.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will receive a big dose of sunshine when Regulation FD
takes effect on Oct. 23. The directive, from the Securities and
Exchange Commission, will end disclosure of corporate information
to some people and not others, including guidance on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are already complying with the new rule. In a
number of cases _ Intel and Eastman Kodak, for example _ what they
had to say was not pretty. Nor was the reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Hill, director of research at First Call/Thompson
Financial, which tracks analysts' earnings estimates, took time
last week to talk about Regulation FD and the profit outlook for
the remainder of the year. Here are excerpts from the
conversation. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. It seems many companies are already complying with this rule. Do
you agree? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. I think that is correct. I don't have an exact figure, but there
are certainly a meaningful number of companies that are doing this.
No one can remember, for example, the last time Alcoa preannounced
their earnings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. What sort of impact do you foresee when everybody is forced to
live by the new rule?  &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. I don't know if you will see the full impact in the first couple
of quarters, because I think some corporate lawyers will advise
some companies to clam up completely, or close to it.
</P>
<P>
   That is not in the best interest of the companies, because they
will find that the earnings estimates will be more volatile, in
bigger ranges. And I think companies that don't say anything will
start losing some coverage if they are not giving guidance.
</P>
<P>
   But once the dust settles, it will be pretty much business as
usual, except that instead of giving guidance individually to
analysts, the guidance will come in the form of a preannouncement
or a Webcast. And we are going to see a lot more Webcasting of
conference calls and meetings.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. If the number of companies making preannouncements increases,
will the stock market become even more volatile?  &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. It will create more volatility because the ranges on earnings
estimates will be somewhat wider, and surprises will be more
frequent on both the upside and the downside.
</P>
<P>
   On average, over the last six years, companies have beaten
estimates by nearly three percentage points. That may get squeezed
down to a smaller number.  &QL; 
Q. How will this rule affect analysts? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. This will make their job harder rather than easier, but that is
good.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of good analysts out there, but a number knew
they could get away with not doing all the homework they should
because they could regurgitate what the company was telling them.
</P>
<P>
   There should be a two-way relationship between an analyst and
the company he or she is covering.
</P>
<P>
   As an independent, outside observer, an analyst is supposed to
do some digging. But the analyst should be contributing as much
information to the company as they are getting. The relationship
should be valuable to both sides.  &QL; 
Q. Even with the downside preannouncements, will third-quarter
profits be healthy?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Up until a week ago, we thought preannouncements were running
at about a normal pace. But since then we have changed our tune.
Now we are saying we will see more warnings than usual. Even if
some of those are due to Regulation FD, that is not the whole
story: there is a problem out there in that there are more
companies with earnings problems than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Right now we are expecting earnings growth of 16.4 percent for
the third quarter, down from an estimated 18.8 percent in early
July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q. What about the fourth quarter? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. There could be some problems in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   You are seeing these warnings for the third quarter because the
American economy is slowing, energy prices are higher and the euro
is weak. I think all three of these factors will be in play again
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market is correct in paying attention to the
preannouncements we have seen, not for the impact they had in the
third quarter, but rather for the effect they will have on
fourth-quarter results. And the fourth quarter will tell us where
we are headed in the first quarter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. Which are the strong and weak sectors? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. Consumer cyclicals _ be it autos, housing or apparel _ have
problems. Basic materials companies _ the papers, metals and
chemicals _ have also been crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Energy companies are going to do well in the third quarter. The
estimate for the sector now is an earnings increase of 91 percent,
up from 80 percent on Sept. 1. And technology is going to do well,
with a projected increase of 35 percent.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6833 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-RUN-DRESCHLER-BOS     09-29 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN-DRESCHLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESCHLER'S USES AGE-OLD SKILL TO JUMP TO GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The world-class athlete opened the window to greet the
big day. She felt the wilting humidity and the whipsaw wind. Her
optimally conditioned body instinctively responded to the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   She crawled back into bed. And stayed there. And stayed some
more.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't necessarily the classic preparatory routine of
champions, but for Heike Drechsler, the emphasis is on ``classic''
more than ``champion.'' Oh, she awoke Friday morning as the owner
of four Olympic medals _ two bronze, a silver, and a gold _ but
they were antiques, from 1988 and '92. Her treasure chest also
included six world championship medals, including a pair of golds,
but they, too, were ancient, from 1983, '87, and '91.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, technically, Drechsler was still at the top of the game,
scheduled to compete Friday night in the Olympic long jump at
Stadium Australia. But she was supposed to be merely present, not a
presence. The most pertinent statistic by which to gauge her
potential for success was this:
</P>
<P>
   Age: 35.
</P>
<P>
   Make that 36 by Christmas, the cusp of middle age, when the
weather becomes more of a consideration in how much your bones will
shriek and creak than in how far your body will jump against women
almost closer in age to your 11-year-old son than to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to win today (was) in my thinking when I wake
up,'' said Drechsler. ``I just want to rest and lay around. I
looked and saw the heat and the wind and was a little afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   But the athlete who was an old lady, competitively speaking,
became a grande dame by bedtime. In fact, she had to stay up past
it, because late Friday, she was still answering questions from the
world media about how she captured her second long jump gold medal
eight years after her first _ and dashed Marion Jones's crusade to
win five golds here.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Drechsler outleaped everyone with a best of 6.99 meters
on her third of six attempts. That was enough to nudge her past
runner-up Fiona May of Italy and bronze medalist Jones, America's
Olympic cover girl. Both landed 6.92 meters into the sand pit, but
May earned her second straight long jump silver because she had no
fouls while trick-or-treat jumper Jones accumulated four.
</P>
<P>
   It was not startling that Jones, the 100- and 200-meter titlist,
lost, for the long jump is her weakest event. But it was astounding
that Drechsler won, for she has been around so long that she
initially competed for a now-defunct country _ East Germany, which
was reunified with its neighboring nemesis to the west a decade
ago. By then, Drechsler had earned fame as the youngest world
champion ever (18, in the '83 long jump), served as Jackie
Joyner-Kersee's foil in the Seoul Games long jump of '88, and, as
one of history's most versatile athletes, set world records in the
200 and long jump.
</P>
<P>
   Since East Germany was absorbed into one republic, Drechsler had
won Olympic gold in the '92 long jump at Barcelona, but in the
mid-1990s she'd also been involved in some of the lingering
ugliness from the days of a divided Germany. A book was published
exposing the East German state policy of giving its premier
athletes illicit drugs, and Drechsler was identified as one of the
artificially enhanced wunderkind. Enraged, she sued but lost in
court and was forced to apologize to the authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not fair to accuse the East Germans of doing things over
which they may have had no control or known nothing about,'' said
German jump coach Wolfgang Killing. ``It was a long time ago. I
think if we all got together and asked, we all have a fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Drechsler seemed to have experienced a mother lode of them in
recent years. She'd gotten divorced and been shuffled to the
periphery of the international stage, a victim of age and, not
coincidentally, injuries. She was infirm for the Atlanta Games of
'96, and when she developed a foot problem a week before last
year's world championships, she wondered why she was hanging
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``But four weeks later, I looked at my spikes and knew I still
wanted to do this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even when beset by yet another setback this year _ a torn calf
muscle that cost her five weeks of training and rendered her an
afterthought coming to Sydney _ Drechsler resisted retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love sports very much,'' she said. ``In the beginning, it
was great. After 20 years, I still don't have feelings to give up
my fight in the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't have particularly optimistic feelings Friday,
even when she finally dragged herself to the stadium and found that
the humidity and wind had abated somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it was a dream to win the gold medal,'' said
Drechsler at her victory press conference. ``This year was not so
easy. And I wasn't sure about a medal, especially gold. I have
strong ladies sitting beside me.''
</P>
<P>
   Second- and third-place ladies. But at least the ever gracious
Jones _ who ``grew up watching Heike and Jackie compete against
each other'' _ figured she'd received a consolation prize in
addition to her bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell my grandkids in 30 years,'' she said, ``that I
competed against one of the greatest long jumpers in history.''
</P>
<P>
   And lost to her. That would be an appropriate epitaph for
Drechsler's career. Except it doesn't seem ready for one just yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-HOLOCAUSTRADIO     09-29 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HOLOCAUSTRADIO-0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI RADIO SHOW CLOSES FAMILY GAPS, OPENS OLD WOUNDS
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ They call in with painful, unfinished business from
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, Hadaya, is looking for her uncle who escaped the Nazi
Holocaust to join the Soviet Army and was last heard from in a
postcard in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman was separated from an orphaned boy her family
cared for more than 50 years ago on their weeks-long refugee
journey from Europe. It turns out he's now a lawyer near Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   Still, others call inquiring about lost aunts and uncles who
were shoved out of the family consciousness by memories too bitter
for their parents to pass on.
</P>
<P>
   They are survivors, and children of survivors, of the Holocaust.
And they have found an unlikely home on Israel's afternoon drive
time radio.
</P>
<P>
   Five days a week for about 12 minutes a day, radio host Yaron
Enosh goes over the faxes or calls on his new show, ``The
Department for Seeking Relatives _ The Next Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to victims of the Holocaust, the show reaches out to
Israelis who have lost track of comrades from Israel's wars or
relatives separated in the waves of hectic immigration that built
the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Enosh says he aims to reunite and repair the ``holes'' in
families still fractured from the national and ethnic catastrophes
faced by Israel, and Jews around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Israelis call in each day, and more than 90 have
found loved ones, or people with information about loved ones,
since the program began in early August. Some were reunited on the
air, making for somber and suspenseful reality programming.
</P>
<P>
   It began as an experiment.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Enosh, 45, realized he could not answer his
12-year-old daughter's questions for a school family tree project.
There were too missing branches.
</P>
<P>
   All of his grandparents, and several aunts and uncles perished
in the Holocaust. His parents, who escaped the Holocaust by fleeing
Poland for Russia, did not like to talk about the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to talk to my friends and many of them had the same
problem,'' Enosh says. ``But, I didn't know how big a phenomenon it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   He was soon to find out. His boss at the Voice of Israel,
Israel's national radio station, gave him a time slot in the summer
to discuss something ``light.'' Instead, he made the topic missing
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   He took the name of the show from a department in the Jewish
Agency, a charitable organization that facilitates immigration to
Israel. In the late 1940s and early 1950s, Israelis sat riveted by
their radio as the department would read the names of immigrants _
the Holocaust survivors _ who had made it to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But, the new show was not a sure hit. Israelis have wavered over
the decades over how much they have wanted to delve into the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The Holocaust killed about 6 million Jews _ a million more Jews
than the number living in Israel now _ and convinced the world of
the need for a Jewish refuge. A day of mourning for the Holocaust
every spring is still revered throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Holocaust also raises the specter of a vulnerability
that Jews never want to relive.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, says Rachel Peterburg, general director of a social
services center for Holocaust survivors, many Jews had arrived
before World War II to build what would become Israel and they
faced their own hardships. They were sometimes resentful of the
boatloads of needy Holocaust immigrants, noting that they had
declined to come help develop a Jewish state until the catastrophe
occurred in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But, Peterburg said the past 15 years have seen a greater
Israeli willingness to hear about the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   According to Peterburg, there are about 200,000 Holocaust
survivors living in Israel and another 160,000 Israelis who were
small children just after, or while, the Holocaust was ending.
</P>
<P>
   The time seems right for the new radio program. According to
Enosh, ratings are not yet available, but more than 250 people
contact the show daily with requests about missing relatives or
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Enosh said he feels he has tapped into something central in the
Israeli psyche. He describes it as ``the big holes we have'' in
which family members are missing and, for the younger generation,
roots are obscured.
</P>
<P>
   He says about two-thirds of the requests that come to the show
concern the Holocaust. The rest seek people lost in the large
immigration to Israel from Morocco, Yemen and other eastern
countries, or from people looking for those they fought beside in
Israel's wars.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is still a small country, with maybe 5 million Jewish,
and one million Arab citizens. Frequently, someone can hear a name
on a radio program and know friends or neighbors from the same
family, platoon or town of origin.
</P>
<P>
   The stories have been riveting.
</P>
<P>
   Kalman Gomeh, 52, was born in a refugee camp in Cyprus after
World War II. His father disappeared and his mother, a survivor of
horrible death camp traumas, was unable to care for him.
</P>
<P>
   He moved through several foster families growing up to become a
self-made, hard-driving, computer executive. The gaps in his past
seemed distant, until his wife convinced him to call Enosh's show
and inquire for information about his father.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks later, while shopping in a hardware store, one
of the show's producers called his mobile phone and told him he had
received a response from a half-sister in Israel _ a half-sister he
didn't know he had.
</P>
<P>
   Gomeh and the sister were hooked up on the air. Suddenly, the
boisterous Gomeh was speechless. His new half-sister told him his
father lived in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   For Gomeh, it was an exciting and disturbing revelation. For
once, he had a family, complete with new siblings, nephews and
nieces. But, he was still angry at his father, now 79 years old,
for leaving him and starting another family far away.
</P>
<P>
   They have spoken by phone. Gomeh said his father ``cried like a
baby'' and asked that his lost son not judge him. Gomeh's
sentiments are mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the father, after all. Even if he screwed me, even if he
cheated me and threw me away, he's your father and you have to know
him,'' Gomeh says, his eyes tearing up.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he says he is glad for the new radio show, not only
for him but for the many others who have similar stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is closing the historical gaps,'' he says. ``It is making
people come together.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For information about the Holocaust, visit the Yad Vashem
memorial museum site:
</P>
<P>
   www.yad-vashem.org.il
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
