<HEADER>
A6838 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a BC-LOW-FAT-MILK-DANGER-N     09-29 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOW-FAT-MILK-DANGER-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAZARDS OF A HEALTHY CHOICE  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., OCT. 2, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By JOANNA MARCHANT  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist/RBI Magazines Ltd.  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drinking low-fat rather than whole milk could be more likely to
infect you with food-poisoning bugs such as Salmonella and E. coli,
according to PHLS researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Although large dairies used by supermarkets use modern
equipment, most small dairies use pasteurizing machines that were
built before skimmed milk became popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't designed to separate the milk during the
pasteurization process,'' says Anita Rampling of the PHLS in
Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   To meet today's demand for low-fat milk, these dairies modified
their machines to skim off the cream. But Rampling and her
colleague Melody Greenwood investigated two modified farm dairies
which had failed a test designed to detect inadequately treated
milk. They found that the alteration often means the milk is no
longer pasteurized properly, so some bacteria are able to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flow rate is speeded up, so the milk is not held at high
temperature for long enough,'' Rampling says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been problems with on-farm pasteurization in the
past,'' says a spokeswoman for the Food Standards Agency. ``But we
are not aware of this particular problem.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds that dairies that don't pasteurize their milk properly
could ultimately be shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Rampling says the problem is compounded by the way milk is
checked to ensure pasteurization has worked. The test looks for
phosphatase, an enzyme that is destroyed during pasteurization. But
phosphatase tends to bind to the fat in milk, so when the cream is
skimmed off, much of the enzyme goes with it. This means that
low-fat milk can test negative for the enzyme even if it hasn't
been pasteurized properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``For skimmed milk, you need a more sensitive test,'' says Ted
Langridge, an independent food science consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Rampling wants the law changed to ensure low-fat milk undergoes
such tests, which are available. Langridge agrees but goes further,
saying all milk and not just the low-fat variety should be screened
this way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
