<HEADER>
Q2503 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-CONVICTS-CHAMPION-NNS     09-29 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVICTS-CHAMPION-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VINDICATOR OF INNOCENT CHOOSES HIS BATTLES CAREFULLY 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
    &HT;     ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from the NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE
report of FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 29, 2000, is available as a ``separate
buy.'' For information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA
WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at 732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697; e-mail, weyded(at)nytimes.com 
 &HT;     Art Advisory: With photo of James McCloskey and A.B. Butler Jr.
(NNS1); for information about purchasing art call 202-383-7824 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Optional trim to 800 words 
 &HT;     By ROBERT STERN 
 &HT;     c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ In its 17 years of work for the wrongly
convicted, Jim McCloskey's Centurion Ministries has freed and won
vindication for 22 innocent people facing the death penalty or a
life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   For them, Centurion was a long shot. For Centurion to intervene
on their behalf, they had to be sure shots.
</P>
<P>
   Their cases had to be compelling; their claims of innocence
credible; their past, though not necessarily crime-free, at least
devoid of a pattern of earlier violent crimes, said McCloskey,
Centurion's founder, president and executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only interested in complete, factual innocence,''
McCloskey said, noting that his lack of confidence in some others'
innocence doesn't mean those people are guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Also important is whether ``chances (are) pretty solid that
they're going to be good, quiet, law-abiding citizens if they're
going to be released from prison,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the convicts whose struggles Centurion champions are
the ``voiceless, anonymous, forgotten, forsaken people'' who have
not become magnets for some political agenda, McCloskey said.
</P>
<P>
   The little-known A.B. Butler Jr. and several dozen others around
the country matched Centurion's criteria and won its help.
</P>
<P>
   The well-known Mumia Abu-Jamal and countless others have _
either directly or through their advocates _ sought Centurion's
help over the years, but didn't get it, McCloskey said.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Jamal was convicted in the 1981 shooting death of
Philadelphia Police Officer Daniel Faulkner. His case is just the
type McCloskey would _ and has _ dismissed. One reason, McCloskey
says, is that he isn't sold on Abu-Jamal's proclaimed innocence.
Another is that Abu-Jamal has a network of supporters around the
world who often spark political protests on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, those for whom Centurion is most likely to fight,
like Butler, have little name recognition and nowhere else to turn,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Butler became the 22nd person whose freedom and
exoneration Centurion secured, by proving he did not kidnap and
rape a Texas woman in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Centurion recently brought Butler from his Texas home to its
Princeton office, where he took his name off the group's
active-case list. It had been on that list since McCloskey gave
Butler his nonprofit agency's full commitment five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Full commitment means McCloskey often works with a private
investigator and a defense attorney for five years or more to
uncover the evidence to free the wrongly convicted person.
</P>
<P>
   Butler's road to freedom and Texas Gov. George W. Bush's pardon
in June began with a letter pleading his case to Centurion about
seven years ago, after having exhausted other avenues of appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without (Centurion), I probably would still be in prison right
now,'' said Butler, who served 17 years of a 99-year prison term
for crimes DNA tests proved he did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   Convincing McCloskey to fully devote Centurion to a case is like
winning the lottery, said Joan Whalen, the former Centurion worker
whose two-year correspondence with Butler was instrumental in
gaining McCloskey's support for him.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the selection process is random. Rather, it's that
McCloskey doesn't take full commitment to a case lightly.
</P>
<P>
   If he did, it would waste Centurion's scarce resources, which
consist of six employees, 22 volunteers and a $700,000 annual
budget, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   McCloskey decided not to risk those resources on Abu-Jamal's
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying he's guilty, but his claims of innocence are
not nearly as compelling as a lot of other cases,'' McCloskey said.
Even so, McCloskey feels Abu-Jamal did not receive a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Taylor, professor of theology and culture at Princeton
Theological Seminary, leads one Abu-Jamal advocacy group, Academics
for Mumia Abu-Jamal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's fair to set Mumia off in another place by
saying he might be guilty until he has a fair trial,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the American legal system, ``a person is innocent whatever
the doubts anyone has about the case until proven guilty in a fair
trial,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While Centurion can afford to give its full attention only to
the most compelling of the cases it deems credible, McCloskey says
his organization ignores no appeals it receives involving cases
with life or death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Before McCloskey commits to a promising case in full, a
Centurion case worker typically spends up to two years
corresponding with the convict to learn who that person is and
whether the details supporting the claims of innocence in the
letters remain consistent over time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, if the claims continue to appear credible, McCloskey
visits the potential candidate in prison for a one-on-one
interview. The inmate must convince McCloskey of his innocence
during that interview or Centurion will reject the case.
</P>
<P>
   And if Centurion's investigation reveals strong evidence of
guilt instead of innocence, as happened with three of its cases,
McCloskey will halt Centurion's fight for the inmate's freedom, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we ever catch you lying or have serious doubts that you're
not innocent, we drop your case,'' McCloskey said.
</P>
<P>
   PH END STERN
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Stern is a staff writer for The Times of Trenton, N.J.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6854 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-LAWS     09-29 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-LAWSUIT-$ADV01-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE HOME'S UNPLANNED ADDITION: A COURTROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
 By ROY FURCHGOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ We had done all the right things. We checked the
record of the home improvement contractor with state regulators and
the Better Business Bureau. We inspected the contractor's jobs in
progress. We checked references. We wrote and signed a detailed
contract and an additional written agreement that the contractor
would forfeit $100 for each day the job ran late. If the work
didn't go smoothly, we thought, we were covered.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, a year later, we were in a Baltimore courtroom, fighting
over a project that had run months late and was never finished _
and it was the contractor who was suing us.
</P>
<P>
   The contractor-homeowner relationship is a famously fraught one.
Almost everyone has heard horror stories about remodeling projects
from hell, and read the usual tips about how to head off trouble.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when the dispute winds up in litigation is seldom
dissected. Our experience disabused us of some cherished notions
about day-to-day civil justice and exposed the near-uselessness of
many of our precautions, especially when contractors are in such
short supply that homeowners have almost no leverage over them.
</P>
<P>
   The story starts with a house that my girlfriend, Guillemette
Brouillat, bought in November 1998 in Canton, a mainly industrial
area of Baltimore being gentrified with a technology center, stores
and waterfront condominiums. She paid $77,000 for a fixer-upper
near the tech center on a block that seemed poised for a
renaissance. Together, we set out to get the place up to scratch.
</P>
<P>
   After interviewing about a dozen contractors, we chose Russell
L. Miller, a friend of a friend of mine. Miller returned calls
promptly, showed up on time for meetings, had good references, no
complaints against him on file, and he didn't object to our desire
to do the paint and tile work ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   He was not the least-expensive contractor around, but time meant
as much to Guillemette as price, because of the high cost of
renting space elsewhere while the work was done. Plus, her mortgage
agreement mandated higher interest charges during construction, and
a six-month deadline for completion.
</P>
<P>
   Demolition started on time, and the framing went quickly. But
progress soon slowed, then seemed to come to a halt. The nine weeks
specified in the contract elapsed. Nervous, we started doing more
of the work ourselves, and barely got the house to a state that
would satisfy the bank in time.
</P>
<P>
   As is usual with home improvements, Miller had been receiving
partial payments along the way, with a final payment of $7,314 due
on completion, plus $1,899 for work added to the project after it
had begun. By our initial reckoning, the job ran 91 days over,
making the late fee $9,100, almost as much as the $9,212 we owed
Miller. We wrote to him, offering to pay $1,899 for the extra work
and call the rest even. That was a lot less than he was expecting
but, we thought, more than he was strictly entitled to. We awaited
a counterproposal.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Guillemette was served with a legal notice: Miller's
company, M&AMP;M Restorations, wanted to put a lien on the house for
the entire $9,212, ignoring the late fees, and was suing us to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   We hired a lawyer, Thomas A. Baker, a construction industry
specialist, who explained to us our first mistake: calling the
$100-a-day fee a penalty. As in most other states, Maryland law
generally allows ``damages'' for whatever the delay cost us out of
pocket, but not ``penalties,'' so a judge could throw out the whole
contract on that technicality, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Financially speaking, mistake No. 2 was plowing ahead with
litigation despite Baker's warning that the cost could rapidly
outstrip the amount at issue. But an emotional calculus was at
work: Guillemette was losing sleep worrying about the dispute,
fighting back would make us feel better, and lawyers don't charge
all that much more than therapists. So we countersued, asking for a
delay penalty that we now reckoned at $9,800, plus $4,521 to repair
faulty work.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, Baker had us spend tedious hours
amassing an accordion file full of photographs, specification
sheets, building codes, timetables and other evidence to support
our claim. Meanwhile, we received the specifics of M&AMP;M's claim,
which basically said the delay was our fault.
</P>
<P>
   (Asked last week to comment for this article, Miller said:
``Delays were caused by the homeowner's inability to complete the
work she had charged herself with doing in a reasonable amount of
time.'')
</P>
<P>
   We were sure that, given our evidence, the court had to back our
delay claim. But that was mistake No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Irrespective of proof, Baker told us, courts generally discard
such claims: ``Judges tend to say, `Is the work complete? If so,
pay the contractor.'''
</P>
<P>
   On Baker's advice, we grudgingly switched our sights to more
promising legal territory: work defects. Courts, he said, usually
support homeowners who hold back from a contractor the amounts they
spend to correct poor work. But by fixing some problems ourselves
and putting others off, we had made mistake No. 4: The courts,
Baker told us, care only about money actually spent and rarely
compensate homeowners for work they do themselves.
</P>
<P>
   (Asked last week to comment on the faulty-work claim, Miller
said, ``There were no complaints from the homeowner to myself or
any of my employees until after I had brought a lawsuit against
them.'')
</P>
<P>
   We were learning that at this level, lawsuits are anything but a
high-minded contest of evidence and argument. The court's main goal
is to clear cases from a crowded docket, and there is little
patience for aggrieved homeowners expecting meticulous pursuit of
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   When our first court date arrived in May neither side had budged
from an initial meeting in which we had offered to pay $4,000 of
the $9,212 Miller wanted, but he had come down by only $1,000, to
$8,212.
</P>
<P>
   Before hearing any arguments or testimony, Judge Richard T.
Rombro called the lawyers into chambers to get the bidding going
again. We raised our offer to $5,200, Miller came down to $7,412,
and Baker told us we seemed headed for a settlement at around
$6,000. We thought we could do better in a trial _ mistake No. 5,
since each additional day in court added $1,500 to our legal fees.
But the emotional math still added up, so we held firm.
</P>
<P>
   The next time around, in mid-June before Judge John C. Byrnes,
the settlement tango was reprised. ``The judge thinks the case will
settle for $6,000,'' our lawyer told us. Still too high, we
thought. But when Miller unexpectedly agreed to that figure, we
were on the spot: refusing might seem unreasonable to the judge,
who might find for Miller in a trial to teach us a lesson. Still,
the judge had yet to see our evidence. We decided to roll the dice.
</P>
<P>
   That might have become mistake No. 6, but for a curious turn of
events. The judge called Guillemette into chambers _ ``to bang her
over the head,'' Baker told me outside. The judge was polite but
firm, Guillemette reported afterward: ``He said, `We are not trying
this case over a couple of hundred dollars.'''
</P>
<P>
   Guillemette offered to drop the delay claim, and told the judge,
``I just want enough to fix the defects.'' He asked what proof she
had _ any photographs, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   At last! Guillemette produced our bulging accordion file,
starting with holes in water-damaged basement walls where light
could be seen streaming in.``They left it like that?'' he asked
her, amazed. Guillemette was dismissed and Miller summoned.
</P>
<P>
   We settled on a payment of $5,800 of the $9,212 Miller wanted.
All our trouble had won us a reduction of $3,412.
</P>
<P>
   We considered it a moral victory, if a pyrrhic one _ Baker's
bill came to $6,914, even after a generous gift of a day's fees,
and the house still needed work.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Over sandwiches afterward, we discussed how justice works in a
case like ours. Baker explained that while our case was unique and
all-important to us, judges have seen thousands like it. ``The
judge first meets with the lawyers to see if he trusts them,''
Baker said _ a wash in our case, with experienced local lawyers on
each side. Next, the judge might ask a few questions to help steer
the parties toward a settlement. Evidence might only enter into the
matter to satisfy the judge's curiosity, as in our case, or at a
trial, if settlement talks failed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Our fight didn't make economic sense in the end, but we thought
that we would at least be leaving a record that could guide other
homeowners. Again we were mistaken. To complete the settlement, we
had to agree to withdraw a complaint we had filed against M &AMP; M
with the Maryland Home Improvement Commission _ and the Better
Business Bureau does not report complaints that have been settled
out of court. There is a public record of the suit at the
courthouse, but you'd have to know just where to look.
</P>
<P>
   Having learned some expensive lessons, we thought about some
remodeling that my house needs, and asked Baker how we could
immunize ourselves against winding up in court again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't,'' he said, almost cheerfully. He insisted on paying
for lunch. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
