<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6889 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV0     09-29 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECUADOR'S ELECTRICITY MEETS GLOBAL POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Oct. 1) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANTHONY DEPALMA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a story about the search for corporate citizenship, and
a cautionary tale of money, influence and the limits of American
power.
</P>
<P>
   The tale begins in 1925 in Augusta, Maine, where a local company
provocatively named American Foreign Power and Electric legally
incorporated a subsidiary, the Electric Co. of Ecuador (Emelec by
its Spanish acronym), to serve the rapidly growing city of
Guayaquil.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from Maine to Ecuador, but such was the reach of
Yankee business ingenuity in those pre-globalization days. Foreign
Power had already set up similar, quite lucrative companies in
Argentina, Bolivia, Chile and Cuba. All were acquired in 1960 by
Boise Cascade, the forest products company, which was interested
because American Foreign Power had originally burned wood for fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The Ecuadorian operation thrived for years, even after the
government started regulating its rates. Then, in the mid-1980s,
disputes began flaring. The American owners said they could no
longer charge enough to cover costs; the government said Emelec was
not meeting the terms of its concession.
</P>
<P>
   In binding arbitration, the company won a ruling that the
government had broken the 1925 contract and owed Emelec $52
million. The government refused to pay.
</P>
<P>
   While this dispute simmered, Emelec changed hands several times,
eventually coming under the control of a Bahamas-based entity owned
by an Ecuadorian tycoon named Fernando Aspiazu who has been in
trouble with his government. Yet it remained an American
corporation, filing an American tax return each year, though it
hasn't reported a profit or paid a dollar in taxes since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Now the story takes a twist. Aspiazu also happened to own a bank
in Ecuador, the Banco del Progreso, which failed in 1999. To
recapitalize the bank, he took steps to sell stock in his power
company, which he placed in a trust.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Ecuador seized the bank before the sale, and
arrested Aspiazu. (He has not been charged, but remains in jail.)
Aspiazu then tried to keep the power company's assets out of
government hands by creating another trust to sell Emelec's assets
and repay thousands of angry bank depositors. An American, Peter
Heberling of the Latin America Finance Group, was named the sole
trustee, and William Van Dieppen, president of the group, planned
to help with the liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiazu's motives are less than clear, but he seemed to think he
could act like Robin Hood. ``More than 500,000 families are
affected by the bank's failure,'' Van Dieppen said. ``Making sure
they get repaid can't hurt Aspiazu's chances of having his name
rehabilitated.''
</P>
<P>
   Any American investor lured by Latin America's promise fears
corruption and complication, which go hand in hand. Ecuador is one
of South America's least stable countries, and early this year
things really started to come apart. The economy was in such a
shambles that the president, Jamil Mahuad, tried to scrap its
currency in favor of dollars, but people took to the streets, the
army took the Presidential Palace and Mahuad took off for quieter
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   As the dust was settling, Van Dieppen was talking to four
potential American buyers for Emelec, including Enron. But the new
president of Ecuador, Gustavo Noboa, needed to send a message that
things had changed in the country for people like Aspiazu. He sent
troops and the police to seize Emelec headquarters in Guayaquil.
</P>
<P>
   The company appealed to the American embassy in Quito, only to
be told that Emelec, the direct descendant of American Foreign
Power, was not considered an American corporation. ``The State
Department did not do its homework,'' Van Dieppen said, adding that
he thought that the ambassador, Gwen Clare, had sided with the
Ecuadorian government. Van Dieppen said his calls to the ambassador
and the State Department were not returned. ``We felt totally
abandoned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Dieppen then turned to the one tried-and-true fallback for
any company anywhere in the world: He hired lawyers to push
Emelec's interests in Washington. He went to Capitol Hill and lined
up the support of Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C. For a time he also paid
Kissinger McLarty Associates, the high-octane Washington consulting
firm led by Henry Kissinger and Thomas F. McLarty III, President
Clinton's former chief of staff, to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   The investment in influence apparently paid off. On Aug. 28,
Clare said in a letter that the dispute had been raised by
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright during a visit to Ecuador.
``The government of Ecuador should quickly and fairly sort out the
competing claims on Emelec's assets,'' Clare wrote, adding that she
looked forward to working with the trust.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official familiar with the case said the
embassy's initial reaction was based on a mistrust of Aspiazu's
role. But after Helms' office and Emelec's lawyers and
representatives in Washington expressed interest, department
officials decided to take another look. ``Some things could have
been resolved faster,'' the official conceded. ``But these guys had
a lot of things on their platter.''
</P>
<P>
   He was alluding to the new administration led by Noboa, who also
seems to have changed his position. When he was victoriously
touring Emelec's seized offices, he brushed off reporters'
questions about constitutional violations, declaring, ``I have to
do what I need to do _ impose order on this country.'' But in a
recent speech to New York investors, he seemed almost contrite,
saying that the confidence of American investors, which Ecuador
desperately needs, is being restored because the nation is
``beginning to change.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what happened to American Foreign Power exposes some
of the rules of global influence game as it is now played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never assume that the United States government is necessarily
going to be on your side in your hour of need,'' Van Dieppen said.
Without top-notch representation in Washington, he said, ``no one
is going to take you seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Or in Guayaquil, either, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
