s p BC-DEBATES-NNS &LR;      09-29 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEBATES COULD BE KEY TO UNDECIDED VOTERS IN CLOSE RACE 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   
 &HT;     Embargoed against use before Sunday  &HT;     ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from the NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE
report of FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 29, 2000, is available as a ``separate
buy.'' For information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA
WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at 732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697; e-mail, weyded(at)nytimes.com 
 &HT;     
 &HT;     With a sidebar, `DEBATE-HIGHLIGHTS' 
 &HT;     Optional trim to 1,200 words 
 &HT;     By BILL WALSH 
 &HT;     c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The wild swings in popularity between Vice
President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush throughout the
summer have made for a volatile and unpredictable presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As the two hopefuls prepare for their first debate Tuesday in
Boston, public opinion polls find them locked in a contest that has
suddenly become too close to call. With just over a month to go
before the election, experts say the stakes in the debates couldn't
be higher.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore and Bush have been campaigning for more than a
year, the three televised meetings will be the first opportunity
for voters to see them alongside one another. A slightly more
flexible debate format is expected to allow for more unscripted
give-and-take than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debates are most important in closely contested elections,
like this one,'' said Alan Schroeder, a journalism professor and
author of the recent book ``Presidential Debates: 40 Years of
High-Risk TV.'' ``For that bloc of undecided voters who hold the
key to the election, the debates are what they are waiting for.''
</P>
<P>
   While polls show a narrow slice of undecided voters, analysts
say that a segment of the support for both candidates is extremely
soft, which might explain the double-digit leads both men have
enjoyed and then watched vanish throughout the summer. That
fair-weather support, the experts say, means voters could be swayed
by a stellar or disastrous debate performance.
</P>
<P>
   It's happened before. In 1976, a tight race forced President
Gerald Ford to debate an obscure Georgia governor and peanut farmer
named Jimmy Carter. In the closing moments of one of their debates,
Ford made the astonishing assertion that ``there is no Soviet
domination of Eastern Europe.'' A follow-up question failed to
convince Ford to back off his claim.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was replayed in news reports and, although the
term wasn't invented yet, became the ``sound bite'' of the debate.
A few weeks later, Carter inched by Ford in what was the closest
presidential election of the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reinforced this impression that Ford was a bumbler, which
was a false impression to begin with,'' said David Perlmutter, a
professor of political communication at Louisiana State University.
``It shows the demand for these candidates to be eloquent. This
wasn't true in the pre-TV era.''
</P>
<P>
   The first televised presidential debate, in 1960, almost didn't
occur. Massachusetts Sen. John F. Kennedy challenged incumbent Vice
President Richard Nixon to an on-air face-off, but Nixon's advisers
strongly argued against it. They sensed that the medium would be
kinder to the good-looking, articulate young senator than to their
boss.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was well aware of the political benefits of television.
Writing in TV Guide in 1959, he said that a candidate's ``TV
impression'' had little to do with his stand on issues, but rather
intangibles like perceived ``honesty, vigor, compassion and
intelligence ... the candidate's image.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kennedy and Nixon finally squared off, 66 million viewers
tuned in to watch. They saw Kennedy, tanned and resplendent in a
dark blue suit, seemingly at ease before the TV cameras and studio
lights. Nixon, meanwhile, looked pallid and was dressed in dour
gray. He sat bolt upright in his seat and fidgeted.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Robert Dole, a staunch Nixon loyalist, said he
remembered hearing the debate on the car radio as he drove home to
Kansas and figured the vice president won easily with his mastery
of the issues. But when Dole saw a replay on television, he
concluded that Kennedy ``wiped him out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore and Bush camps have learned from the past. Gore has
studiously worked at shedding his reputation for woodenness while
Bush has tried to get rid of the smirk that seemed permanently
stuck to his face and made audiences wonder if he thought
everything was a joke.
</P>
<P>
   LSU's Perlmutter also said that debate preparation these days is
heavily weighted with pre-scripted ``gotcha!'' lines and even
snappy comebacks in the hopes of knocking an opponent off stride
and scoring the sound bite of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most memorable debate jibe came during a vice
presidential face-off in 1988 when veteran Sen. Lloyd Bentsen
launched his famous ``You, Senator, are no Jack Kennedy'' comment
at Dan Quayle, his startled vice presidential opponent.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to make the debates less scripted, the Commission
on Presidential Debates has experimented with different formats
that force candidates to interact more freely and leave more room
for the unexpected. In 1992, at the urging of then-Gov. Clinton,
the debates took on a town hall flavor with questions from
undecided voters in the audience. They were the most-watched
debates ever.
</P>
<P>
   This year's first debate will be fairly traditional, with Gore
and Bush standing behind podiums on a stage answering questions
from public television newsman Jim Lehrer. The vice presidential
debate on Thursday and the Oct. 11 presidential face-off, however,
will feature the two candidates sitting at the same table with a
moderator, who will have the latitude to ask follow-up questions.
The town hall format will return for the final presidential debate
Oct. 17 in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts agree that the debates are Gore's to lose. At a
time when the economy is robust, unemployment is low and crime
statistics continue to fall, political experts say that the onus is
on Bush to convince voters that it is time for new leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Faucheux, editor of Campaigns and Elections Magazine, said
Bush should avoid dwelling on the Clinton scandals of the past
eight years, tempting as it may be to try to tar Gore with them. He
said, however, that Gore's own involvement in fund-raising scandals
is fair game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were Bush, I wouldn't utter the words `Bill Clinton' at
all,'' Faucheux said. ``To make this a referendum on the past is a
loser for Bush. If he makes the election about the last eight
years, the Democrats win because the statistics are on their
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Faucheux said that Gore, meanwhile, needs to remind voters that
``they are better off than they were eight years ago and don't
change the horse in mid-stream.'' LSU's Perlmutter said Gore also
has to be wary of ``stretching the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president is renowned for his hyperbolic claims, from
inventing the Internet to being the inspiration for ``Love Story.''
Last week Gore came under renewed fire for telling a bogus story
about the high prices his mother-in-law had to pay for her
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were Gore's campaign consultant, I would prescreen all of
his anecdotes,'' Perlmutter said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the high stakes of this year's debates, two major
television networks won't carry the first one. NBC said it has a
contractual conflict and will broadcast a Major League Baseball
playoff game Tuesday. Fox has decided to forgo all of the debates
and air entertainment programs instead. The debates will be carried
on both networks' cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This marks the first year that the debates will be carried over
the Internet. FreedomChannel.com will do a simulcast of the debates
and last week offered the third-party candidates, who have been
excluded from the TV debates, a chance to take part in the Web
versions.
</P>
<P>
   FreedomChannel.com has invited Green Party candidate Ralph
Nader, the Reform Party's Pat Buchanan, Natural Law nominee John
Hagelin, Libertarian candidate Harry Browne and Constitution Party
nominee Howard Phillips to submit videotaped answers to the same
questions put to Gore and Bush. The tapes will be posted on the
Internet site within 48 hours after the actual debate.
</P>
<P>
   JL END WALSH
</P>
<P>
   Bill Walsh may be contacted at: bill.walsh(at)newhouse.com
</P>
</TEXT>
