s p BC-DEBATE-HIGHLIGHTS-NNS     09-29 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-HIGHLIGHTS-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HIGHLIGHTS AND LOWLIGHTS FROM TELEVISED DEBATES 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   
 &HT;     With `DEBATES,' embargoed against use before Sunday  &HT;     ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from the NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE
report of FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 29, 2000, is available as a ``separate
buy.'' For information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA
WEYDERT of The New York Times Syndicate at 732-390-4480; fax,
732-390-4697; e-mail, weyded(at)nytimes.com 
 &HT;     
 &HT;     c.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Some key moments from earlier presidential debates:
</P>
<P>
   _ Nixon vs. Kennedy, 1960. In the first nationally televised
presidential debate, Sen. John F. Kennedy demonstrated a mastery of
the medium. He looked relaxed and tanned, while Vice President
Richard Nixon, who had refused CBS' offer of makeup and was running
a fever, appeared nervous and pallid. Radio listeners thought Nixon
clobbered his young opponent with an expert grasp of the issues,
but TV viewers were wowed by Kennedy's ease and grace. It was the
image that came to define Camelot.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ford vs. Carter, 1976. President Gerald Ford had held his own
through much of the debate with the little-known Georgia governor,
Jimmy Carter. But in answer to a reporter's question in the closing
minutes, Ford made a remarkable blunder when he asserted, ``There
is no Soviet domination of Eastern Europe.'' Ford figured it was a
minor misstep, but the comment dogged him for the rest of the
election.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carter vs. Reagan, 1980. Carter sought to portray his
Republican opponent as a coldhearted conservative by accusing him
of opposing Medicare. Former California governor Ronald Reagan's
good-natured reply, ``There you go again,'' became one of the most
memorable lines of any debate. Carter would acknowledge years later
that it showed how relaxed Reagan was and that he had a sense of
humor. Reagan scored again in his closing moments by asking
viewers, ``Are you better off than you were four years ago?''
Voters apparently decided they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reagan vs. Mondale, 1984. Reagan appeared lost and confused in
the first debate and would attribute his poor performance to
``overtraining.'' When the inevitable ``age issue'' arose in the
second meeting, Reagan was ready. He dryly responded, ``I will not
make age an issue in this campaign. I am not going to exploit for
political purposes my opponent's youth and inexperience.'' The
crowd roared and even former Vice President Walter Mondale laughed.
He would say later that he knew he had lost the election the moment
he walked off the stage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush vs. Dukakis, 1988. In a gaffe-filled election, Michael
Dukakis' emotionless debate performance against Vice President
George Bush seemed to crystallize voters' concerns about the
Massachusetts governor's robotic personality. In the first question
of the debate, the liberal Democrat was asked if he would favor the
death penalty if his wife, Kitty, were raped and murdered. Dukakis
responded with a dry, wonkish recitation of his long-held
opposition to capital punishment. Voters were underwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle vs. Bentsen. In the vice presidential debate, a
much-maligned Sen. Dan Quayle sought to dispel his image as a
lightweight by noting that he had served in the U.S. Senate as long
as John F. Kennedy. His opponent, veteran Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas, turned to Quayle and scolded, ``Senator, I served with Jack
Kennedy. Jack Kennedy was a friend of mine, and Senator, you're no
Jack Kennedy.'' Quayle remained unpopular, but Bush won the
election.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush vs. Clinton vs. Perot, 1992. At the urging of then-Gov.
Bill Clinton, a town hall format was chosen for the first-ever
three-way presidential debate. Bush, whose popularity had tanked
along with the economy, seemed ill at ease from the start. In
contrast to the gregarious Clinton and the yakety Ross Perot, Bush
seemed wooden and uncomfortable. In full view of the TV cameras,
Bush broadcast his impatience by sneaking a peek at his watch,
twice. Bush would call it ``a little thing,'' but the gesture
seemed to confirm suspicions that he viewed the election process as
a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   JL END
</P>
</TEXT>
