<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE ATTACKS BUSH PLAN FOR ALASKA OIL AND GAS EXPLORATION
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEVY CHASE, Md. _ Vice President Al Gore rushed to the defense
of Alaska's pristine 19 million-acre Arctic National Wildlife
Refuge in a long distance debate with Texas Gov. George W. Bush on
energy policy Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore called the refuge a ``precious environmental treasure'' in
challenging Bush's proposal to open a portion of the Arctic
wilderness to gas and oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's comments came after he toured the lush wooded compound in
suburban Washington that serves as headquarters for the Audubon
Naturalist Society. The hastily arranged tour allowed the
Democratic presidential nominee to respond to an energy policy
speech Bush, the Republican nominee, delivered earlier in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The two presidential candidates have sparred over energy for
more than a week now since Gore persuaded President Clinton to
release 30 million barrels of oil from the nation's
571-million-barrel emergency supply in order to contain spiraling
gasoline prices and ease heating oil shortages before winter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused the administration of ``inattention and misplaced
priorities'' in its energy policies Friday as he outlined his own
10-year plan to open the Alaska wilderness to drilling, develop
alternative fuel sources and coax oil exporting countries to
provide steady oil supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore immediately seized on the Arctic wilderness proposal to
repeat his charges that Bush, a former oil man, is beholden to the
oil industry, which has provided substantial financial backing to
this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drilling for oil in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge _ one
of our greatest national treasures _ is bad environmental policy,
and bad energy policy,'' Gore said from a podium set up near a
butterfly meadow. ``The area is fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I will fight for all Americans, who deserve to have
our environment protected against those who would set the oil
companies loose in the most beautiful, fragile parts of our
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental organizations responded similarly to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drilling the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge would be like
damming the Grand Canyon for hydropower or tapping Yellowstone's
Old Faithful for geothermal energy,'' said Adam Kolton, a senior
official with the Alaska Wilderness League. ``There is no
environmentally friendly way to raid America's most sensitive and
cherished Arctic wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush insisted, however, that 1.5 million acres, or about 8
percent of the refuge, could be explored in an ``environmentally
responsible'' way.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bush was posing ``a false and outdated choice''
between a clean environment and energy security. ``We can achieve
both if we make responsible decisions,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to raising the environmental risks of exploring for
oil in the refuge, Gore questioned whether the amount of oil that
could be reaped would be worth the effort. ``It would take years
and years of development _ to reap just a few months of increased
oil supply,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 19 million-acre refuge is roughly the size of the state of
South Carolina, located on the northernmost edge of Alaska. Its 1.5
million acres along the coast are considered the most promising for
oil and gas exploration, holding about 7.6 billion barrels of
recoverable oil. That compares to about 23 billion barrels in the
lower 48 states.
</P>
<P>
   According to federal agencies, it would take between 7 and 12
years for lease sales, permits and environmental reviews if oil
exploration were permitted in the refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore defended the administration's release of oil from
the emergency reserve to address short-term emergencies, he said
the United States must end its dependence on oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to build our lives around a fuel source that is
distant, uncertain and too easily manipulated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also called for better mass transit and for the revamping of
``dirty old power plants'' into modern, clean energy providers, as
well as investment in new technologies to clean up the environment
and incentives to encourage auto makers to build more efficient
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Nettags:
</P>
<P>
   www.algore2000.com
</P>
<P>
   www.georgewbush.com
</P>
<P>
   www.alaskawild.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
