<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Sept. 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   High pressure will remain the dominant weather feature across
the Northeast on Saturday, providing mostly sunny days and crisp
nights. After patchy morning frost in the interior valleys of the
Northeast, readings will rebound in the afternoon to near normal.
Breezes will become light from the south.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will develop along the Southeast coast
as a jet stream disturbance intercepts an old front. Some places
will have brief bursts of heavy rain. The interior Southeast will
be partly to mostly sunny.
</P>
<P>
   The Plains will turn noticeably warmer, with some spots from
western Nebraska to Texas reaching the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   A cool front pushing into the Northwest will direct moist air
inland from the Pacific, causing showers and low clouds. Southern
California will turn warm with offshore winds.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FOG SEASON
</P>
<P>
   Autumn is the foggiest season in much of the interior East. Fog
forms when when air near the ground is cooled enough for the water
vapor in the atmosphere to condense into visible water droplets. In
early autumn, the moist air of the warm season lingers near the
surface of the earth. At the same time, the lengthening hours of
darkness allow more of the day's heat to dissipate. The cooled air
at the ground is dense and therefore drains into low spots in the
terrain, making valleys prone to fog while nearby hilltops often
remain in the clear. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
