<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6919 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-KIDNAP-HSNL-     09-29 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-KIDNAP-HSNL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA-KIDNAP 
 
FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 1, 2000 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
COLOMBIA KIDNAP VICTIMS HEAR OF HOPE BY RADIO &QL; 
with/ COLOMBIA KIDNAP-BOOK &QL; 
 &QL; 
By JOHN OTIS &QL; 
(C 2000) Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Reading slowly from handwritten notes at a
radio station, shell-shocked women and somber men do their best to
sound upbeat as they deliver reports of birthday parties, family
trips and school report cards.
</P>
<P>
   The homespun anecdotes are for a captive audience.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by relatives of kidnapping victims, the twice-weekly
radio program broadcast by state-run Radio Nacional in Bogota
provides news, messages of hope and audio love letters for
Colombians being held hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay healthy, calm and courageous as you go through these
trying times,'' one woman said in a message to her abducted husband
during a recent taping of the program. ``Try to find something good
in this situation. Be positive, and realize that God is on your
side.''
</P>
<P>
   The program, called In Search of Lost Freedom, has plenty of
potential listeners. With more than 2,000 people snatched so far
this year, Colombia has the highest rate of kidnappings in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Although the victims often spend months in the wilderness in
wretched conditions, their captors sometimes allow them to listen
to the radio.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, a handful of radio programs in Bogota and
other Colombian cities have sprung up to connect hostages with
their friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best way to do it because radio reaches every part
of the country,'' said Vivana Esguerra, the host of In Search of
Lost Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the number of Colombian kidnap victims has
skyrocketed thanks to Marxist rebels who partially finance their
36-year war against the government by extracting huge ransoms
payments for their hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for example, the National Liberation Army, the
smaller of the nation's two main guerrilla groups known as the ELN,
raided several restaurants on the outskirts of the city of Cali.
They grabbed more than 50 people.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing paramilitary groups and criminal gangs also take
hostages.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday nights when In Search of Lost Freedom is taped, dozens
of people fill the studio for a chance to speak into the
microphones for two or three minutes. As they wait, they nervously
cross out words, add new paragraphs and recite the letters to
themselves in hushed voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you get a knot in your throat, and you can barely
talk,'' said Maria Velasquez, as she waited to read a message to
her kidnapped husband.
</P>
<P>
   One woman broke down crying midway through her letter. Esguerra
urged her to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relax, breathe deeply, and start again,'' Esguerra said,
taking the woman's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of kidnap victims who live in far-off towns sometimes
fax their messages to the station or send prerecorded cassettes. On
one tape, a woman added a few verses of Happy Birthday for her
kidnapped boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Hostages recently released by their captors often show up at
Radio Nacional to provide news about fellow kidnap victims still
being held.
</P>
<P>
   Between speakers, a musician fills the airwaves by playing a
grand piano. After the program, relatives of hostages exchange hugs
and encouraging words.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd is a mix of the well-to-do and the working class, a
reflection of how Colombia's kidnapping business has evolved.
</P>
<P>
   Kidnappers used to focus on the rich. But as the nation's civil
war intensified in the 1990s, guerrilla groups began targeting
farmers, middle-class families and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   One woman at the studio delivered a message to her brother, a
baker who was grabbed by rebels three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they took him by mistake. But now they want a $25,000
ransom,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of the speakers' relatives have been missing for years
and are presumed dead. Yet their family members arrive at the radio
station every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the studio, everyone is equal,'' Esguerra said. ``From the
sons of the ostentatious millionaire to the wife of a humble
disappeared person, they all have the chance to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Some relatives suspect they are speaking into a void, that their
messages go unheard.
</P>
<P>
   But many hostages who have been freed say that they were
faithful _ and grateful _ listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Leszli Kalli, who was held for 373 days when the ELN skyjacked
an Avianca domestic flight last year, said that the missives from
her family broadcast from a radio station in the Colombian city of
Bucaramanga gave her strength during her darkest hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday evening, my mother advised me to repeat to myself
that I am rock solid and that nothing will ever hurt me,'' Kalli
wrote in her diary, which was later published and became a
best-selling book in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I adore Tuesdays when they transmit the messages.... Thank
you, God, for this gift that you gave me of being able to listen to
my mother,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge, a former hostage who gave only his first name, said that
his rebel captors didn't approve of the broadcasts. He used to
crawl under the covers of his bed with a transistor radio on low
volume and secretly listen to the messages.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Jorge came up with a code that a fellow hostage, who
was freed before him, passed on to Jorge's family. The code allowed
relatives to broadcast messages updating Jorge on the status of
ransom negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In one message, for example, Jorge's wife said that the imported
American paper for the printing press was too expensive and that
she would buy Colombian paper instead. That meant guerrilla demands
in U.S. dollars were too steep and that the two sides were debating
a smaller ransom to be paid in Colombian pesos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been very difficult without the radio. I would
have preferred to die,'' said Jorge, who spent a year in the hands
of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, the nation's largest
rebel group known as the FARC.
</P>
<P>
   However, in her book How to Survive a Kidnapping, author Martha
Lucia Aristizabal points out that for some hostages, the experience
of hearing loved ones can be painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard them on the radio and, despite feeling happy, I also
felt depressed,'' says one former hostage in the book. ``I thought
about my family, and it made me very sad, and I knew that things
would only get worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I decided to pretend that I was alone in life,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
