<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6933 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-COLOMBIAKIDNAPBOOK-HN     09-29 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA-KIDNAP.BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 KIDNAPBOOK-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  with COLOMBIA-KIDNAP 
 
FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 1, 2000 
 
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) . 
 
KIDNAPPING BOOKS BECOME BEST SELLERS 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN OTIS &QL; 
(C 2000) Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Life as a hostage in the mountains of
Colombia did not agree with Leszli Kalli. She was bitten by a
scorpion. She developed anorexia, and she argued constantly with
fellow kidnapping victims.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the 18-year-old student grew so bored that she
shaved her head in desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way to escape this monotony,'' Kalli wrote in her
diary. ``Everyone thinks that I have grave mental problems, but the
worst part is that I think so, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalli was one of 46 people kidnapped by Marxist rebels last year
when they skyjacked an Avianca domestic flight. Her harrowing
account of 373 days in captivity was published in June, just two
months after she was released.
</P>
<P>
   Called Secuestrada, or Kidnapped, the book is the latest in a
string of publications inspired by Colombia's status as world
leader in kidnappings. It became an instant best seller here.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 2,945 people were abducted in Colombia _ a rate of
more than eight per day.
</P>
<P>
   ``These books are very dramatic. People buy them, because there
is a sense that anyone in Colombia can be kidnapped,'' said
Francisco Miranda, who reviews books for the Bogota daily El
Tiempo.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian soap operas often weave hostage crises into their
plots. Free Country, a Bogota support group for relatives of
kidnapping victims, sponsors an annual prize for the best thesis
about abductions by a university student.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, artist Maria Elvira Echeverri, who was
snatched by guerrillas last year, will open an exhibition of 72
paintings based on the experience.
</P>
<P>
   The literary trend began in 1996 when Gabriel Garcia Marquez
published News of a Kidnapping, a true-life account of 10 prominent
Colombians who were abducted by henchmen working for drug kingpin
Pablo Escobar in 1990. Escobar's mission was to pressure the
Colombian government into eliminating a law that allowed drug
traffickers to be extradited to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia Marquez wrote that some of the guards were constantly
high on crack and loved to threaten their hostages. But others grew
fond of their captives and gave them birthday cakes and Christmas
presents and even asked if they could date their daughters.
</P>
<P>
   When the central figure in the book was about to be freed, one
of her guards gave her a 9 mm shell to remember him by. ```Here,'
he said, not really joking,'' Garcia Marquez wrote. ```The bullet
we didn't shoot you with.'''
</P>
<P>
   Another recent best seller is How to Survive a Kidnapping, a
step-by-step manual for hostages and their families.
</P>
<P>
   The book includes chapters on negotiating with kidnappers and
dealing with fears of dying as well as thoughts of suicide. It
offers suggestions for freed hostages on how to put their lives
back together. Published earlier this year, the book is already in
its second edition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people who buy it are victims,'' said author
Martha Lucia Aristizabal.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1728EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
