<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6934 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GUCCI-MISTRESS-$ADV01     09-29 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-MISTRESS-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DARK GUCCI'S SUNSHINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Oct. 1) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To Sara Gay Forden, the most compelling character in
her new book ``The House of Gucci'' (William Morrow) may well have
been the one that got away. Forden's labyrinthine tale of familial
corruption, betrayal and greed in the renowned Italian luxury
empire spans the decades from 1921, when Guccio Gucci founded the
company, to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the author provides revealing glimpses of a
multitudinous cast of players, in particular Maurizio Gucci, whose
1995 murder, arranged by his former wife, is the book's framing
drama.
</P>
<P>
   One subject who eluded Forden during her research, however, was
Sheree McLaughlin Loud, a rangy American former model, who was
Maurizio Gucci's girlfriend during the turbulent years 1984 to
1990. Described in the book as the single ``ray of sunshine'' in
Gucci's life, Loud refused to return Forden's calls.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, Loud materialized at a book party for Forden given
by Rizzoli. Tears welling in her eyes, the tall, fair-haired Loud
embraced the author and confided, ``Those were some of the most
intense years of my life.'' She said that after reading the book,
she regretted her decision not to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, at her office in midtown Manhattan, Loud, 41,
who is now the communications director for Giorgio Armani's
Collezioni label, recalled the years of intimacy with Gucci, a
grandson of the company founder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't tell a lot of people about my relationship with
Maurizio while it was happening, and I saw no reason to tell Sara
when she called,'' said Loud, dressed in an understated Armani knit
top and trousers. ``My experience in Italy had quite simply changed
my life. I didn't want it to be in some gossip book.''
</P>
<P>
   During her six-year relationship with Gucci, whom she met during
preliminaries for the 1984 America's Cup regatta, she made almost
weekly commutes between New York and Milan. ``I traveled by
Concorde, then by private plane, and I would arrive in Milan almost
any hour of the day or night,'' Loud said. ``To me the trip was
nothing _ it was just like a ride to the Hamptons.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gucci was separated from his wife, Patrizia
Reggiani. ``There weren't too many stabilizing people around him _
he had hardly any friends,'' Loud recalled. She spent days lolling
on the deck of his yacht, the Creole, or at his chalet in St.
Moritz.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci, who owned 50 percent of the company, was consumed by a
desire to restore the luster of Gucci's image, tarnished over the
years by cheap, overdistributed goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was living a movie,'' said Loud, who was 25 when
she met Gucci, 10 years her senior, referring to both her love
affair and the House of Gucci itself. So intimidated was she at the
start of the affair that she refused to set foot in the Fifth
Avenue store. ``After a year, I did go, and I bought this one
little bag, just to show him that I liked his product,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In dark moments, Gucci brooded. Domenico De Sole, Gucci's chief
executive, was in talks with Investcorp, the merchant bank, which
bought Gucci in 1993 and provided the funds for the house's
spectacular turnaround under the designer Tom Ford. Loud recalled
that after De Sole clinched the deal with Investcorp, Gucci
considered him a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought everyone was betraying him,'' she said. ``He swore
to me that Patrizia was trying to kill him. He told me she was
poisoning him.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Loud dismissed his suspicions. ``I'm from
Connecticut, you know,'' she said. ``I come from practical people.
For me that kind of thinking is just too bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggiani, whom the Italian press dubbed the Black Widow, had
long sought her former husband's ruin. She was convicted two years
ago of engineering his murder and sentenced to 29 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Loud has since gone on to a new life. Last summer, she married
Rob Loud, a money manager, and is expecting her first child in
March. At work, she has her hands full, overseeing public relations
and marketing for Le Collezioni. But her years with Gucci haunt
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe Patrizia had him killed,'' she said,
incredulous. ``All that belongs to another world. And I was another
person. I dream about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
