<HEADLINE>
PENNSYLVANIA DIRECTS TRAFFIC TO ITS WEB ADDRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Neb.)   (For release Sunday, Oct. 1)  
 By MICKEY MEECE  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pennsylvania is using traffic jams to generate more hits _ not
fender-benders, but visits to its official site on the World Wide
Web.
</P>
<P>
   The state has put its Web address _ www.state.pa.us _ across the
bottom of its new blue, white and yellow license plates, albeit in
type small enough that only those with excellent vision or a
penchant for tailgating can see it.
</P>
<P>
   By June 2002, 9 million of these 72 square-inch billboards will
be issued in the state's first complete plate replacement since
1976.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing the new plates, Gov. Tom Ridge said, ``The old,
faded yellow ones sent exactly the wrong signal.'' The right
signal, he said, was to promote the state's high-technology
prowess.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the strategy has worked, said Anthony Haubert, a
spokesman. ``The number of hits on our Web site has increased
dramatically,'' he said. ``While it could be due to a number of
reasons, we do have the feeling that the deployment generated a lot
of those inquiries.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that advertising the site helped to ``put the state at
the forefront of technology and e-government.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the new design has received mixed reviews in the
Keystone State, the idea has caught on elsewhere. In 2002, Nebraska
will introduce a license plate imprinted with its own Web address:
www.state.ne.us.
</P>
<P>
   With several new cars promising built-in Internet access, will
motorists succumb to the temptation to visit the Keystone State in
cyberspace even as they cruise the Pennsylvania Turnpike in real
time?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
