<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6948 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN     09-29 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR JONES, A DISAPPOINTMENT IN BRONZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sports of the Times) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Fun is winning.
</P>
<P>
   Losing is no fun.
</P>
<P>
   Someone has to win; someone has to lose.
</P>
<P>
   At these Olympics, you get so many versions of winning and
losing. Five or six times a day, depending on the event, the
athlete, the expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones gave another variation Friday night when her quest
for a unique place in history ended where many thought it might _
in the long jump pit.
</P>
<P>
   Heike Drechsler of Germany won the event, in what has become a
typical Sydney Olympic performance: not record-breaking, not
especially beautiful. Tough, grueling. Olympian.
</P>
<P>
   Fiona May of Italy won her second consecutive silver, and Jones
won the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked Jones if, given all that has happened here,
she is having fun at her first Olympics, Jones said, ``Fun is
winning. That's what it comes down to.''
</P>
<P>
   She came to Sydney with a goal of becoming the first female
track and field athlete to win five gold medals in an Olympics. She
has had a pretty special Olympics: gold in the 100 meters, gold in
the 200, a bronze medal in the long jump. A bronze medal in her
part-time sport.
</P>
<P>
   Jones took six jumps and fouled on four of them. Her last jump
was the best of the competition. But she fouled. The red flag went
up, on the jump and on posterity.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the last jump, you have to lay it all on the line,'' Jones
said. ``This is what every athlete dreams of: coming back on your
last jump and jumping further than you ever have in your life. I
was very aggressive down the runway, very fast. Thought I took off
well, looked around and saw I was around that seven-meter mark;
unfortunately I turned around and saw the gentleman flip up that
red flag and kind of dashed all my hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones knew going into these games that the downside of setting
her goals so high was that her first Olympics might seem hollow if
she missed obtaining even one of her hoped-for five gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in myself,'' she said. ``I let myself down
today and overall I'll be able to look back on my Sydney experience
and smile and say it was a very good experience, especially if we
win two golds tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Jones won the bronze in the 100 meters or 200 meters you
could reasonably call it a sports failure _ a star who did not live
up to her potential when it mattered most. Not so in the long jump:
Jones didn't lose the gold. The 35-year-old Drechsler won it.
</P>
<P>
   May, Jones and Drechsler have chased each other relentlessly in
the long jump this year. In Brussels, Belgium, in August, Tatyana
Kotova of Russia won the competition. Drechsler finished second,
May third and Jones fifth. Earlier in August, in Zurich,
Switzerland, Jones won the event with a jump of 6.93 meters.
Drechsler finished third. In a meet in Rome last June Kotova won
the long jump, May was second and Jones was third.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Drechsler was right at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you separate yourself from the riveting narrative and
detour to a compelling character outside the narrative. Drechsler
is such a character. She has lived four Olympic lives, competed
through the evolution of a nation, once competing with a wall down
its spine, now a nation with no boundaries. She is a 35-year-old
single mother, the ancient mariner with a familiar story. Competing
in her fourth Games, Drechsler is the last of the old German
Democratic Republic athletes. The last from another era of great
performance and suspect methods.
</P>
<P>
   When someone brought up the old system, Drechsler was curt.
``Not going to talk about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Drechsler won her first world championship in 1983 at age 18.
She competed in her first Olympic Games in Seoul in 1988. In those
games Drechsler was out-dueled by the great Jackie Joyner Kersee
who set an Olympic record of 7.40 meters. The loss began a rivalry
with Kersee that would last more than 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Drechsler won the gold medal at the Barcelona Games, Kersee won
the bronze. Jones, 16 at the time, chose not to compete in the
Games. Drechsler missed the Atlanta Games. Joyner, hampered by a
right hamstring injury, leaped from seventh to bronze on her final
attempt. She wept; getting that bronze was like winning the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Drechsler spoke about the difference between winning
an Olympic gold in 1992, when her country was just beginning the
mending process of becoming one, and in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just 11 years ago and now, we're coming together,'' she said.
``The team is really a team and I don't feel like East or West. We
are a team. It's not so easy for the people,'' she added. ``East
and West have other history and it's not so easy pulling together.
This will be a generation problem, but I feel we have now distanced
ourselves and we are really a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Things end and stuff happens. Hicham El Guerrouj of Morocco had
not lost at the men's 1,500 meters since the end of 1997. Friday he
was caught on the final stretch and defeated by Noah Ngeny of
Kenya. An amazing streak was over.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the eyes of a global audience, Marion Jones has gone
from spectacular and historic to merely tremendous. She goes from
possibly winning five golds to winning ``just four.'' She can take
heart in the fact that Wilma Rudolph _ one of the greatest female
sprinters of all time _ only won three Gold medals at the 1960
Games, and we still invoke her name.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones knows all this and knows that the further she goes
from Sydney, the more special her first Olympics will be. For now,
the bottom line is the bottom line. ``Fun is winning,'' Jones said
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-29-00 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000929.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-29 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6952 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-HONDA-$ADV     09-29 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-HONDA-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDA CIVIC: STILL LEADER OF THE PACK BUT THE WOLVES ARE NIPPING AT
ITS HEELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Oct. 1) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ After just three decades in the American auto market,
Honda is poised to sell a million cars and trucks in the United
States this year. And it was the Civic that built the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The first one arrived in 1973 as OPEC was shutting off the oil
spigot. The Civic, then a tiny, efficient subcompact, was the right
car in the right place at the right time. Now a substantial small
car, the Civic remains a leader in fuel economy and emissions, and
the redesigned 2001 model is arriving at a time of tight oil
supplies and high prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Civic is built in 12 countries and sold in 140. More than 10
million have been sold worldwide, and it is on track to be the
best-selling small car in America for the sixth straight year. The
Civic has won quality awards and engineering acclaim. The coupes
and hatchbacks have proved wildly popular among young car
customizers.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2001 model faces the toughest competition yet. Ford's
flashy Focus, introduced a year ago, is running not far behind the
Civic in sales and was the world's best-selling car in the first
half of this year. Nissan beefed up its 2000 Sentra and gave it
more power. Volkswagen's Jetta and New Beetle offer fresh,
driver-oriented alternatives to Japan's dependable but boring
transportation appliances. Meanwhile, improved cars from three
Korean automakers are winning budget-minded buyers.
</P>
<P>
   After a week in which I drove both a gold EX sedan and a
bright-red EX coupe, I would still put the Civic at the top of the
small-car class, but not by nearly the margin I've given it in the
past. If I were shopping for a small car, I'd surely take a serious
look at the much-improved competition.
</P>
<P>
   Honda is not a company that embraces radical change, so it
shouldn't be surprising that the look and feel of the latest,
seventh-generation Civic have changed only subtly. Why mess with a
winning formula? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Ford made a fashion statement with its Focus,
Volkswagen played cute with its Beetle and Chrysler went retro with
its PT Cruiser, Honda has followed a conservative styling path. It
did make the sedan, which was designed in Japan, and the coupe,
which was planned in the United States, more distinct from each
other _ the same course it took with the current two-door and
four-door Accords. The Civic sedan, which went on sale in
September, has crisper lines, and it reminded me of a classy,
well-tailored suit. Its nose is shorter and more sloping. The
coupe, which goes on sale in mid-October, has a lower roofline and
a sleeker look. Its windshield and rear pillar have a lower,
sportier rake than those of the sedan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Civic is now shorter, but larger in most other dimensions.
It looks and feels substantial for a small car. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is noticeably roomier inside, too, thanks largely to a more
space-efficient suspension. As measured by the government, the
space for both passengers and cargo has increased. Indeed, the
Environmental Protection Agency has moved it up to the compact
class, from subcompact status.
</P>
<P>
   Rear passengers benefit most, because the more compact
suspension allows the floor to be completely flat. The center
tunnel is gone, thanks to a repackaging of the underbody parts. All
passengers get much more comfortable and supportive seats.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard is so clean and uncluttered that I thought
something was missing. I suspected that Honda had taken content out
of the car to trim costs, but when I ran through a checklist of the
test cars' equipment, everything was there _ except, perhaps, some
character. Is it possible for a design to be too efficient?
</P>
<P>
   The three-door hatchback, whose sales had been slipping, has
been dropped. Both the sedan and coupe are available as the base
DX, the midlevel LX and the top-of-the-line EX. The coupe also
comes as the fuel-efficient HX, which achieves about 40 mpg.
Another sedan, the GX, is powered by natural gas and is classified
as an ``super ultra low emission'' vehicle; Honda calls its
powerplant ``the cleanest internal-combustion engine in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the performance-oriented Si is missing, though Honda is
planning new one.
</P>
<P>
   A holdout on the use of side air bags in its vehicles, Honda has
finally relented. Side bags are now offered on all Civics for $250,
and they include a cutoff system that prevents them from deploying
if they could put a child or a small adult in danger. Antilock
brakes, previously limited to the most expensive models, are now
also available on all Civics for $250 extra. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are three-point safety belts for all five seating
positions, and pretensioners pull the front shoulder belts tightly
in a crash. Sensors determine how much force there should be in the
air bags' deployment, depending on the crash's severity and whether
the driver and passenger are buckled. There are tethers for
child-safety seat and an emergency release inside the trunk. While
the federal government has not yet crash-tested the 2001 Civic,
Honda says its tests indicate that the car will achieve the top,
five-star rating.
</P>
<P>
   If it does, the more rigid body structure will be partly
responsible. The stiffer body improves the already responsive
handling. In fact, the new chassis, which could certainly handle
more horsepower, cries out for a more potent powertrain.
</P>
<P>
   All Civics are equipped with 1.7-liter, four-cylinder engines,
up from 1.6 liters last year, that meet ultra-low-emission
standards in all 50 states. The DX and LX have a 115-horsepower
version, up from 106. The engine in the EX has variable valve
timing, which improves the torque, or getaway response, and raises
horsepower to 127. While that is respectable, it cannot match the
class-leading 145 of the Nissan Sentra SE.
</P>
<P>
   The Civic DX, LX and EX are available with a five-speed manual
or a four-speed automatic transmission. (The HX and GX are
available with a continuously variable transmission, an automatic
that shifts constantly instead of at fixed points.) The EX sedan
that I tested was equipped with the automatic; the coupe had the
five-speed manual. Both are silky smooth _ among the best
transmissions in any small car. The brakes are excellent, too,
bringing the cars to straight, quick stops in panic maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the Civic's quality seems impeccable. Gaps between
exterior body panels are impressively closer even than on previous
models, and they fit much closer than the pieces of small cars from
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Honda says that prices have gone up only slightly on comparably
equipped models, though fully equipped Civics now brush
uncomfortably close to $20,000 _ at the top of the class. Base
prices range from $13,200 to about $18,000. The tested EX sedan,
which received the most added equipment and largest price
increases, totaled $18,239.
</P>
<P>
   Civic buyers are among the industry's youngest and most loyal,
returning for a second or third Civic or moving up to an Accord or
Acura. They are also relatively affluent, and 55 percent are women.
These buyers may find the '01 model reassuringly competent. Still,
some may wonder, as I did, if the car has sacrificed a bit of its
distinctive style and personality in its quest for an ever-larger
market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
